e56e7c63-5ce1-4fda-96b6-65e15530d3d2	Natureza Urbana	Breno Pilot	breno@naturezaurbana.net	Tourism Masterplan for Fogo and Brava Islands, Cape Verde	IMPLEMENTED	SUBMITTED	SECTION_III	Brava & Fogo Islands	Cape Verde	14.896567	-24.5415	The project’s aim was to develop the Tourism Master Plan for Fogo and Brava Islands in order to identify the particularities, potentialities and specific needs for sustainable tourism development.	The initial studies focused on characterizing the tourists who visit Cape Verde, surveying and analyzing the country's tourist resources, which made it possible to identify the needs of Fogo and Brava Islands for the development of the plan. Based on this methodology, it was possible to identify the potentialities to be strengthened and the challenges to be overcome, providing a cohesive basis for building the actions of the Tourism Masterplan.	Fogo Island, with population of 35,213, depends on tourism and wine, coffee and goat cheese production. Enhancing tourism opportunities will increase the locals’ earnings and the protection and conservation of the environmental resources that are the basis of the tourist attraction. This appreciation goes through the resolution of several current problems, such as the scarcity of reception facilities, the difficulty in air connections and improvements in basic infrastructure.	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	IFF20	Pedro Lira and Manoela Machado (Coordination); Camila Sanches (Project Leader), Julia Marini, Julia Ximenes and Giulia Corsi (team).	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
e6fcdaba-12ef-4867-b4e0-cc4b1cad249b	Unknown	Unknown	marizarquitectonica53@gmail.com	PLAN DE MANEJO DE BARRIO FUNDACIONAL	PLANNED	SUBMITTED	SECTION_V	Mendoza	Argentina	\N	\N	PLAN DE MANEJO DE BARRIO FUNDACIONAL- EL CASO DEL CENTRO HISTÓRICO DE LA CIUDAD DE OAXACA DE JUÁREZ, DADOS LOS MARCOS JURÍDICOS NO CUENTA CON UN PLAN DE MANEJO. El presente trabajo tiene como finalidad el planteamiento de un Plan de Manejo de barrio como un proceso organizado que define las actuaciones necesarias que se deben realizar para conseguir un cambio o evolución desde una situación de partida, es decir cómo se encuentra ahora el barrio, a una situación deseada para ese territorio, para la sociedad que lo habita y el patrimonio cultural que la representa. Estos cambios deben representar un mejoramiento en la calidad de vida de sus habitantes, así como en la preservación y puesta en valor de su Patrimonio Cultural. Principios del Plan, al constituirse en una herramienta para el manejo integral del Barrio, debe cumplir con principios fundamentales que van estrechamente ligados al su papel frente a sus beneficiarios y actores directos que es la población en general; así, el plan deber ser: • Participativo: para incorporar a la sociedad en la formulación del Plan y que esta actúe con responsabilidades, como veedora de su cumplimiento. (sector público, privado y sociedad civil) . • Sustentable: Se propenderá al buen uso y cuidado de los recursos territoriales (naturales, culturales, patrimoniales) disponibles para garantizar el disfrute de las generaciones venideras.  * Incluyente: debe acoger visiones y propuestas desde la diversidad de sociedad civil: étnica, cultural, generacional, género.  * Integral: debe analizar la problemática y las soluciones tomando en cuenta aspectos socioeconómicos, paisajísticos, ambientales, culturales, funcionales, entre otros, tanto internos como de la ciudad en general y de la región según sea su rol geopolítico.  * Dinámico: debe ser considerado como un proceso continuo que debe ser evaluado y mejorado constantemente.  LA VISIÓN GENERAL ES REPLANTEAR LA FORMA DE HACER LOS PLANES DE GESTIÓN QUE CORRESPONDEN A LA PLANEACIÓN DE LO MACRO A LO MICRO,  EL PRESENTE PLANTEAMIENTO DEL PROYECTO COMPRENDE EL DISEÑO DE UN PLAN MICRO A ESCALA DE BARRRIO Y/O HASTA DE MANZANA PARA REALIZAR EL DIAGNOSTICO DE LA SITUACIÓN ACTUAL Y LA PLANECIÓN A CORTO PLAZO, PERO CON VISIÓN DE UNA META TRAZADA EN LA HISTORICIDAD DEL BARRIO Y SU VOCACIÓN HACIA EL FUTURO.	PLAN DE MANEJO DE BARRIO FUNDACIONAL- EL CASO DEL CENTRO HISTÓRICO DE LA CIUDAD DE OAXACA DE JUÁREZ, DADOS LOS MARCOS JURÍDICOS NO CUENTA CON UN PLAN DE MANEJO. El presente trabajo tiene como finalidad el planteamiento de un Plan de Manejo de barrio como un proceso organizado que define las actuaciones necesarias que se deben realizar para conseguir un cambio o evolución desde una situación de partida, es decir cómo se encuentra ahora el barrio, a una situación deseada para ese territorio, para la sociedad que lo habita y el patrimonio cultural que la representa. Estos cambios deben representar un mejoramiento en la calidad de vida de sus habitantes, así como en la preservación y puesta en valor de su Patrimonio Cultural. Principios del Plan, al constituirse en una herramienta para el manejo integral del Barrio, debe cumplir con principios fundamentales que van estrechamente ligados al su papel frente a sus beneficiarios y actores directos que es la población en general; así, el plan deber ser: • Participativo: para incorporar a la sociedad en la formulación del Plan y que esta actúe con responsabilidades, como veedora de su cumplimiento. (sector público, privado y sociedad civil) . • Sustentable: Se propenderá al buen uso y cuidado de los recursos territoriales (naturales, culturales, patrimoniales) disponibles para garantizar el disfrute de las generaciones venideras.  * Incluyente: debe acoger visiones y propuestas desde la diversidad de sociedad civil: étnica, cultural, generacional, género.  * Integral: debe analizar la problemática y las soluciones tomando en cuenta aspectos socioeconómicos, paisajísticos, ambientales, culturales, funcionales, entre otros, tanto internos como de la ciudad en general y de la región según sea su rol geopolítico.  * Dinámico: debe ser considerado como un proceso continuo que debe ser evaluado y mejorado constantemente.  LA VISIÓN GENERAL ES REPLANTEAR LA FORMA DE HACER LOS PLANES DE GESTIÓN QUE CORRESPONDEN A LA PLANEACIÓN DE LO MACRO A LO MICRO,  EL PRESENTE PLANTEAMIENTO DEL PROYECTO COMPRENDE EL DISEÑO DE UN PLAN MICRO A ESCALA DE BARRRIO Y/O HASTA DE MANZANA PARA REALIZAR EL DIAGNOSTICO DE LA SITUACIÓN ACTUAL Y LA PLANECIÓN A CORTO PLAZO, PERO CON VISIÓN DE UNA META TRAZADA EN LA HISTORICIDAD DEL BARRIO Y SU VOCACIÓN HACIA EL FUTURO.	See detailed description	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-04-18 12:59:53.078529	2026-04-18 12:59:53.078529	P6	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
2699fe3f-b23d-4ed4-93ca-55efefe97b58	SuperSpace Architecture	Unknown	info@superspacearch.com	Suncatcher: scarcity and abundance meet art and innovation	PLANNED	SUBMITTED	SECTION_III	Muharraq	Bahrain	26.2594	50.6108	"The Suncatcher" explores sustainable design by aligning its form with the sun’s analemma curve to optimize solar energy capture. Around 4200 m² of integrated solar panels generate 1500 MWh/year—more than conventional roofs—offsetting emissions equal to 633 car trips from Bahrain to Istanbul or the carbon absorbed by 17,000 tree seedlings over a decade. Made from locally sourced desert sand concrete, it reduces transport impact and supports resource efficiency. Its form also channels rainwater and morning dew toward the base, helping create a more hospitable microclimate and supporting plant life in an otherwise arid environment.	"The Suncatcher" explores sustainable design by aligning its form with the sun’s analemma curve to optimize solar energy capture. Around 4200 m² of integrated solar panels generate 1500 MWh/year—more than conventional roofs—offsetting emissions equal to 633 car trips from Bahrain to Istanbul or the carbon absorbed by 17,000 tree seedlings over a decade. Made from locally sourced desert sand concrete, it reduces transport impact and supports resource efficiency. Its form also channels rainwater and morning dew toward the base, helping create a more hospitable microclimate and supporting plant life in an otherwise arid environment.	See detailed description	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-04-18 13:00:00.604992	2026-04-18 13:00:00.604992	P47	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
9da558ea-3731-442e-b05f-3125fff56bcd	American Institute of Architects	Su Chang Design Research Office	sc@suchang.design	Helio Hut	IMPLEMENTED	SUBMITTED	SECTION_I	Logroño	Spain	42.46411	-2.44852	Helio Hut is an urban canopy for the experience of thermal delight. Located in Logroño’s Parque Felipe VI, the design is based on the idea that architectural environments can arouse in the public a desire for comfort and pleasure, exploration and participation. Conceived as a device for sun-filtering, the roof system modulates the relationship between natural daylight, direct heat gain, solar radiation, and thermal comfort. The roof geometries allow the warm morning sun to transmit through the canopy while blocking the hot afternoon sun, creating a series of microclimates under the roof with mediated levels of comfort throughout the day. Its ever-changing pattern of shadows gives another layer of tactility to the space. The goal is to experiment with the potential of using the environment’s thermal comfort as a tool to invite public participation and exploration, creating a direct, tangible, and experiential connection between the human body and the urban environment.\r\n\r\nLearning from local crafting techniques, the weaving angles of the esparto structure are mediated so that each segment of the woven structures can respond to specific sun angles. The woven materials are dyed with different colors to modulate heat absorption, make visible the radiation intensity, and enhance the vibrancy of the park.	PUBLIC SPACE + THERMAL DELIGHT\r\nThe design of Helio Hut is based on the idea that architectural environments can arouse in the public a desire for comfort and delight, exploration and participation. As an urban canopy to reclaim under-used public space, Helio Hut foregrounds its environment to create a site-specific collective place within the open landscape of Logroño’s Parque Felipe VI, making tangible the movement of the sun and its thermal impact on our public space in Logroño. \r\n\r\n\r\nHUMAN BODIES + URBAN ENVIRONMENT\r\nThe structure is a public device for sun-filtering - modulating the relationship between natural daylight, direct heat gain, solar radiation, and thermal comfort. The idea is to allow the warm morning sun to transmit through the roof while blocking the hot afternoon sun, creating a series of microclimates under the roof with mediated levels of comfort throughout the day. Its ever-changing pattern of shadows gives another layer of tactility to the space. The goal is to experiment with the potential of using the environment’s thermal comfort as a tool to invite public participation and exploration, creating a direct, tangible, and experiential connection between the human body and the urban environment.\r\n\r\n\r\nTRADITION + TECHNOLOGY \r\nHelio Hut's hovering canopy is formed from an aggregation of identical geometric modules. Using low-carbon plywood panels, the cantilever modules surrounding the central pillar utilize standardized, prefabricated plywood components, each comprises of a main frame structure with a superstructure slotted on top. Learning from the esparto weaving tradition in Spain, we create a series of esparto structures inserted into the roof frames, providing mediated thermal comfort for the users below. The goal is to experiment with the potential of fusing traditional crafts with contemporary fabrication and simulation technologies and to discover new material possibilities for public space making.\r\n\r\n\r\nSENSATION + PARTICIPATION\r\nThe weaving angles of the esparto structure are mediated through solar analysis to modulate direct heat gain and radiation. Each segment of the woven structures will be dyed with different colors to modulate heat absorption, make visible the radiation intensity, and add visual vibrancy to the park. The vibrant color and shadow patterns will create new sensations for the public visiting the pavilion at different times of the day.	Ensure healthy lives and promote well-being for all at all ages\r\n\r\nThe design of Helio Hut foregrounds the importance of the environment for urban spaces to public well-being. The goal is to enhance the safety and comfort of outdoor urban spaces, so more people can enjoy social interaction and public gatherings outside of their own rooms. \r\n\r\nThe design of Helio Hut allows the warm morning sun to transmit through the roof while blocking the hot afternoon sun, creating a series of microclimates under the roof with mediated levels of comfort throughout the day. With these strategies, the project creates a sense of environmental delight for the often over-heated outdoor space in Logroño allowing citizens of all ages to engage in the outdoor environment for various kinds of activities. Through these social interactions, we hope the design can also enhance the citizens’ sense of belonging, and create a more inclusive urban space for everyone in the city.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nMake cities and human settlements inclusive, safe, resilient and sustainable\r\n\r\nMany public spaces in big cities today are underused due to the increasingly extreme weather throughout the year. In response to this situation, the design of Helio Hut is based on the idea that architectural environments can arouse in the public a desire for comfort and delight, exploration and participation. Conceived as an urban canopy projects generous shadows onto the urban ground for public gathering and leisure activities, Helio Hut makes tangible the movement of the sun and its thermal impact on our public space in Logroño. \r\n\r\nThe Helio Hut is proposed to be made using a low-carbon, prefabricated method of construction using locally sourced timber to create structures that can last long in the weathering situation. This environment-based design approach encourages the public’s return to the park and increases the inclusiveness, safety, social interaction, and environmental resilience of the park. The goal is to enhance the sense of belonging and safety of the urban space by re-engaging the public through environmental considerations, making it both socially and environmentally sustainable.	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	IFF13	Su Chang, Lam Hin Fung Sherman, Lam Yu Sze	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
89c52abd-06a3-4947-bba3-804562e970d0	Oualalou+Choi	Oualalou+Choi	info@oualalouchoi.com	Pavilion for the Kingdom of Morocco at EXPO 2020 Dubai	IMPLEMENTED	APPROVED	SECTION_III	Dubai	United Arab Emirates	25.270678	55.299413	The Morocco Pavilion at the 2021 Expo in Dubai showcases how traditional Moroccan design and construction techniques can find new relevance in contemporary design and urban development efforts.	The Pavilion’s exterior envelope is composed of a 4000 m², 33 m high rammed earth facade, an ambitious technical feat pioneering in its advancement of rammed earth construction methods. Rammed earth, a traditional building material in Morocco, plays a key role in passively regulating indoor conditions in hot and arid places. Its use in the Pavilion proves that it is a material at once traditional and innovative, offering an example of how such building methods can serve to inspire more sustainable models of urban development.	The Pavilion’s 34-meter-high rammed earth façade is an ambitious technical feat pioneering in its advancement of rammed earth construction methods. Rammed earth, a traditional building material in Morocco, plays a key role in passively regulating indoor conditions in hot and arid places. To achieve the heights of the Morocco Pavilion’s facade, raw and compacted rammed earth was formed into prefabricated panels coupled with a lightweight concrete frame. Its use in the Pavilion proves that it is a material at once traditional and innovative, offering an example of how traditional building methods can serve to inspire more sustainable models of urban development. \r\nIn line with this commitment to sustainability, after the conclusion of the 2020 Expo, the Pavilion is converted into a housing complex, with existing facilities adapted into apartments and communal spaces.	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	LDP14	Oualalou+Choi	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
ae1c2e7f-5b81-4475-b8a5-22c49cebe2df	SuperSpace Architecture	Unknown	info@superspacearch.com	125m3 : pre-manifactured fabricated modular housing system	PLANNED	SUBMITTED	SECTION_I	London	United Kingdom	51.5074	-0.1278	125m³ is a modular, pre-manufactured housing system designed to address the urgent need for adaptable, affordable, and sustainable urban living amid growing city populations. Inspired by industrial mass production, it offers standardized yet customizable modules that reduce construction time and costs while promoting community and ecological well-being. The system supports diverse living, working, and social spaces, integrates renewable energy solutions, and fosters participatory design. 125m³ aims to revitalize housing by enabling flexible, scalable, and affordable homes that grow with society’s evolving needs.	125m³ is a modular, pre-manufactured housing system designed to address the urgent need for adaptable, affordable, and sustainable urban living amid growing city populations. Inspired by industrial mass production, it offers standardized yet customizable modules that reduce construction time and costs while promoting community and ecological well-being. The system supports diverse living, working, and social spaces, integrates renewable energy solutions, and fosters participatory design. 125m³ aims to revitalize housing by enabling flexible, scalable, and affordable homes that grow with society’s evolving needs.	See detailed description	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-04-18 13:00:00.604992	2026-04-18 13:00:00.604992	P35	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
170f6365-287b-4e2f-9087-d135f25410d4	NY Hub	Manon Vandommele	manonvandommele@gmail.com	Education Center: new learning opportunities	IMPLEMENTED	APPROVED	SECTION_V	New York City	United States of America	40.71427	-74.00597	The project aims to rethink architecture as an instrument of inclusion by providing educational facilities that embrace the sensory surprises of New York, offering new learning opportunities in the heart of Manhattan. The proposed architectural interventions aim to create new configurations of spaces for interaction and socialization for schools, and especially for children growing up in a city where everything is tenfold. This new way of thinking about spaces was achieved through the use of sequences and variations that are omnipresent in New York. For the detailed development of the project, the intervention sites are located in a neighborhood in the heart of Manhattan, along 8th Avenue. Both sites offer a strong relationship to the streetscape and represent a great opportunity to provide new educational spaces for New York schools.	The new principle of extracurricular spaces forms a new qualitative resilient system that uses the existing qualities of the neighborhood to build complementary spaces to the city’s schools. Through their structural design and their principle of openness to the city, the educational centers express a unique architectural identity in the urban fabric. Human interactions and acquisition of knowledge among children are enhanced by the extracurricular facilities offered, which can also be used by anyone requiring facilities such as those proposed. Schools have complementary spaces for teaching, learning, creating new opportunities for socialization, etc. New learning methods are created by the stimulation between the activity of the streetscape and the extracurricular facilities. The sequences and variations actively present in the city have made it possible to propose new ways of thinking the spatial organization of a classroom, a playground, a cafeteria, etc. The sharing of knowledge and the strong relationship with a city in constant movement are essential elements for the growth of children, allowing them to improve their ability to adapt to unexpected situations. By integrating these functions into the urban fabric of Manhattan’s neighborhoods, a resilient network takes place, optimizing the social and educational integration of children and residents of the city. In this way, the educational centers are an extension of the existing schools of New York, complementing the overcrowded neighborhoods of Manhattan. The architecture of the educational centers creates a strong relationship with the streetscape of the neighborhood and allows children to benefit from school spaces that offer new learning conditions by using the exceptional qualities of the city: sequences, variations and overload of sense. The centers add quality to children’s educational experience and provide new learning opportunities that can be seen as a new vision for New York’s future schools. It is a human-centered approach that addresses the feelings of individuals in a sensory overloaded environment. A new resilient network of schools in Manhattan offering new learning opportunities.	Located between Pennsylvania Station and Times Square, the district of the two sites selected for the development of the project is primarily made up of businesses, offices, hotels, theaters and housing. Many of these businesses and offices are empty, hotels are closing one after the other, and the Covid 19 pandemic has only made the situation worse. There is a certain lack of liveliness and authenticity in an area where so much is happening. Thousands of people pass through every day, there is an unmistakable proximity to the city’s points of interest because it is located in the heart of Manhattan. What is missing from these spots and what is the ingredient of a city, of a neighborhood, are schools. Schools in which children have proper spaces for a good education, with outdoor spaces and work areas appropriate to their needs. Most of the schools in the area are located in old buildings where the playgrounds are missing, the interior spaces are too small and not designed for school facilities. Children are somehow cut off from the reality of what is going on in the city. They enter a building and lose the notion of the city. The majority of large New York schools with spacious facilities, outdoor playgrounds and access to natural areas are located in the northern part of Manhattan, where there is very little human activity, where there are no crowds, and where the realities of New York do not show up. However, realities of New York are for me characterized by this constant disorder where many events occur at the same time. There is an overload of sense that sometimes can be too much, but it is part of the reality of the city. Therefore, I will propose to introduce new learning opportunities in these areas through the creation of an educational center offering additional spaces for educational purposes linked to high schools, elementary schools and kindergartens. Those educational centers would be located in several places in the city in order to have a resilient educational system accessible to all. Kindergarten, primary and secondary schools can rent all or part of the spaces offered, for full or half days, and welcome children to offer them traditional and extracurricular activities that are at the level of the neighborhood and not often found in these places. Making the choice to introduce afterschool spaces in areas such as Times Square and Madison Square Garden is a way to connect with the city, with the sensory overload in which children grow up. It is an educational center that learns children to deal with the mess, the real New York, where there are too many people, too many billboards, too many cars, too much noise, too many smells, too many things going on at once.\r\nThe principle of the education center aims to expand into multiple areas of Manhattan to provide K-12 schools with multiple access points with different types of activities offered depending on the center and its location. It is a resilient network system that seeks to provide new and complementary learning opportunities in an environment where sensory overload and overcrowding are pervasive. The sequences and variations analyzed above are the main tools for the implementation of these centers. Different centers will be strategically located to connect with both Manhattan schools and direct access to the many activities in the city. The creation of this network of educational centers is the establishment of educational resilience within the different neighborhoods of Manhattan. These out-of-school spaces will offer neighboring schools the opportunity to have different activities not accessible in their schools by providing new kinds of classrooms, play spaces, sports facilities, dining spaces, etc. These spaces can also benefit the city’s occupants when they are not being used by the various schools. These are multi-purpose spaces that provide both new learning opportunities for children and sharing spaces for citizens. This resilient community strategy is spread across several points of interest in Manhattan neighborhoods.\r\nThe educational centers are designed in harmony with the liveliness of what happens in the street, with the different levels of intimacy that can be felt, the variations in the facades that have a direct impact on the relationship between the interior environment and the pedestrians, the important variations of our senses that engender all kinds of feelings in our body, as well as the visual sequences offered around the sites. The project is developed on the basis of sequences and variations, meaning that it is a school where hundreds of people pass through a corridor that is in direct relation to the classrooms but also to the playgrounds, where reading and eating complement each other, where hearing the sound of claxons and the yelling of people are part of the many daily events of the children’s education, etc. It is about learning from the harshness of the city, from the simultaneity of these sequences and variations and using them as qualities within educational spaces.\r\nBeing in a city like New York, it is also to have a feeling of “too much” very quickly by the important presence of skyscrapers everywhere around us. In these moments, it is important to be able to refocus on ourself and find other ways to experience the city, one of them is to connect with nature. Human beings are genetically predisposed to feel a sense of pleasure when surrounded by natural environments and this can quickly become a need when we are in a dense environment where concrete and asphalt are the main elements around us. We are systematically drawn to nature because it brings a sense of serenity in times of chaos, soothing in times of stress, and simply well-being at any time of the day. Several green spaces are present in Manhattan, including Central Park which is one of the largest parks in New York, allowing residents to escape the city’s crowds and disconnect from the visual and audio chaos while taking a walk. On a more human scale, there are also pocket parks which are generally located in the center of the chaos and which allow to have the feeling of being in a park while being in a dense urban landscape. These are an effective solution when the implementation of a park is not possible due to a lack of space. Furthermore, providing children with green outdoor spaces improves their ability to concentrate and their cognitive skills. It seems essential to incorporate the notion of natural environment within an educational project located in a place overcrowded and overloaded with (unexpected) events. The green spaces will then allow the children to create a balance between the important presence of activities around them and the calm provided by these natural environments.	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	IFF10	Manon Vandommele - NY Hub - Flanders House - Kris Scheerlinck	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
91101d5a-07f9-4b63-a2dc-3adc431d73c4	Perceive	Fatiha Polin	perceive.rd@gmail.com	Rupgaon Knowledge Exchange Center	IMPLEMENTED	APPROVED	SECTION_IV	Rupganj	Bangladesh	23.7714	90.4766	The Rupgao project embodies a research-driven architectural methodology, beginning with an in-depth, systematic study upon commission. This study thoroughly investigated the site and its surrounding context, community, analyzing various structures—from traditional mud and bamboo homes to hybrid bamboo-mud constructions and buildings with locally sourced precast columns. Each element was evaluated based on material availability, sourcing distance, and local artisans' expertise, alongside critical environmental considerations such as reusability, ecological impact, and the consequences of resource extraction. The site, situated nine feet below road level, required careful deliberation regarding land-filling. The potential environmental repercussions—such as increased carbon emissions and displaced earth—were rigorously assessed, with a strong emphasis on preserving local microorganisms, vegetation, and trees. Material Selection & Sustainable Design: Material choices prioritized sustainability, flood resistance, and cost efficiency. Natural materials were elevated to prevent ground moisture damage, with each component pre-processed to determine its optimal structural role. Construction Challenges & Structural Innovation: The project’s complexity demanded collaboration among artisans, local communities, and management teams. A key challenge was constructing a two-story bamboo-mud hybrid structure with sufficient strength to support a suspended earthen double floor. To mitigate environmental risks, the plinth was slightly raised, protecting against erosion, water damage, and natural disasters. Site Layout & Functional Spaces: The site’s elongated north-south orientation (192 ft long, 95 ft wide, 9 ft deep) accommodated a 185 ft × 22 ft double storied structure.  The upper level includes: • An administrative office • Seven multipurpose classrooms (four convertible to accommodations) • A dual-purpose library and meditation space The lower floor features: • A display center • A seminar hall/multipurpose hall • A dining nook with outdoor cooking area • Caretaker/service staff quarters Universal accessibility was prioritized with a front ramp connecting the both levels, and future expansions; such as a secondary ramp or staircase on the west corridor which can be integrated without structural compromise. Traditional Craftsmanship & Eco-Conscious Techniques To preserve authenticity, the project avoided iron nails and pins, instead relying on skilled artisans to bind the bamboo-mud framework with locally sourced recycled plastic ropes—reducing plastic waste while maintaining structural integrity. The reinforced bamboo-mud flooring not only ensures sustainability but also offers superior thermal insulation, enhancing indoor comfort.	The Rupgao project embodies a research-driven architectural methodology, beginning with an in-depth, systematic study upon commission. This study thoroughly investigated the site and its surrounding context, community, analyzing various structures—from traditional mud and bamboo homes to hybrid bamboo-mud constructions and buildings with locally sourced precast columns. Each element was evaluated based on material availability, sourcing distance, and local artisans' expertise, alongside critical environmental considerations such as reusability, ecological impact, and the consequences of resource extraction. The site, situated nine feet below road level, required careful deliberation regarding land-filling. The potential environmental repercussions—such as increased carbon emissions and displaced earth—were rigorously assessed, with a strong emphasis on preserving local microorganisms, vegetation, and trees. Material Selection & Sustainable Design: Material choices prioritized sustainability, flood resistance, and cost efficiency. Na