2d5844c2-da91-4820-8af5-e8df40584929	Weber Thompson	Rachael Meyer	rmeyer@weberthompson.com	Northlake Commons Regional Bioswale	IMPLEMENTED	APPROVED	SECTION_V	Seattle	United States of America	47.6062	-122.3321	Northlake Commons (NLC), a private development north of downtown Seattle, sets a new precedent for a public-private partnership with Seattle Public Utilities (SPU). Through this replicable model with SPU, NLC is a leader in prioritizing and positively impacting the ecological, economic, and social health of the greater community.   Located between the transforming Northlake maritime neighborhood and the single-family Wallingford community, Northlake Commons is a 275,000sf mass timber, commercial building. At the north end of the site, the 27-mile Burke Gilman Trail intersects with NLC’s plaza, welcoming trail users to a mix of retail and publicly accessible open space that bisects the building and frames a stunning view of Lake Union and Downtown Seattle.  A meandering pathway through the project culminates in a pedestrian connection to a greenspace where the building’s footprint was intentionally held back from the 200-foot Lake Union shoreline buffer. The greenspace doubles as a regional swale becoming the first in a series of projects to receive public funding. Northlake Commons goes above and beyond, cleaning over an acre of polluted roadway runoff, exceeding the site’s stormwater mitigation code requirements.	Northlake Commons (NLC), a private development north of downtown Seattle, sets a new precedent for a public-private partnership with Seattle Public Utilities (SPU). Through this replicable model with SPU, NLC is a leader in prioritizing and positively impacting the ecological, economic, and social health of the greater community.   Located between the transforming Northlake maritime neighborhood and the single-family Wallingford community, Northlake Commons is a 275,000sf mass timber, commercial building. At the north end of the site, the 27-mile Burk