bdf9de22-e788-462b-9c79-28d91232f945	Faculty of Engineering, Alexandria University	Dr. Heba Magdy Mohamed Jahin; Asst Lect. Rowan Hany Hassan Elsheikha; Nouran Mostafa Farrag; Yassin Mohamed Ibrahim; Nour El-Rahman Yasser El-Tayfa; Salma Mohamed Younis; Sohila ehab gad; Marwan Ehab Mohamed; Marwan Adel Elsayed; Alaa Gamal Mohamed; Shahe	bhadley@rkarch.com	Environment and Natural Resources 2	IMPLEMENTED	APPROVED	SECTION_V	Tucson	United States of America	32.2226	-110.9747	The Environment and Natural Resources 2 (ENR2) building at the University of Arizona stands as a model for climate-adaptive design and sustainability-centered research. Completed in 2015 and certified LEED Platinum, ENR2 was envisioned as a living laboratory that would not only house environmental science programs but embody the very systems, values, and strategies these disciplines explore.  Located in Tucson, Arizona—a city defined by its arid climate and dramatic desert landscapes—ENR2 responds directly to both its ecological and academic context. Inspired by the sculpted forms of desert slot canyons, the building’s central courtyard is more than a visual metaphor. It is a functional environmental system, organizing airflow, social interaction, and water collection around a shaded, vegetated spine that anchors the building in place. Curving anodized aluminum scrims recall the vertical striations and desert varnish of natural canyon walls, while terraces planted with native species mimic the ecology of desert mesas, providing shade, comfort, and habitat.  ENR2 was designed as the centerpiece of the University’s environmental and climate-related research programs. It houses the Arizona Institute for Resilience, the School of Geography, Development & Environment, the Department of Mathematics, and several interdisciplinary labs focused on climate modeling, water policy, and earth systems science. By co-locating these programs within a building that exemplifies sustainable performance, ENR2 actively supports cross-disciplinary research, education, and community outreach. Its design invites occupants to learn from the building itself—turning systems into teaching tools and infrastructure into shared knowledge.  The building’s core environmental strategies are rooted in passive design. Massive concrete walls provide thermal mass, absorbing heat during the day and releasing it at night, aligning with Tucson’s dramatic diurnal temperature shifts. The courtyard’s canyon-like form shades the interior spaces and promotes stack ventilation. Solar chimneys and operable windows enable nighttime flushing, reducing mechanical cooling loads. Shaded exterior walkways and planted terraces serve as outdoor circulation and gathering areas, extending usable space while minimizing energy-intensive conditioned zones.  ENR2 also incorporates innovative active systems to reduce energy use. These include underfloor low-velocity displacement ventilation, active chilled beams for localized cooling, demand-controlled ventilation, and daylight-responsive lighting. Together, these systems achieve energy savings of over 30% compared to typical laboratory buildings. Water use is reduced by more than 40%, thanks in part to an integrated harvesting and reuse system that collects up to 260,000 gallons of rainwater annually from rooftop and terrace runoff. HVAC condensate is also recovered and redirected to irrigation, and all landscape irrigation is supplied by non-potable reclaimed water.  Beyond technical performance, ENR2 functions as a dynamic educational platform. The building’s systems are visible and monitored in real time, with data made available to students and researchers. An experimental rooftop agrivoltaic installation combines solar panels with native vegetation to explore the interplay between energy production and ecological performance—critical in arid climates where shading improves both plant survival and panel efficiency. These research installations double as outdoor classrooms, allowing students to engage directly with the building as a living system.  Social sustainability and long-term adaptability were also key design drivers. The ground floor includes a café, auditorium, and classrooms that activate the public realm and create informal collaboration spaces. Office areas are built on accessible raised flooring systems to accommodate reconfiguration as programs evolve. The spatial layout encourages interdisciplinary interaction, while also providing quiet, high-performance work environments.  In a region facing acute challenges from climate change—heat, drought, water scarcity—ENR2 demonstrates how architecture can serve not just as shelter, but as an active contributor to knowledge and resilience. The building is tailored to its climate and region, and scalable as a model for institutions in similar environments worldwide.  ENR2 is not a statement of sustainability in isolation—it is a deeply integrated, purpose-driven facility that puts climate response, research, and education at the heart of its form and function. It is architecture as ecosystem, as pedagogy, and as catalyst. For these reasons, ENR2 exemplifies the UIA’s goals of promoting architecture that advances the sustainable transformation of the built environment and supports the urgent global work of climate adaptation and ecological stewardship.	The Environment and Natural Resources 2 (ENR2) building at the University of Arizona stands as a model for climate-adaptive design and sustainability-centered research. Completed in 2015 and certified LEED Platinum, ENR2 was envisioned as a living laboratory that would not only house environmental science programs but embody the very systems, values, and strategies these disciplines explore.  Located in Tucson, Arizona—a city defined by its arid climate and dramatic desert landscapes—ENR2 responds directly to both its ecological and academic context. Inspired by the sculpted forms of desert slot canyons, the building’s central