ver 30% compared to typical laboratory buildings. Water use is reduced by more than 40%, thanks in part to an integrated harvesting and reuse system that collects up to 260,000 gallons of rainwater annually from rooftop and terrace runoff. HVAC condensate is also recovered and redirected to irrigation, and all landscape irrigation is supplied by non-potable reclaimed water.  Beyond technical performance, ENR2 functions as a dynamic educational platform. The building’s systems are visible and monitored in real time, with data made available to students and researchers. An experimental rooftop agrivoltaic installation combines solar panels with native vegetation to explore the interplay between energy production and ecological performance—critical in arid climates where shading improves both plant survival and panel efficiency. These research installations double as outdoor classrooms, allowing students to engage directly with the building as a living system.  Social sustainability and long-term adaptability were also key design drivers. The ground floor includes a café, auditorium, and classrooms that activate the public realm and create informal collaboration spaces. Office areas are built on accessible raised flooring systems to accommodate reconfiguration as programs evolve. The spatial layout encourages interdisciplinary interaction, while also providing quiet, high-performance work environments.  In a region facing acute challenges from climate change—heat, drought, water scarcity—ENR2 demonstrates how architecture can serve not just as shelter, but as an active contributor to knowledge and resilience. The building is tailored to its climate and region, and scalable as a model for institutions in similar environments worldwide.  ENR2 is not a statement of sustainability in isolation—it is a deeply integrated, purpose-driven facility that puts climate response, research, and education at the heart of its form and function. It is architecture as ecosystem, as pedagogy, and as catalyst. For these reasons, ENR2 exemplifies the UIA’s goals of promoting architecture that advances the sustainable transformation of the built environment and supports the urgent global work of climate adaptation and ecological stewardship.	See detailed description	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-04-18 13:00:15.086189	2026-04-18 13:00:15.086189	P98	Dr. Heba Magdy Mohamed Jahin; Asst Lect. Rowan Hany Hassan Elsheikha; Nouran Mostafa Farrag; Yassin Mohamed Ibrahim; Nour El-Rahman Yasser El-Tayfa; Salma Mohamed Younis; Sohila ehab gad; Marwan Ehab Mohamed; Marwan Adel Elsayed; Alaa Gamal Mohamed; Shaheen Mohamed; Nouran Elshafie; Kenzy Ekramy; MennaTullah Ezzat; Nour Elden Mohamed	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
cf2acc98-cd20-49fa-86fa-a0731da710c3	SuperSpace Architecture	Unknown	info@superspacearch.com	solarCLOUD : harvests the energy of the sun in harmony with the circadian rhythm of life	PLANNED	SUBMITTED	SECTION_III	Masdar City	United Arab Emirates	24.4296	54.6173	solarCLOUD is a landart installation at Masdar City’s portal, made of 1500 solar balloons woven with solar fabric. It creates a shaded park by day, harvesting 2,070 MWh solar &kinetic energy annually, moving like a kinetic sculpture—offsets 983 metric tons of CO₂ per year—the equivalent of planting over 45,000 tree seedlings. At night, it transforms into a digital art platform with light shows co-created by artists & users. Aligned with Masdar’s sustainable vision, solarCLOUD is both a public power plant and a shared cultural space—an urban icon that connects the anima of earth & sun with its community, reflecting the circadian rhythm of nature as the interactive digital heart of the city.	solarCLOUD is a landart installation at Masdar City’s portal, made of 1500 solar balloons woven with solar fabric. It creates a shaded park by day, harvesting 2,070 MWh solar &kinetic energy annually, moving like a kinetic sculpture—offsets 983 metric tons of CO₂ per year—the equivalent of planting over 45,000 tree seedlings. At night, it transforms into a digital art platform with light shows co-created by artists & users. Aligned with Masdar’s sustainable vision, solarCLOUD is both a public power plant and a shared cultural space—an urban icon that connects the anima of earth & sun with its community, reflecting the circadian rhythm of nature as the interactive digital heart of the city.	See detailed description	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-04-18 13:00:08.127452	2026-04-18 13:00:08.127452	P53	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
37d38f2e-ce3a-4cf3-91e7-fb2712a45255	Quintau Arquitetura Paisagística	Thiago Frizon, Fernanda Rabelo, Thiago Brito, Artur Souto, Hélika Limeira, Laura Nomizo, Heloisa Farache	h-jahin@alexu.edu.eg	Unburdened- A Campus Journey from Pressure to Presence, Redesigning Educational Spaces for Student Well-Being and Sustainable Development.	PLANNED	APPROVED	SECTION_III	Alexandria	Egypt	31.2001	29.9187	Project description A 2021 study by the American Society for Engineering Education (ASEE) found that 1 in 3 engineering students experience depression. A growing concern mirrored both locally and globally. Yet, most educational facilities are designed with efficiency, overshadowing students’ emotional and psychological needs. lack of green, open areas and communal environments leads to burnout, dissociation, and disconnection. This project reimagines the campus as a new space that actively offers support to mental health by prioritizing student experience, connection with nature, and opportunities for interaction to improve emotional growth and embed a sense of comfort and relief.	Project description A 2021 study by the American Society for Engineering Education (ASEE) found that 1 in 3 engineering students experience depression. A growing concern mirrored both locally and globally. Yet, most educational facilities are designed with efficiency, overshadowing students’ emotional and psychological needs. lack of green, open areas and communal environments leads to burnout, dissociation, and disconnection. This project reimagines the campus as a new space that actively offers support to mental health by prioritizing student experience, connection with nature, and opportunities for interaction to improve emotional growth and embed a sense of comfort and relief.	See detailed description	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-04-18 13:00:21.972357	2026-04-18 13:00:21.972357	P103	Thiago Frizon, Fernanda Rabelo, Thiago Brito, Artur Souto, Hélika Limeira, Laura Nomizo, Heloisa Farache	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
cd22e4cb-246d-4dd4-943c-423e84298bd8	AIA	Yan Chen – Lead Architect and Design Director Xiaogang Zhou – Urban Planner and Senior Technical Consultant	CONTATO@QUINTAU.COM.BR	Infraestrutura Sustentável e Regeneração Paisagística da Árvore do Amor	PLANNED	APPROVED	SECTION_V	Maxaranguape	Brazil	-5.5208	-35.2614	The Quintau Landscape Architecture project for the Árvore do Amor (Tree of Love) in Maxaranguape/RN, encompasses 5,000m² of sustainable infrastructure and landscape regeneration. It focuses on valuing the natural and tourist heritage, articulating environmental conservation, social inclusion, and community development. Addressing existing degradation, the project proposes accessible paths, educational signage, low-impact structures, and native vegetation regeneration (dunes/restingas) with species like guajiru and mandacaru-da-praia. It includes permeable parking, viewpoints, an elevated walkway, the Árvore do Amor core with interactive elements, and a restored kiosk. The lighting follows ecological guidelines (1,800K-2,200K, "full cut-off", sensors, nighttime shutdown), minimizing impact on fauna and complying with CONAMA regulations. Aligned with SDGs (11, 13, 15), the project aims to be a benchmark in coastal green infrastructure, promoting local ecological balance and community well-being through innovative, nature-based solutions.	The Quintau Landscape Architecture project for the Árvore do Amor (Tree of Love) in Maxaranguape/RN, encompasses 5,000m² of sustainable infrastructure and landscape regeneration. It focuses on valuing the natural and tourist heritage, articulating environmental conservation, social inclusion, and community development. Addressing existing degradation, the project proposes accessible paths, educational signage, low-impact structures, and native vegetation regeneration (dunes/restingas) with species like guajiru and mandacaru-da-praia. It includes permeable parking, viewpoints, an elevated walkway, the Árvore do Amor core with interactive elements, and a restored kiosk. The lighting follows ecological guidelines (1,800K-2,200K, "full cut-off", sensors, nighttime shutdown), minimizing impact on fauna and complying with CONAMA regulations. Aligned with SDGs (11, 13, 15), the project aims to be a benchmark in coastal green infrastructure, promoting local ecological balance and community well-being through innovative, nature-based solutions.	See detailed description	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-04-18 13:00:21.972357	2026-04-18 13:00:21.972357	P104	Yan Chen – Lead Architect and Design Director Xiaogang Zhou – Urban Planner and Senior Technical Consultant	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
