9e8add94-cb21-45ef-acac-32ccf8939e2c	TKCA Architects Sdn Bhd	Ar. Rien Tan, Ar. Howie Lam	tkca.info@gmail.com	Skyblox Co-Living Housing	IMPLEMENTED	APPROVED	SECTION_IV	Bukit Jalil	Malaysia	3.0604	101.6917	SkyBlox Co-Living Housing in Setapak, Kuala Lumpur, is a pioneering model of urban living that redefines what affordable and sustainable housing can be. As Malaysia’s first landed co-living development of its kind, the project goes beyond architecture to act as a social infrastructure—one that fosters community, inclusivity, and environmental responsibility. With over 320 en-suite rooms designed to house more than 500 residents, SkyBlox introduces an innovative and scalable housing typology built on people-centered values.  What sets SkyBlox apart is its strong emphasis on social sustainability. From the very beginning, the project was shaped through a participatory design process that actively involved local authorities, stakeholders, and future residents. Multiple stakeholder meetings were held to understand the diverse needs, aspirations, and concerns of the Setapak community. These consultations helped identify key social challenges such as housing affordability, urban isolation, lack of safe communal spaces, and the desire for a stronger sense of community. Rather than imposing a design solution, the team listened first—allowing these insights to directly shape the architectural response.  The result is a development that feels organic and grounded in the needs of its users. The master plan is designed to encourage interaction and mutual care, featuring communal kitchens, laundries, pocket gardens, flexible lounges, and open corridors that double as social bridges. These shared spaces become vital social nodes where residents from different backgrounds—students, young professionals, small families, and expatriates—can come together naturally, creating opportunities for connection, empathy, and collaboration. By embedding these moments of interaction into the everyday experience of living, SkyBlox cultivates a vibrant micro-community within a dense urban setting.  The architectural expression draws from a “Back to Nature” philosophy, emphasizing openness, greenery, and emotional well-being. Ground-oriented instead of vertical, the housing blocks allow for a closer relationship with the land and a human-scaled living environment. Each unit is part of a modular assembly built using Prefabricated Prefinished Volumetric Construction (PPVC)—a sustainable construction method that reduces material waste and shortens building time while offering flexibility in layout and scalability. This approach allows the design to evolve with community needs or be replicated in different urban contexts facing similar housing challenges.  The integration of biophilic design principles—green balconies, central courtyards, and community farming spaces—not only softens the built environment but reinforces the residents’ connection with nature and each other. These features were directly inspired by feedback from community consultations, which revealed a strong desire for green, open, and safe shared environments. The “SkyBox” multipurpose pavilion at the heart of the development further anchors the project as a place of gathering, celebration, and learning.  Environmental sustainability is embedded through passive design strategies that promote natural ventilation and daylighting. Buildings are oriented and designed to reduce energy usage, incorporating deep overhangs, operable windows, and HVLS fans to optimize thermal comfort. Rainwater harvesting and low-carbon materials contribute to long-term ecological stewardship. Yet sustainability here goes beyond resource efficiency—it is about sustaining human relationships, emotional health, and a sense of shared purpose.  In terms of land use, SkyBlox adopts a compact yet breathable footprint, enabling a high-density living experience without sacrificing quality or dignity. The co-living model promotes shared resources over duplication, reducing living costs while increasing access to amenities. This balance between private space and shared environments was fine-tuned through dialogue with potential users, ensuring that different lifestyle needs could be met within a cohesive framework.  Economically, the project disrupts the assumption that quality design is exclusive or expensive. Through its efficient modular construction and shared amenity model, SkyBlox achieves affordability without compromising on spatial quality, sustainability, or user experience. It empowers a diverse range of individuals to live in a well-designed, inclusive, and safe environment—a critical step in addressing the urban housing crisis in Malaysia and beyond.  SkyBlox also brings new opportunities to the local economy. By integrating retail components and small business-friendly spaces into its design, it encourages entrepreneurship and local employment. The project thus functions not only as a housing solution, but also as a community and economic catalyst.  Ultimately, SkyBlox is a bold yet thoughtful reimagining of urban housing. It combines innovative construction methods with community-driven design to create a housing solution that is scalable, inclusive, and deeply responsive to both people and place.	SkyBlox Co-Living Housing in Setapak, Kuala Lumpur, is a pioneering model of urban living that redefines what affordable and sustainable housing can be. As Malaysia’s first landed co-living development of its kind, the project goes beyond architecture to act as a social infrastructure—one that fosters community, inclusivity, and environmental responsibility. With over 320 en-suite rooms designed to house more than 500 residents, SkyBlox introduces an innovative and scalable housing typology built on people-centered values.  What sets SkyBlox apart is its strong emphasis on social sustainability. From the very beginning, the project was shaped through a participatory design process t