ftens the built environment but reinforces the residents’ connection with nature and each other. These features were directly inspired by feedback from community consultations, which revealed a strong desire for green, open, and safe shared environments. The “SkyBox” multipurpose pavilion at the heart of the development further anchors the project as a place of gathering, celebration, and learning.  Environmental sustainability is embedded through passive design strategies that promote natural ventilation and daylighting. Buildings are oriented and designed to reduce energy usage, incorporating deep overhangs, operable windows, and HVLS fans to optimize thermal comfort. Rainwater harvesting and low-carbon materials contribute to long-term ecological stewardship. Yet sustainability here goes beyond resource efficiency—it is about sustaining human relationships, emotional health, and a sense of shared purpose.  In terms of land use, SkyBlox adopts a compact yet breathable footprint, enabling a high-density living experience without sacrificing quality or dignity. The co-living model promotes shared resources over duplication, reducing living costs while increasing access to amenities. This balance between private space and shared environments was fine-tuned through dialogue with potential users, ensuring that different lifestyle needs could be met within a cohesive framework.  Economically, the project disrupts the assumption that quality design is exclusive or expensive. Through its efficient modular construction and shared amenity model, SkyBlox achieves affordability without compromising on spatial quality, sustainability, or user experience. It empowers a diverse range of individuals to live in a well-designed, inclusive, and safe environment—a critical step in addressing the urban housing crisis in Malaysia and beyond.  SkyBlox also brings new opportunities to the local economy. By integrating retail components and small business-friendly spaces into its design, it encourages entrepreneurship and local employment. The project thus functions not only as a housing solution, but also as a community and economic catalyst.  Ultimately, SkyBlox is a bold yet thoughtful reimagining of urban housing. It combines innovative construction methods with community-driven design to create a housing solution that is scalable, inclusive, and deeply responsive to both people and place.	See detailed description	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-04-18 13:00:39.923528	2026-04-18 13:00:39.923528	P170	Ar. Rien Tan, Ar. Howie Lam	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
b327ef22-cf6d-48b3-9abd-cbe54b7ac7ec	ACE, AIA, AK Germany	Prof. Dr. Thomas Spiegelhalter, Edgar Wilson	spiegelhalterstudio@gmail.com	Grande Calusa 2025–2100: Resilient Coastal Living through AI-Driven Carbon-Neutral Urban Design	PLANNED	APPROVED	SECTION_V	Fort Myers	United States of America	26.6406	-81.8723	Grande Calusa 2025–2100 is a transformative, AI-optimized, hurricane-resilient mixed-use development in Fort Myers and Sanibel Island, Florida, designed as a net-zero, carbon-neutral smart campus resilient through 2100. Inspired by the adaptive intelligence of the Indigenous Calusa people, the project fuses ancestral land stewardship with cutting-edge environmental technologies. The 22.6-acre master plan—replacing a Hurricane Ian-destroyed outlet mall—features three aerodynamic high-rise towers, 200 social workforce housing units, a 200-room hotel, a 15,000 sq. ft. performing arts and conference centre, and over 65,000 sq. ft. of reconfigurable retail and restaurant space. Buildings are raised on 15-foot podiums to protect from storm surge, with integrated bioswales, solar canopies, and stormwater retention systems. Advanced computational fluid dynamics (CFD), wind tunnel testing, and AI simulations (using Forma AI, TestFit, Revit BIM, and Generative BIM) shape climate-adaptive architecture and optimise daylight, thermal comfort, energy harvesting, and water reuse. The urban grid prioritises walkability, social equity, Indigenous cultural representation, and educational art spaces.	Grande Calusa 2025–2100 is a transformative, AI-optimized, hurricane-resilient mixed-use development in Fort Myers and Sanibel Island, Florida, designed as a net-zero, carbon-neutral smart campus resilient through 2100. Inspired by the adaptive intelligence of the Indigenous Calusa people, the project fuses ancestral land stewardship with cutting-edge environmental technologies. The 22.6-acre master plan—replacing a Hurricane Ian-destroyed outlet mall—features three aerodynamic high-rise towers, 200 social workforce housing units, a 200-room hotel, a 15,000 sq. ft. performing arts and conference centre, and over 65,000 sq. ft. of reconfigurable retail and restaurant space. Buildings are raised on 15-foot podiums to protect from storm surge, with integrated bioswales, solar canopies, and stormwater retention systems. Advanced computational fluid dynamics (CFD), wind tunnel testing, and AI simulations (using Forma AI, TestFit, Revit BIM, and Generative BIM) shape climate-adaptive architecture and optimise daylight, thermal comfort, energy harvesting, and water reuse. The urban grid prioritises walkability, social equity, Indigenous cultural representation, and educational art spaces.	See detailed description	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-04-18 13:00:39.923528	2026-04-18 13:00:39.923528	P173	Prof. Dr. Thomas Spiegelhalter, Edgar Wilson	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
7b153b2d-2421-4b89-990b-1427dd7a9956	VIPB Associates	Contact	contact@vspbassociates.com	Bundh Rejuvenation Trail	IMPLEMENTED	SUBMITTED	SECTION_IV	Gurugram	India	28.4595	77.0266	The Bundh rejuvenation project was conceived in 2015 as a pioneering citizen-driven, urban regeneration initiative focused on transforming a deteriorated forest and waterway to a linear, barrier-free nature park.  The Bundh was historically built as an earthen check dam to serve as an efficient water retention system for the city. Over the years, this had been encroached upon and reduced to a garbage dumping ground and open defecation area. With the aim to provide an open space network and green infrastructure for sustainable alternative mobility, the project was conceived to reclaim the Bundh and revive the degraded canal, in the heart of Gurugram.   A design proposal was drawn up to create a public place and eco-mobility corridor in the form of a ‘Linear Park’, with walking and cycling tracks providing non-motorized linkages through the city. This would promote an environment friendly movement system for short-distance commute across the city. This forest corridor would also create a ‘green lung’ for Gurugram and provide a natural setting for leisure facilities to the adjoining residential areas.   The primary purpose was to - • Rebuild the derelict bundh as an ecological network • Transform the urban backyard into an alternative mobility corridor • Rejuvenate it as a vibrant urban public space  The project utilizes the tools of ‘landscape urbanism’ and ‘socially responsive design approach’ to repurpose an old, historic infrastructure to create a safe, inclusive and accessible Public Space for the city of Gurugram.  Highlights of the project are: • A 5.2km long barrier-free, ecological network in the form of a linear nature-park • Revival of the forest and ecosystem…the lost biodiversity habitat was reclaimed by native plants that attract avian species • Conservation of natural resources and reduced project costs by divergent ways of recycling of materials.  [35000 cubic meters of construction debris, from landfill & construction sites in Gurugram, have been utilized for earth-fill operations and old discarded kerbstones were recycled to make toe-walls, for seating, and retaining walls]  • An effective rain water harvesting system comprising french drains, sub-surface perforated piping and recharge pits. This storm-water management system ensures zero discharge from the site into the municipal drains, and also helps to rejuvenate the canal. • A good solid waste management system with compost pits for collection of bio-degradable waste, for on-site generation of plant manure. • Use of renewable energy for lighting solutions with solar pole mounted lights Since the place is open 24X7, simple detailing using natural, local materials - for long term durability, low maintenance and resilience to vandalism - were considered. The construction workers were sourced from the neighbouring squatter settlements, to promote a sense of belonging for the new place.  The Bundh Eco-restoration Project is a unique citizens-driven initiative that addressed the challenges of urban regeneration and sustainability through climate positive design and the provision of a socially inclusive, safe, barrier-free movement corridor…with public spaces for social and cultural interaction.   Once deemed as a derelict, unusable area; the rejuvenated Bundh has now become a landmark public place. It has given the vulnerable user groups a much required sense of dignity of movement and feeling of social equality. Currently hundreds of walkers, cyclists and fitness enthusiasts use this space each day to move across the city, exercise or enjoy a quiet moment, away from the hustle and bustle of the city.	The Bundh rejuvenation project was conceived in 2015 as a pioneering citizen-driven, urban regeneration initiative focused on transforming a deteriorated forest and waterway to a linear, barr