ains, sub-surface perforated piping and recharge pits. This storm-water management system ensures zero discharge from the site into the municipal drains, and also helps to rejuvenate the canal. • A good solid waste management system with compost pits for collection of bio-degradable waste, for on-site generation of plant manure. • Use of renewable energy for lighting solutions with solar pole mounted lights Since the place is open 24X7, simple detailing using natural, local materials - for long term durability, low maintenance and resilience to vandalism - were considered. The construction workers were sourced from the neighbouring squatter settlements, to promote a sense of belonging for the new place.  The Bundh Eco-restoration Project is a unique citizens-driven initiative that addressed the challenges of urban regeneration and sustainability through climate positive design and the provision of a socially inclusive, safe, barrier-free movement corridor…with public spaces for social and cultural interaction.   Once deemed as a derelict, unusable area; the rejuvenated Bundh has now become a landmark public place. It has given the vulnerable user groups a much required sense of dignity of movement and feeling of social equality. Currently hundreds of walkers, cyclists and fitness enthusiasts use this space each day to move across the city, exercise or enjoy a quiet moment, away from the hustle and bustle of the city.	See detailed description	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-04-18 13:00:31.097334	2026-04-18 13:00:31.097334	P130	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
de6a2e79-f313-487b-8d22-eebfbb96d79a	Mayorga + Fontana Architects	Unknown	arquitectos@mayorga-fontana.com	Cesar Government Square-Park (Valledupar, Colombia)	IMPLEMENTED	SUBMITTED	SECTION_V	Valledupar	Colombia	10.4631	-73.2532	The redesign project for the urban complex comprising the Government Square-Park and the Cesar Regional Administration Building in Valledupar (Colombia). This has been an opportunity to propose and create an urban center for the city and its surroundings, adapted to the social, economic, and environmental needs of a city characterized as a key population center in the region; a hub for agricultural, agro-industrial, and livestock production and marketing; and also for being a representative center of Colombian culture and folklore, home to the Festival de la Leyenda Vallenata, an important musical genre recognized both nationally and internationally.  The Government Square of the department of Cesar is located in the extension zone of the municipality's founding and institutional center, which has long been the main hub for cultural, educational, and health services in the city. Within an irregularly shaped block and in the midst of a medium- and low-density urban fabric, the Government building is located, connected to the city by the Guatapurí River-Historic Center (Plaza Alfonso López)-Government Square of the department of Cesar axis. The conditions of this strategic location and urban growth have made the area the subject of proposals to accommodate new uses and integrate existing ones. The elimination of perimeter enclosures, the pedestrian interconnection of the existing urban fabric, the proposal for mixed-use public spaces, and the conservation and increase of urban green space have been the key design decisions.  The project is organized based on an analysis of existing natural and built features, pedestrian networks, public and vehicular transport accessibility, social appropriation dynamics, and the political and cultural values and reference points associated with the area. Firstly, the institutional square for citizen gatherings and demonstrations stands out, which in a single strip establishes the link between the future Vallenata Music Cultural Center, the Civic Square of the Flags, and the Government Headquarters building. Secondly, tree-lined paths are established that, in addition to connecting the surrounding streets, integrate century-old trees, water, and existing vegetation, as well as local historical monuments.  Finally, the urban edges of the complex are activated through the strategic location of elements and urban areas for social appropriation: a large pergola that serves as a bus stop and shaded space, a building that serves as a café and public restrooms, a children's play area, gardens, and shaded institutional accesses and parking lots.   The proposed urban design radically opens up the city and democratizes the existing institutional complex, proposing a new system of public and collective spaces that introduces new uses and promotes various forms of social appropriation under accessible, inclusive, and climate-friendly conditions. Just as it reuses and adapts the existing building, it preserves and protects trees of great heritage value. The Government Building, Institutional Square, urban park, pedestrian connections, playgrounds, neighborhood facilities, vegetation, and water now form a unified, open, and climate-adapted complex.   The project establishes a new institutional center, mixed-use and green with high symbolic value compatible with everyday urban life and proximity, a democratic and educational space that educates citizens to take care of their environment, where polycentrism, centrality, urbanity, and biodiversity come together in one place.	The redesign project for the urban complex comprising the Government Square-Park and the Cesar Regional Administration Building in Valledupar (Colombia). This has been an opportunity to propose and create an urban cent