5152c0ba-a559-46b5-b077-840cdcbb7016	Studio Lotus	Media	media@studiolotus.in	Mehrangarh Fort Visitor Centre	IN_PROGRESS	SUBMITTED	SECTION_IV	Jodhpur	India	26.2389	73.0243	Overview Set within the Mehrangarh Fort precinct, the Visitor Centre redefines how we build in heritage contexts. Designed as a modular, dry-assembled system of stone and steel, it treads lightly on the terrain while allowing flexibility for future needs. The project combines artisan-led construction, indigenous materials, and native desert planting to minimise environmental impact. It reclaims civic space for inclusive public use—creating shaded promenades, interpretive landscapes, and culturally embedded architecture. The result is a prototype for sustainable, contextual, and equitable development at world heritage sites.  Project Summary  The design for the extension—a Visitor Centre—attempts to create an architectural system rather than a mere set of buildings, one that is supremely functional, highly contextual to the region and its history, and also ambitious and responsive to the needs of the 21st century.  Jodhpur sits between the hot-arid, and composite climate zones of India, bordering a desert-type climate. Holding global heritage significance, it has served as the capital of the Rathore Rajput Kingdom since 1406 and houses the world-famous Mehrangarh Fort. These monuments, along with the architecture of several thousand local houses, use a local pink sandstone for construction, commonly called choka or balasar. Given the climatic, historic, cultural and architectural context, the project implements a considered stone-based architectural approach, including in its shaping and installation.  Separate entry and exit routes providing expansive Fort views and creating distinct experiences at each point. Retaining a single sunken structure from Mehran Bazaar, a new platform has been added, the elevated structure designed to mitigate the ecological impact of the high visitor footfall—the complex receives over a million visitors a year. The massing develops as a series of pods strategically juxtaposed to guide the circulation of various stakeholders across the platform, creating pockets of space between the existing land and built edges.  In section, the new intervention retains one of the existing sunken structures and builds a new set of structures around it as pods, to fulfil the programmatic requirements. These pods are built such that they can be modified and added on to, as requirements and visitor footfalls to the Fort vary, without requiring any major rework.  The building treads lightly on the ground. The lightness and adaptable nature of its stone and steel structure, while capable of outlasting concrete structures by a factor of 2, if not more, seems to float on the landscape. Quiet yet expressive, strong yet subservient in its humble presence to the permanence and power of the Fort, it expresses a new way of building that is a highly sustainable and sensitive alternative to the inflexible, carbon and material-intensive nature of current standard construction methodologies.  A Systems Approach - A New Way of Building The design takes forward the functional parameters from the brief to be: ● HIGHLY FUNCTIONAL & RESPONSIVE towards the existing context: The scheme identifies modes of design and construction that evolve to meet the visitor centre’s changing needs. Hence, the design objectives are focused on: ● EASE OF CONSTRUCTION at efficient costs ● High Degree of LOCALISATION using both in materiality and craft skills ● FLEXIBILITY/ RE-CONFIGURATION for future, newer uses ● MODULARITY: Could the buildings be altered, expanded or contracted, or even dismantled, with minimum effort and impact?  The metal and stone lattice system of dry construction is a purpose-built structural and construction system allowing a quick and clean process of building that is Flexible, Modular, and Highly Adaptable both during and post-construction. The woven nature of the steel lattice that holds stone slabs and other alternative panels including plasterboard walls, door and window systems, and stone jalis, also allows for easy movement and crossover of services throughout the structure.  The kit-of-parts approach ensures that each stone can be handled by a team of four to five individuals, reducing the need for heavy machinery on site. In their finishing too, traditional methods like bush-hammering have been embraced, avoiding reliance on mechanical equipment. By making the process artisan-led, the project has not only minimised the environmental impact but also provided opportunities for income generation, fostering a sense of craftsmanship and community involvement.	Overview Set within the Mehrangarh Fort precinct, the Visitor Centre redefines how we build in heritage contexts. Designed as a modular, dry-assembled system of stone and steel, it treads lightly on the terrain while allowing flexibility for future needs. The project combines artisan-led construction, indigenous materials, and native desert planting to minimise environmental impact. It reclaims civic space for inclusive public use—creating shaded promenades, interpretive landscapes, and culturally embedded architecture. The result is a prototype for sustainable, contextual, and equitable development at world heritage sites.  Project Summary  The design for the extension—a Visitor Centre—attempts to create an architectural system rather than a mere set of buildings, one that is supremely functional, highly contextual to the region and its history, and also ambitious and responsive to the needs of the 21st century.  Jodhpur sits between the hot-arid, and composite climate zones of India, bordering a desert-type climate. Holding global heritage significance, it has served as the capital of the Rathore Rajput Kingdom since 1406 and houses the world-famous Mehrangarh Fort. These monuments, along with the architecture of several thousand local houses, use a local pink sandstone for construction, commonly called choka or balasar. Given the climatic, historic, cultural and architectural context, the project implements a considered stone-based architectural approach, including in its shaping and installation.  Separate entry and exit routes providing expansive Fort views and creating distinct experiences at each point. Retaining a single sunken structure from Mehran Bazaar, a new platform has been added, the elevated structure designed to mitigate the ecological impact of the high visitor footfall—the complex receives over a million visitors a year. The massing develops as a series of pods strategically juxtaposed to guide the circulation of various stakeholders across the platform, creating pockets of space between the existing land and built edges.  In section, the new intervention retains one of the existing sunken structures and builds a new set of structures around it as pods, to fulfil the programmatic requirements. These pods are built such that they can be modified and added on to, as requirements and visitor footfalls to the Fort vary, without requiring any major rework.  The building treads lightly on the ground. The lightness and adaptable nature of its stone and steel structure, while capable of outlasting concrete structures by a factor of 2, if not more, seems to float on the landscape. Quiet yet expressive, strong yet subservient in its humble presence to the permanence and power of the Fort, it expresses a new way of building that is a highly sustainable and sensitive alternative to the inflexible, carbon and material-intensive nature of current standard construction methodologies.  A Systems Approach - A New Way of Building The design takes forward the functional parameters from the brief to be: ● HIGHLY FUNCTIONAL & RESPONSIVE towards the existing context: The scheme identifies modes of design and construction that evolve to meet the visitor centre’s changing needs. Hence, the design objectives are focused on: ● EASE OF CONSTRUCTION at efficient costs ● High Degree of LOCALISATION using both in materiality and craft skills ● FLEXIBILITY/ RE-CONFIGURATION for future, newer uses ● MODULARITY: Could the buildings be altered, expanded or contracted, or even dismantled, with minimum effort and impact?  The metal and stone lattice system of dry construction is a purpose-built structural and construction system allowing a quick and clean process of building that is Flexible, Modular, and Highly Adaptable both during and post-construction. The woven nature of the steel lattice that holds stone slabs and other alternative panels including plasterboard walls, door and window systems, and stone jalis, also allows for easy movement and crossover of services throughout the structure.  The kit-of-parts approach ensures that each stone can be handled by a team of four to five individuals, reducing the need for heavy machinery on site. In their finishing too, traditional methods like bush-hammering have been embraced, avoiding reliance on mechanical equipment. By making the process artisan-led, the project has not only minimised the environmental impact but also provided opportunities for income generation, fostering a sense of craftsmanship and community involvement.	See detailed description	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-04-18 13:00:00.604992	2026-04-18 13:00:00.604992	P36	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
ba354d6f-16b8-4937-a7fd-2b8040a3dfe2	Lungo Fucile	Unknown	info@lungofucile.com	Ferdi Tayfur Museum and Art Park	IMPLEMENTED	SUBMITTED	SECTION_II	Adana	Turkey	37	35.3213	Ferdi Tayfur Museum and Art Park: A Model for Sustainable Urban Regeneration through Culture  In the heart of Adana, Türkiye, the Ferdi Tayfur Museum and Art Park revitalizes a once-unused municipal plot in Sarıçam District, located alongside a highway and surrounded by unplanned and architecturally low-value developments. Financed by the Sarıçam Municipality, this project demonstrates how an underutilized area can be transformed into a cultural and environmental asset for the community. The development includes a music museum, a public music library, and a café, all embedded within a publicly accessible landscape designed for year-round social interaction and ecological function.  Completed between 2024 and 2025, the project responds to the growing need for inclusive public spaces in rapidly urbanizing areas. Instead of demolishing or replacing what already exists, the design adds value through context-sensitive architectural and landscape interventions. The park offers much-needed breathing space, aiming to reintroduce cultural identity and environmental awareness to an area that has long suffered from lack of planning and public engagement.  The architectural language of the museum and its adjacent structures is intentionally low-rise and open, responding to the local climate, where summer temperatures often exceed 35°C. Semi-open spaces and shaded walkways create naturally ventilated areas for users to gather, rest, or attend events such as the outdoor cinema. These passive climate strategies reduce energy needs and enhance user comfort without relying on mechanical systems.  A strong emphasis on sustainability is reflected throughout the site. The museum roof is equipped with solar panels that generate electricity for the buildings, reducing dependency on external energy sources. Rainwater collected from rooftops and landscape surfaces is reused for irrigation and greywater systems. One of the standout features is the biological pool, which maintains water quality through natural filtration systems without the use of chemicals—offering a model of ecological water management in public landscapes.  The music library and designated workshop areas provide opportunities for creative and educational engagement, especially for children and young people. These spaces are designed to support informal learning, music appreciation, and collaborative activities, making the park not just a recreational destination but also an educational and cultural resource for the city.  The integration of a café, children's playground, and rich landscape design supports a multi-generational user base. Seating areas, green zones, and event spaces are distributed throughout the park to ensure accessibility and comfort for families, the elderly, and people with disabilities. This inclusivity is central to the project’s vision of creating a vibrant, open, and welcoming environment that nurtures community identity.  by providing accessible outdoor spaces that encourage physical and mental wellness.  through its music library and child-focused workshops that foster lifelong learning.  via rainwater harvesting systems and eco-friendly water reuse strategies.  with on-site renewable energy generation through solar panels.  by offering cultural, social, and green spaces that improve urban life.  through passive design, energy efficiency, and climate-responsive planning.  by implementing a biological pond that sustains aquatic life without pollutants.  The Ferdi Tayfur Museum and Art Park stands as a testament to how a modestly scaled, public-sector project can successfully address multiple layers of urban challenge—cultural disconnection, environmental degradation, and lack of community space—within a holistic and sustainable design framework.	Ferdi Tayfur Museum and Art Park: A Model for S