93b96507-3f15-471f-a270-79673277ea20	BELarq Arquitetura	Unknown	duleal@belarq.com.br	AJURUOCA TOURIST, LEISURE AND CULTURAL CENTER - EXTREMA MUNICIPALITY	PLANNED	SUBMITTED	SECTION_V	Extrema	Brazil	-22.8561	-46.319	Located in Extrema, the project serves both locals and sustainable tourism, celebrating the area’s history and nature. Key actions: restoring the space with contemplation areas, a main lake, a small beach, and two building complexes (reception, cafés, restaurants, exhibition spaces, and a memorial). It prioritizes accessibility, native biodiversity, and unique experiences. Aligned with SDGs, it promotes responsible tourism, environmental preservation, social inclusion, and cultural value. Partnerships with local/environmental agencies support sustainable implementation.	Located in Extrema, the project serves both locals and sustainable tourism, celebrating the area’s history and nature. Key actions: restoring the space with contemplation areas, a main lake, a small beach, and two building complexes (reception, cafés, restaurants, exhibition spaces, and a memorial). It prioritizes accessibility, native biodiversity, and unique experiences. Aligned with SDGs, it promotes responsible tourism, environmental preservation, social inclusion, and cultural value. Partnerships with local/environmental agencies support sustainable implementation.	See detailed description	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-04-18 13:00:15.086189	2026-04-18 13:00:15.086189	P83	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
f8ae20bf-86b7-406c-952c-2df5e94a8cd4	Federacion de Colegio de Arquitectos de la República Mexicana	Héctor Alejandro Martínez Gaona	bentanfoussalma@yahoo.com	Belvédère Pool: A Revival of Architecture in the Heart of Nature	IMPLEMENTED	APPROVED	SECTION_III	Tunis	Tunisia	36.819	10.1658	Challenge The Belvédère Pool, an emblematic Art Deco landmark built in 1933 on former tennis grounds and approved in a 1932 urban sports plan, is one of over 400 Art Deco buildings in Tunis—and among its most iconic. Nestled on the edge of the capital’s largest urban park, the pool had been abandoned for decades, its reinforced concrete weakened by natural aging and material fatigue typical of heritage structures from that era. Technical assessments and laboratory testing revealed that 95% of the building no longer met safety, structural, or material standards, prompting the necessary demolition of nearly the entire structure, except for its iconic silhouette.  The core challenge was to dismantle and reconstruct the pool using precise, respectful methods that preserved its architectural soul and original proportions. This included on-site measurements and advanced documentation tools such as 3D laser scanning and point cloud modeling. Other significant challenges included meeting stringent environmental and accessibility requirements—PRM compliance, separate barefoot and shoe-wearing flows—and integrating sustainable infrastructure. The ambitious timeline of only six months intensified these efforts, requiring tight coordination between architects, engineers, artisans, and public institutions throughout summer, weekends and holiday periods.  In the course of extensive research and site investigations, several original decorative elements were identified as missing or significantly altered over the years. This included the elegant Art Deco candelabras that once surrounded the pool and the perimeter fencing, originally composed of reconstituted stone claustras. Archival photographs and surviving fragments on site enabled the design team to accurately reconstruct these features. The perimeter fencing claustras were reimagined using Glass Reinforced Concrete (GRC)—a contemporary material offering both aesthetic fidelity and enhanced durability, thus reviving emblematic details that had long been lost.  Contribution The Belvédère Pool has been reimagined as a fully modern, inclusive, and sustainable civic facility, while remaining faithful to its historic silhouette and spirit. Spanning 8,000 m²—over 40% of which is dedicated green space—the restored site preserves century-old trees and introduces native plant species to boost biodiversity, shade, and air quality. Natural wood pergolas, soft landscape features, and renewed fences with reconstructed claustras reinforce the park’s architectural heritage. The historic columned kiosk was also rebuilt using archival documentation and traditional materials.  The main pool and adjacent wading pool were reconstructed using a “box within a box” structural system, reducing the original 4.48 m depth to a safer 2.1 m. The iconic diving board was preserved and secured with a transparent glass enclosure, balancing historical memory and contemporary safety. Modern filtration and heating systems were discreetly integrated, while the pool deck and terraces were repaved with Gioia variety white Carrara marble from the original quarry. Structural foundations were also laid to accommodate a future full roof, allowing for year-round use.  Accessibility was central to the design, with ramps, PRM-adapted facilities, and clearly separated circulation paths enhancing user safety and comfort. The venue now includes 700 seats and optimized layouts for a wide range of activities. Despite demolishing 95% of the original structure, the project stands as a meticulous and respectful reinterpretation of the original pool—guided by advanced documentation techniques and heritage expertise.  Ultimately, the Belvédère Pool project revives a long-neglected public space as a vibrant, inclusive, and future-ready landmark that honors the architectural, cultural, and environmental legacy of Tunis.	Challenge The Belvédère Pool, an emblematic Art Deco landmark built in 1933 on former tennis grounds and approved in a 1932 urban sports plan, is one of over 400 Art Deco buildings in Tunis—and among its most iconic. Nestled on the edge of the capital’s largest urban park, the pool had been abandoned for decades, its reinforced concrete weakened by natural aging and material fatigue typical of heritage structures from that era. Technical assessments and laboratory testing revealed that 95% of the building no longer met safety, structural, or material standards, prompting the necessary demolition of nearly the entire structure, except for its iconic silhouette.  The core challenge was to dismantle and reconstruct the pool using precise, respectful methods that preserved its architectural soul and original proportions. This included on-site measurements and advanced documentation tools such as 3D laser scanning and point cloud modeling. Other significant challenges included meeting stringent environmental and accessibility requirements—PRM compliance, separate barefoot and shoe-wearing flows—and integrating sustainable infrastructure. The ambitious timeline of only six months intensified these efforts, requiring tight coordination between architects, engineers, artisans, and public institutions throughout summer, weekends and holiday periods.  In the course of extensive research and site investigations, several original decorative elements were identified as missing or significantly altered over the years. This included the elegant Art Deco candelabras that once surrounded the pool and the perimeter fencing, originally composed of reconstituted stone claustras. Archival photographs and surviving fragments on site enabled the design team to accurately reconstruct these features. The perimeter fencing claustras were