nvironmental legacy of Tunis.	See detailed description	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-04-18 13:00:21.972357	2026-04-18 13:00:21.972357	P118	Héctor Alejandro Martínez Gaona	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
af9d1e2c-145e-4dd0-9c55-f8b5106e985d	Weber Thompson	Unknown	rmeyer@weberthompson.com	Northlake Commons Regional Bioswale	IMPLEMENTED	SUBMITTED	SECTION_V	Seattle	United States of America	47.6062	-122.3321	Northlake Commons showcases how innovative design and public-private partnerships can dramatically improve regional water quality and community connectivity. As the first private commercial development in Seattle to host a regional bioswale that treats public stormwater, the project filters 2.6 million gallons of roadway runoff annually before it reaches Lake Union. Through collaboration with Seattle Public Utilities and the Seattle Parks Department, the site integrates stormwater management, pollinator habitat, and a new public park along the Burke-Gilman Trail. This visionary project is transforming industrial land into a thriving, connected, and environmentally restorative community hub.	Northlake Commons showcases how innovative design and public-private partnerships can dramatically improve regional water quality and community connectivity. As the first private commercial development in Seattle to host a regional bioswale that treats public stormwater, the project filters 2.6 million gallons of roadway runoff annually before it reaches Lake Union. Through collaboration with Seattle Public Utilities and the Seattle Parks Department, the site integrates stormwater management, pollinator habitat, and a new public park along the Burke-Gilman Trail. This visionary project is transforming industrial land into a thriving, connected, and environmentally restorative community hub.	See detailed description	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-04-18 13:00:15.086189	2026-04-18 13:00:15.086189	P78	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
1d60cb23-3ec9-4e8c-9f5e-f19634712c38	MSA University	Unknown	melsaeed@msa.edu.eg	Tawheed/ Layers	PLANNED	SUBMITTED	SECTION_III	6th of October City	Egypt	29.0331	30.9694	proposal1: The study proposes a mathematically retrofitting pavilion system for Cairo's heritage retail corridors, transforming chaotic street geometries into regulated, human-scaled, shading-optimized, and modular pavilion inserts. The design approach is inspired by Islamic geometry, mathematical optimization, and leaf structures, with folded plates in perforated triangular modules. The system combines stochastic generation and constraint satisfaction, working like a multi-objective optimization problem. The mashrabiya serves as an inspiration for enhancing natural ventilation, light control, interior comfort, and reflecting cultural identity. The system supports sustainability by utilizing local materials and reflects cultural identity through decorative patterns. Proposal2: The proposal proposes using coral reefs as a material inspiration and formal strategy for designing lightweight, sustainable, and climatically responsive shading structures for street vendors in El-Quseer, a historic coastal town. The design addresses challenges such as lack of structured vending zones, underutilized public spaces, climate overexposure, and visual disharmony. The proposal also suggests using coral reefs in architecture to tackle sustainability and employ mathematical logic.	proposal1: The study proposes a mathematically retrofitting pavilion system for Cairo's heritage retail corridors, transforming chaotic street geometries into regulated, human-scaled, shading-optimized, and modular pavilion inserts. The design approach is inspired by Islamic geometry, mathematical optimization, and leaf structures, with folded plates in perforated triangular modules. The system combines stochastic generation and constraint satisfaction, working like a multi-objective optimization problem. The mashrabiya serves as an inspiration for enhancing natural ventilation, light control, interior comfort, and reflecting cultural identity. The system supports sustainability by utilizing local materials and reflects cultural identity through decorative patterns. Proposal2: The proposal proposes using coral reefs as a material inspiration and formal strategy for designing lightweight, sustainable, and climatically responsive shading structures for street vendors in El-Quseer, a historic coastal town. The design addresses challenges such as lack of structured vending zones, underutilized public spaces, climate overexposure, and visual disharmony. The proposal also suggests using coral reefs in architecture to tackle sustainability and employ mathematical logic.	See detailed description	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-04-18 13:00:00.604992	2026-04-18 13:00:00.604992	P29	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
d1f1c63b-a07a-4151-9c5a-46bfd2b0f896	In Situ Architecture	Unknown	f.quandt@insitu.ch	Lagerplatz Winterthur, Kopfbau Halle 118	IMPLEMENTED	SUBMITTED	SECTION_I	Winterthur	Switzerland	47.4994	8.7243	The Lagerplatz in Winterthur, once an industrial site of Sulzer AG, has transformed into a vibrant urban quarter. In 2010, the Stiftung Abendrot acquired the site and, together with Denkstatt Sàrl, initiated a participatory, sustainable redevelopment. A flagship project is K.118, designed by baubüro in situ: an upward extension built almost entirely from reused materials such as steel, timber, straw, and clay. Prioritizing circular construction and low embodied energy, the project reduced greenhouse gas emissions by 60% and saved 500 tons of primary resources – a pioneering model of regenerative architecture.	The Lagerplatz in Winterthur, once an industrial site of Sulzer AG, has transformed into a vibrant urban quarter. In 2010, the Stiftung Abendrot acquired the site and, together with Denkstatt Sàrl, initiated a participatory, sustainable redevelopment. A flagship project is K.118, designed by baubüro in situ: an upward extension built almost entirely from reused materials such as steel, timber, straw, and clay. Prioritizing circular construction and low embodied energy, the project reduced greenhouse gas emissions by 60% and saved 500 tons of primary resources – a pioneering model of regenerative architecture.	See detailed description	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-04-18 13:00:08.127452	2026-04-18 13:00:08.127452	P56	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
a944b116-a2e9-4953-8837-7d72100538f9	Zabriskie Studio	Unknown	milena.katic@zabriskie.rs	InGrid Schneider Electric Hub - Transformation of the Novkabel Factory Industrial Hall	IMPLEMENTED	SUBMITTED	SECTION_II	Novi Sad	Serbia	45.2671	19.8335	The InGrid Schneider Electric Hub project transforms part of the Novkabel factory complex through reconstruction and adaptive reuse. This project repurposed a former industrial hall into a carbon-neutral, LEED Platinum-certified modern office building for Schneider Electric, establishing it as a future tech hub. This initiative marks a key step in converting an industrial zone into a mixed-use neighborhood.  Although the production halls of Novkabel have negligible architectural value, the first one was decided to be treated as a monument, a reminder raising awareness of the times when Novkabel was leading the prosperous domestic industry.  High standards in working conditions from the period when Novkabel was a symbol of the city of Novi Sad, inspired us to design a space where those at work could coexist with green space and nature, ensuring a high-quality environment for workers today. Maintaining the continuity of values was one of our most important tasks.  Novkabel was a 20th century socially sanctified industrial giant and a symbol of the city of Novi Sad, second largest city in Serbia. It consciously invested not only in raising the quality of working and living conditions of its employees but also worked for the benefit of the entire community.  Novkabel built positive and strong connections in the minds of residents, creating a strong sense of identity. The absence of utilitarian functions and programs in the last three decades, after the fall of former Yougoslavia, caused a gradual degradation of the space of the complex - with all its immanent values decomposed, remaining alive only in the collective memory of older generations.  Novkabel production hall has been transformed to fit a purpose in today’s world, preserving it in a way that the history and the values it stood for are transmitted to future generations. It refers to its built and natural context, and bonds with nature, by making new green ambiences part of it, ensuring a high-quality environment for workers today.  The existing greenery was treated as an unusual, large start-up capital and it was planned to be emphasized, preserved and enriched. This is why the project focused on creating new open courtyards internally and introducing 600 square metres of additional floor area through new “floating” mezzanine levels. The entire functional organization stems from the concept of incorporating greenery, translucence, natural ventilation and light into the working space, so the place can be healthy and comfortable for the users. The middle space of the hall remained open along the entire height and void of any specific function, to serve as an inner square in terms of space and functionality, offering high quality collective gathering space. 11.000 m² of ground floor base with additional 6.000 m² of floating galleries and almost 1.000 m² of green spaces accomplished inside the structure itself made it possible to design an office building with the uncharacteristic typology – a small town in just two levels with great diversity of interior ambiances, allowing for an easy orientation in space with lines of movement that offer frequent meeting opportunities, interaction and information exchange with great flexibility of working spaces. An enhanced opportunity to create a community of employees is made possible by a large common gathering space. The project integrates responsible land use planning, preserves the natural and built environment, and minimizes carbon emissions in production and ongoing use.  It was transformed without occupying more unbuilt areas, but with creating new open areas inside.  It has prioritized environmental benefits in its built and natural context. It is carbon neutral, and LEED Platinum certified, using only renewable sources of energy. It is setting a way for an old industrial zone to transform into vibrant mixed-use neighborhood.	The InGrid Schneider Electric Hub project transforms part of the Novkabel factory complex through reconstruction and adaptive reuse. This project repurposed a former industrial hall into a carbon-neutral, LEED Platinum-certified modern office building for Schneider Electric, establishing it as a future tech hub. This initiative marks a key step in converting an industrial zone into a mixed-use neighborhood.  Although the production halls of Novkabel have negligible architectural value, the first one was decided to be treated as a monument, a reminder raising awareness of the times when Novkabel was leading the prosperous domestic industry.  High standards in working conditions from the period when Novkabel was a symbol of the city of Novi Sad, inspired us to design a space where those at work could coexist with green space and nature, ensuring a high-quality environment for workers today. Maintaining the continuity of values was one of our most important tasks.  Novkabel was a 20th century socially sanctified industrial giant and a symbol of the city of Novi Sad, second largest city in Serbia. It consciously invested not only in raising the quality of working and living conditions of its employees but also worked for the benefit of the entire community.  Novkabel built positive and strong connections in the minds of residents, creating a strong sense of identity. The absence of utilitarian functions and programs in the last three decades, after the fall of former Yougoslavia, caused a gradual degradation of the space of the complex - with all its immanent values decomposed, remaining alive only in the collective memory of older generations.  Novkabel production hall has been transformed to fit a purpose in today’s world, preserving it in a way that the history and the values it stood for are transmitted to future generations. It re