9e983601-2072-461d-968d-076031c24461	VSPB Associates	Unknown	contact@vspbassociates.com	REDEVELOPMENT OF DULIYAN GANGA RAILWAY STATION -- A Sustainable Civic Landmark at the Rural-Urban Interface	IN_PROGRESS	SUBMITTED	SECTION_IV	Dhuliyan	India	24.6833	87.9333	The redevelopment of Dhuliyan Ganga Railway Station forms a part of the modernization initiatives of the Indian Railways. Yet, the project carries a greater significance here. More than just a transit facility, the new station is poised to become the most prominent public building and de facto civic landmark in a town that lacks meaningful architectural references. It will serve as a vital shared public space, supporting the everyday mobility of diverse user groups.  Located in Murshidabad district of West Bengal, Dhuliyan occupies a politically and geographically strategic position. It sits near both the international border with Bangladesh and the inter-state boundary with Jharkhand, at the point where the Ganges divides into the Padma and the Bhagirathi rivers. The Railway Station functions as a crucial transport node in this borderland setting.  Dhuliyan, a municipal town with an estimated population around 130,000 in 2023, is surrounded by eight Census Towns and several villages that collectively form a larger agglomeration. The railway station serves as the primary economic and mobility node in this typical Indian rural-urban transition zone that is marked by low incomes, limited upward mobility, and a large informal workforce. The railway system offers the most accessible and affordable means of travel for work, healthcare, trade, and social reasons here. Despite its modest NSG-5 classification, the station is among the top 100 in India for passenger volume and bookings, underscoring its critical role in everyday life.  The redevelopment vision is shaped by several key goals: to reclaim the station as an urban asset; to transform it into a civic landmark with upgraded, world-class amenities; to reflect the cultural and material specificity of the region through design; to ensure inclusive, barrier-free access for all users; and to embed environmental sustainability through holistic, climate-responsive strategies.  The architectural vocabulary draws inspiration from regional specificity and contemporary aspiration while addressing the practical requirements of a high-footfall, low-maintenance public building. A unique design feature used here is the ‘Green Concourse’, a first-of-its-kind space in Indian Railways, that combines a covered and open-to-sky feel in a public space, welcomes natural light and ventilation while minimizing energy consumption, and provides opportunities to grow plants to add colour and vibrancy.   The Gangetic plain, the larger context of the project, is known for the tradition of brick manufacturing. The material choices, thus, reinforce the regional identity and environmental sensibility of the project. Crafted terracotta screen (jaali) serves as passive cooling device that filters sunlight and allows cross-ventilation of the river breeze. Their modular design helps quality control too. The use of terracotta cladding, tensile membrane roofing, and light steel structures keeps the building low-carbon and cost-effective.  Accessibility has been carefully embedded into the planning and design. Walkability is prioritized even in the vehicular access zones to ensure safe, barrier-free movement with universal design standards, while signage throughout the station is clear and multi-lingual. All counters and information desks include lowered sections for wheelchair users. Seating areas are distributed at regular intervals across platforms and waiting zones to cater to those with limited mobility.   The Dhuliyan Ganga Railway Station Redevelopment represents a sustainable, inclusive, and locally rooted project in India’s rural-urban interface that reimagines public infrastructure as a space of pride, connectivity, and possibility.	The redevelopment