9ee65bc4-738f-4254-afed-607d068d2b9d	Unknown	Unknown	mharchitects.eg@gmail.com	Dr. Mohamed Hendawi	PLANNED	SUBMITTED	SECTION_III	New Administrative Capital	Egypt	30.02	31.8	Visionary Design by Dr. Mohamed Hendawi & MH Architects Purposeful Eco-Friendly Architecture Architect Dr. Mohamed Hendawi and his talented team at MH Architects have crafted Helios Health Park as a model of eco-friendly, biophilic design. Their mission is to:  Enhance users’ well-being  Elevate Egypt’s built environment  Apply the UN Sustainable Development Goals (SDGs) to urban design  Address critical challenges in contemporary man-made environments  Biophilic Design: Reconnecting People with Nature Recognizing a gap in Egypt’s current architectural landscape, the design team embraced the biophilic design concept—a philosophy that connects humans with nature. This approach directly supports UN SDG Goal 11: Sustainable Cities and Communities, aiming to make cities more inclusive, resilient, and environmentally harmonious.  Reducing Stress in Medical Environments A key focus of Helios Health Park is to reduce user stress, especially for those visiting medical facilities. The design achieves this by:  Providing outdoor waiting spaces surrounded by greenery  Creating pleasant indoor waiting areas filled with natural daylight and, where possible, natural ventilation  Incorporating large terraces and vegetated outdoor zones for relaxation and social interaction  Functional and User-Centric Spaces Ground & First Floors:  Dedicated to food and beverage outlets  Feature outdoor social gathering and dining areas tailored to user behaviors  Large terraces on the first floor connect with the ground floor’s KIA fish tank, offering a unique environment for enjoying nature and socializing  Second Floor:  Designed for kids’ areas and beauty salons, catering to families and personal care needs  Upper Floors:  Divided into two wings/buildings, interconnected by expansive outdoor waiting areas filled with vegetation, art installations, and juice bars  Each wing features hanging gardens and large vegetated terraces as part of the outdoor social gathering and waiting zones Helios Health Park is designed to effectively reduce heat gain and sunlight glare in Egypt’s arid climate through the use of artistic shaded devices integrated into its architecture. These shading elements serve multiple purposes: they protect interior and exterior spaces from excessive solar radiation, thereby lowering indoor temperatures and minimizing glare, while also adding aesthetic value to the building’s facade. This approach aligns with the principles of biophilic and sustainable design by enhancing occupant comfort and reducing reliance on mechanical cooling systems, which is crucial in hot, dry environments like Egypt. The building’s facade incorporates decorative screens and panels that create intricate patterns, providing shading that filters harsh sunlight without completely blocking natural daylight. This balance ensures well-lit interiors that avoid the discomfort and energy waste associated with direct sun exposure. Additionally, the tiered structure with balconies and terraces adorned with vegetation further contributes to shading and cooling by creating microclimates and reducing heat absorption on building surfaces  Enhancing Social Interaction and Well-being Every aspect of Helios Health Park is designed to foster positive social interactions and create uplifting experiences. The integration of nature, art, and communal spaces provides users with opportunities to relax, connect, and enjoy their surroundings—making visits to the facility less stressful and more enjoyable.  A New Benchmark for Egyptian Architecture Helios Health Park stands as a pioneering example of how thoughtful, sustainable design can transform urban environments and improve quality of life. By prioritizing well-being, community, and a strong connection to nature, Dr. Mohamed Hendawi and MH Architects are setting a new standard for the future of Egypt’s built environment.	Visionary Design by Dr. Mohamed Hendawi & MH Architects Purposeful Eco-Friendly Architecture Architect Dr. Mohamed Hendawi and his talented team at MH Architects have crafted Helios Health Park as a model of eco-friendly, biophilic design. Their mission is to:  Enhance users’ well-being  Elevate Egypt’s built environment  Apply the UN Sustainable Development Goals (SDGs) to urban design  Address critical challenges in contemporary man-made environments  Biophilic Design: Reconnecting People with Nature Recognizing a gap in Egypt’s current architectural landscape, the design team embraced the biophilic design concept—a philosophy that connects humans with nature. This approach directly supports UN SDG Goal 11: Sustainable Cities and Communities, aiming to make cities more inclusive, resilient, and environmentally harmonious.  Reducing Stress in Medical Environments A key focus of Helios Health Park is to reduce user stress, especially for those visiting medical facilities. The design achieves this by:  Providing outdoor waiting spaces surrounded by greenery  Creating pleasant indoor waiting areas filled with natural daylight and, where possible, natural ventilation  Incorporating large terraces and vegetated outdoor zones for relaxation and social interaction  Functional and User-Centric Spaces Ground & First Floors:  Dedicated to food and beverage outlets  Feature outdoor social gathering and dining areas tailored to user behaviors  Large terraces on the first floor connect with the ground floor’s KIA fish tank, offering a unique environment for enjoying nature and socializing  Second Floor:  Designed for kids’ areas and beauty salons, catering to families and personal care needs  Upper Floors:  Divided into two wings/buildings, interconnected by expansive outdoor waiting areas filled with vegetation, art installations, and juice bars  Each wing features hanging gardens and large vegetated terraces as part of 