dc105329-c4f3-4a22-9b71-faab593fa0ad	Natureza Urbana	Breno	breno@naturezaurbana.net	Capivari Park	IMPLEMENTED	SUBMITTED	SECTION_V	Campos do Jordão	Brazil	-22.7394	-45.5889	Located in the tourist center of Campos do Jordão, Capivari Park was revitalized to enhance public space, connect with the neighborhood, and attract a broader audience. The central area was opened for gatherings and events, while new buildings were positioned along the perimeter, respecting the topography and ensuring smooth transitions with the city. Linear elements in furniture and façades reference the site’s railway heritage, and diverse planting compositions create varied landscape scenes. Implemented in phases, the project improved access, parking, and infrastructure, fostering tourism integrated with the natural setting.	Located in the tourist center of Campos do Jordão, Capivari Park was revitalized to enhance public space, connect with the neighborhood, and attract a broader audience. The central area was opened for gatherings and events, while new buildings were positioned along the perimeter, respecting the topography and ensuring smooth transitions with the city. Linear elements in furniture and façades reference the site’s railway heritage, and diverse planting compositions create varied landscape scenes. Implemented in phases, the project improved access, parking, and infrastructure, fostering tourism integrated with the natural setting.	See detailed description	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-04-18 12:59:53.078529	2026-04-18 12:59:53.078529	P9	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
4c4a5390-2a24-4b5b-80d8-1baad9b4f5cb	Círculo Cuadrado	Unknown	serranoplus@circulocuadrado.com.mx	Congreso del Estado de Puebla	IMPLEMENTED	SUBMITTED	SECTION_V	Puebla	Mexico	19.0413	-98.2062	The new State Congress of Puebla integrates iconic architecture into the natural and historical setting. Built from 2023 to 2024, its sustainable design includes green roofs covering 59.92% of the surface, permeable areas, and energy-efficient strategies. The building’s L-shaped configuration adapts to the topography, housing legislative spaces, an auditorium, and a central atrium. Public art, recycled materials, and native landscaping reinforce environmental and cultural identity. The project revitalized a marginalized neighborhood, restored public space, and created inclusive areas for community use. A mural by José Lazcarro marks the entrance, honoring “The Battle of Puebla.”	The new State Congress of Puebla integrates iconic architecture into the natural and historical setting. Built from 2023 to 2024, its sustainable design includes green roofs covering 59.92% of the surface, permeable areas, and energy-efficient strategies. The building’s L-shaped configuration adapts to the topography, housing legislative spaces, an auditorium, and a central atrium. Public art, recycled materials, and native landscaping reinforce environmental and cultural identity. The project revitalized a marginalized neighborhood, restored public space, and created inclusive areas for community use. A mural by José Lazcarro marks the entrance, honoring “The Battle of Puebla.”	See detailed description	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-04-18 12:59:53.078529	2026-04-18 12:59:53.078529	P18	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
b86abfe5-cb96-4b5f-8014-033d90521063	Unknown	Unknown	shaimaa.fayed@gmail.com	The path	PLANNED	SUBMITTED	SECTION_III	Cairo	Egypt	30.0444	31.2357	This project, sited in El Fustat, Cairo, reclaims a transitional urban void adjoining the historic Aqueduct—a monumental remnant of the Fatimid city—as a catalyst for cultural revitalization and sustainable housing. Conceived as a living gateway to the city’s new urban spine, the mixed-use housing complex is designed to host not only residents but also traditional artisans, reviving local crafts and reinforcing a collective cultural memory.  Copper craftsmanship, a vanishing tradition in Egypt, serves as the thematic and functional core of the project. Historically used in Islamic architecture and domestic life, copper work has seen a steep decline with the advent of modern materials. This project integrates copper artisanship spatially and economically—through dedicated studios, market spaces, and living units—thus ensuring its transmission, adaptation, and visibility in the 21st century.  The design prioritizes inclusive and participatory processes. Local craftspeople, urban historians, and residents were engaged in co-design sessions to identify spatial needs and cultural aspirations. The resulting architecture is a synthesis of modern modularity and traditional morphology—narrow passages, shaded courtyards, and adaptable units—promoting thermal comfort and social interaction.  Environmental sustainability is embedded through the use of passive ventilation, natural lighting, water reuse systems, and local low-impact materials. Green roofs and shaded corridors mitigate urban heat, while flexible unit layouts adapt to changing family needs. The project not only minimizes ecological impact but also promotes socio-cultural resilience.  Civic functions are distributed at the ground level, including workshops, a cultural archive, and a marketplace—blurring the boundary between public and private, resident and visitor. The public realm is conceived as an open museum of making, where craft processes unfold in real time, reconnecting locals and visitors with the living traditions of Cairo.  In essence, this project is a contemporary reweaving of tradition and innovation. It is not merely a housing scheme, but a regenerative model that reconciles past and future, crafts and cities, people and place.	This project, sited in El Fustat, Cairo, reclaims a transitional urban void adjoining the historic Aqueduct—a monumental remnant of the Fatimid city—as a catalyst for cultural revitalization and sustainable housing. Conceived as a living gateway to the city’s new urban spine, the mixed-use housing complex is designed to host not only residents but also traditional artisans, reviving local crafts and reinforcing a collective cultural memory.  Copper craftsmanship, a vanishing tradition in Egypt, serves as the thematic and functional core of the project. Historically used in Islamic architecture and domestic life, copper work has seen a steep decline with the advent of modern materials. This project integrates copper artisanship spatially and economically—through dedicated studios, market spaces, and living units—thus ensuring its transmission, adaptation, and visibility in the 21st century.  The design prioritizes inclusive and participatory processes. Local craftspeople, urban historians, and residents were engaged in co-design sessions to identify spatial needs and cultural aspirations. The resulting architecture is a synthesis of modern modularity and traditional morphology—narrow passages, shaded courtyards, and adaptable units—promoting thermal comfort and social interaction.  Environmental sustainability is embedded through the use of passive ventilation, natural lighting, water reuse systems, and local low-impact materials. Green roofs and shaded corridors mitigate urban heat, while flexible unit layouts adapt to changing family needs. The project not only minimizes ecological impact but also promotes socio-cultural resilience.  Civic functions are distributed at the ground level, including workshops, a cultural archive, and a marketplace—blurring the boundary between public and private, resident and visitor. The public realm is conceived as an open museum of making, where craft processes unfold in real time, reconnecting locals and visitors with the living traditions of Cairo.  In essence, this project is a contemporary reweaving of tradition and innovation. It is not merely a housing scheme, but a regenerative model that reconciles past and future, crafts and cities, people and place.	See detailed description	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-04-18 13:00:31.097334	2026-04-18 13:00:31.097334	P144	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
7571fc98-47ff-4d5c-abba-6751a6704a02	Pieris.Architects, Eirini I. Michail, IT KV CONSULTING ENGINEERS, Ecoscapes Landscape Architecture, NeaPolis Lighting, Vector	Constantinos Pieris, Stella Pieri, Pieros Pieris, Nadia Lazaridou, Lydia Sklavou, Evi Katsikoudi	info@pierisarchitects.com	Urban Forest Residence	IN_PROGRESS	APPROVED	SECTION_I	Kifissia	Greece	38.0745	23.8156	Tucked into the quiet, green enclave of Kefalari in Northern Athens, the “Urban Forest” Residence represents a thoughtful fusion of architecture, ecology, and well-being. This private residence isn’t merely a building—it is an experience rooted in sustainability and emotional connection to place. It demonstrates how a home can serve not only as a shelter but also as a sanctuary that nurtures the body, calms the mind, and respects the land it stands on. At the heart of the project is a deep respect for the existing forested environment. Mature trees were preserved and protected during the design and construction process, becoming a natural perimeter that offers both shade and privacy. Rather than altering the terrain, the architecture folds itself into the site’s contours. This approach reflects a light-touch philosophy, minimizing disturbance to the natural systems while enhancing the biodiversity of the site through careful landscape interventions by Ecoscapes Landscape Architecture. The residence’s name—Urban Forest—is more than metaphor. It speaks to a design ethos that aims to restore ecological balance in an urban context, supporting SDG 15: Life on Land. The outdoor environment is enriched with native and aromatic plants such as lavender, rosemary, and olive trees, which attract pollinators, support soil health, and create a sensory connection with the Mediterranean landscape. The architectural language is informed by Scandinavian design principles and the Danish concept of hygge—a philosophy centered on simplicity, contentment, and well-being. The interior spaces are warm, tactile, and filled with natural materials. Light wood, soft textiles, and indirect lighting by NeaPolis Lighting create a subtle, calming ambiance that supports mental wellness. This emphasis on atmosphere and emotional well-being directly supports SDG 3: Good Health and Well-Being by promoting spaces that foster calm, rest, and happiness. Large openings, expansive windows, and sliding doors dissolve the boundary between interior and exterior, allowing for natural ventilation, daylight, and immersive views. The garden, pool, and outdoor lounge areas become seamless extensions of the living space. These spatial strategies not only enhance comfort but also reduce reliance on mechanical systems, reinforcing SDG 13: Climate Action. From a performance standpoint, the building integrates passive design strategies with modern technology. The structure—engineered by Eirini I. Michail—is optimized for insulation and structural integrity, while the mechanical systems provided by IT KV Consulting Engineers prioritize energy efficiency. The home is equipped with solar panels and high-efficiency HVAC, and its envelope is designed to minimize thermal losses. These features represent a commitment to SDG 9: Industry, Innovation, and Infrastructure, proving that innovation in building technologies can coexist with minimalism and aesthetic sensitivity. The project also illustrates how low-density residential architecture can still contribute meaningfully to urban sustainability. Instead of isolating itself from its surroundings or overdeveloping the site, the residence becomes an example of context-sensitive planning. By maintaining a small footprint and prioritizing green space, it supports SDG 11: Sustainable Cities and Communities, encouraging a model of suburban development that is integrated with nature rather than separate from it. Construction practices further reflect environmental responsibility. Locally sourced materials, durable finishes, and low-waste building methods are prioritized. The home's compact yet generous design minimizes embodied energy, while its operational systems are designed for long-term efficiency and resilience. Even in areas such as lighting, the design team sought energy-conscious solutions that still evoke a sense of domestic warmth and elegance. But perhaps what defines the “Urban Forest” Residence most clearly is its emotional quality. This is a place where architecture does not dominate, but recedes—where daily rituals like reading by the window, enjoying coffee in the morning light, or listening to cicadas in the garden become experiences of quiet joy. It reflects a new paradigm of luxury that is rooted not in excess, but in mindfulness, connection, and care. As the world continues to reckon with environmental degradation and the mental strain of fast-paced urban life, projects like this one show how residential architecture can be part of the solution. By creating spaces that are environmentally responsible, emotionally nurturing, and technically forward-looking, the “Urban Forest” Residence offers a gentle yet powerful blueprint for how we might live more harmoniously—with nature, with others, and with ourselves.	Tucked into the quiet, green enclave of Kefalari in Northern Athens, the “Urban Forest” Residence represents a thoughtful fusion of architecture, ecology, and well-being. This private residence isn’t merely a building—it is an experience rooted in sustainability and emotional connection to place. It demonstrates how a home can serve not only as a shelter but also as a sanctuary that nurtures the body, calms the mind, and respects the land it stands on. At the heart of the project is a deep respect for the existing forested environment. Mature trees were preserved and protected during the design and construction process, becoming a natural perimeter that offers both shade and privacy. Rather than altering the terrain, the architecture folds itself into the site’s contours. This approach reflects a light-touch philos