12dc64eb-030e-4982-8559-01c7040f8dbf	EMARA Architecture and Urbanism	Shiekh Intekhab Alam	emaraarchitects@gmail.com	ASHRAY REC Foundation Old Age Home	IMPLEMENTED	APPROVED	SECTION_IV	Leh	India	34.160889	77.581696	A community village for the elderly with Shelter Services – Modular, comprehensive & elder-friendly, also envisaged as a Wellness, Geriatric health care center, and day-care center, designed keeping in mind the vulnerability of the cold desert region as well the comfort of the people, especially during winters.	The special feature of the project is its use of indigenous technique of construction, the project takes help from local craftsmanship and wisdom not only at the building level but also at the Masterplan level, the site as a resultant is a secure habitat for old age people, the building designed by ‘rammed earth’ mixed with concrete balancing strength with insulation keeping in mind the low temperature & harsh winters of the cold desert region. Solarised walls, especially for bathrooms (“Tombe” walls), which have specially insulated & south facing walls for sunshine which prevents the freezing of water from the tank to the pipe outlet. The landscape allows for a certain kind of local feel to the built environment.	Old age home at shey, Ladakh is envisaged as a small village for old age people who either have been abandoned by their own family or have no one to take care, the land for the site was donated by the local politician after the 2014 flash flood in Ladakh. Sustainability here is not a choice but a way of life, the learnings from traditional wisdom and local craftsmen has helped make the project an all year habitable space. The temperature at site varies from +30 Degree to -30 Degree, the design hence is a affordable, low maintenance, energy efficient model for the entire region. It promotes well being for elderly but also provides wisdom to the young.	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	LDP3	Shiekh Intekhab Alam (Architect), Nazir Din (Engineer), Amrita Kaur Slatch	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
6c1bb930-2202-45c2-99ac-0f933a4247ac	Pieris Architects	Unknown	info@pierisarchitects.com	Viva Wallet HQ	IMPLEMENTED	SUBMITTED	SECTION_I	Athens	Greece	37.9838	23.7275	The Viva Wallet Headquarters in Marousi, Athens, is a landmark project that reimagines the modern workplace through a deep integration of sustainability, biophilic design, and adaptability to digital-era work culture. Designed by Pieris.Architects and completed in 2023, the 7,600 m² twin-building complex underwent a full refurbishment to serve as Viva Wallet’s European base. As a fintech operating across 24 countries, the company required a headquarters that reflects its innovation-driven ethos while providing a high-performance, emotionally responsive environment for over 450 employees. The design prioritizes flexibility, wellness, and ecological consciousness. At its core is a central atrium that brings natural light into the heart of the building, enhancing orientation, connection, and visual comfort. The spatial layout responds to the needs of a hybrid workforce, offering a diverse mix of zones that support collaboration, deep focus, and informal interaction. From brainstorming “caves” and communal lounges to quiet retreat areas and a rooftop terrace, the environment supports autonomy, creativity, and productivity across different workstyles. Social and professional areas are designed to adapt fluidly to events, meetings, or moments of rest, reinforcing a sense of participation and inclusion. Well-being is embedded throug the architectural experience. Amenities such as a gym, daycare, rooftop café, and the Code Bites restaurant curated by chef Leonidas Koutsopoulos offer physical and emotional support for daily routines. The design supports mental health through quiet zones, adaptable furnishings, and biophilic principles that reduce cognitive fatigue. The inclusion of 2,234 Mediterranean plants from 35 species—including olive, lavender, thyme, and almond—not only improves indoor air quality but also enhances psychological comfort. The greenery is not ornamental but structural, transforming the atrium and rooftop into living ecosystems that connect occupants with the rhythms of nature. Technological resilience and adaptability are key aspects of the project. As a fintech hub, the building integrates robust digital infrastructure and security, while its modular design allows for future spatial reconfiguration. The architecture encourages innovation through openness and layered transparency, supporting both focused work and cross-disciplinary interaction. The atrium acts as a social condenser, enabling spontaneous collaboration while organizing circulation and light. Sustainability is addressed through passive environmental strategies such as natural ventilation, thermal massing, and daylight optimization, all contributing to a reduced energy footprint. Materials are thoughtfully selected for their regional origin and low environmental impact, including stone, timber, and natural textiles. Vertical gardens and a planted roof mitigate the urban heat island effect, improve stormwater management, and enhance insulation. These features demonstrate how commercial buildings can contribute to climate resilience while maintaining comfort and efficiency. The project also restores ecological value within the urban context. By incorporating native and adaptive plant species that support pollinators and biodiversity, the building becomes a regenerative agent rather than a neutral structure. The rooftop garden and vertical planting blur the line between building and landscape, positioning the headquarters as both a workplace and an urban habitat. The Viva Wallet Headquarters is a spatial manifestation of the company’s values: progressive, inclusive, sustainable, and attuned to the evolving nature of work. It contributes meaningfully to the United Nations Sustainable Development Goals, specifically SDGs 3, 8, 9, 13, and 15, by promoting health and well-being, enabling decent and inclusive work, supporting infrastructure for innovation, addressing climate impact, and fostering life on land. In doing so, it sets a new benchmark for what corporate architecture can achieve—blending technical sophistication with human-centric principles to create a workplace ecosystem that is both regenerative and future-ready.	The Viva Wallet Headquarters in Marousi, Athens, is a landmark project that reimagines the modern workplace through a deep integration of sustainability, biophilic design, and adaptability to digital-era work culture. Designed by Pieris.Architects and completed in 2023, the 7,600 m² twin-building complex underwent a full refurbishment to serve as Viva Wallet’s European base. As a fintech operating across 24 countries, the company required a headquarters that reflects its innovation-driven ethos while providing a high-performance, emotionally responsive environment for over 450 employees. The design prioritizes flexibility, wellness, and ecological consciousness. At its core is a central atrium that brings natural light into the heart of the building, enhancing orientation, connection, and visual comfort. The spatial layout responds to the needs of a hybrid workforce, offering a diverse mix of zones that support collaboration, deep focus, and informal interaction. From brainstorming “caves” and communal lounges to quiet retreat areas and a rooftop terrace, the environment supports autonomy, creativity, and productivity across different workstyles. Social and professional areas are designed to adapt fluidly to events, meetings, or moments of rest, reinforcing a sense of participation and inclusion. Well-being is embedded throug the architectural experience. Amenities such as a gym, daycare, rooftop café, and the Code Bites restaurant curated by chef Leonidas Koutsopoulos offer physical and emotional support for daily routines. The design supports mental health through quiet zones, adaptable furnishings, and biophilic principles that red