It contributes meaningfully to the United Nations Sustainable Development Goals, specifically SDGs 3, 8, 9, 13, and 15, by promoting health and well-being, enabling decent and inclusive work, supporting infrastructure for innovation, addressing climate impact, and fostering life on land. In doing so, it sets a new benchmark for what corporate architecture can achieve—blending technical sophistication with human-centric principles to create a workplace ecosystem that is both regenerative and future-ready.	See detailed description	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-04-18 13:00:39.923528	2026-04-18 13:00:39.923528	P169	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
7d75113a-5a2c-41b0-adaa-7b499b4f1b6c	#1 individual (dead) painter #2: Individual architect	Paolo Caroli	P.Caroli@archiworld.it	the Common Good	IMPLEMENTED	APPROVED	SECTION_I	Pisa	Italy	43.718811	10.398847	Rules for a sustainable future: an analogy between the 1338AD ‘Allegory of Good and Bad Government’ fresco and the UN 2030AD Agenda	ENCYCLOPEDIA GALACTICA*:\r\n“Both the 1338AD fresco called ‘Allegory of the good government’ and the UN 2030AD Agenda, declined into 17 goals, are prehistorical documents showing some attempts to stop or at least curb the destructive drift of the terrestrial society before its own collapse.”\r\n\r\n* All quotations from the Encyclopedia Galactica here reproduced are taken from the 116th Edition published in 1020 F.E. by the Encyclopedia Galactica Publishing Co., Terminus, with permission of the publishers.	Most of the human needs can be satisfied only by living in Communities. With the growth (read globalization) of its dimensions, we forgot that the very base of a Community is the shared concept of Common Good.\r\nThe ‘Allegory’ anticipates and includes all the SDGs (as indicated in the attached images), and shows how they were ruled in the small but organized Siena around the 1338AD.\r\nThe city itself, with all his private and public architectures, is a common good as the house of the Community.	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	IFF42	#1 Ambrogio Lorenzetti #2 Paolo Caroli	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
227ffc7a-3d63-47a5-a96a-6c7848c7ab5b	IAB, Institute of Architects Bangladesh	Sarita Rahman	saritaanusha@yahoo.com	Bagaan, a vertical community farming	IMPLEMENTED	SUBMITTED	SECTION_IV	Dhaka	Bangladesh	23.766169	90.390771	Vertical farming in urban areas can be a great solution for both senior citizens and job-seeking young people.\r\n\r\nFor senior citizens, vertical farming can provide them with a new and exciting hobby that can keep them active and engaged in their community. It can also provide them with a source of fresh, healthy produce, which is particularly important for older individuals who may have limited mobility or access to transportation.\r\n\r\nFor job-seeking young people, vertical farming can offer a range of opportunities. They can work in urban farms as growers, caretakers, or even in marketing and sales. As urban farming continues to grow in popularity, there will be more job opportunities for people with a range of skills and interests.\r\n\r\nIn addition to job opportunities, vertical farming can also offer young people the chance to learn about sustainable agriculture and urban food systems. They can gain valuable experience and knowledge that they can use to pursue careers in related fields or even start their own businesses.\r\n\r\nOverall, vertical farming has the potential to benefit both senior citizens and job-seeking young people in urban areas. It can provide fresh produce, employment opportunities, and a sense of community and purpose.	With the climate change, Bangladesh, a deltaic plain, is expected to experience frequent flooding and other ecological hazards which can lead to extensive pressure in agricultural production and biodiversity. As a result, the food security will be at risk. This paper discusses in details the elements related to farming such as land, water, pesticides, seeds, food supply, food safety, etc. and its impacts on those components in Bangladesh. As for instance, it is discussed how agriculture promotes the land loss and an estimated total area of the tropical forest in Bangladesh was reduced to 900 km2 in 2019, from 966 km2 in 2001. Also, a discussion takes place regarding the food supply and the idea of food miles is briefly mentioned and how it is impacting the supply of food and is adding to the woes of the farmers in Bangladesh, particularly in light of pandemics like Covid-19.\r\n\r\nThe paper further discusses the potential of multi-disciplinary intervention, including architecture, to address the concerns related to agriculture and climate change. The concept of vertical farming from an architectural point-of-view is discussed in this paper. Case studies from the projects of renowned architects like Dr. Ken Yeang are studied to fully the principles of this kind of farming along with studies of successful implementations from countries like Japan, South Korea, Netherlands etc. \r\n\r\nLastly, the paper introduces the project Bagaan- a new visionary model for the climate adaptation of off-grid, integrated and resilient urban farming that can power and feed self-reliant families around a neighborhood. The proposed project is expected to reduce carbon emission and also the land use by 98% and grow the percentage of 100% organic while creating job opportunities and self-reliance within a community, mostly amongst the elderly adults. The paper shows a positive correlation in the ageing population getting involved in farming and green works. Hence, the target group of Bagaan is mostly the elderly citizens, who will be comprising of bigger portion of the demography of Bangladesh by the year 2050. Bagaan aims to explore the production of diverse range of agricultural products within a climatically controlled containers, with provision of machine learning technologies with easy-to-use UXP (user experience) platform, while reducing the food mile mentioned before, but the enhancing the quality of food. The paper also briefly mentions how Bagaan satisfies the Sustainable Development Goals 2030, by directly sufficing the Goal-1, 2, 3, 5, 8, 9, 10, 11, 12, and 13.	Smart agriculture and next-gen farmers are important concepts for achieving the SDGs related to agriculture and food security.\r\n\r\nSmart agriculture involves using modern technologies such as precision agriculture, drones, sensors, and artificial intelligence to optimize crop yields, reduce waste, and increase efficiency. It also involves using data and analytics to make informed decisions about planting, fertilizing, irrigation, and pest management, among other things.\r\n\r\nNext-gen farmers, on the other hand, refer to the younger generation of farmers who are more educated, tech-savvy, and diverse than their predecessors. These farmers bring new ideas, skills, and perspectives to the agricultural sector, which can help drive innovation, improve productivity, and enhance sustainability. Next-gen farmers can also play an important role in promoting sustainable and regenerative farming practices that protect the environment and support local communities.\r\n\r\nTogether, smart agriculture and next-gen farmers can help address some of the major challenges facing the agricultural sector, including climate change, resource scarcity, and food insecurity. By adopting innovative technologies and practices, and by promoting diversity and inclusivity in the agricultural workforce, we can create a more sustainable, equitable, and resilient food system for the future.	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	IFF47	Sarita Rahman, Minami Islam Khan	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
