6df8d6cf-a317-43bd-8fd8-0f8ae2e2086d	Studio Salima Naji architectes	Unknown	atelier@salimanaji.org	AGADIR OUFELLA’S FORTRESS & PLATFORM	PLANNED	APPROVED	SECTION_III	Agadir	Morocco	30.4278	-9.5981	The project is based on a multidisciplinary scientific protocol (archaeologists, historians, anthropologists, architects and engineers) in line with the principles of open and participatory science, while harnessing digital technologies for conservation purposes. In parallel with the archaeological excavations and the gradual restoration of the monument, a participatory approach is being put in place with the survivors and the bearers of memory. The committee of earthquake victims validated each stage of the entire project: the restoration of the fortress, the intramural tour route with a decking reminiscent of the old alleyways, the reorganization of access points, the entire site was reconfigured with the support of the architect's authority. In view of the tragedy, it was vital to respect the memory of the victims and the pain of the survivors. No body could be buried in the Kasbah, and the old medina had become a giant burial ground. The decking system was therefore essential to enable the historic site to be appropriated and to pay tribute to the dead. The network of wooden footbridges allows visitors to explore the site without treading on the ground. Semi burried services Platform To ensure that only the fortress is visible at the top of the hill, all services have been buried. The interior and surroundings of the fortress have been preserved to maintain the exceptional character of the site as a place of history and contemplation, and the services required by visitors have been buried at the foot of the monument. It is also the focal point of the traffic plan, where the various modes of public transport meet and the historic footpaths are redeveloped for all types of visitor.  A platform designed to welcome the public to a reconfigured site The reception platform will respond to all the technical parameters without obliterating the highly complex symbolic dimension of such a complex of buildings. The fortress of Agadir was classified by Cherifian Dahirs from 1932 onwards with easement zones and non-aedificandi zones. A delimited zone limits the height of new buildings (to 3 m) and compliance with the previous land-use coefficient (COS). The nine-metre height required to operate the cable car's machines justified the choice of a ramp to house all the services in two buildings that spread all the requirements over two levels (R-1 and R-2). All the terraces on the reception platform are accessible, allowing visitors to enjoy the landscape from a vantage point. These constraints made it possible to partially bury the service platform (R-1 and R-2) and to distribute three entities over several underground levels: a cable car station (from which only the exit emerges), an R-1 building reserved for a café and reception areas (toilets, information point) and, further down, the belvedere restaurant, R-2. Visitors can arrive by footpath, free shuttle bus or cable car, all of which provide access to the fortress, while all the services are buried underground to make the site invisible from the foot of the fortress. From a distance, the impact is imperceptible. Renewal of vernacular seismic systems As a tribute to the victims of the earthquake, it was decided to avoid the all-concrete approach and to propose a discernible earthquake-resistant construction system that updated the vernacular construction systems of the Atlas region. On the one hand, to reinvest in ‘ancestral’ earthquake-resistant processes and on the other because, unfortunately, far too many victims had been impossible to save under concrete slabs. The construction system of treated wood and 80 cm dry stone is based on an earthquake-resistant method used in the High Atlas (Ait Bou Guemmez Valley) and in other parts of the world (Nepal, Pakistan, Himalayas). The wall is built on a BA foundation (perimeter footings), and the walls are then gradually erected horizontally, course by course, using alternating layers of dry stone masonry and wood, without any mortar. The stone filler material is masonry, while the outer and inner walls are held together by wooden braces. This arrangement, which consists of alternating stone and wood, makes it possible to absorb the effects of shearing in the event of an earthquake, thus meeting seismicity standards in an innovative way.	The project is based on a multidisciplinary scientific protocol (archaeologists, historians, anthropologists, architects and engineers) in line with the principles of open and participatory science, while harnessing digital technologies for conservation purposes. In parallel with the archaeological excavations and the gradual restoration of the monument, a participatory approach is being put in place with the survivors and the bearers of memory. The committee of earthquake victims validated each stage of the entire project: the restoration of the fortress, the intramural tour route with a decking reminiscent of the old alleyways, the reorganization of access points, the entire site was reconfigured with the support of the architect's authority. In view of the tragedy, it was vital to respect the memory of the victims and the pain of the survivors. No body could be buried in the Kasbah, and the old medina had become a giant burial ground. The decking system was therefore essential to enable the historic site to be appropriated and to pay tribute to the dead. The network of wooden footbridges allows visitors to explore the site without treading on the ground. Semi burried services Platform To ensure that only the fortress is visible at the top of the hill, all services have been buried. The interior and surroundings of the fortress have been preserved to maintain the exceptional character of the site as a place of history and contemplation, and the services required by visitors have been buried at the foot of the monument. It is also the focal point of the traffic plan, where the various modes of public transport meet and the historic footpaths are redeveloped for all types of visitor.  A platform designed to welcome the public to a reconfigured site The reception platform will respond to all the technical parameters without obliterating the highly complex symbolic dimension of such a complex of buildings. The fortress of Agadir was classified by Cherifian Dahirs from 1932 onwards with easement zones and non-aedificandi zones. A delimited zone limits the height of new buildings (to 3 m) and compliance with the previous land-use coefficient (COS). The nine-metre height required to operate the cable car's machines justified the choice of a ramp to house all the services in two buildings that spread all the requirements over two levels (R-1 and R-2). All the terraces on the reception platform are accessible, allowing visitors to enjoy the landscape from a vantage point. These constraints made it possible to partially bury the service platform (R-1 and R-2) and to distribute three entities over several underground levels: a cable car station (from which only the exit emerges), an R-1 building reserved for a café and reception areas (toilets, information point) and, further down, the belvedere restaurant, R-2. Visitors can arrive by footpath, free shuttle bus or cable car, all of which provide access to the fortress, while all the services are buried underground to make the site invisible from the foot of the fortress. From a distance, the impact is imperceptible. Renewal of vernacular seismic systems As a tribute to the victims of the earthquake, it was decided to avoid the all-concrete approach and to propose a discernible earthquake-resistant construction system that updated the vernacular construction systems of the Atlas region. On the one hand, to reinvest in ‘ancestral’ earthquake-resistant processes and on the other because, unfortunately, far too many victims had been impossible to save under concrete slabs. The construction system of treated wood and 80 cm dry stone is based on an earthquake-resistant method used in the High Atlas (Ait Bou Guemmez Valley) and in other parts of the world (Nepal, Pakistan, Himalayas). The wall is built on a BA foundation (perimeter footings), and the walls are then gradually erected horizontally, course by course, using alternating layers of dry stone masonry and wood, without any mortar. The stone filler material is masonry, while the outer and inner walls are held together by wooden braces. This arrangement, which consists of alternating stone and wood, makes it possible to absorb the effects of shearing in the event of an earthquake, thus meeting seismicity standards in an innovative way.	See detailed description	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-04-18 13:00:31.097334	2026-04-18 13:00:31.097334	P146	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
8c63b09b-072a-4633-af14-3213536fcd71	Unknown	Unknown	jasonwu1987@gmail.com	Tsinghua Zero-Carbon Space	IMPLEMENTED	SUBMITTED	SECTION_IV	Beijing	China	39.9042	116.4074	The Tsinghua Zero-Carbon Space is a green public area that serves as a vital platform for promoting the campus's carbon neutrality initiative. We employ two key principles to achieve this goal: The first principle is "zero-carbon building operation." We consider the invisible carbon emissions of the materials used throughout the construction process, aiming to establish this space as a premier hub for demonstrating carbon neutrality on campus. The second principle focuses on students’ education. We strive to transform this space into a nurturing environment for developing future leaders in carbon neutrality, integrating exhibition education with opportunities for learning exchanges.  Energy Carbon Reduction--PEDF technology is an essential approach for achieving sustainable development in the building sector. The Sanjiao Zero-Carbon Space employs a rooftop photovoltaic power generation system that includes power storage, a direct current (DC) power system, and a flexible power supply system. The roof is equipped with 500 square meters of photovoltaic panels, totaling 99.6 kW, with an expected annual power generation capacity of about 96,000 kWh. Additionally, the facility includes a 215 kWh (280 Ah) energy storage device, which stores electricity during the day for use at night, thereby reducing carbon emissions by 54.60 tons per year. An air source heat pump is also installed to manage the cooling and heating needs of the space. Furthermore, the adoption of DC LED lamps results in greater energy savings compared to traditional AC-DC conversion methods. Overall, these strategies enhance the efficiency of energy utilization.  Carbon Reduction in Construction--We designed a central sunken courtyard to serve as a sponge garden for rainwater absorption and planted four sequoias that can absorb 15.64 kg of carbon dioxide annually. This design not only minimizes the carbon footprint but also provides a pleasant green environment for students. Additionally, we used carbon-negative concrete blocks for the walls, which save 22.63 kg of carbon emissions per ton compared to conventional concrete blocks. Instead of paint or cement, we employed bamboo panels for the exterior finish of the walls. These panels can absorb 1.6 tons of carbon dioxide per cubic meter, and the entire exterior treatment absorbs a total of 20.8 tons of carbon dioxide. Before construction, we compiled a document titled "Tsinghua Sanjiao Zero-Carbon Space Green and Low-Carbon Construction Requirements" to guide the entire process.  Carbon Reduction in Operation--The project incorporates an intelligent energy control system that displays and regulates power allocation in real time. Utilizing a ‘Mechanism Framework + AI’ for in-depth energy savings, it achieves high-precision performance predictions and global optimization, reducing operational energy consumption. The bathrooms are equipped with highly efficient water-saving fixtures, saving over 20% more water than conventional options. Students can enjoy vegetarian cold lunches here as an alternative to food from the gas canteen. The indoor and outdoor study and communication areas maximize the use of natural light and ventilation during transitional seasons, significantly lowering energy consumption. Additionally, the CIM-based campus carbon neutrality diagnostic platform monitors and recommends ways to optimize overall campus carbon emissions.  Carbon Reduction in Education- The Sanjiao Zero-Carbon Space serves as a platform for the university's scientific research, where an interdisciplinary team of educators can test and	The Tsinghua Zero-Carbon Space is a green public area that serves as a vital platform for promoting the campus's carbon neutrality initiative. We employ two key principles to achieve this goal: The first principle is "zero-carbon bui