ry would reduce the prejudice associated with this settlement, preventing its development and initiate social cohesion between the two worlds, here everyone would feel included. Part of this intervention would be privately accessible to only residents of Kati pahari and part of it would be open for all. In the second phase of the thesis a void called Qasba ground is selected to empower the locals, this ground has skill based , revenue generation and communal programs. The void is located at the heart of Qasba colony and it acts as a common node for all communities. The design solution would empower and uplift communities.   Technical information The construction of the solution provided is sustainable and quick, made from scaffolding and the walls are made by combining the recyclable corrugated sheets with dry grass as insulating material.	See detailed description	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-04-18 13:00:31.097334	2026-04-18 13:00:31.097334	P147	Sumayya Akbar	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
c3afcbd7-6682-46e0-9ae8-8a26ef486772	Pieris Architects	Unknown	info@pierisarchitects.com	“Porpatisies” Residence	PLANNED	SUBMITTED	SECTION_I	Tinos	Greece	37.5382	25.1663	Porpatisies Residence is located in Kaminia, on the wind-exposed western edge of Tinos island. Here, in a terrain sculpted by powerful weather patterns and geological history, the project is conceived not simply as a dwelling, but as a contemporary interpretation of Cycladic life—rooted in place, guided by context, and open to innovation.  The natural slope of the site, though challenging, is embraced as a defining element. Rather than flatten the land or resist its inclination, the design works with it. The house unfolds across four distinct volumes, arranged in a terraced configuration that follows the topography. Each unit steps gently down the hill, preserving the contours and enabling framed views of the surrounding landscape. This layout enhances privacy while maintaining a clear architectural cohesion across the ensemble.  The massing reflects a dual approach: embedded solidity and sculptural elevation. A significant portion of the residence is built into the hillside, drawing from vernacular strategies that use earth for insulation and stability. These subterranean spaces offer natural thermal control and a sense of calm enclosure. In contrast, the above-ground components rise as pristine white volumes—minimal, geometric, and luminous—recalling the iconic Cycladic forms that dot the Aegean islands. Together, they compose a dialogue of concealment and emergence, tradition and abstraction.  Circulation within the residence is carefully choreographed. Covered walkways, shaded patios, and intimate courtyards create a series of spatial thresholds that transition between inside and outside. These elements serve functional and experiential purposes: they protect from prevailing winds, encourage natural ventilation, and provide shaded outdoor areas suited to different times of day. Movement through the site becomes a rhythm—structured yet organic, defined by light, breeze, and view.  Each residential volume is autonomous yet interconnected, offering seclusion without isolation. Outdoor spaces linked by a shared network of stone paths and terraces allow for social interaction and communal moments, without compromising individual retreat. The site plan ensures that every unit has its own orientation, opening to unique vistas and microclimates shaped by the terrain and architecture.  Material selection is rooted in the character of the island. Locally sourced stone is used for retaining walls and supporting structures, anchoring the residence visually and environmentally to its setting. White plastered surfaces reflect the intense island sun while aligning with Tinos’ architectural codes. Timber elements, such as sliding screens and shutters, introduce warmth and tactility. These screens are delicately patterned after traditional lithokentimata, the ornamental stone latticework seen in the island’s dovecotes, offering both cultural continuity and functional shading.  The architectural language is understated and purposeful. Openings are precisely sized and placed to optimize daylight and airflow while minimizing heat gain. Overhangs and built-in shading devices are integrated seamlessly into the form. The play of light and shadow across the building surfaces becomes a key feature of the daily experience, animated by the movement of the sun and filtered through screens that respond to use and season.  While contemporary in execution, the design maintains a sense of restraint and timelessness. The architecture neither imitates tradition nor rejects it; instead, it abstracts and refines it. The use of passive design principles is fundamental. The thermal mass of the stone, the earth-sheltered spaces, the cross-ventilation enabled by strategic openings—all reduce reliance on mechanical systems and create a comfortable, self-regulating environment.  The landscaping, developed by GREENWAYS Landscape Architecture, further reinforces the project’s connection to place. Native species are prioritized to minimize water use and maintain the ecological integrity of the site. The outdoor areas are designed to blend seamlessly into the natural terrain, offering informal gathering spaces, shaded corners, and planted buffers that respond to wind and sun.  Porpatisies Residence is more than a house—it is a study in coexistence. It seeks to belong, to remain quiet yet present, responding to the elements with clarity and care. Its architecture is shaped by the land and in turn shapes the experience of living within it. In this way, it becomes a model for sensitive, durable, and place-based design—both contemporary and enduring, local and open, grounded and aspirational.	Porpatisies Residence is located in Kaminia, on the wind-exposed western edge of Tinos island. Here, in a terrain sculpted by powerful weather patterns and geological history, the project is conceived not simply as a dwelling, but as a contemporary interpretation of Cycladic life—rooted in place, guided by context, and open to innovation.  The natural slope of the site, though challenging, is embraced as a defining element. Rather than flatten the land or resist its inclination, the design works with it. The house unfolds across four distinct volumes, arranged in a terraced configuration that follows the topography. Each unit steps gently down the hill, preserving the contours and enabling framed views of the surrounding landscape. This layout enhances privacy while maintaining a clear architectural cohesion across the ensemble.  The massing reflects a dual approach: embedded solidity and sculptural elevation. A significant portion of the residence is built into the hillside, drawing from vernacular strategies that use earth for insulation and stability. These subterranean spaces offer natural thermal control and a sense of calm enclosure. In contrast, the above-ground componen