11bc2ec4-1951-4c53-9384-25828f330a5e	SuperSpace Architecture	Unknown	info@superspacearch.com	storySPACE : a new tradition of storytelling	PLANNED	SUBMITTED	SECTION_IV	Tangshan	China	39.631	118.18	StorySpace transforms a desolate industrial cooling tower in Tangshan into a cultural landmark—a “lighthouse of stories.” Located in the heart of China’s porcelain capital, the project honors the city’s leading ceramic industry by reimagining its waste into a new material language. Through digital storytelling, recycled porcelain and vitrified ceramic, and a spiraling interior inspired by ancient scrolls and pagodas, it reconnects the city’s heroic past with a sustainable future. Acting as both an immersive micro-museum and interactive city guide, it invites all generations to experience, contribute to, and continue the tales of resilience. Blending tradition, technology, and environmental care, StorySpace creates a dreamlike realm of light, memory, and collective imagination.	StorySpace transforms a desolate industrial cooling tower in Tangshan into a cultural landmark—a “lighthouse of stories.” Located in the heart of China’s porcelain capital, the project honors the city’s leading ceramic industry by reimagining its waste into a new material language. Through digital storytelling, recycled porcelain and vitrified ceramic, and a spiraling interior inspired by ancient scrolls and pagodas, it reconnects the city’s heroic past with a sustainable future. Acting as both an immersive micro-museum and interactive city guide, it invites all generations to experience, contribute to, and continue the tales of resilience. Blending tradition, technology, and environmental care, StorySpace creates a dreamlike realm of light, memory, and collective imagination.	See detailed description	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-04-18 12:59:53.078529	2026-04-18 12:59:53.078529	P22	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
711a24f0-66af-432a-be45-91ab88d4f931	Pieris Architects	Unknown	info@pierisarchitects.com	Secret Garden Residence	IMPLEMENTED	SUBMITTED	SECTION_I	Kifissia	Greece	38.0745	23.8156	Set within the pine-covered landscape of Kifissia, The Secret Garden Residence is envisioned as a home where architecture, memory, and nature are deeply intertwined. Inspired by Frances Hodgson Burnett’s novel of the same name, the project imagines a space that evolves like a story—layered, intimate, and responsive to the lives within it. But beyond its literary reference, this residence is grounded in real-world responsibility. It responds to the global challenges of climate change, environmental degradation, and urban wellbeing by aligning closely with three key United Nations Sustainable Development Goals: SDG 3 (Good Health and Well-being), SDG 9 (Industry, Innovation and Infrastructure), and SDG 15 (Life on Land). From its earliest sketches, the design was rooted in the belief that a home can be more than shelter—it can be a healing, intelligent, and regenerative environment. Every aspect of the project, from its structure and systems to its textures and topography, was developed with this philosophy at its core. The architecture prioritizes human well-being not through spectacle, but through subtlety. Light moves slowly through the spaces, filtered by timber screens and softened by natural stone. Rooms are positioned to open gently to the surrounding forest, creating a sense of continuity between interior and landscape. Here, nature isn’t a backdrop—it is part of the architecture itself. Garden paths meander through native undergrowth. Courtyards become outdoor rooms. Pine trees rise up beside windows, casting long shadows that shift throughout the day. This immersion in nature isn’t just aesthetic—it’s essential to health. The residence follows biophilic design principles to support mental and physical well-being. Carefully considered airflow, passive cooling strategies, and operable openings ensure fresh air circulates throughout the home, while daylight is maximized to reduce reliance on artificial lighting. Materials are natural and non-toxic—stone, untreated wood, and lime-based plasters—all chosen to support a calm, clean atmosphere. Together, these elements create an environment where wellness is embedded in the everyday experience of space. Beneath this poetic surface lies an innovative infrastructure that embodies sustainability without compromise. In partnership with Theodosiou Engineers and mechanical designer Efthimios G. Pariotis, the project incorporates high-efficiency, low-impact technologies including a ground-source heat pump system and radiant floor heating. Passive thermal strategies are used alongside photovoltaic panels and rainwater harvesting to significantly reduce energy consumption and water use. These systems are not visible or imposed—they are seamlessly integrated into the architecture, allowing the house to perform quietly, intelligently, and with minimal ecological cost. The construction approach reflects the same sensitivity. Materials are locally sourced, supporting the regional economy while reducing the carbon footprint associated with transport. Local stone and sustainably harvested Greek timber not only tie the house to its landscape, but also showcase the potential for a regenerative building process that honors place and tradition. Digital design tools like BIM and energy modeling were used throughout the process to reduce waste, optimize performance, and coordinate across disciplines with precision—ensuring that every decision serves a greater environmental and social purpose. At the same time, the project makes a deliberate effort to preserve and enhance the ecological integrity of the site. The design strategy avoids disruption to the terrain, preserving the majority of existing trees and natural groundcover. Instead of flattening the landscape, the home gently steps with it, forming terraces that embrace the slope and celebrate the forest’s rhythm. Native and drought-tolerant species are introduced to support biodiversity, while permeable surfaces allow water to filter back into the ground, reducing runoff and supporting the health of the local ecosystem. Architectural features like green roofs, bird habitats, and insect hotels are integrated discreetly into the structure, reinforcing the idea that this home does not dominate the land—it lives with it. These subtle interventions invite wildlife to return and thrive, making the residence not just a place for people, but a small ecosystem in its own right. In the end, The Secret Garden Residence is a reflection of what architecture can be when guided by care—care for the people who live in it, for the land it touches, and for the future it helps to shape. By aligning storytelling with sustainability, the home becomes both a sanctuary and a statement: that living well and living responsibly are not only compatible, but inseparable.	Set within the pine-covered landscape of Kifissia, The Secret Garden Residence is envisioned as a home where architecture, memory, and nature are deeply intertwined. Inspired by Frances Hodgson Burnett’s novel of the same name, the project imagines a space that evolves like a story—layered, intimate, and responsive to the lives within it. But beyond its literary reference, this residence is grounded in real-world responsibility. It responds to the global challenges of climate change, environmental degradation, and urban wellbeing by aligning closely with three key United Nations Sustainable Development Goals: SDG 3 (Good Health and Well-being), SDG 9 (Industry, Innovation and Infrastructure), and SDG 15 (Life on Land). From its earliest sketches, the design was rooted in the belief that a home can be more than shelter—it can be a healing, intelligent, and regenerative environment. Every aspect of the project, from its structure and systems to its textures and topography, was developed with 