9d59b40c-31e4-4797-8a42-5a3c819c48b4	Pool Arch	Entwicklung	entwicklung@poolarch.ch	BLS Maintenance Hall Oberburg	IN_PROGRESS	SUBMITTED	SECTION_I	Oberburg	Switzerland	46.9963	7.6171	At the interface of landscape and settlement, the new BLS workshop hall exemplifies a contemporary piece of public infrastructure that merges functionality with material and environmental responsibility. The project continues the Swiss tradition of carefully designed railway architecture. Built with a robust concrete base and a wooden superstructure made almost entirely of prefabricated local timber, it reduces the building’s ecological footprint and contributes to a high-quality working environment. The refined articulation of the façade and roof gives the large building a sensitive scale and architectural clarity.	At the interface of landscape and settlement, the new BLS workshop hall exemplifies a contemporary piece of public infrastructure that merges functionality with material and environmental responsibility. The project continues the Swiss tradition of carefully designed railway architecture. Built with a robust concrete base and a wooden superstructure made almost entirely of prefabricated local timber, it reduces the building’s ecological footprint and contributes to a high-quality working environment. The refined articulation of the façade and roof gives the large building a sensitive scale and architectural clarity.	See detailed description	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-04-18 13:00:08.127452	2026-04-18 13:00:08.127452	P54	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
6d96709e-6da2-4749-8693-2704c934b7de	SuperSpace Architecture	Unknown	info@superspacearch.com	In Trace of Time: A Living Bio-Sculpture	PLANNED	SUBMITTED	SECTION_II	Istanbul	Turkey	41.0082	28.9784	“In Trace of Time” is a living bio-sculpture made of moss-infused bio-concrete and reclaimed building scraps, forming a physical and symbolic link between a historic structure and a long-standing tree. It honors memory, resilience, and interspecies kinship while sequestering the carbon equivalent of 275 seedlings over a decade. Designed as a public resting and gathering spot, it enhances urban biodiversity, cools the microclimate, and offers a space for reflection, community interaction, and informal learning. With its sculptural form and ecological intent, it stands as a quiet but persistent node of memory, material innovation, and climate-conscious urban culture.	“In Trace of Time” is a living bio-sculpture made of moss-infused bio-concrete and reclaimed building scraps, forming a physical and symbolic link between a historic structure and a long-standing tree. It honors memory, resilience, and interspecies kinship while sequestering the carbon equivalent of 275 seedlings over a decade. Designed as a public resting and gathering spot, it enhances urban biodiversity, cools the microclimate, and offers a space for reflection, community interaction, and informal learning. With its sculptural form and ecological intent, it stands as a quiet but persistent node of memory, material innovation, and climate-conscious urban culture.	See detailed description	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-04-18 13:00:00.604992	2026-04-18 13:00:00.604992	P40	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
0893909d-4bfc-4e8e-9576-635bbc6ac511	The Miller Hull Partnership, LLP	Architect: The Miller Hull Partnership, LLP / Interior Designer: Charlie Hellstern Interior Design / General Contractor: Clark Construction, LLC / Landscape Architect: Anne James Landscape Architecture LLC / Structural Engineer: Quantum Consulting Enginee	nverkist@millerhull.com	Loom House	IMPLEMENTED	APPROVED	SECTION_V	Bainbridge Island	United States of America	47.6262	-122.5211	Located on a beautifully landscaped bluff overlooking Puget Sound, Loom House is an extensive renovation of a classic 1960s mid-century home, consisting of a main house and an office. The design respects the original architectural character of Hal Moldstad’s mid-century home that thrives in a rejuvenated Pacific Northwest landscape. This project achieved Living Building Certification through net positive energy and water, food production and adhering to a strict materials Red List. Inspired by weaving together people, place, community and equity, Loom House provides owners with a prototype to renovate their homes using resilient retrofitting strategies.	Located on a beautifully landscaped bluff overlooking Puget Sound, Loom House is an extensive renovation of a classic 1960s mid-century home, consisting of a main house and an office. The design respects the original architectural character of Hal Moldstad’s mid-century home that thrives in a rejuvenated Pacific Northwest landscape. This project achieved Living Building Certification through net positive energy and water, food production and adhering to a strict materials Red List. Inspired by weaving together people, place, community and equity, Loom House provides owners with a prototype to renovate their homes using resilient retrofitting strategies.	See detailed description	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-04-18 13:00:08.127452	2026-04-18 13:00:08.127452	P71	Architect: The Miller Hull Partnership, LLP / Interior Designer: Charlie Hellstern Interior Design / General Contractor: Clark