f6f0fab5-688e-415c-aad9-75d04d232818	NIVASA	Akhila Ramesh, Anitha Mahendra	nivasaworks@gmail.com	Co-Creating Construction Labour Communities - RMZ Azure	IMPLEMENTED	APPROVED	SECTION_IV	Bangalore	India	12.9716	77.5946	Nivasa is a not-for-profit, Design Social Venture and we facilitate humane and dignified housing conditions for the urban and rural poor, through design thinking.  Our principal areas of intervention are: · Project GRIHA, which is about developing customized design solutions that consider local material, environment, socio-cultural sensitivities & economic activities, and dissemination of template to contractors, skilled workers and the larger community. · Supporting re-development of villages in a holistic manner where we contribute to design and help in execution of infrastructure and housing needs. · Project Suit Case -This initiative creates housing prototypes as a modular solution for urban homelessness. · Co-creating Construction Labour Communities (CLC) is to catalyse an initiative amongst all stakeholders to move from labour camp to labour community in every construction project  CO- CREATING CONSTRUCTION LABOUR COMMUNITIES CLC  NIvasa’s vision is to promote humane, dignified & vibrant living environments for construction labourers and our mission is to influence intervention in Housing and Infrastructure, Education, Health and Hygiene, Recreation and Vocational/skill Training for welfare of construction labourers.  · Our Strategy to achieve the goals is to use K.A.I.P.A principles to bring about behavioural change in stakeholder mindset. This will ensure a more intrinsic change rather than an imposed one. K. The Knowledge that we need to bring about change. A. Creating Awareness in others on the need for change. I. Intention- ensuring the stake holder gets the intention to bring about the change. P. The stake holder in time becomes a Practitioner of the change. A. The stake holder turned Practitioner now becomes an Advocate of change.   · Our Concept is to ensure a sense of Partnership, Ownership and Community amongst all stakeholders.  · Our thrust is on enabling improved living conditions, improved working conditions and improved worker welfare initiatives.  Addressing these aspects together is key for meaningful change and impact.  What can we do to make things better?  1. Design - Master plan, individual units, kitchens, washrooms, amenities and landscaped areas are designed using standards and guidelines to bring about a change in living conditions.   2. Changing mindsets with Stakeholder engagement: Developers and contractors are engaged through workshops, awareness sessions, tender guidelines, design guidelines, monitoring systems, and benchmarking.  3. Labourer engagement to changing mind-sets of the labourer community in partnership with grass-root NGOs  IMPLEMENTATION STRATEGY 1. PRODUCT - Design of physical infrastructure, including templates for house prototypes, kitchens, dining, and sanitation units.   2. PROCESS - Preparation of manuals, check lists, tender guidelines, design guidelines, monitoring systems, benchmarking systems  3. PEOPLE - Engagement of developer / contractor’s project, site, EHS and vendor teams  4. PREREQUISITE - Active and consistent involvement throughout the engagement period is identified as crucial to the project's successful outcomes.  Impact post intervention   Feedback from clients and other stakeholders  - Reduced attrition rates among labourers - Improvements in construction quality and productivity - Recognition and appreciation from other developers has encouraged contractors to provide better facilities in the CLC - Regular visits from the management team has been associated with reported increases in morale within labour communities  - Higher attendance and reduced incidences of illness - Increased open communication regarding site or community issues and enhanced rapport between labourers and contractors - Substantial behavioural change in labourers. Lesser complaints and conflicts. Greater ease in labour management - Observed increase in self-motivation among labourers regarding cleanliness  Feedback shared by Labourer communities  - Access to better basic amenities (water, electricity food) - Visits from the management team brings contentment and assurance - The rooms are less crowded rooms, greater privacy, and opportunities for rest and recreation - We have bathroom stalls, and privacy - Rainwater does not flow into our rooms - We have our own storage - The pathways are not slushy - The yoga sessions help us with our aches and pains and general well-being	Nivasa is a not-for-profit, Design Social Venture and we facilitate humane and dignified housing conditions for the urban and rural poor, through design thinking.  Our principal areas of intervention are: · Project GRIHA, which is about developing customized design solutions that consider local material, environment, socio-cultural sensitivities & economic activities, and dissemination of template to contractors, skilled workers and the larger community. · Supporting re-development of villages in a holistic manner where we contribute to design and help in execution of infrastructure and housing needs. · Project Suit Case -This initiative creates housing prototypes as a modular solution for urban homelessness. · Co-creating Construction Labour Communities (CLC) is to catalyse an initiative amongst all stakeholders to move from labour camp to labour community in every construction project  CO- CREATING CONSTRUCTION LABOUR COMMUNITIES CLC  NIvasa’s vision is to promote humane, dignified & vibrant living environments for construction labourers and our mission is to influence intervention in Housing and Infrastructure, Education, Health and Hygiene, Recreation and Vocational/skill Training for welfare of construction labourers.  · Our Strategy to achieve the goals is to use K.A.I.P.A principles to bring about behavioural change in stakeholder mindset. This will ensur