5b918025-c932-417f-b677-0c39d5e561c1	Unknown	Unknown	tkca.info@gmail.com	SkyBlox Co-Living Housing	IMPLEMENTED	SUBMITTED	SECTION_IV	Kuala Lumpur	Malaysia	3.139	101.6869	SkyBlox Co-Living Housing in Setapak, Kuala Lumpur is a pioneering model of urban living that redefines what affordable and sustainable housing can be. As Malaysia’s first landed co-living development of its kind, the project goes beyond architecture to act as a social infrastructure—one that fosters community, inclusivity, and environmental responsibility. With over 320 en-suite rooms designed to house more than 500 residents, SkyBlox introduces an innovative and scalable housing typology built on people-centered values.  What sets SkyBlox apart is its strong emphasis on social sustainability. From the start, the project was shaped through a participatory design process involving local authorities, stakeholders, and future residents. Multiple stakeholder meetings were held to understand diverse needs, aspirations, and concerns of the Setapak community. These consultations helped identify key social challenges such as housing affordability, urban isolation, lack of safe communal spaces, and desire for a stronger sense of community. Rather than imposing a design solution, the team listened first—allowing these insights to directly shape the architectural response.  The result is a development that feels organic and grounded in the needs of its users. The master plan encourages interaction and mutual care, featuring communal kitchens, laundries, pocket gardens, flexible lounges, and open corridors that double as social bridges. These shared spaces become vital social nodes where residents from different backgrounds—students, young professionals, small families, and expatriates—can come together naturally, creating opportunities for connection, empathy, and collaboration. By embedding these moments of interaction into daily life, SkyBlox cultivates a vibrant micro-community within a dense urban setting.  The architectural expression draws from a “Back to Nature” philosophy, emphasizing openness, greenery, and emotional well-being. Ground-oriented instead of vertical, the housing blocks allow a closer relationship with the land and a human-scaled living environment. Each unit is part of a modular assembly built using Prefabricated Prefinished Volumetric Construction (PPVC)—a sustainable method that reduces waste and shortens build time while offering flexibility in layout and scalability. This allows the design to evolve with community needs or be replicated in different urban contexts facing similar housing challenges.  Biophilic design principles—green balconies, central courtyards, and community farming spaces—not only soften the built environment but strengthen the residents’ connection with nature and each other. These features were directly inspired by community feedback, which revealed a strong desire for green, open, and safe shared environments. The “SkyBox” multipurpose pavilion at the heart of the development further anchors the project as a place of gathering, celebration, and learning.  Environmental sustainability is embedded through passive design strategies that promote natural ventilation and daylighting. Buildings are oriented and designed to reduce energy usage, incorporating deep overhangs, operable windows, and HVLS fans to optimize thermal comfort. Rainwater harvesting and low-carbon materials contribute to long-term ecological stewardship. Yet sustainability here goes beyond resource efficiency—it is about sustaining human relationships, emotional health, and a shared purpose.  In terms of land use, SkyBlox adopts a compact yet breathable footprint, enabling high-density living without sacrificing quality or dignity. The co-living model promotes shared resources over duplication, reducing living costs while increasing access to amenities. This balance between private and shared space was fine-tuned through dialogue with potential users, ensuring different lifestyle needs could be met within a cohesive framework.  Economically, the project disrupts the assumption that quality design is exclusive or expensive. Through its efficient modular construction and shared amenity model, SkyBlox achieves affordability without compromising spatial quality, sustainability, or user experience. It empowers a diverse range of individuals to live in a well-designed, inclusive, and safe environment—a critical step in addressing the urban housing crisis in Malaysia and beyond.  SkyBlox also brings new opportunities to the local economy. By integrating retail components and small business-friendly spaces into its design, it encourages entrepreneurship and local employment. The project thus functions not only as a housing solution, but also as a community and economic catalyst.  Ultimately, SkyBlox is a bold yet thoughtful reimagining of urban housing. It combines innovative construction methods with community-driven design to create a housing solution that is scalable, inclusive, and deeply responsive to both people and place. More than a building, it is a social infrastructure—an urban village where architecture enables connection, sustainability, and a better way of living.	SkyBlox Co-Living Housing in Setapak, Kuala Lumpur is a pioneering model of urban living that redefines what affordable and sustainable housing can be. As Malaysia’s first landed co-living development of its kind, the project goes beyond architecture to act as a social infrastructure—one that fosters community, inclusivity, and environmental responsibility. With over 320 en-suite rooms designed to house more than 500 residents, SkyBlox introduces an innovative and scalable housing typology built on people-centered values.  What sets SkyBlox apart is its strong emphasis on social sustainability. From the start, the project was shaped through a participatory design process involving local authorities, stakeholders, and future residents. Multiple stakeholder meetings were held to understand diverse needs, aspirations, and concerns of the Setapak community. These consultations helped identify key social challenges such as housing affordability, urban isolation, lack of safe communal spaces, and desire for a stronger sense of community. Rather than imposing a design solution, the team listened first—allowing these insights to directly shape the architectural response.  The result is a development that feels organic and grounded in the needs of its users. The master plan encourages interaction and mutual care, featuring communal kitchens, laundries, pocket gardens, flexible lounges, and open corridors that double as social bridges. These shared spaces become vital social nodes where residents from different backgrounds—students, young professionals, small families, and expatriates—can come together naturally, creating opportunities for connection, empathy, and collaboration. By embedding these moments of interaction into daily life, SkyBlox cultivates a vibrant micro-community within a dense urban setting.  The architectural expression draws from a “Back to Nature” philosophy, emphasizing openness, greenery, and emotional well-being. Ground-oriented instead of vertical, the housing blocks allow a closer relationship with the land and a human-scaled living environment. Each unit is part of a modular assembly built using Prefabricated Prefinished Volumetric Construction (PPVC)—a sustainable method that reduces waste and shortens build time while offering flexibility in layout and scalability. This allows the design to evolve with community needs or be replicated in different urban contexts facing similar housing challenges.  Biophilic design principles—green balconies, central courtyards, and community farming spaces—not only soften the built environment but strengthen the residents’ connection with nature and each other. These features were directly inspired by community feedback, which revealed a strong desire for green, open, and safe shared environments. The “SkyBox” multipurpose pavilion at the heart of the development further anchors the project as a place of gathering, celebration, and learning.  Environmental sustainability is embedded through passive design strategies that promote natural ventilation and daylighting. Buildings are oriented and designed to reduce energy usage, incorporating deep overhangs, operable windows, and HVLS fans to optimize thermal comfort. Rainwater harvesting and low-carbon materials contribute to long-term ecological stewardship. Yet sustainability here goes beyond resource efficiency—it is about sustaining human relationships, emotional health, and a shared purpose.  In terms of land use, SkyBlox adopts a compact yet breathable footprint, enabling high-density living without sacrificing quality or dignity. The co-living model promotes shared resources over duplication, reducing living costs while increasing access to amenities. This balance between private and shared space was fine-tuned through dialogue with potential users, ensuring different lifestyle needs could be met within a cohesive framework.  Economically, the project disrupts the assumption that quality design is exclusive or expensive. Through its efficient modular construction and shared amenity model, SkyBlox achieves affordability without compromising spatial quality, sustainability, or user experience. It empowers a diverse range of individuals to live in a well-designed, inclusive, and safe environment—a critical step in addressing the urban housing crisis in Malaysia and beyond.  SkyBlox also brings new opportunities to the local economy. By integrating retail components and small business-friendly spaces into its design, it encourages entrepreneurship and local employment. The project thus functions not only as a housing solution, but also as a community and economic catalyst.  Ultimately, SkyBlox is a bold yet thoughtful reimagining of urban housing. It combines innovative construction methods with community-driven design to create a housing solution that is scalable, inclusive, and deeply responsive to both people and place. More than a building, it is a social infrastructure—an urban village where architecture enables connection, sustainability, and a better way of living.	See detailed description	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-04-18 13:00:21.972357	2026-04-18 13:00:21.972357	P127	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
59f62aca-32bc-4d10-be9d-bb2b8b6b1128	Unknown	Unknown	haiyang_arch@163.com	Tile & Tulle ——Courtyard No.45 of Xizongbu Hutong	IMPLEMENTED	SUBMITTED	SECTION_IV	Beijing	China	39.9042	116.4074	Courtyard No. 45 in Xizongbu Hutong, a meticulously revitalized historic site in central Beijing，near 1.5km from the Forbidden City, exemplifies an innovative model of adaptive reuse that integrates contemporary commercial vitality with respectful heritage conservation. Originally a traditional Beijing courtyard, the building had suffered severe degradation due to prior unsympathetic uses, informal extensions, and long-term neglect. The project's core objective was the sensitive preservation of cultural identity while revitalizing the site as a dynamic and sustainable retail space. Collaborating with the Vera Wang bridal brand, the design transformed the dilapidated courtyard into an elegant boutique, blending Chinese architectural traditions with Western contemporary aesthetics. The renovation began by thoroughly assessing the historical context and the courtyard’s physical conditions, determining that the preservation of the original architectural order and spatial relationships was paramount. To restore its historical charm, unsightly additions were meticulously removed, and the central courtyard was restored to its original layout in the 1700s. This renewal also revived the iconic walnut tree, a symbol of the site’s continuity, which had been suffocated by previous interventions. An essential design challenge was integrating modern retail functions without altering the courtyard’s heritage form. To address this, the architects adopted an innovative underground spatial expansion strategy. This discreet subterranean addition created essential showroom and service spaces, allowing above-ground structures to remain authentically preserved. Ingenious incorporation of skylights into the courtyard floor enabled natural illumination of the basement spaces, maintaining visual connections between the old and the new. Material choices and contemporary interventions were thoughtfully balanced with historical authenticity. Traditional timber craftsmanship was employed to reconstruct the north main hall, preserving structural integrity and heritage character. Conversely, floor-to-ceiling glass facades introduced a subtle modern aesthetic, enhancing transparency and contrasting with the original grey-tiled roofs. These contemporary insertions were deliberately minimalistic, showcasing both architectural restraint and innovation. Sustainability played a pivotal role throughout the project. Extensive reuse of original building materials, such as reclaimed grey bricks and timber elements, significantly reduced the carbon footprint of the renovation. Energy efficiency was further enhanced through the careful use of insulated glazing and advanced HVAC systems. Additionally, the natural ventilation and daylighting inherent in the original courtyard layout were leveraged to reduce energy consumption. Culturally, Courtyard No. 45 serves as a powerful example of preserving local identity amid rapid urban development. By harmoniously integrating luxury retail functions within a heritage setting, the project demonstrates the commercial viability of historic conservation. The transformed courtyard now stands as a destination that both honors its past and contributes to the neighborhood’s contemporary vitality, drawing visitors who appreciate its authentic cultural ambiance. Economically, the Vera Wang boutique has brought renewed vibrancy to the area, stimulating local businesses and employment opportunities. Its presence attracts both local and international visitors, reinforcing the neighborhood’s identity and catalyzing further investment in heritage-oriented developments. The successful commercial integration into this traditional community context provides a compelling model for sustainable urban regeneration. This adaptive reuse of Courtyard No. 45 embodies the thoughtful synergy between heritage preservation, innovative architectural strategies, and economic sustainability. Its transformation into a high-end retail destination not only revitalizes an iconic urban heritage site but also illustrates the profound potential of historic environments to adapt creatively to contemporary commercial needs. Ultimately, Courtyard No. 45 exemplifies how modern design approaches and respect for historical authenticity can coexist to achieve sustainable urban renewal, becoming a benchmark project for adaptive reuse in Beijing and beyond.	Courtyard No. 45 in Xizongbu Hutong, a meticulously revitalized historic site in central Beijing，near 1.5km from the Forbidden City, exemplifies an innovative model of adaptive reuse that integrates contemporary commercial vitality with respectful heritage conservation. Originally a traditional Beijing courtyard, the building had suffered severe degradation due to prior unsympathetic uses, informal extensions, and long-term neglect. The project's core objective was the sensitive preservation of cultural identity while revitalizing the site as a dynamic and sustainable retail space. Collaborating with the Vera Wang bridal brand, the design transformed the dilapidated courtyard into an elegant boutique, blending Chinese architectural traditions with Western contemporary aesthetics. The renovation began by thoroughly assessing the historical context and the courtyard’s physical conditions, determining that the preservation of the original architectural order and spatial relationships was paramount. To restore its historical charm, unsightly additions were meticulously removed, and the central courtyard was restored to its original layout in the 1700s. This renewal also revived the iconic walnut tree, a symbol of the site’s continuity, which had been suffocated by previous interventions. An essential design challenge was integrating modern retail functions without altering the courtyard’s heritage form.