d employment opportunities. Its presence attracts both local and international visitors, reinforcing the neighborhood’s identity and catalyzing further investment in heritage-oriented developments. The successful commercial integration into this traditional community context provides a compelling model for sustainable urban regeneration. This adaptive reuse of Courtyard No. 45 embodies the thoughtful synergy between heritage preservation, innovative architectural strategies, and economic sustainability. Its transformation into a high-end retail destination not only revitalizes an iconic urban heritage site but also illustrates the profound potential of historic environments to adapt creatively to contemporary commercial needs. Ultimately, Courtyard No. 45 exemplifies how modern design approaches and respect for historical authenticity can coexist to achieve sustainable urban renewal, becoming a benchmark project for adaptive reuse in Beijing and beyond.	See detailed description	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-04-18 13:00:00.604992	2026-04-18 13:00:00.604992	P43	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
e235dbc6-77df-4321-9d16-6d899832cc67	TKCA Architects Sdn Bhd	Ar. Ts. IDr. Rien Tan Kwon Chong	duarqui.design@gmail.com	HEALTH TOURISM MODULE	IMPLEMENTED	APPROVED	SECTION_V	La Paz	Bolivia	-16.5	-68.1193	The project protects the ecosystem, uses local materials, and safeguards the biodiversity of birds and plants. It aims to provide a comfortable, ergonomic, sustainable, and ecological environment. The driving idea is based on a modular grid, utilizing pink rock stone with stone toilets and sinks, rustic bronze faucets, and pine wood doors, whose properties withstand the extreme weather conditions of the Andean plateau. The orientation and access openings respond appropriately to sunlight and low temperatures. The module requires short-term maintenance, does not harm the local flora and fauna, and strengthens community customs. The HEALTH TOURISM MODULE is part of a larger tourism project. Its main objective is to provide a comfortable, ergonomic, sustainable, and ecological environment characteristic of the site. The design of the artifacts satisfies a delegation of 25 people per visit, making their construction essential for tourists. The driving idea was born from a modular grid that meets anthropometric standards and proper material handling.  Added to this was the unique use of the site's richness, the pink rock, whose properties defined the shape. Another detail was to create an architecture that would withstand the extreme weather conditions of the site, with winters and winds so extreme that they crack the concrete. The Andean plateau has its own characteristics, and the project does not distort the natural image provided by the site. The bathrooms were designed in this way, both with fixtures made of local pink stone, two suspended stone sinks, rustic bronze faucets, natural pine doors, and concrete floors to seal the water flow in the showers and for cleaning the bathrooms. The orientation and opening of the entrances were organized according to the times of greatest use of this module, appropriately responding to water use during times of low temperatures. The other element was to shield the entrances from the prevailing winds. The height of the project is based on ergonomics and the use of traditional community tools, avoiding cranes or stone assembly equipment used in the city.  The construction was carried out by semi-skilled workers; however, it is sustainable due to the low pollution, waste, and use of local tools. The project's dissemination to the community, its construction, and its current operation did not generate material contamination or damage groundwater. It is self-sustaining, requires no short-term maintenance, does not harm the local flora or fauna, and has strengthened the community customs of the families in the association. The SANITARY TOURISM MODULE project of the Patacalamachi City of Stone ecotourism association (A.E.C.P.C.P.) is the work of the Calle and Tancara families, who were born and live in the Andean highlands of the department of La Paz in Bolivia. These families, children, grandchildren, and great-grandchildren of two brothers, Casiano and Emeterio, managed to consolidate the association and rescue the attractions preserved in their native lands, from Chulpares, mummies, cave paintings, footprints, and stone markings. A protected moorland during the conflict with the Incas, their paths were a refuge due to the predominance of stone. Lacking agricultural development, the community chose to share its cultural and touristic wealth with the world. Thus was born the communal tourism project, which includes a hostel, bathroom module, water collection, trail opening, ancestral sewing rooms, and mountain camping.	The project protects the ecosystem, uses local materials, and safeguards the biodiversity of birds and plants. It aims to provide a comfortable, ergonomic, sustainable, and ecological environment. The driving idea is based on a modular grid, utilizing pink rock stone with stone toilets and sinks, rustic bronze faucets, and pine wood doors, whose properties withstand the extreme weather conditions of the Andean plateau. The orientation and access openings respond appropriately to sunlight and low temperatures. The module requires short-term maintenance, does not harm the local flora and fauna, and strengthens community customs. The HEALTH TOURISM MODULE is part of a larger tourism project. Its main objective is to provide a comfortable, ergonomic, sustainable, and ecological environment characteristic of the site. The design of the artifacts satisfies a delegation of 25 people per visit, making their construction essential for tourists. The driving idea was born from a modular grid that meets anthropometric standards and proper material handling.  Added to this was the unique use of the site's richness, the pink rock, whose properties defined the shape. Another detail was to create an architecture that would withstand the extreme weather conditions of the site, with winters and winds so extreme that they crack the concrete. The Andean plateau has its own characteristics, and the project does not distort the natural image provided by the site. The bathrooms were designed in this way, both with fixtures made of local pink stone, two suspended stone sinks, rustic bronze faucets, natural pine doors, and concrete floors to seal the water flow in the showers and for cleaning the bathrooms. The orientation and opening of the entrances were organized according to the times of greatest use of this module, appropriately responding to water use during times of low temperatures. The other element was to shield the entrances from the prevailing winds. The height of the project is based on ergonomics and the use of traditional community tools, avoiding cranes or stone assembly equipment used in the city.  The construction was carried out by semi-skilled workers; however, it is sustainable due to the low pollution, waste, and use of local tools. The project's dissemination to the community, its construction, and its current operation did not generate material contamination or damage groundwater. It is self-sustaining, requires no short-term maintenance, does not harm the local flora or fauna, and has strengthened the community customs of the families in the association. The SANITARY TOURISM MODULE project of the Patacalamachi City of Stone ecotourism association (A.E.C.P.C.P.) is the work of the Calle and Tancara families, who were born and live in the Andean highlands of the department of La Paz in Bolivia. These families, children, grandchildren, and great-grandchildren of two brothers, Casiano and Emeterio, managed to consolidate the association and rescue the attractions preserved in their native lands, from Chulpares, mummies, cave paintings, footprints, and stone markings. A protected moorland during the conflict with the Incas, their paths were a refuge due to the predominance of stone. Lacking agricultural development, the community chose to share its cultural and touristic wealth with the world. Thus was born the communal tourism project, which includes a hostel, bathroom module, water collection, trail opening, ancestral sewing rooms, and mountain camping.	See detailed description	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-04-18 13:00:21.972357	2026-04-18 13:00:21.972357	P126	Ar. Ts. IDr. Rien Tan Kwon Chong	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
bb868866-daf2-4aac-83de-cbe66a55740e	Kirk Studio	JW	jw@kirk.studio	JCU Engineering & Innovation Place	IMPLEMENTED	SUBMITTED	SECTION_IV	Townsville	Australia	-19.2576	146.8216	JCU Engineering & Innovation Place  KIRK’s vision for the EIP was a building for the engineering and allied disciplines to celebrate, collaborate, create, learn, innovate and sustain, within an integrated technical landscape derived from state-of-the-art performative design tools to create a new benchmark for the tropical building.  The EIP is positioned on a significant gateway for JCU. Positioned at the junction of Mount Stuart and Magnetic Island axes, the project is the heart of a future industry crossroads. It is a catalyst junction, informing the future organisation and function of the precinct and contributes to JCU’s aspiration for the campus masterplan. The unique dry tropical climate is the basis for developing an authentic building response to the place, and in turn the enduring identity of the EIP.  The design integrates the Engineering & Innovation Place, Ideas Market, and University Mall programs to form a single, unified project. This amalgamation of shared program and function creates a gathering hub within the university. An interactive street serves to gather the labs, workplaces, learning areas and market program with high levels of visual and physical connection. The building's form is entirely conceived in response to the site that is situated in an evolving context with climatic conditions that yield a unique architectural response specific to the tropics whilst establishing JCU as a knowledge Centre for tropical architecture.  Our approach was to make a building that redefines what it means to build in the tropics. It uniquely allows the façade to be entirely transparent from within, and without relying on local convention for costly protective screening. A large dramatic parasol roof is conceived as a series of folded plates. The idea that the shape uses simple structural elements and provides the necessary structural performance is a reference to a universal idea of innovation.  JCU EIP is a next-generation space for pedagogical innovation - an exciting opportunity for JCU to take the lead in teaching, learning and research. The EIP replaces 20,000m² of conventional learning & research spaces with 10,000m² of new pedagogical space. This is achieved through improved utilisation to enhance multi-modal, & social learning spaces - flexible areas where students, academics and industry participants can dynamically interact to cross-pollinate and develop ideas.  The EIP defines a new benchmark in passive sustainability leveraged with low energy active systems that are demonstrable and effective. External solar control is an essential aspect of any tropically located building but to achieve a building largely reliant on passive cooling on a large-scale institutional building in the tropics is unprecedented.  Sustainability strategies were kept simple and avoided bespoke, technically driven systems. This demonstrates sustainable design is about innovatively responding to first principles that capitalise on the natural environment. The EIP is a permeable building that enhances the campus micro-climate. The siting and planning of the building enhances prevailing air movement to provide higher comfort levels. Performative design technologies were utilised to demonstrate the potential for comfortable mixed-mode spaces and improved micro-climate. This delivers on JCU’s ambition for a walkable, connected campus.	JCU Engineering & Innovation Place  KIRK’s vision for the EIP was a building for the engineering and allied disciplines to celebrate, collaborate, create, learn, innovate and sustain, within an integrated technical landscape derived from state-of-the-art performative design tools to create a new benchmark for the tropical building.  The EIP is positioned on a significant gateway for JCU. Positioned at the junction of Mount Stuart and Magn