e83a246e-5b75-49cc-aacd-ed0bf3bce2e7	Malik Architecture	Arjun	arjun@malikarchitecture.com	House of Solid Stone	IMPLEMENTED	SUBMITTED	SECTION_IV	Jaipur	India	26.9124	75.7873	The project revives stone as a primary structural material through timeless load-bearing techniques. Dry interlocking cavity walls and full-span stone vaults were developed without steel frames or concrete. Local stonemasons, guided by generational knowledge, crafted every element—from quarry to assembly—redefining stone beyond cladding. The design merges indigenous craft with engineering to create architecture that is materially honest, culturally rooted, and structurally innovative.  The spatial layout uses a central courtyard and interlacing voids to enable stack-effect ventilation and natural light while protecting from Rajasthan’s harsh sun. Deep overhangs and hand-cut operable stone screens regulate privacy and solar ingress. Hollow cavity stone walls provide insulation, achieving a 5–7°C indoor-outdoor temperature differential. These spatial and tectonic strategies create a passive, low-energy, climate-responsive home rooted in vernacular techniques yet constructed with global structural sensibility.	The project revives stone as a primary structural material through timeless load-bearing techniques. Dry interlocking cavity walls and full-span stone vaults were developed without steel frames or concrete. Local stonemasons, guided by generational knowledge, crafted every element—from quarry to assembly—redefining stone beyond cladding. The design merges indigenous craft with engineering to create architecture that is materially honest, culturally rooted, and structurally innovative.  The spatial layout uses a central courtyard and interlacing voids to enable stack-effect ventilation and natural light while protecting from Rajasthan’s harsh sun. Deep overhangs and hand-cut operable stone screens regulate privacy and solar ingress. Hollow cavity stone walls provide insulation, achieving a 5–7°C indoor-outdoor temperature differential. These spatial and tectonic strategies create a passive, low-energy, climate-responsive home rooted in vernacular techniques yet constructed with global structural sensibility.	See detailed description	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-04-18 13:00:21.972357	2026-04-18 13:00:21.972357	P124	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
2b39f5d3-08f2-4111-9b1e-45bd787f0458	SuperSpace Architecture	Unknown	info@superspacearch.com	Garden Dunes: in search of the horizon	PLANNED	SUBMITTED	SECTION_III	Dubai	United Arab Emirates	25.2048	55.2708	Garden Dunes reimagines vertical urban living with a façade that captures the geography of the region, blending the shifting forms of local sand dunes with the harsh, dynamic path of the sun’s analemma. This design harmoniously reflects the area’s distinctive natural elements and solar patterns, creating a striking and contextually relevant architectural landmark. This residential building harmonizes nature-tech & culture, creating a striking sustainable living in the city. Its fluid, undulating metal panels mimic the natural movement of dunes, and the movement of the sun while integrating sustainable features like water collection & distribution systems to nourish lush green terraces. Enhanced by photovoltaic solar films & dichroic foil, the façade offers captivating light and shadow effects, optimizing energy efficiency & minimizing UV impact. becoming a testament to innovative design, blending cutting-edge technology with aesthetic beauty to provide a unique, eco-friendly living experience.	Garden Dunes reimagines vertical urban living with a façade that captures the geography of the region, blending the shifting forms of local sand dunes with the harsh, dynamic path of the sun’s analemma. This design harmoniously reflects the area’s distinctive natural elements and solar patterns, creating a striking and contextually relevant architectural landmark. This residential building harmonizes nature-tech & culture, creating a striking sustainable living in the city. Its fluid, undulating metal panels mimic the natural movement of dunes, and the movement of the sun while integrating sustainable features like water collection & distribution systems to nourish lush green terraces. Enhanced by photovoltaic solar films & dichroic foil, the façade offers captivating light and shadow effects, optimizing energy efficiency & minimizing UV impact. becoming a testament to innovative design, blending cutting-edge technology with aesthetic beauty to provide a unique, eco-friendly living experience.	See detailed description	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-04-18 13:00:00.604992	2026-04-18 13:00:00.604992	P33	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
ec15f3b3-59b6-40f2-a162-ecee29000739	SuperSpace Architecture	Unknown	info@superspacearch.com	Valens Housing : Adaptive Reuse as New Heritage	PLANNED	SUBMITTED	SECTION_II	Istanbul	Turkey	41.0082	28.9784	Valens Housing proposes a visionary reuse of Istanbul’s Valens Aqueduct—not only as a heritage landmark but as a model for activating underused urban infrastructure. Instead of demolition, the project increases density through lightweight, disassemblable wooden modules using circular dry-construction systems. It blends past and future, preserving collective memory while offering climate-responsive, inclusive housing solutions. This approach advocates for urban regeneration through modular, low-impact architecture, offering a replicable framework for cities to transform dormant structures into sustainable and socially engaging environments.	Valens Housing proposes a visionary reuse of Istanbul’s Valens Aqueduct—not only as a heritage landmark but as a model for activating underused urban infrastructure. Instead of demolition, the project increases density through lightweight, disassemblable wooden modules using circular dry-construction systems. It blends past and future, preserving collective memory while offering climate-responsive, inclusive housing solutions. This approach advocates for urban regeneration through modular, low-impact architecture, offering a replicable framework for cities to transform dormant structures into sustainable and socially engaging environments.	See detailed description	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-04-18 12:59:53.078529	2026-04-18 12:59:53.078529	P7	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
cd5978fa-90bc-4615-b410-229b28f5340c	Studio Lotus	Unknown	media@studiolotus.in	Brownfield Re-development of Lakshmi Mills	IN_PROGRESS	SUBMITTED	SECTION_IV	Coimbatore	India	11.0168	76.9558	Set on 21-acres, a 100-year old defunct textile mill in Coimbatore, the project reclaims industrial heritage to create much-lacking urban public infrastructure. Through adaptive reuse, minimal demolition of existing structures, and pedestrian-first planning, arises a porous civic precinct anchored by commerce, culture, placemaking and green space. By limiting new construction and using frugal material interventions, the project has achieved an 82% reduction in embodied carbon (saving 501 kgCO₂e/m²) as compared to a new-build. The redevelopment, designed in phases, has catalysed economic growth–local businesses reporting 15-20% increase in sales–while restoring a sense of place and identity.   Project Summary  In an era marked by rapid urbanisation and greenfield development, India's cities are grappling with the challenge of vehicle-centric planning and a critical scarcity of genuine communal spaces. Against this backdrop, a cluster of defunct cotton mills has been given new life—and a new purpose. Formerly home to Lakshmi Mills, one of India’s oldest yarn and fabric manufacturing companies, the iconic site at a major urban node is now the focal point of a massive redevelopment initiative. This project exemplifies the potential of adaptive reuse and placemaking, revitalising underutilised urban areas and fostering a deeper sense of connection between people and their cities.  Straddling a major traffic artery, the 21-acre site functions as a walkable community hub with a host of public functions. A visually permeable boundary wall was designed to blur the lines between the precinct and the surrounding neighbourhood. Certain structures and sheds were earmarked for demolition or restructuring to enhance circulation and functionality, while vehicular access was restricted to the periphery to prioritise walkability and create a pedestrian-friendly environment. Open green areas and avenues lined with shade-giving trees have been integrated into the design scheme as a counterpoint to the site's industrial landscape, offering respite from the urban bustle. Secondary walkways have been reinforced, linking public nodes and providing diverse routes for circulation, further encouraging exploration and discovery. Wayfinding totems are thoughtfully placed to improve connectivity, while historical accounts and plaques elevate the experience by facilitating guided narrative walks and tours.  Studio Lotus’ approach towards the revitalisation is driven by a deep commitment to honouring the mills’ original architectural features and quirks, including the industrial shell, existing roofing system, and structural elements. Exposed brick walls and steel beams complement contemporary finishes, creating a unique blend of old and new that speaks to the site's industrial heritage.   Had the project pursued complete demolition followed by new construction, the associated embodied carbon emissions were estimated at approximately 606.2 kgCO₂e per square metre. By adopting an adaptive reuse strategy and retaining the majority of the existing built fabric, the project limited its embodied carbon to 105 kgCO₂e per square metre. This approach resulted in a net carbon savings of 501.2 kgCO₂e per square metre.  The phased redevelopment has converted 12 acres of the 21-acre site into a bustling hub of activity, attracting an average of 2,500-3,500 visitors on weekdays and swelling to 6,000-10,000 on weekends. Anticipating this level of engagement, ample parking provisions were incorporated from the outset, ensuring a seamless visitor experience. Anchored by a 1,25,000 sq. ft. Lulu Mall, the precinct hosts the first Starbucks in Coimbatore, several international brands, and a curated selection of local businesses. The ongoing development of a 1,20,000 sq. ft. indoor street market promises to further solidify Lakshmi Mills as a vibrant epicentre of commerce and culture in Coimbatore. Newly established businesses have reported a 15-20% increase in sales compared to initial projections, indicating its substantial contribution to the revitalisation of the area.  Proactive programming and placemaking strategies have been integral to the project from the outset. Even as construction progresses in the third phase, the precinct remains a dynamic, ever-evolving space. Plans for a container food park, outdoor screening areas, and interactive kiosks promise to enrich the visitor experience further. As the project progresses, it continues to emphasise the ideas of community, sustainability, and architectural innovation, promising a vibrant and beloved destination for generations to come.	Set on 21-acres, a 100-year old defunct textile mill in Coimbatore, the project reclaims industrial heritage to create much-lacking urban public infrastructure. Through adaptive reuse, minimal demolition of existing structures, and pedestrian-first planning, arises a porous civic precinct anchored by commerce, culture, placemaking and green space. By limiting new construction and using frugal material interventions, the project has achieved an 82% reduction in embodied carbon (saving 501 kgCO₂e/m²) as compared to a new-build. The redevelopment, designed in phases, has catalysed economic growth–local businesses reporting 15-20% increase in sales–while restoring a sense of place and identity.   Project Summary  In an era marked by rapid urbanisation and greenfield development, India's cities are grappling with the challenge of vehicle-centric planning and a critical scarcity of genuine communal spaces. Against this backdrop, a cluster of defunct cotton mills has been given new life—and a new purpose. Formerly home to Lakshmi Mills, one of India’s oldest yarn and fabric manufacturing companies, the iconic site at a major urban node is now the focal point of a massive re