t carbon savings of 501.2 kgCO₂e per square metre.  The phased redevelopment has converted 12 acres of the 21-acre site into a bustling hub of activity, attracting an average of 2,500-3,500 visitors on weekdays and swelling to 6,000-10,000 on weekends. Anticipating this level of engagement, ample parking provisions were incorporated from the outset, ensuring a seamless visitor experience. Anchored by a 1,25,000 sq. ft. Lulu Mall, the precinct hosts the first Starbucks in Coimbatore, several international brands, and a curated selection of local businesses. The ongoing development of a 1,20,000 sq. ft. indoor street market promises to further solidify Lakshmi Mills as a vibrant epicentre of commerce and culture in Coimbatore. Newly established businesses have reported a 15-20% increase in sales compared to initial projections, indicating its substantial contribution to the revitalisation of the area.  Proactive programming and placemaking strategies have been integral to the project from the outset. Even as construction progresses in the third phase, the precinct remains a dynamic, ever-evolving space. Plans for a container food park, outdoor screening areas, and interactive kiosks promise to enrich the visitor experience further. As the project progresses, it continues to emphasise the ideas of community, sustainability, and architectural innovation, promising a vibrant and beloved destination for generations to come.	See detailed description	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-04-18 13:00:00.604992	2026-04-18 13:00:00.604992	P41	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
d8aa2c9d-ab20-409a-9020-5ed75a1f316e	Pieris.Architects, Georgios Vroxidis, Temek SA, Agropolis, Ecoveritas, Sustain	"Stella Pieri, Pieros Pieris, Constantinos Pieris, Romina Routsi, Aggeliki Xronopoulou, Lydia Sklavou, Maria Antonogiannaki, Marilena Maragkaki, Polykarpos Kotsidis "	info@pierisarchitects.com	Oxygen	IMPLEMENTED	APPROVED	SECTION_I	Athens	Greece	37.9838	23.7275	Perched just above Athens’ iconic Olympic Stadium, the “Oxygen” residential development is a landmark in sustainable architecture and a pioneering project in the Greek housing market. Completed in 2023 by Patmou S.A., this 5,700 m² complex comprises 27 residences, offering a mix of one-, two-, and three-bedroom apartments distributed across one or two levels. More than just a collection of modern homes, Oxygen represents a paradigm shift in urban residential development—being the first project in Greece to achieve BREEAM certification, a globally recognized standard for sustainable building. The design of Oxygen draws inspiration from the natural elements of water, earth, and sky, creating a built environment that responds to ecological, social, and spatial needs. The undulating, wave-like forms of the architecture not only sculpt a visually dynamic profile but also serve a practical function—carving out pockets of green spaces while subtly delineating private and communal zones. The use of Y-shaped columns, reminiscent of branching tree trunks, reinforces the project’s biophilic ethos, while simultaneously supporting the structure and enhancing its sculptural presence. These features all contribute to SDG 15 (Life on Land), by integrating nature into the urban environment and encouraging biodiversity through thoughtfully landscaped spaces, vertical gardens, and the use of native plant species curated by landscape designers Agropolis. At its core, Oxygen is designed around human well-being and environmental responsibility. Every decision—from site orientation to material selection—was made with the dual goals of comfort and sustainability. The residences are designed to maximize natural light and ventilation, and each unit includes access to outdoor spaces, helping foster a strong connection to nature. These attributes directly support SDG 3 (Good Health and Well-being) by creating environments that enhance physical comfort, mental health, and quality of life. Additional amenities such as a sheltered, year-round outdoor gym surrounded by lush landscaping and open-air communal areas facilitate social connection and active living within an urban setting—an important feature in a post-pandemic world where access to safe, shared spaces is increasingly valued. Oxygen’s design is also a reflection of resilience and adaptability, shaped by the lessons of the COVID-19 pandemic. The architecture accommodates evolving domestic needs such as remote work, flexible living arrangements, and multi-functional interior layouts. This adaptability aligns with SDG 11 (Sustainable Cities and Communities) by promoting inclusive, safe, and responsive urban housing that meets the demands of contemporary life without compromising environmental stewardship. Sustainability in construction and long-term operation is a key pillar of the project. Oxygen integrates environmentally responsible materials and cutting-edge systems for water management, waste reduction, and energy efficiency. Collaborating with sustainability consultants Ecoveritas and engineering experts TEMEK SA, the project utilized life-cycle thinking to reduce embodied carbon and optimize resource use—advancing SDG 12 (Responsible Consumption and Production). Meanwhile, the project’s alignment with SDG 13 (Climate Action) is evident in its passive design strategies, the incorporation of green infrastructure, and the emphasis on reducing urban heat through landscaping and green surfaces. From an engineering and infrastructure standpoint, Oxygen also contributes to SDG 9 (Industry, Innovation and Infrastructure). With structural input from Georgios Vroxidis and execution by Sustain Construction Company, the project implemented innovative approaches in design and construction—balancing architectural ambition with long-term durability and performance. Its use of prefabricated components, smart water systems, and advanced lighting technologies ensures that the infrastructure is both efficient and future-proof. Collectively, these design and planning strategies form a holistic approach to sustainability that transcends aesthetics. Oxygen is not just a visually striking development; it is a living system that responds to the needs of people, nature, and the planet. By embedding the principles of environmental stewardship, social well-being, and flexible living, the project offers a template for resilient urban housing in Greece and beyond. The combination of forward-thinking design, technical precision, and ecological sensitivity makes “Oxygen” a flagship example of how architecture can respond to the multifaceted challenges of our time.	Perched just above Athens’ iconic Olympic Stadium, the “Oxygen” residential development is a landmark in sustainable architecture and a pioneering project in the Greek housing market. Completed in 2023 by Patmou S.A., this 5,700 m² complex comprises 27 residences, offering a mix of one-, two-, and three-bedroom apartments distributed across one or two levels. More than just a collection of modern homes, Oxygen represents a paradigm shift in urban residential development—being the first project in Greece to achieve BREEAM certification, a globally recognized standard for sustainable building. The design of Oxygen draws inspiration from the natural elements of water, earth, and sky, creating a built environment that responds to ecological, social, and spatial needs. The undulating, wave-like forms of the architecture not only sculpt a visually dynamic profile but also serve a practical function—carving out pockets of green spaces while subtly delineating private and communal zones. The use of Y-shaped columns, reminiscent of branching tree trunks, reinforces the project’s biophilic ethos, while simultaneously supporting the structure and enhancing its sculptural presence. These features all contribute to SDG 15 (Life on Land), by integrating nature into the urban environment and encouraging biodiversity through thoughtfully landscaped spaces, vertical gardens, and the use of native plant species curated by landscape designers Agropolis. At its core, Oxygen is designed around human well-being and environmental responsibility. Every decision—from site orientation to material selection—was made with the dual goals of comfort and sustainability. The residences are designed to maximize natural light and ventilation, and each unit includes access to outdoor spaces, helping foster a strong connection to nature. These attributes directly support SDG 3 (Good Health and Well-being) by creating environments that enhance physical comfort, mental health, and quality of life. Additional amenities such as a sheltered, year-round outdoor gym surrounded by lush landscaping and open-air communal areas facilitate social connection and active living within an urban setting—an important feature in a post-pandemic world where access to safe, shared spaces is increasingly valued. Oxygen’s design is also a reflection of resilience and adaptability, shaped by the lessons of the COVID-19 pandemic. The architecture accommodates evolving domestic needs such as remote work, flexible living arrangements, and multi-functional interior layouts. This adaptability aligns with SDG 11 (Sustainable Cities and Communities) by promoting inclusive, safe, and responsive urban housing that meets the demands of contemporary life without compromising environmental stewardship. Sustainability in construction and long-term operation is a key pillar of the project. Oxygen integrates environmentally responsible materials and cutting-edge systems for water management, waste reduction, and energy efficiency. Collaborating with sustainability consultants Ecoveritas and engineering experts TEMEK SA, the project utilized life-cycle thinking to reduce embodied carbon and optimize resource use—advancing SDG 12 (Responsible Consumption and Production). Meanwhile, the project’s alignment with SDG 13 (Climate Action) is evident in its passive design strategies, the incorporation of green infrastructure, and the emphasis on reducing urban heat through landscaping and green surfaces. From an engineering and infrastructure standpoint, Oxygen also contributes to SDG 9 (Industry, Innovation and Infrastructure). With structural input from Georgios Vroxidis and execution by Sustain Construction Company, the project implemented innovative approaches in design and construction—balancing architectural ambition with long-term durability and performance. Its use of prefabricated components, smart water systems, and advanced lighting technologies ensures that the infrastructure is both efficient and future-proof. Collectively, these design and planning strategies form a holistic approach to sustainability that transcends aesthetics. Oxygen is not just a visually striking development; it is a living system that responds to the needs of people, nature, and the planet. By embedding the principles of environmental stewardship, social well-being, and flexible living, the project offers a template for resilient urban housing in Greece and beyond. The combination of forward-thinking design, technical precision, and ecological sensitivity makes “Oxygen” a flagship example of how architecture can respond to the multifaceted challenges of our time.	See detailed description	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-04-18 13:00:39.923528	2026-04-18 13:00:39.923528	P153	"Stella Pieri, Pieros Pieris, Constantinos Pieris, Romina Routsi, Aggeliki Xronopoulou, Lydia Sklavou, Maria Antonogiannaki, Marilena Maragkaki, Polykarpos Kotsidis "	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
1f9185c2-8481-4bb1-a22b-d6d62a5ceb7e	Pieris.Architects	Constantinos Pieris, Stella Pieri, Pieros Pieris, Margarita Varla, Electra Kefalloniti, Romina Routsi, Marianna Tzouti	info@pierisarchitects.com	"Olon Dimitsana” Wellness Hotel	IN_PROGRESS	APPROVED	SECTION_I	Dimitsana	Greece	37.5898	22.0418	Located in the heart of Arcadia, Greece, the Olon Dimitsana Wellness Hotel is a boutique hospitality project that brings together wellness, sustainability, and cultural heritage. Currently under construction by Olon Group, the hotel reimagines a 1950s abandoned building as a contemporary retreat deeply embedded in the character and traditions of the mountainous village of Dimitsana.  Set at an elevation of 950 meters, the hotel spans a gross floor area of 1,400 m² and includes 37 guest accommodations: 26 rooms, five junior suites, and six luxury suites. Guests will also have access to a wellness spa, a restaurant focused on seasonal local cuisine, a cozy bar lounge, and a multi-purpose seminar area that can host up to 80 people. The aim is to offer a destination of holistic renewal—where architecture, landscape, and experience align to nourish body, mind, and spirit.  Central to the vision is the adaptive reuse of the existing mid-century structure. Rather than demolish and rebuild, the project retains and strengthens the original framework, conserving embodied energy and reinforcing the cultural memory of the site. This approach not only supports sustainable development goals but also honors the building’s connection to the local community. The design responds to Dimitsana’s traditional architecture, incorporating natural stone, wood, and lime-based finishes. These are interpreted through a contemporary lens to create a timeless and welcoming atmosphere.  The spatial configuration balances privacy and connection. Rooms and suites are positioned to maximize views and sunlight, while public spaces are woven throughout the building and grounds to encourage gathering and reflection. The natural slope of the terrain is embraced, resulting in layered terraces, quiet corners, and smooth transitions between indoor and outdoor areas. Interiors are defined by a warm, earthy palette with tactile surfaces and hand-finished details that reflect regional craft traditions. Locally inspired elements—such as “Kaplan” textiles with geometric motifs—add richness and meaning to the design.  Wellness at Olon Dimitsana extends beyond the traditional spa experience. The program includes nature-based rituals, guided forest walks, meditation, and seasonal activities rooted in local customs. Nutrition is integral to the wellness philosophy, with the restaurant offering thoughtfully prepared meals using organic produce from local farms and foragers. The goal is to create a restorative environment where guests feel reconnected—to themselves, to the landscape, and to the heritage of the place.  The hotel is also committed to social sustainability. From the early planning stages, the project has engaged local craftsmen, tradespeople, and suppliers, ensuring that economic benefits remain within the community. Beyond construction, the hotel will serve as a cultural platform—hosting exhibitions, talks, and events that celebrate Arcadian identity and connect guests with local knowledge and traditions.  Construction is being executed in carefully planned phases. After structural reinforcement and external envelope work, the team has moved into the internal layout, MEP installations, and the beginning of interior fit-outs. The landscaping and final material finishes will follow. Each phase incorporates sustainable practices, including the use of local, non-toxic materials and minimal-impact construction methods.  Landscape design is grounded in ecological sensitivity. Native plant species are used exclusively to preserve biodiversity and require minimal irrigation. Hardscaping is minimized to avoid disrupting the existing ecosystem, and rainwater collection, composting, and responsible water management are integrated into the site strategy.  As the project advances, it continues to reflect and support global sustainability goals. Olon Dimitsana has aligned its objectives with the United Nations Sustainable Development Goals (SDGs), specifically SDG 3 (Good Health and Well-being), 7 (Affordable and Clean Energy), 9 (Industry, Innovation and Infrastructure), 11 (Sustainable Cities and Communities), 12 (Responsible Consumption and Production), 13 (Climate Action), and 15 (Life on Land). These values are evident in the architectural choices, energy systems, community partnerships, and landscape interventions.  When complete, Olon Dimitsana will serve as a forward-thinking model for sustainable rural hospitality. It redefines the wellness hotel—not simply as a destination for comfort, but as a place for cultural immersion, environmental care, and personal renewal. In doing so, it offers a vision of tourism that is not only luxurious, but purposeful, place-based, and deeply respectful of its environment and origins.	Located in the heart of Arcadia, Greece, the Olon Dimitsana Wellness Hotel is a boutique hospitality project that brings together wellness, sustainability, and cultural heritage. Currently under construction by Olon Group, the hotel reimagines a 1950s abandoned building as a contemporary retreat deeply embedded in the character and traditions of the mountainous village of Dimitsana.  Set at an elevation of 950 meters, the hotel spans a gross floor area of 1,400 m² and includes 37 guest accommodations: 26 rooms, five junior suites, and six luxury suites. Guests will also have access to a wellness spa, a restaurant focused on seasonal local cuisine, a cozy bar lounge, and a multi-purpose seminar area that can host up to 80 people. The aim is to offer a destination of holistic renewal—where architecture, landscape, and experience align to nourish body, mind, and spirit.  Central to the vision is the adaptive reuse of the existin