efalloniti, Romina Routsi, Marianna Tzouti	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
f7a81ce4-8f8d-45cb-ab00-1ea0fe194ef1	NSP Sekkei	Unknown	y.sakai@nsp-sekkei.com	Roadside Station Hojo	IMPLEMENTED	SUBMITTED	SECTION_IV	Hokuei	Japan	35.5011	133.8414	Located in Hokuei Town in central Tottori Prefecture, facing the Sea of Japan and surrounded by scenic white sand dunes and pine forests, Michi-no-Eki Hōjō Park had been in operation for over 30 years. Aging facilities and declining visitor numbers prompted its transformation into a new regional hub for tourism, community exchange, and disaster prevention, now reborn as Michi-no-Eki Hōjō. The exterior design draws inspiration from the rippling patterns of the Hōjō sand dunes, the calm horizon of the Sea of Japan, and the gentle contours of the local farmland—expressed through the softly curving roofline. The resulting architecture offers a sense of originality and warmth that gently embraces all who visit. The building comprises a main station hall and an annex with a disaster prevention warehouse and a universally accessible parking area. These linked curved forms create visual harmony and enhance wayfinding and usability. To further improve visibility, a steel-framed tower is positioned at the center of the main building, clearly signaling the entrance while also serving as a seasonal lighting feature. Heavy rooftop equipment such as electrical cubicles and emergency generators are housed behind the tower to minimize flood risk and allow easy maintenance access. The steel structure reliably supports these loads while ensuring future structural integrity and management ease. The core space—the eastern wing for Direct-from-the-farm Market—is built with a tree-like V-pillar spatial truss system. LVL members extend diagonally from high concrete foundations, while sawn timber elements branch upward to evoke a forest canopy. Despite its visual complexity, the structure efficiently transfers loads. The ceiling’s diagonal members combine reciprocal framing and tensioned beams, creating an expansive open space using minimal materials in optimal configurations. The retail area and kids’ corner feature a simpler single-direction diagonal framing system, with the roof’s soft curvature revealing changes in angle that lend the space a distinctive atmosphere. In the kids’ corner, where rainy-day play areas are scarce in the region, a high-ceilinged indoor space supports net and wooden play equipment, offering a safe and spacious environment for families regardless of weather. From the earliest stages, structural planning leveraged the local LVL factory’s advantage, focusing on the dimensional stability and design flexibility of LVL. By combining it with sawn timber, a unique and rational wood structure was developed. Anticipating procurement challenges, the town of Hokuei coordinated with stakeholders to prepare and stock materials over the course of a year prior to construction. This required strong regional collaboration, led by the Central Tottori Forestry Cooperative, aligning harvesting plans, supply coordination, and processing workflows with local sawmills and precut manufacturers. Construction complexities were recognized during the design phase. After the contractor was appointed, 1/10 and 1/5-scale models were created, and detailed structural coordination meetings were held involving architects, structural engineers, contractors, and the on-site carpenters. The 1/5 model faithfully represented materials—LVL for LVL, sawn timber for timber—reflecting the builders' deep commitment. The structural erection process involved ground assembly of V-truss sections, reciprocal frames, and tensioned beams, lifted into place by crane. Although one month had been scheduled, construction was completed in about 20 days—thanks to favorable weather, early procurement of SD15-grade timber and LVL, thorough structural coordination, and skilled execution by the site team. The opening of Michi-no-Eki Hōjō marked the long-awaited emergence of a vibrant new gathering place for the region. Anticipation ran high among residents and visitors alike, with around 500 people queuing before the official opening on April 25. During the Golden Week holidays, over 54,000 people visited in just 12 days—a powerful testament to renewed local energy and interest. This figure accounts for roughly one-sixth of the annual visitor goal of 330,000, indicating a strong start. While revenue targets remain undisclosed, projections suggest that continued momentum could realistically reach 1 million annual visitors and ¥1 billion in annual sales. As a new landmark and gateway to local charm, Michi-no-Eki Hōjō is poised to grow as a place beloved by many.	Located in Hokuei Town in central Tottori Prefecture, facing the Sea of Japan and surrounded by scenic white sand dunes and pine forests, Michi-no-Eki Hōjō Park had been in operation for over 30 years. Aging facilities and declining visitor numbers prompted its transformation into a new regional hub for tourism, community exchange, and disaster prevention, now reborn as Michi-no-Eki Hōjō. The exterior design draws inspiration from the rippling patterns of the Hōjō sand dunes, the calm horizon of the Sea of Japan, and the gentle contours of the local farmland—expressed through the softly curving roofline. The resulting architecture offers a sense of originality and warmth that gently embraces all who visit. The building comprises a main station hall and an annex with a disaster prevention warehouse and a universally accessible parking area. These linked curved forms create visual harmony and enhance wayfinding and usability. To further improve visibility, a steel-framed tower is positioned at the center of the main building, clearly signaling the entrance while also serving as a seasonal lighting feature. Heavy rooftop equipment such as electrical cubicles and emergency generators are housed behind the tower to minimize flood risk and allow easy maintenance access. The steel structure reliably supports these loads while ensuring future structural integrity and management ease. The core space—the eastern wing for Direct-from-the-farm Market—is built with a tree-like V-pillar spatial truss system. LVL members extend diagonally from high concrete foundations, while sawn timber elements branch upward to evoke a forest canopy. Despite its visual complexity, the structure efficiently transfers loads. The ceiling’s diagonal members combine reciprocal framing and tensioned beams, creating an expansive open space using minimal materials in optimal configurations. The retail area and kids’ corner feature a simpler single-direction diagonal framing system, with the roof’s soft curvature revealing changes in angle that lend the space a distinctive atmosphere. In the kids’ corner, where rainy-day play areas are scarce in the region, a high-ceilinged indoor space supports net and wooden play equipment, offering a safe and spacious environment for families regardless of weather. From the earliest stages, structural planning leveraged the local LVL factory’s advantage, focusing on the dimensional stability and design flexibility of LVL. By combining it with sawn timber, a unique and rational wood structure was developed. Anticipating procurement challenges, the town of Hokuei coordinated with stakeholders to prepare and stock materials over the course of a year prior to construction. This required strong regional collaboration, led by the Central Tottori Forestry Cooperative, aligning harvesting plans, supply coordination, and processing workflows with local sawmills and precut manufacturers. Construction complexities were recognized during the design phase. After the contractor was appointed, 1/10 and 1/5-scale models were created, and detailed structural coordination meetings were held involving architects, structural engineers, contractors, and the on-site carpenters. The 1/5 model faithfully represented materials—LVL for LVL, sawn timber for timber—reflecting the builders' deep commitment. The structural erection process involved ground assembly of V-truss sections, reciprocal frames, and tensioned beams, lifted into place by crane. Although one month had been scheduled, construction was completed in about 20 days—thanks to favorable weather, early procurement of SD15-grade timber and LVL, thorough structural coordination, and skilled execution by the site team. The opening of Michi-no-Eki Hōjō marked the long-awaited emergence of a vibrant new gathering place for the region. Anticipation ran high among residents and visitors alike, with around 500 people queuing before the official opening on April 25. During the Golden Week holidays, over 54,000 people visited in just 12 days—a powerful testament to renewed local energy and interest. This figure accounts for roughly one-sixth of the annual visitor goal of 330,000, indicating a strong start. While revenue targets remain undisclosed, projections suggest that continued momentum could realistically reach 1 million annual visitors and ¥1 billion in annual sales. As a new landmark and gateway to local charm, Michi-no-Eki Hōjō is poised to grow as a place beloved by many.	See detailed description	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-04-18 13:00:00.604992	2026-04-18 13:00:00.604992	P42	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
4057e73d-3889-432a-a739-55f9ab80e9e8	Malik Architecture	Arjun	arjun@malikarchitecture.com	IF.BE (Ice Factory Ballard Estate)	IMPLEMENTED	SUBMITTED	SECTION_IV	Mumbai	India	19.076	72.8777	IF.BE transforms/ reimagines a 140-year-old ice factory in Mumbai’s historic Ballard Estate into a vibrant cultural hub for architecture, design, and the arts. Anchored in principles of adaptive reuse and heritage restoration, the space weaves together craft, culture, and climate resilience around a central banyan tree and a richly layered spatial narrative. As a dynamic urban forum, IF.BE fosters collaboration, critical discourse, and micro-scale urban renewal.   IF.BE demonstrates how sustainability can be rooted in memory. By restoring a 140-year-old ice factory, it preserves embodied energy and avoids the environmental cost of demolition. The project uncovers the site’s original anatomy while integrating new spaces through a dialogue with the old. It breathes new life into an industrial relic, using passive design strategies hence maximising natural light and ventilation. As an architect-led, self-funded initiative, it challenges conventional redevelopment models. By fostering public dialogue, creative economies, and ecological sensitivity, IF.BE becomes a blueprint for inclusive, climate-conscious, and heritage-based urban regeneration.	IF.BE transforms/ reimagines a 140-year-old ice factory in Mumbai’s historic Ballard Estate into a vibrant cultural hub for architecture, design, and the arts. Anchored in principles of adaptive reuse and heritage restoration, the space weaves together craft, culture, and climate resilience around a central banyan tree and a richly layered spatial narrative. As a dynamic urban forum, IF.BE fosters collaboration, critical discourse, and micro-scale urban renewal.   IF.BE demonstrates how sustainability can be rooted in memory. By restoring a 140-year-old ice factory, it preserves embodied energy and avoids the environmental cost of demolition. The project uncovers the site’s original anatomy while integrating new spaces through a dialogue with the old. It breathes new life into an industrial relic, using passive design strategies hence maximising natural light and ventilation. As an architect-led, self-funded initiative, it challenges conventional redevelopment models. By fostering public dialogue, creative economies, and ecological sensitivity, IF.BE becomes a blueprint for inclusive, climate-conscious, and heritage-based urban regeneration.	See detailed description	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-04-18 13:00:21.972357	2026-04-18 13:00:21.972357	P125	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
