6c1260fd-d997-4e1a-9937-8d4085d04fd8	Pool Architekten	Unknown	entwicklung@poolarch.ch	Ziegelei Ost Allschwil	PLANNED	SUBMITTED	SECTION_I	Allschwil	Switzerland	47.5497	7.5401	Ziegelei Ost is a future-oriented district taking shape on a site layered with industrial history. Once a clay pit and brickyard, the site today offers fertile ground for a new form of urban productivity—one that brings together work, culture, and community. The project preserves key elements of the existing structures and terrain, transforming them into a mixed-use ensemble rooted in place.  Instead of clearing the site, the planning strategy builds upon its substance. Robust halls made of local brick are retained and repurposed. Construction materials such as excavated clay are reintroduced into the building process. New architectural typologies—including dense additions and a high-rise along Binningerstrasse—expand the programmatic spectrum while maintaining generous public space. The Lettenwiese, a green recreational area emerging from the site's former excavation pit, becomes the spatial heart of the neighbourhood.  At the core of the project is an iterative development model—growing through dialogue with local stakeholders, future users and the municipality. Productive ground floors, open typologies and adaptable structures form the basis for a living quarter of short distances. Here, everyday production and experimental use coexist, framed by a landscape that makes room for both continuity and change.	Ziegelei Ost is a future-oriented district taking shape on a site layered with industrial history. Once a clay pit and brickyard, the site today offers fertile ground for a new form of urban productivity—one that brings together work, culture, and community. The project preserves key elements of the existing structures and terrain, transforming them into a mixed-use ensemble rooted in place.  Instead of clearing the site, the planning strategy builds upon its substance. Robust halls made of local brick are retained and repurposed. Construction materials such as excavated clay are reintroduced into the building process. New architectural typologies—including dense additions and a high-rise along Binningerstrasse—expand the programmatic spectrum while maintaining generous public space. The Lettenwiese, a green recreational area emerging from the site's former excavation pit, becomes the spatial heart of the neighbourhood.  At the core of the project is an iterative development model—growing through dialogue with local stakeholders, future users and the municipality. Productive ground floors, open typologies and adaptable structures form the basis for a living quarter of short distances. Here, everyday production and experimental use coexist, framed by a landscape that makes room for both continuity and change.	See detailed description	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-04-18 13:00:15.086189	2026-04-18 13:00:15.086189	P93	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
da2ebd04-d249-4d53-a5d3-f99d581f9d92	Unknown	Unknown	arqmiri@gmail.com	From Bridge to Bridge: Environmental Regeneration, Recreational Spaces, and the Internet of Things	PLANNED	SUBMITTED	SECTION_V	Villahermosa	Mexico	17.9892	-92.9475	Project Overview The De Puente a Puente project proposes the comprehensive revitalization of the Carrizal Riverbank between the Parque Tabasco Bridge and the Bosques de Saloya Bridge in Villahermosa, Tabasco. This currently degraded and underutilized strip is reimagined as an ecological, social, and technological corridor. The intervention seeks to reestablish the city’s connection with its river through actions that regenerate the natural environment, provide high-quality public spaces, and apply smart technologies for efficient management. The project aims to promote environmental conservation, sustainable mobility, and community ownership of public space.  Global Inspiration for River Regeneration The proposal draws inspiration from successful international experiences in river restoration and urban regeneration. A paradigmatic example is the Cheonggyecheon River in Seoul, where an elevated highway was removed to restore the natural stream and convert it into a linear park, significantly improving environmental quality and revitalizing the local economy. Another reference is the Nervión Estuary in Bilbao, once highly polluted and now transformed into an urban development axis, with pedestrian and cycling infrastructure that has enhanced urban value and mobility. These examples demonstrate that reclaiming urban rivers yields not only ecological but also social and economic benefits. De Puente a Puente adapts these lessons to Villahermosa’s context to give new life to the Carrizal River as a driver of sustainable development.  Intervention Strategies The project is structured around three main pillars: environmental restoration, urban infrastructure, and the application of emerging technologies.  1. Riparian Ecosystem Restoration and Reforestation The project includes selective reforestation to restore the natural ecosystem. Moisture-tolerant species like water zapote and weeping willow will be planted near the river. In the intermediate zone, trees such as macuilis and ceiba will provide shade and regulate humidity. In the urban fringe, ornamental and fruit-bearing trees like guayacán, nance, and zapote will be introduced, which also attract pollinators. The goal is to preserve healthy vegetation, and community reforestation days will be organized to promote public engagement and environmental stewardship.  2. Sustainable Architectural Design and Public Spaces Pedestrian paths will be constructed using permeable eco-friendly pavers, and bike lanes will use ecological asphalt. Rest areas will be equipped with low-impact urban furniture: coconut palm benches and tables, green pergolas, and filtered hydration stations. Bicycle parking and inclusive signage will be provided. Lighting will come from solar-powered smart streetlights with motion sensors, and the area will include surveillance systems and passive security features. For accessibility, the design includes interactive screens in Mexican Sign Language, visual alarms, and audio descriptions. Floating docks made of water-resistant materials will also be built to facilitate sustainable water transport, integrating the river as a route for mobility and recreation.  3. Internet of Things (IoT) for Smart Public Space Management Technological innovation will optimize maintenance and park operations. Smart trash bins equipped with sensors will notify cleaning services in real time when collection is needed, reducing unnecessary trips. An intelligent irrigation system controlled by soil moisture sensors will activate only when necessary, helping conserve water. For public safety, the project will include AI-enabled video surveillance cameras and emergency stations with panic buttons linked to a monitoring center. Visitors’ experiences will be enhanced through digital signage and QR codes with ecological and cultural information, also available in accessible formats.  Conclusions We conclude that De Puente a Puente is a comprehensive proposal aiming to transform the Carrizal Riverbank into a model of sustainable urban regeneration, combining ecological restoration, green infrastructure, and smart technologies. Beyond offering a recreational space, the project seeks to boost the local economy, promote environmental education, and build social cohesion. Its adaptable design allows it to be replicated along other segments of the Carrizal River or other water bodies throughout Tabasco.	Project Overview The De Puente a Puente project proposes the comprehensive revitalization of the Carrizal Riverbank between the Parque Tabasco Bridge and the Bosques de Saloya Bridge in Villahermosa, Tabasco. This currently degraded and underutilized strip is reimagined as an ecological, social, and technological corridor. The intervention seeks to reestablish the city’s connection with its river through actions that regenerate the natural environment, provide high-quality public spaces, and apply smart technologies for efficient management. The project aims to promote environmental conservation, sustainable mobility, and community ownership of public space.  Global Inspiration for River Regeneration The proposal draws inspiration from successful international experiences in river restoration and urban regeneration. A paradigmatic example is the Cheonggyecheon River in Seoul, where an elevated highway was removed to restore the natural stream and convert it into a linear park, significantly improving environmental quality and revitalizing the local economy. Another reference is the Nervión Estuary in Bilbao, once highly polluted and now transformed into an urban development axis, with pedestrian and cycling infrastructure that has enhanced urban value and mobility. These examples demonstrate that reclaiming urban rivers yields not o