nly ecological but also social and economic benefits. De Puente a Puente adapts these lessons to Villahermosa’s context to give new life to the Carrizal River as a driver of sustainable development.  Intervention Strategies The project is structured around three main pillars: environmental restoration, urban infrastructure, and the application of emerging technologies.  1. Riparian Ecosystem Restoration and Reforestation The project includes selective reforestation to restore the natural ecosystem. Moisture-tolerant species like water zapote and weeping willow will be planted near the river. In the intermediate zone, trees such as macuilis and ceiba will provide shade and regulate humidity. In the urban fringe, ornamental and fruit-bearing trees like guayacán, nance, and zapote will be introduced, which also attract pollinators. The goal is to preserve healthy vegetation, and community reforestation days will be organized to promote public engagement and environmental stewardship.  2. Sustainable Architectural Design and Public Spaces Pedestrian paths will be constructed using permeable eco-friendly pavers, and bike lanes will use ecological asphalt. Rest areas will be equipped with low-impact urban furniture: coconut palm benches and tables, green pergolas, and filtered hydration stations. Bicycle parking and inclusive signage will be provided. Lighting will come from solar-powered smart streetlights with motion sensors, and the area will include surveillance systems and passive security features. For accessibility, the design includes interactive screens in Mexican Sign Language, visual alarms, and audio descriptions. Floating docks made of water-resistant materials will also be built to facilitate sustainable water transport, integrating the river as a route for mobility and recreation.  3. Internet of Things (IoT) for Smart Public Space Management Technological innovation will optimize maintenance and park operations. Smart trash bins equipped with sensors will notify cleaning services in real time when collection is needed, reducing unnecessary trips. An intelligent irrigation system controlled by soil moisture sensors will activate only when necessary, helping conserve water. For public safety, the project will include AI-enabled video surveillance cameras and emergency stations with panic buttons linked to a monitoring center. Visitors’ experiences will be enhanced through digital signage and QR codes with ecological and cultural information, also available in accessible formats.  Conclusions We conclude that De Puente a Puente is a comprehensive proposal aiming to transform the Carrizal Riverbank into a model of sustainable urban regeneration, combining ecological restoration, green infrastructure, and smart technologies. Beyond offering a recreational space, the project seeks to boost the local economy, promote environmental education, and build social cohesion. Its adaptable design allows it to be replicated along other segments of the Carrizal River or other water bodies throughout Tabasco.	See detailed description	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-04-18 13:00:31.097334	2026-04-18 13:00:31.097334	P129	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
ce3eb2d7-34ac-45d2-a7d5-93d25e9c967d	SJK Architect	Unknown	rupali@sjkarchitect.com	Sparkrill International School	IMPLEMENTED	SUBMITTED	SECTION_IV	Mumbai	India	19.076	72.8777	The masterplan prioritises walkability, safety, and comfortable outdoor spaces by integrating the sites natural features—rock formations, boulders, and water channels into the design. Large public spaces, including a cricket field with amphitheatre seating, entrance plaza, water harvesting pond, football field, and informal courts, are centrally placed along the north-south axis. Building blocks are arranged around these, with modulated heights and tree-lined edges providing shade and year-round usability. Unlike conventional school layouts that isolate playgrounds, embedding public spaces within the built environment ensures constant “eyes on the street,” enhancing safety and community. The main access curves around the cricket pitch, leading to a central rock formation at the academic plaza. The primary wing lies to the east, secondary to the west, and arts and dining blocks along the pond between academic and residential zones. Hostel blocks and staff quarters cluster around the football field to the south, ensuring safe access and play opportunities beyond school hours. The design fosters informal and exploratory learning by leveraging nature and the built environment as educators alongside traditional classrooms. Inspired by Rajasthan’s buildings with self shading devices in hot and dry climate, the campus features narrow, shaded, and organically laid-out streets between east-west oriented classroom blocks, that harness prevailing winds and ensure year-round thermal comfort. Scaled-down courtyard proportions and staggered layouts introduce an element of play and break away from rigidity. Street widths vary to support different functions—6 m for circulation, 8 m for classroom spillovers and informal play, and 11 m for congregation, with steps, boulders, and trees. These larger streets double as event zones and open classrooms, supporting unstructured play that fosters creativity and social-emotional development. Streets are further enriched with indigenous plants, open water channels, and natural features, encouraging physical exploration and hands-on learning. During rains, children interact with rainwater channels, sailing paper boats and intuitively learning about buoyancy, water flow slopes, and natural systems—turning everyday experiences into learning moments.  The indoor learning spaces employ several passive design strategies to optimize natural light and ventilation for students thermal comfort and physical well-being. The two-storeyed classroom blocks are oriented north-south with a curved roof profile sloping gently from the north to the south. Large windows on the north facade admit glare-free north light inside the classrooms, while deep overhangs on the south shade the corridors—effectively minimising heat gain. Ventilators are designed on the corridor-side walls to facilitate optimum cross-ventilation.  Several design considerations are made to ensure safety and a sense of emotional comfort for young students, especially those living away from their families by de-scaling the built environment.  On the ground floor, window sill heights are lowered to 0.45 metres, to ensure that young children can easily see outside and engage with the outdoor environment. On the upper floor corridors, the curved roof is lowered to a height of 1.9 metres, creating cosy, child-friendly proportions. The material and colour palette comprises natural kota stone, terracotta clay roofing tiles, and pops of bright colours across the campus, adding a touch of warmth and softness to the built environment.  All the classrooms and circulation areas are naturally ventilated and daylit for most part of the day; passive climate-responsive strategies ensure that both indoor and outdoor spaces are thermally comfortable without air conditioning, even in the hot and dry climate of Warangal. This results in significant savings in operational energy costs.  Additionally, water and waste management systems are integrated on-site to promote judicious use of natural resources. Rainwater harvesting ponds are designed at the site’s lowest levels to minimise runoff and facilitate natural percolation into the soil. By employing porous brick pavers and consolidated soil as paving materials, the landscape strategy ensures that the site facilitates the natural percolation of rainwater. Reed beds are planted near the dining block to treat wastewater and reuse it for irrigation of the landscape on-site. A kitchen garden with composting pits is also proposed near the arts and dining block, where students can learn about gardening and various composting methods practically — inculcating awareness about sustainable living practices from a young age. The cultivation of native vegetation further enhances the site's biodiversity, creating a thriving and resilient ecosystem that attracts and supports various forms of life.	The masterplan prioritises walkability, safety, and comfortable outdoor spaces by integrating the sites natural features—rock formations, boulders, and water channels into the design. Large public spaces, including a cricket field with amphitheatre seating, entrance plaza, water harvesting pond, football field, and informal courts, are centrally placed along the north-south axis. Building blocks are arranged around these, with modulated heights and tree-lined edges providing shade and year-round usability. Unlike conventional school layouts that isolate playgrounds, embedding public spaces within the built environment ensures constant “eyes on the street,” enhancing safety and community. The main access curves around the cricket pitch, leading to a central rock formation at the academic plaza. The primary wing lies to the east, secondary to the west, and arts and dining blocks along the pond between academic and residential zones. Hos