ebfd828c-0477-4dfa-a101-158da2898c6c	Pool Architekten	Unknown	entwicklung@poolarch.ch	Haus Adeline Favre – ZHAW Departement Gesundheit, Winterthur	IMPLEMENTED	SUBMITTED	SECTION_I	Winterthur	Switzerland	47.4994	8.7243	A health education campus embedded in the industrial fabric of Winterthur: the Haus Adeline Favre transforms a former machinery hall into a vertical learning environment. Its introverted layout inverts the logic of the city block, drawing light and life into a central courtyard. Terraces, bridges, and platforms create spatial variety for study, exchange, and recreation. The building supports interdisciplinary learning while anchoring the public university within the evolving urban fabric of Lokstadt.	A health education campus embedded in the industrial fabric of Winterthur: the Haus Adeline Favre transforms a former machinery hall into a vertical learning environment. Its introverted layout inverts the logic of the city block, drawing light and life into a central courtyard. Terraces, bridges, and platforms create spatial variety for study, exchange, and recreation. The building supports interdisciplinary learning while anchoring the public university within the evolving urban fabric of Lokstadt.	See detailed description	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-04-18 13:00:15.086189	2026-04-18 13:00:15.086189	P95	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
fd999aea-5972-426e-94b2-149f46259304	Chamber of Architects of Turkey (TMMOB Mimarlar Odası)	Sinan Gunay and Nurhayat Oz /SUPERSPACE	info@superspacearch.com	LEAFY: Artificial Gardens of Kinetic Leaves that help shape Actual Parks	PLANNED	APPROVED	SECTION_III	Abu Dhabi	United Arab Emirates	24.4539	54.3773	Leafy, an artificial garden of modular, kinetic leaves that mimic the intelligence of forest canopies, creates resilient, regenerative microclimates in heatwave-prone, water-scarce, hyper-arid cities. It provides adaptive shade, evaporative cooling, & independent irrigation to help both people and plants thrive—a clean, passive climate-conditioning system for public spaces. Addressing this ecological disconnection, Leafy promotes public health, emotional well-being, and a renewed sensitivity to the fragility of both nature and human life. A climate-positive system, it fuses industrial ecology with nature, reimagining public space as a living, responsive, and harmonious environment.  For a detailed presentation please visit the google drive link below: superspace_leafy_2024v_   https://drive.google.com/drive/folders/1JsmJvJCgB-lusoGCCyqsU6CnR3WhYr5d?usp=sharing	Leafy, an artificial garden of modular, kinetic leaves that mimic the intelligence of forest canopies, creates resilient, regenerative microclimates in heatwave-prone, water-scarce, hyper-arid cities. It provides adaptive shade, evaporative cooling, & independent irrigation to help both people and plants thrive—a clean, passive climate-conditioning system for public spaces. Addressing this ecological disconnection, Leafy promotes public health, emotional well-being, and a renewed sensitivity to the fragility of both nature and human life. A climate-positive system, it fuses industrial ecology with nature, reimagining public space as a living, responsive, and harmonious environment.  For a detailed presentation please visit the google drive link below: superspace_leafy_2024v_   https://drive.google.com/drive/folders/1JsmJvJCgB-lusoGCCyqsU6CnR3WhYr5d?usp=sharing	See detailed description	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-04-18 13:00:15.086189	2026-04-18 13:00:15.086189	P82	Sinan Gunay and Nurhayat Oz /SUPERSPACE	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
1d2e1840-3e2d-4c1c-8911-1129e69d33f9	RICHÄRD | KENNEDY ARCHITECTS + GLHN	Jim Richärd, FAIA + Stephen Kennedy, AIA + Andrew Timberg, AIA	jasonwu1987@gmail.com	YongFeng Street-Corner Transformation	IMPLEMENTED	APPROVED	SECTION_IV	Beijing	China	39.9042	116.4074	A previously desolate and enclosed street corner has been revitalized into an open, inviting park that offers picturesque mountain views. Created to foster inclusiveness, equality, and sustainability, this park acts as a lively public space for the surrounding community. Once choked with thick woods and weeds, the area not only hindered pedestrian access but also cut off local businesses from the street. This initiative was collaboratively proposed and executed by street officials, urban planners, and architects to improve the living conditions and restore dignity for residents and workers in the vicinity. The design features a clear and accessible pedestrian pathway, reestablishing connections within the community. A pavilion outfitted with solar photovoltaic panels guarantees that the park functions with complete energy self-sufficiency. At night, low-level induction lights gently illuminate the area, enhancing safety and allowing for extended use into the evening.	A previously desolate and enclosed street corner has been revitalized into an open, inviting park that offers picturesque mountain views. Created to foster inclusiveness, equality, and sustainability, this park acts as a lively public space for the surrounding community. Once choked with thick woods and weeds, the area not only hindered pedestrian access but also cut off local businesses from the street. This initiative was collaboratively proposed and executed by street officials, urban planners, and architects to improve the living conditions and restore dignity for residents and workers in the vicinity. The design features a clear and accessible pedestrian pathway, reestablishing connections within the community. A pavilion outfitted with solar photovoltaic panels guarantees that the park functions with complete energy self-sufficiency. At night, low-level induction lights gently illuminate the area, enhancing safety and allowing for extended use into the evening.	See detailed description	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-04-18 13:00:15.086189	2026-04-18 13:00:15.086189	P96	Jim Richärd, FAIA + Stephen Kennedy, AIA + Andrew Timberg, AIA	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
76a6009a-c2dc-4a37-b3cf-1295c6669b15	United Architects of the philippines	KDAS Group: Ar. Kazandra Yap, Ar. David Cabigao, Leon Fernandez, Ivy Belza, Sophia Estabaya	mail@kdasgroup.com	Tibay Buhay Inclusive Center	PLANNED	APPROVED	SECTION_IV	Gubat	Philippines	12.9199	124.1212	Set amidst the rural landscapes of Sorsogon, the Tibay Buhay Inclusive Center is a prototype facility that reimagines what inclusive, community-driven design can be. Envisioned as a space of belonging, resilience, and growth, the center serves adults with different abilities and their caregivers, providing a nurturing environment that blends education, therapy, and livelihood in a single ecosystem.  The planning of the site revolves around an infinity loop pathway—a deliberate circulation strategy that offers freedom of movement, intuitive wayfinding, and a sense of continuity. This loop acts as both a physical and symbolic spine, representing interconnectedness, personal exploration, and safe return—essential values for individuals who thrive on structure, autonomy, and familiarity.  At the center of the plan lies the Inclusive Center (2), designed in a C-shape layout that conceptually mimics an embracing hand. The structure cradles a central courtyard, which functions as a communal core and passive cooling zone, inspired by traditional courtyard systems and enhanced with bioclimatic features. Clay tiles along the roof allow water to trickle down and cool the passing air—an approach influenced by beehive cooling systems. Air enters through vented breeze blocks and circulates across the open-plan multipurpose hall, creating a naturally ventilated, climate-responsive interior.  Surrounding the Inclusive Center are key supporting programs:  The Café (3), positioned beside the main hall, serves as a transitional space between private therapy and public interaction. It becomes a venue for PDAs to showcase their work, gain livelihood, and practice social integration.  The Vegetable Garden (1) and Greenhouse (10) form the heart of the therapeutic and skill-building activities. These productive spaces encourage grounding, responsibility, and sensory engagement with the earth.  Quiet Rooms (7) and Meditation Spaces (9) are strategically distributed along the loop, offering refuge and regulation for users who may feel overwhelmed, supporting emotional and sensory needs.  The Amphitheater and Bioswale Garden (5) create an open-air space for creative expression, community events, and stormwater management, highlighting how landscape architecture can serve both environmental and cultural roles.  Built with local and regenerative materials—such as bamboo, mud clay, coconut derivatives, and anahaw—the project is deeply rooted in vernacular wisdom. These materials are not only ecologically sustainable but also familiar to local laborers, making construction and future replication feasible in other rural areas. The architecture responds to its tropical setting and seismic context, with steep roofs, low-impact structures, and flexible planning that can expand or contract depending on future needs.  The spatial planning also honors volunteers and caregivers, with a dedicated Visitors' Accommodation (4) and a reserved space for future residential quarters. These provisions ensure that those who give care also receive it—in the form of respite, privacy, and detachment when needed.  Throughout the site, the guiding principles of the project come to life:  Inclusivity is felt in the sensory-friendly spaces, universal circulation, and intentional design of all rooms.  Grounded Experience is manifested through tactile materials, earthy palettes, and the connection to soil, light, and air.  Growth is enabled through skill-based programming and architectural flexibility that encourages participation and self-discovery.  Adaptability drives the design decisions, from the material choices to the layout ensuring the building evolves with its users and environment.  Ultimately, the Tibay Buhay Inclusive Center is more than a facility. It’s an architectural framework for empowerment, where design is a silent teacher, a source of comfort, and a catalyst for inclusion. As it stands in the rural province, it echoes one powerful belief: “Architecture matters when it builds a world where every person regardless of ability feels safe, seen, and able to grow.”	Set amidst the rural landscapes of Sorsogon, the Tibay Buhay Inclusive Center is a prototype facility that reimagines what inclusive, community-driven design can be. Envisioned as a space of belonging, resilience, and growth, the center serves adults with different abilities and their caregivers, providing a nurturing environment that blends education, therapy, and livelihood in a single ecosystem.  The planning of the site revolves around an infinity loop pathway—a deliberate circulation strategy that offers freedom of movement, intuitive wayfinding, and a sense of continuity. This loop acts as both a physical and symbolic spine, representing interconnectedness, personal exploration, and safe return—essential values for individuals who thrive on structure, autonomy, and familiarity.  At the center of the plan lies the Inclusive Center (2), designed in a C-shape layout that conceptually mimics an embracing hand. The structure cradles a central courtyard, which functions as a communal core and passive cooling zone, inspired by traditional courtyard systems and enhanced with bioclimatic features. Clay tiles along the roof allow water to trickle down and cool the passing air—an approach influenced by beehive cooling systems. Air enters through vented breeze blocks and circulates across the open-plan multipurpose hall, creating a naturally ventilated, climate-responsive interior.  Surrounding the Inclusive Center are key supporting programs:  The Café (3), positioned beside the main hall, serves as a transitional space between private therapy and public interaction. It becomes a venue for PDAs to show