ces to the layout ensuring the building evolves with its users and environment.  Ultimately, the Tibay Buhay Inclusive Center is more than a facility. It’s an architectural framework for empowerment, where design is a silent teacher, a source of comfort, and a catalyst for inclusion. As it stands in the rural province, it echoes one powerful belief: “Architecture matters when it builds a world where every person regardless of ability feels safe, seen, and able to grow.”	See detailed description	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-04-18 13:00:39.923528	2026-04-18 13:00:39.923528	P166	KDAS Group: Ar. Kazandra Yap, Ar. David Cabigao, Leon Fernandez, Ivy Belza, Sophia Estabaya	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
797ccc84-55b0-4732-aa2e-3f4f01ff1efd	Unknown	Weijiayin	weijiayin2@163.com	Children Friendly Center of Xuzhou	IMPLEMENTED	SUBMITTED	SECTION_IV	Xuzhou	China	34.2044	117.2844	Children Friendly Center is a supporting educational facility for the 13th Xuzhou International Horticultural Expo.  The small building is located in a relatively wide and independent base, with functions including a children's activity room, a parent-child restaurant, a book bar, and an independent scenic entrance. It is a children's activity camp built for children to safely and happily approach and explore nature, and will continue to operate after the event. The small building and large base provide us with the opportunity to create a place where architecture and natural landscape are fully integrated, creating a friendly, open, and fun indoor activity space for children, while also providing a natural outdoor playground.  The starting point of design was to find a geometric element that would provide efficiency in standardization and spatial organization, as well as interest in geometric properties.  In the two-dimensional plane, with the densely arranged standard activity room as the core, the building grows and fissions in two directions: westward, it rotates and spreads along the stream, while eastward, it splits into several independent small monomers, completely dissolving the entire building volume into the forest.  On the three-dimensional section, the terraces of the architectural complex undulate according to the needs of the surrounding terrain and landscape. The geometric characteristics of the pentagonal spatial units provide a rich variety of elevation connections, creating different types of spatial experiences such as playing in the water, overlooking the scenery, and reading in the book bar.  When roaming in this small geometric world, people can feel the nature in the geometric frame anytime and anywhere, and the small polygonal units bring short turns and frequent rhythm changes in space, inadvertently creating a “geometric garden” - this kind of spatial change and fun, bringing people a relaxed and open experience.	Children Friendly Center is a supporting educational facility for the 13th Xuzhou International Horticultural Expo.  The small building is located in a relatively wide and independent base, with functions including a children's activity room, a parent-child restaurant, a book bar, and an independent scenic entrance. It is a children's activity camp built for children to safely and happily approach and explore nature, and will continue to operate after the event. The small building and large base provide us with the opportunity to create a place where architecture and natural landscape are fully integrated, creating a friendly, open, and fun indoor activity space for children, while also providing a natural outdoor playground.  The starting point of design was to find a geometric element that would provide efficiency in standardization and spatial organization, as well as interest in geometric properties.  In the two-dimensional plane, with the densely arranged standard activity room as the core, the building grows and fissions in two directions: westward, it rotates and spreads along the stream, while eastward, it splits into several independent small monomers, completely dissolving the entire building volume into the forest.  On the three-dimensional section, the terraces of the architectural complex undulate according to the needs of the surrounding terrain and landscape. The geometric characteristics of the pentagonal spatial units provide a rich variety of elevation connections, creating different types of spatial experiences such as playing in the water, overlooking the scenery, and reading in the book bar.  When roaming in this small geometric world, people can feel the nature in the geometric frame anytime and anywhere, and the small polygonal units bring short turns and frequent rhythm changes in space, inadvertently creating a “geometric garden” - this kind of spatial change and fun, bringing people a relaxed and open experience.	See detailed description	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-04-18 13:00:21.972357	2026-04-18 13:00:21.972357	P108	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
3d610ff5-6baa-48bc-91e9-54f3a86d5321	Vitti Sthapati Brindo LTD	Md Ishtiaque Zahir Titas (Team Leader), Iqbal Habib, Md. Mehedi Hasan	vittibd@gmail.com	Rejuvenate Zimkhana Sheikh Rasel Park and Baburail Canal Restoration	IMPLEMENTED	APPROVED	SECTION_IV	Dhaka	Bangladesh	23.7104	90.4074	Once a vital trade route for boats carrying jute and rice paddy between the Dhaleshwari and Shitalakshya rivers, Baburail Canal was once deeply embedded in the daily life and economy of Narayanganj. Over time, however, it became overwhelmed by pollution, encroachment, and neglect, turning the area into a City of Conflict & Violence.  The approach was rooted in participatory design, with local communities, policymakers, and various user groups actively involved in the planning process. The initiative also included Environmental and Social Impact Assessments, as well as biodiversity studies, to ensure sustainability and inclusivity.  Through extensive community engagement and dialogue, the project successfully relocated encroachers voluntarily, avoiding forced evictions. This process minimized social conflict and set a precedent for socially responsible urban regeneration. National-level workshops and stakeholder consultations were held to shape a collective vision for the canal’s restoration, ensuring that the design reflected the diverse needs of the community, with an emphasis on inclusivity, sustainability, and social justice.  The 405-meter-long canal now features multifunctional public spaces accessible to all ages, genders, and abilities. These spaces include floating decks, ghats, stepped edges, shaded walkways, and dedicated areas for women, children, seniors, and recreational activities. This design fosters social sustainability, ensuring equitable access to public space for everyone, regardless of background or ability. The revitalized canal also integrates ecological layers, using native plants like Hijol and Jarul to reinforce natural slopes and reduce erosion, while promoting biodiversity and enhancing passive cooling. A Wetland was designed using local aquatic species like water lilies, forming microhabitats that reduce erosion, revive ecosystems, and attract birds and pollinators. A bicycle lane with permeable paving and pedestrian walkways made of locally sourced gravel further supports sustainable urban mobility and groundwater recharge.  The project has transformed the Baburail Canal from a neglected, polluted space into a lively, thriving public area that serves as a cultural and recreational hub. The inclusion of the Fine Arts Institute as a cultural center highlights Narayanganj’s rich tradition of shared cultural expression. Flexible indoor and outdoor venues host exhibitions, performances, and seasonal festivities, making culture an accessible and dynamic part of daily life. Native flowering trees, which bloom with the seasons, create visual experiences that connect visitors emotionally to nature’s cycle, strengthening their sense of place and belonging.  By bridging nature, culture, and justice, the project has not only restored the canal but also strengthened civic trust and community stewardship. It serves as a model for urban regeneration, promoting peaceful, inclusive development through a conflict-free approach. The project demonstrates how urban design can be a tool for sustainability, social justice, and community cohesion, setting a precedent for future regeneration projects in cities facing similar challenges.	Once a vital trade route for boats carrying jute and rice paddy between the Dhaleshwari and Shitalakshya rivers, Baburail Canal was once deeply embedded in the daily life and economy of Narayanganj. Over time, however, it became overwhelmed by pollution, encroachment, and neglect, turning the area into a City of Conflict & Violence.  The approach was rooted in participatory design, with local communities, policymakers, and various user groups actively involved in the planning process. The initiative also included Environmental and Social Impact Assessments, as well as biodiversity studies, to ensure sustainability and inclusivity.  Through extensive community engagement and dialogue, the project successfully relocated encroachers voluntarily, avoiding forced evictions. This process minimized social conflict and set a precedent for socially responsible urban regeneration. National-level workshops and stakeholder consultations were held to shape a collective vision for the canal’s restoration, ensuring that the design reflected the diverse needs of the community, with an emphasis on inclusivity, sustainability, and social justice.  The 405-meter-long canal now features multifunctional public spaces accessible to all ages, genders, and abilities. These spaces include floating decks, ghats, stepped edges, shaded walkways, and dedicated areas for women, children, seniors, and recreational activities. This design fosters social sustainability, ensuring equitable access to public space for everyone, regardless of background or ability. The revitalized canal also integrates ecological layers, using native plants like Hijol and Jarul to reinforce natural slopes and reduce erosion, while promoting biodiversity and enhancing passive cooling. A Wetland was designed using local aquatic species like water lilies, forming microhabitats that reduce erosion, revive ecosystems, and attract birds and pollinators. A bicycle lane with permeable paving and pedestrian walkways made of locally sourced gravel further supports sustainable urban mobility and groundwater recharge.  The project has transformed the Baburail Canal from a neglected, polluted space into a lively, thriving public area that serves as a cultural and recreational hub. The inclusion of the Fine Arts Institute as a cultural center highlights Narayanganj’s rich tradition of shared cultural expression. Flexible indoor and outdoor venues host exhibitions, performances, and seasonal festivities, making culture an accessible and dynamic part of daily life. Native flowering trees, which bloom with the seasons, create visual experiences that connect visitors emotionally to nature’s cycle, strengthening their sense of place and belonging.  By bridging nature, culture, and justice, the project has not only restored the canal but also strengthened civic trust and community stewardship. It serves as a model for urban regeneration, promoting peaceful, inclusive development through a conflict-free approach. The project demonstrates how urban design can be a tool for sustainability, social justice, and community cohesion, setting a precedent for future regeneration projects in cities facing similar challenges.	See detailed description	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-04-18 13:00:08.127452	2026-04-18 13:00:08.127452	P55	Md Ishtiaque Zahir Titas (Team Leader), Iqbal Habib, Md. Mehedi Hasan	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
f6f3cfdf-68ea-41a9-970e-b8009d0184b0	The Oval Partnership Ltd. ; Beijing Institute of Architectural Design Co, Ltd. (BIAD) ; FARMWORK PTE. LTD ; Guangzhou Jimei Design Engineering Co.,Ltd. ; COOPERS Hill GVL Greenview Landscape International Design Group ; LIGHTING PLANNERS ASSOCIATES(S) PTE	Architectural Design Consultant: The Oval Partnership ; Director in-charge: Dr. HAO Lin ; Design Team: Peaker Chu, Ray Wong, Bill So, Giuliano Gatti, Norman Li, Rachel Guo, Ciara Lo, Krystal Tsui, Victor So, Kenny Chau ; Local Collaborating Architect: Bei	linhao@ovalpartnership.com	1 Hotel Haitang Bay, Sanya	IMPLEMENTED	APPROVED	SECTION_IV	Beijing	China	39.9042	116.4074	1 Hotel Haitang Bay lies in a prime location fringing the picturesque shoreline of Hainan Island, a tropical haven off the southern coast of China. The hotel comprises 294 distinctively designed rooms, suites, and villas, ranging from 62 to 1,300m², all with stunning views taking in lush landscaped gardens, the poolside setting, and the sea.   Hailed as the world’s first mission-driven, nature-inspired lifestyle hotel brand, 1 Hotel cultivates the best of environmentally conscious design and sustainable architecture, while encouraging eco-awareness and a sense of wellbeing among its guests. At one level this is evident in the understated refinement and ambience of the architecture and interiors, but that is far from the whole story. Mother Nature is front and centre to the hotel’s philosophical ethos, from the mindfulness of local context and vernacular, through to the revitalising and restorative experiences offered to guests.   The project, a considered and careful renovation, transforms an existing Balinese resort design and structure with attributes to suit a more sustainable tourism model. The original vision was sketched out following a simple yet ambitious objective – to create a unique, sustainable, and inspiring experience that redefines what a 21st century hotel should be. The project is a model in what can be achieved with the creation of a sustainable tourism hub, embracing all that is expected from that genre, while fostering greater understanding and connectivity between guests and the natural world around them.   Bringing together both global awareness of sustainable development and a deep understanding of the local site, the design draws inspiration from the raw, rugged beauty of the island, featuring local and reclaimed materials wherever possible, while optimising efficient use of natural energy sources. The result is an exemplar in place-making, rooted in a compelling narrative and cultural authenticity. Nothing is left to chance – even the off-site farm showcases Hainan’s seasonal produce to reduce the hotel’s food-mile footprint, providing organically-grown fruit and vegetables to be enjoyed by guests as a farm-to-table dining experience.   Encapsulating the biodiversity of the local flora and fauna, and mirroring the natural surroundings, verdant landscaped gardens populate the grounds and soften the exterior edges to the built structures. A lush mangrove tree courtyard offers a tranquil retreat and living green walls planted with local vegetation clothe the staggered roof terraces and semi-open courtyards that permeate the built components. These graduated elevations amplify the integrative quality of the architecture within its landscaped surroundings. Warm timbers and weather resistant metals form a harmonious composition alongside locally sourced lava stones, celebrating the beauty of humble, natural materials.   The classic sun, sand, and sea experience is all-encompassing for those who come here purely for Rest & Relaxation, however the hotel's narrative instinctively broadens into nature-based exploration, projecting the unique story of Hainan. These offerings attract eco-conscious travellers seeking meaningful experiences aligned with their values. Capturing the essence of nature inside and out, the overall impact of the design is a luxurious yet sustainable retreat that revolves around Mother Nature and celebrates the area’s rich natural resources.   Built into the design is the principle of minimising the hotel’s footprint and conserving resources. This integrated approach has driven broader concerns such as construction methods, waste management, material sourcing, and interior decor choices, as well as the finer details — from the off-site 180,000 m² ecological farm to the soft-furnishings and accessories in guestrooms.   Public spaces including the lift lobby, main lobby, and guestroom corridors are cooled by natural ventilation systems. Green roofs and roof gardens, amounting to a total 4,640 m², enhance insulation and shading. These shading devices include timber screening and vertical planting along guestroom corridors, trellis arrangements in the outdoor deck area, a sun-protected sky house and the deeply recessed balconies that wrap around guestrooms.    1 Hotel Haitang Bay Sanya blends stunning design with sustainable development, perfectly aligning with the UIA Guidebook for the 2030 Agenda. Its eco-friendly strategies and commitment to global sustainability have earned recognition through various environmental certifications and awards, including LEED Gold Certification, the HKIA Annual Award, International Design Award, and AIA Hong Kong Honors & Awards. These accolades underscore the hotel’s role in advancing responsible architecture and offering an exceptional, environmentally conscious guest experience.	1 Hotel Haitang Bay lies in a prime location fringing the picturesque shoreline of Hainan Island, a tropical haven off the southern coast of China. The hotel comprises 294 distinctively designed rooms, suites, and villas, ranging from 62 to 1,300m², all with stunning views taking in lush landscaped gardens, the poolside setting, and the sea.   Hailed as the world’s first mission-driven, nature-inspired lifestyle hotel brand, 1 Hotel cultivates the best of environmentally conscious design a