6b1d4849-128c-4da0-a0d0-cc4ca6ae6962	NIVASA	Akhila Ramesh, Meenakshi K, Anitha Mahendra, Aditi S, Jean B	nivasaworks@gmail.com	Kottamedu – A Design-led Rural Housing Initiative	IMPLEMENTED	APPROVED	SECTION_IV	Chengalpet	India	12.6921	79.9899	Kottamedu is a small tribal village located approximately 45 km south of Chennai and 16 km from Chengalpet, Tamil Nadu in the Southern part of India. Comprising 28 Irular tribal families, the village has historically depended on occupations such as unskilled agricultural labor, woodcutting, brick making, and construction work. In the wake of the devastating floods of November–December 2015, Kottamedu suffered significant damage, especially to its fragile housing infrastructure. Recognizing the urgent need for flood-resilient shelter, The Banyan—a Chennai-based NGO focusing on accessible mental health care—sought to bring design-centered development to the village and approached Nivasa for intervention. Nivasa’s response to the challenge was rooted in a belief in holistic rural development through participatory, inclusive, and context-sensitive design. Instead of using a conventional provider model, the team adopted an Asset-Based Approach (ABA), which recognizes the strengths, skills, and potential within communities themselves. This method encouraged ownership and dignity by training the villagers in low-tech construction techniques and enabling them to build their own homes using Stabilised Adobe Blocks (SAB), a sustainable and cost-effective alternative to conventional materials. The intervention at Kottamedu was structured around five pillars: housing and infrastructure, access to education, finance, skilling, and physical and mental health. Guided by the Human Centered Design Toolkit, the project was implemented in three phases: understanding the people, place, and time; design and construction; and capacity building. To ensure the designs were both relevant and aspirational, focused group discussions were conducted to understand community customs, beliefs, and needs. Local vernacular architecture was studied to inform climate-responsive designs. Community engagement extended into creative mapping of their settlement evolution through the traditional art of Kolam, making the design process both participatory and culturally rooted. Homes were designed with provisions for living, sleeping, kitchen, storage, and a shaded thinnai (verandah). Toilets and baths were built as detached units with funds from the Panchayat. Designs incorporated Vaastu principles and offered options for vertical expansion. The cost of construction was subsidized through contributions from HCL Foundation and Kotak Mahindra, with homeowners contributing either monetarily or through labor. The family was assessed by a third party microfinance company to understand their ability to contribute financially. This contribution helps in creating a sense of ownership and dignity for the homeowners.  Capacity building was a core component. Community members participated in block making and construction workshops, gaining skills that could potentially generate future income. Though initial enthusiasm was high, sustaining long-term engagement posed challenges—especially as the scale of the project and the lack of consistent manpower created dependencies on external labor. Also the majority of the community members were anemic and malnourished.  Despite these hurdles, the project demonstrated the potential of ABA in Indian rural housing. One notable success was an all-woman household that took full ownership of their new home, serving as a model for others. The project underscored the importance of local connectors, the unpredictability of materials procurement, and the need for better integration of financial support mechanisms that acknowledge community realities. Kottamedu stands as an evolving experiment—a design-led, community-driven intervention that not only provided shelter but aimed to trigger long-term change in how rural housing is envisioned, executed, and sustained in India.	Kottamedu is a small tribal village located approximately 45 km south of Chennai and 16 km from Chengalpet, Tamil Nadu in the Southern part of India. Comprising 28 Irular tribal families, the village has historically depended on occupations such as unskilled agricultural labor, woodcutting, brick making, and construction work. In the wake of the devastating floods of November–December 2015, Kottamedu suffered significant damage, especially to its fragile housing infrastructure. Recognizing the urgent need for flood-resilient shelter, The Banyan—a Chennai-based NGO focusing on accessible mental health care—sought to bring design-centered development to the village and approached Nivasa for intervention. Nivasa’s response to the challenge was rooted in a belief in holistic rural development through participatory, inclusive, and context-sensitive design. Instead of using a conventional provider model, the team adopted an Asset-Based Approach (ABA), which recognizes the strengths, skills, and potential within communities themselves. This method encouraged ownership and dignity by training the villagers in low-tech construction techniques and enabling them to build their own homes using Stabilised Adobe Blocks (SAB), a sustainable and cost-effective alternative to conventional materials. The intervention at Kottamedu was structured around five pillars: housing and infrastructure, access to education, finance, skilling, and physical and mental health. Guided by the Human Centered Design Toolkit, the project was implemented in three phases: understanding the people, place, and time; design and construction; and capacity building. To ensure the designs were both relevant and aspirational, focused group discussions were conducted to understand community customs, beliefs, and needs. Local vernacular architecture was studied to inform climate-responsive designs. Community engagement extended into creative mapping of their settlement evolution through the traditional art of Kolam, making the design process both participatory and culturally rooted. Homes were designed with provisions for living, sleeping, kitchen, storage, and a shaded thinnai (verandah). Toilets and baths were built as detached units with funds from the Panchayat. Designs incorporated Vaastu principles and offered options for vertical expansion. The cost of construction was subsidized through contributions from HCL Foundation and Kotak Mahindra, with homeowners contributing either monetarily or through labor. The family was assessed by a third party microfinance company to understand their ability to contribute financially. This contribution helps in creating a sense of ownership and dignity for the homeowners.  Capacity building was a core component. Community members participated in block making and construction workshops, gaining skills that could potentially generate future income. Though initial enthusiasm was high, sustaining long-term engagement posed challenges—especially as the scale of the project and the lack of consistent manpower created dependencies on external labor. Also the majority of the community members were anemic and malnourished.  Despite these hurdles, the project demonstrated the potential of ABA in Indian rural housing. One notable success was an all-woman household that took full ownership of their new home, serving as a model for others. The project underscored the importance of local connectors, the unpredictability of materials procurement, and the need for better integration of financial support mechanisms that acknowledge community realities. Kottamedu stands as an evolving experiment—a design-led, community-driven intervention that not only provided shelter but aimed to trigger long-term change in how rural housing is envisioned, executed, and sustained in India.	See detailed description	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-04-18 13:00:08.127452	2026-04-18 13:00:08.127452	P59	Akhila Ramesh, Meenakshi K, Anitha Mahendra, Aditi S, Jean B	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
df455742-ed9d-45fe-a0f7-b7dda046c0b1	Architectural Design & Research Institute of Tsinghua University (THAD)	Zhang Wei, Zhao Jingxian, Huang Haiyang, Wang Yue, Li Xiangyi, Zhang Xiaoqian, Cai Mingcheng, Liang Sisi, Zhang Yuben, LI Ruoxing, LI Shiqi, Yang Gengshu, Chen Mingyang, Zhang Xin, Wang Dan	13126719720@163.com	Nanhu Laboratory: A Scholar's Garden of Science and Industry	IMPLEMENTED	APPROVED	SECTION_IV	Jiaxing	China	30.7521	120.75	Nanhu Laboratory is a key component in Jiaxing City's exploration of the development of a "world-class science and technology innovation hub." The laboratory has attracted a number of renowned scientists to settle in, focusing on cutting-edge technologies, and building an innovation hub and science and technology innovation platform. The project consists of three above-ground floors and an interconnected underground section. The Phase One project will cater to approximately 500 users from three scientific teams, while Phase Two, upon completion, will serve around 1,000 employees from six scientific teams spanning six disciplinary areas. The main feature of the design of Nanhu Laboratory is the skillful integration of manufacturing facilities and scientific research functions with the spatial characteristics of Jiangnan gardens. The architecture adopts a courtyard layout, arranged around the central lake and interconnected by corridors, creating a landscaped spatial whole. Different clusters of research buildings accommodate research teams from various disciplines, promoting interdisciplinary collaboration through its integrated layout.  Nanhu labororaty focuses on bio-pharmaceutical research defeating diseases. Traditional garden design wisdom is used in this project to create healthy environment in harmony with existing water and natural environment. Using the modern reinterpretation of Jiangnan style, we aim to create an immersive scientific research environment with distinctive Chinese characteristics. The project satisfies the various needs of research teams led by multiple academicians through careful planning and customized design. It is rooted in the rich cultural heritage of Jiaxing's Jiangnan water towns, creating an atmosphere that combines science, humanities, and arts. Respect the existing environmental context: The project's planning layout fully respects the existing environmental context, with buildings and landscape corridors arranged around the water system. The spatial design seamlessly integrates with the natural surroundings of the water town, presenting a laboratory layout that reflects the unique characteristics of the Jiangnan region. The architectural form alternates between solidity and voids, with volumes arranged in a harmonious and staggered manner, creating a meandering Jiangnan garden scene. The integration of buildings, courtyards, and gardens achieves an organic fusion, ensuring the continuity of architectural space within the historical context. Accommodate future development: The project considers the possibility of constructing a second phase on the eastern side. Shared service and communication centers are positioned on the eastern side of the first phase. Upon completion of the second phase, these functions will become shared facilities between the two clusters. The core of the spatial structure is based on the "one center, two wings, and nine institutes" approach. The "one center" is the central island landscape area, which, in combination with the existing Lizhuang Port and artificial water system, forms a core area that serves the entire park. The "two wings" refer to the two water systems that surround the central island on the site. The "nine institutes" refer to nine research and development clusters arranged around the central island. The first phase of the project includes three research clusters. Architectural materials reflect the local cultural heritage: The building materials predominantly consist of gray metal and warm white stone, echoing the traditional local architecture characterized by "white walls and black tiles". Using the modern reinterpretation of Jiangnan style, we aim to create an immersive scientific research environment with distinctive Chinese characteristics. The design is rooted in the rich cultural heritage of Jiaxing's Jiangnan water towns, creating an atmosphere that combines science, humanities, and arts. The overall architectural style is modern and simple, in line with the characteristics of scientific research buildings. The architectural details reflect the gentle and delicate style of the Jiangnan region, achieving the inheritance of architectural space in the historical context. Customized details: The project satisfies the various needs of research teams led by multiple academicians through careful planning and customized design. The intricate details reflect customization and respect for scientists' individuality: Certain sections of the facade incorporate unique Chinese calligraphy patterns, reflecting the disciplinary characteristics of the scientists. This inclusion enhances scientists' sense of belonging and happiness within their workspace.	Nanhu Laboratory is a key component in Jiaxing City's exploration of the development of a "world-class science and technology innovation hub." The laboratory has attracted a number of renowned scientists to settle in, focusing on cutting-edge technologies, and building an innovation hub and science and technology innovation platform. The project consists of three above-ground floors and an interconnected underground section. The Phase One project will cater to approximately 500 users from three scientific teams, while Phase Two, upon completion, will serve around 1,000 employees from six scientific teams spanning six disciplinary areas. The main feature of the design of Nanhu Laboratory is the skillful integration of manufacturing facilities and scientific research functions with the spatial characteristics of Jiangnan gardens. The arch