, Wang Yue, Li Xiangyi, Zhang Xiaoqian, Cai Mingcheng, Liang Sisi, Zhang Yuben, LI Ruoxing, LI Shiqi, Yang Gengshu, Chen Mingyang, Zhang Xin, Wang Dan	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
5fe68a54-4bc5-4295-ae3d-c5b37e468de4	Maken Architects: Salma Ben Tanfous and Afef Mejri & Issam Ben Ayed, Architect	Command and Supervision: Head Office of Military Engineering - Financing: BIAT - Client / Project Owner: Municipality of Tunis - Design Team: Maken Architects: Salma Ben Tanfous and Afef Mejri & Issam Ben Ayed, Architect - Project Management: Hafedh Keske	ozelci.sumeyye@gmail.com	DEEP FLOW	PLANNED	APPROVED	SECTION_II	Gölbaşı	Turkey	39.7935	32.8064	This proposal reimagines social housing in Ankara’s İncek-Gölbaşı region through a climate-resilient and community-oriented design. Emphasising passive systems, permaculture-based green roofs, and shared spaces, it supports local food production, water reuse, and bioclimatic comfort. Modular layouts and nature-integrated strategies aim to foster social ties and low-impact living while aligning with multiple Sustainable Development Goals. The design process was guided by Bilal Gökgün, Certified Passive House Designer.	This proposal reimagines social housing in Ankara’s İncek-Gölbaşı region through a climate-resilient and community-oriented design. Emphasising passive systems, permaculture-based green roofs, and shared spaces, it supports local food production, water reuse, and bioclimatic comfort. Modular layouts and nature-integrated strategies aim to foster social ties and low-impact living while aligning with multiple Sustainable Development Goals. The design process was guided by Bilal Gökgün, Certified Passive House Designer.	See detailed description	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-04-18 13:00:21.972357	2026-04-18 13:00:21.972357	P113	Command and Supervision: Head Office of Military Engineering - Financing: BIAT - Client / Project Owner: Municipality of Tunis - Design Team: Maken Architects: Salma Ben Tanfous and Afef Mejri & Issam Ben Ayed, Architect - Project Management: Hafedh Keskes - Engineers: Rachid Nouri, Fredj Maatouk, Kais Tabka, Béchir Ben Zaied, Ahmed Adjam - Lighting Design: Amira Ghorbel - Landscape Architect: Mohamed Mrabet, Sopat - Technical Control Office: Veritas - Contractors: SBF, SOTUFIS, SOGELEC, PROTECFER, KCM, SOFIB, MAS, RUSPINA, HOMYLUXE, SOPAT, TUNISIE-CAROTTAGE, POLYNET…	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
e7b94b83-dbbe-4b32-a545-db2cdbd35050	Unknown	Alejandro Gaona	alejandro_gaona@live.com.mx	The Orchid. Nature and Culture Pavilion	PLANNED	SUBMITTED	SECTION_V	Mexico City	Mexico	19.4326	-99.1332	THE ORCHID Nature and Culture Pavilion  Chapultepec is an iconic urban forest located in the heart of Mexico City. Its origins date back to pre-Hispanic times, and for more than five centuries, it has been the scene of crucial moments in Mexico's history.This proposal is based on the premise of minimizing the impact of bio-cultural activities as requested, so the strategy is based on respect for all existing vegetation on the site.  Conceptually, this is a structure that envelops the existing Orchidarium, thereby preserving the site's pre-existing features and enabling the reuse of most of the current construction, avoiding unnecessary demolitions. To achieve this, a primarily light and transparent raised floor (mezzanine) was chosen over the existing concrete slab. Along its length are six structures whose shapes allude to those of orchids. These structures allow for the creation of a continuous, flexible, visually and materially permeable space, or several autonomous, dynamic spaces for holding large-scale events or events with limited, controlled attendance. This allows for the implementation of the required cultural activities and fosters the appropriate conditions for the plant species. The mezzanine (Exhibition Hall) is accessed either via the plaza-staircase from the north or via a terrace-ramp from the east, maintaining ground-level access from the northwest to the southwest, which crosses the current greenhouse. Once through the entrance plaza, the visitor is suspended over a mostly glass surface, where they are welcomed by a spacious vestibule that invites them to make a fluid journey through a generous gallery-corridor from which they can access any point in the Exhibition Hall. Most of the time, the orchids are present beneath their feet, enhancing the completely immersive sensory experience. This surface rests on a metal structure that houses the light, temperature, and humidity control systems.  Protection and preservation protocols are in place to protect the plants from adverse conditions, the construction process is designed so that most of the Pavilion's components are prefabricated or factory-assembled, simply leveling the existing concrete slab. The assembly is then carried out on-site using cranes, this aims to achieve greater control and make the processes more efficient, as well as minimize impacts and reduce execution times until the facilities are operational. The use of environmentally friendly, durable, and low-maintenance materials has been considered at all times, in addition to the employment of preferably local labor.  Chapultepec Forest Nature and Culture  The Chapultepec Forest Nature and Culture project is a comprehensive plan implemented through three guiding axes: environmental, social, and cultural. It consists of forty-one interventions aimed at consolidating Chapultepec Forest as a collective and cultural space for the entire population of the Metropolitan Area of the Valley of Mexico. This project, in balance with the environment, provides efficient connectivity both within the Forest and with the rest of the city. This plan entails the restoration of several areas of the Four Sections of the Forest to create cultural and environmental venues and the construction of new buildings.  This plan was realized through a collaboration between the Ministry of Culture of the Federal Government, the Ministry of Environment of Mexico City, the Ministry of National Defense, the Government of Mexico City, the Presidency of the Republic and the conceptualization of Gabriel Orozco, who is one of the leading contemporary Mexican artists and has also been a definitive figure in international art for more than three decades, constantly challenging the concept of what art can be, how it is made and what it focuses on.  "The Master Plan conceived by Gabriel Orozco and his team is guided by the principles of permaculture, which include care for the land, care for the people, and equitable distribution. In keeping with these principles, the proposal is ecologically respectful, socially responsible, and economically viable. Chapultepec Nature and Culture reaffirms the park's original purpose as a spring and public forest, significantly enriching all its strata; it improves its environmental potential, strengthening and increasing its green areas; and it doubles its cultural offerings, diversifying its public spaces.”  Kurimanzutto Gallery	THE ORCHID Nature and Culture Pavilion  Chapultepec is an iconic urban forest located in the heart of Mexico City. Its origins date back to pre-Hispanic times, and for more than five centuries, it has been the scene of crucial moments in Mexico's history.This proposal is based on the premise of minimizing the impact of bio-cultural activities as requested, so the strategy is based on respect for all existing vegetation on the site.  Conceptually, this is a structure that envelops the existing Orchidarium, thereby preserving the site's pre-existing features and enabling the reuse of most of the current construction, avoiding unnecessary demolitions. To achieve this, a primarily light and transparent raised floor (mezzanine) was chosen over the existing concrete slab. Along its length are six structures whose shapes allude to those of orchids. These structures allow for the creation of a continuous, flexible, visually and materially permeable space, or several autonomous, dynamic spaces for holding large-scale events or events with limited, controlled attendance. This allows for the implementation of the required cultural activities and fosters the appropriate conditions for the plant species. The mezzanine (Exhibition Hall) is accessed either via the plaza-staircase from the north or via a terrace-ramp from the east, maintaining ground-level access