deral Government, the Ministry of Environment of Mexico City, the Ministry of National Defense, the Government of Mexico City, the Presidency of the Republic and the conceptualization of Gabriel Orozco, who is one of the leading contemporary Mexican artists and has also been a definitive figure in international art for more than three decades, constantly challenging the concept of what art can be, how it is made and what it focuses on.  "The Master Plan conceived by Gabriel Orozco and his team is guided by the principles of permaculture, which include care for the land, care for the people, and equitable distribution. In keeping with these principles, the proposal is ecologically respectful, socially responsible, and economically viable. Chapultepec Nature and Culture reaffirms the park's original purpose as a spring and public forest, significantly enriching all its strata; it improves its environmental potential, strengthening and increasing its green areas; and it doubles its cultural offerings, diversifying its public spaces.”  Kurimanzutto Gallery	See detailed description	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-04-18 13:00:21.972357	2026-04-18 13:00:21.972357	P120	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
1f4425e4-d858-4aec-9e2b-e1f51127f6a6	GPA India	Media	media@gpmindia.com	Sarojini Nagar Redevelopment	IN_PROGRESS	SUBMITTED	SECTION_IV	New Delhi	India	28.6139	77.209	The redevelopment renews a 258-acre neighbourhood into a zero-discharge, climate-resilient, transit-oriented, and self-sufficient community. A context-sensitive approach retains the prominent Sarojini Nagar market as a central urban anchor, along with existing trees and key infrastructure (schools, community centres). Addressing patterns of congestion and encroachment, it incorporates 3967 housing units, multilevel parking, commercial zones, and an organised mobility network integrating metro, vehicular, and pedestrian circulation, with inclusive and low-waste construction to support its sustainability goals. This mixed-use redevelopment catalyses long-term urban and economic revitalisation.	The redevelopment renews a 258-acre neighbourhood into a zero-discharge, climate-resilient, transit-oriented, and self-sufficient community. A context-sensitive approach retains the prominent Sarojini Nagar market as a central urban anchor, along with existing trees and key infrastructure (schools, community centres). Addressing patterns of congestion and encroachment, it incorporates 3967 housing units, multilevel parking, commercial zones, and an organised mobility network integrating metro, vehicular, and pedestrian circulation, with inclusive and low-waste construction to support its sustainability goals. This mixed-use redevelopment catalyses long-term urban and economic revitalisation.	See detailed description	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-04-18 13:00:21.972357	2026-04-18 13:00:21.972357	P122	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
cc12d32e-63ae-4097-b585-8ae883158f37	Unknown	Unknown	control.space.gr@gmail.com	The House of Bauxite – Experimental Information Pavilion from Bauxite Residue Materials	IMPLEMENTED	SUBMITTED	SECTION_I	Aspra Spitia	Greece	38.3617	22.8625	The architectural design process was presented with a series of challenges. The most critical issues were as follows: 1. Regarding the integration in the context of Doxiadis’s modern heritage settlement, the pavilion follows the scale and spatial differentiation of Doxiadis’s buildings (in terms of their relative dimensions and proportions and the fluidity between interior and exterior spaces). The new edifice comes as the materialization of an already existing ‘desire path’ starting from the adjacent public square, defining the main access to it as well as the main exhibition brick wall along it. The pavilion is also connected to the coastal walk and road by means of two new small public places sitting areas, enhancing the attractiveness of this part of the settlement and adding a contemporary landmark and place of activity. 2. Removal materials applied were not standardized industrial ones. Thus, the design evolved a two-way adaptive method feeding the building design model with data steaming out of continuous experiments regarding their physical properties and dimensions, the most appropriate ways to apply them, their relative behavior in the material context of the rest of the standardized building materials prescribed, and their aesthetic optimization. An important decision taken was to invest in the aesthetic correlation between the raw and varied surfacing and coloring of bauxite residue materials and the clarity of the general architectural form and organization. In that sense, what binds the two together is the surrounding nature in a harmonious whole. 3. Following Doxiadis’ early synthesis of architecture, planning and ecology, as well as the overall sustainable agenda of RemovAl, the pavilion was designed following international standards in terms of energy efficiency. It is also needed to mention that no trees had to be cut down to erect the new pavilion, and only two olive trees had to be preemptively relocated for their protection. The wall of the pavilion was insulated with BR brick slips, while the floor of the house and surrounding area with the pavement floor tiles. Two benches and a table produced from KU Leuven with the novel BR hybrid binders were placed within the pavilion. The pavilion will house an exhibition with information and materials on the aluminium value chain and the developed technologies for re-use of the Bauxite residue. In terms of its plan and spatial potential, the pavilion may cater for a series of different open air or closed space events, working together with both its immediate surroundings and the existing garden and square. In time the House of Bauxite will help the local community, and all visitors gain trust and acceptance to BR derived building materials.	The architectural design process was presented with a series of challenges. The most critical issues were as follows: 1. Regarding the integration in the context of Doxiadis’s modern heritage settlement, the pavilion follows the scale and spatial differentiation of Doxiadis’s buildings (in terms of their relative dimensions and proportions and the fluidity between interior and exterior spaces). The new edifice comes as the materialization of an already existing ‘desire path’ starting from the adjacent public square, defining the main access to it as well as the main exhibition brick wall along it. The pavilion is also connected to the coastal walk and road by means of two new small public places sitting areas, enhancing the attractiveness of this part of the settlement and adding a contemporary landmark and place of activity. 2. Removal materials applied were not standardized industrial ones. Thus, the design evolved a two-way adaptive method feeding the building design model with data steaming ou