5f7b9e89-78fe-4626-abfa-5ba2dddcfa18	TU Delft	S Corbo	s.corbo@tudelft.nl	EXTERIORLESS. The(Re)Design of the Ordinary	PLANNED	SUBMITTED	SECTION_I	Amsterdam	Netherlands	52.3676	4.9041	Please see here: https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/hns2rtw0abywus6e8esv2/EXTERIORLESS_The-Design-of-the-Ordinary_outcome.pdf?rlkey=ebikgcr2hwtknpi96ycaq3i55&dl=0	Please see here: https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/hns2rtw0abywus6e8esv2/EXTERIORLESS_The-Design-of-the-Ordinary_outcome.pdf?rlkey=ebikgcr2hwtknpi96ycaq3i55&dl=0	See detailed description	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-04-18 13:00:31.097334	2026-04-18 13:00:31.097334	P140	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
7780940b-1ff3-4a6e-a74c-e0a5ccdd62ad	Muraji Architects	Unknown	takeo@muraji.jp	Ogikubo Family Residence	IMPLEMENTED	SUBMITTED	SECTION_IV	Tokyo	Japan	35.6762	139.6503	On the west side of the first floor, there is a shared space open to the community, including a lounge, meeting space, and workshop, designed to be easily accessible to the community. On the east side, there are five residential units. Around the first floor, there is a wooden deck and terrace that can be used in conjunction with the interior and exterior spaces. On the second floor, there is a lounge with a light well in the center, which serves as a shared space for residents and a place for them to connect with each other. On the second floor, five residential units are clustered around each hall on the east and west sides, creating a spatial composition that connects residents to society in stages, from private to public, from the residential units to the halls, then to the second-floor lounge, and finally to the shared spaces on the first floor. This allows residents to choose where they want to connect with society at their own pace.  On the third floor, there are two bathrooms, one for owners and one for shared use. A schedule is set for their use, and residents declare when they want to use them. Outside, there is a rooftop garden that is used for various purposes, such as drying laundry and resting. It is also used as a place to wait for the bath and relax after bathing.  The skylight in the second-floor lounge is equipped with a rainwater sprinkler system for water cooling. Rainwater is first stored in an underground tank, then pumped up and sprinkled onto the glass, contributing to energy conservation while also providing a soothing effect through the movement of the water. These features were realized through a design process involving not only residents but also members of the local community. The owner's vision of creating connections among people, including the community, through multi-generational cohabitation has been realized. Community issues such as childcare support, health consultation rooms, and study sessions have been addressed, contributing to the welfare, health, and education of the community.  These initiatives align with the SDGs: ③ Ensure healthy lives and promote well-being for all, ⑪ Make cities and human settlements inclusive, safe, resilient, and sustainable, ⑬ Take urgent action to combat climate change and its impacts, and ⑰ Strengthen the means of implementation and revitalize the global partnership for sustainable development.	On the west side of the first floor, there is a shared space open to the community, including a lounge, meeting space, and workshop, designed to be easily accessible to the community. On the east side, there are five residential units. Around the first floor, there is a wooden deck and terrace that can be used in conjunction with the interior and exterior spaces. On the second floor, there is a lounge with a light well in the center, which serves as a shared space for residents and a place for them to connect with each other. On the second floor, five residential units are clustered around each hall on the east and west sides, creating a spatial composition that connects residents to society in stages, from private to public, from the residential units to the halls, then to the second-floor lounge, and finally to the shared spaces on the first floor. This allows residents to choose where they want to connect with society at their own pace.  On the third floor, there are two bathrooms, one for owners and one for shared use. A schedule is set for their use, and residents declare when they want to use them. Outside, there is a rooftop garden that is used for various purposes, such as drying laundry and resting. It is also used as a place to wait for the bath and relax after bathing.  The skylight in the second-floor lounge is equipped with a rainwater sprinkler system for water cooling. Rainwater is first 