490616a0-75e5-42bc-b68e-be1bf7c9dc2d	Atelier Global	Unknown	ag-brand@atelier-global.com	Commune STORE	IMPLEMENTED	SUBMITTED	SECTION_IV	Wuyishan	China	27.7568	118.0352	Commune STORE, located in the scenic Houyuan Village of Northern Fujian, transforms an abandoned primary school into a vibrant hub celebrating local rice culture and the natural environment. Our design harmonizes the village’s agricultural heritage with sustainable practices, preserving its charm while introducing modern functionality. Our architectural strategy focuses on restoration, utilizing materials like steel reinforcements and locally sourced elements to create a cohesive roof that serves as a lookout and communal space. This fosters a seamless connection between indoor and outdoor areas, with key features such as an infinity pool and terraced layout enhancing the relationship with the surrounding landscape. By prioritizing local labor and materials, Commune STORE engages the community and promotes sustainability. The project aims to revive traditional rice farming and empower youth, celebrating the village’s cultural spirit while forging a sustainable future where nature and community thrive together.	Commune STORE, located in the scenic Houyuan Village of Northern Fujian, transforms an abandoned primary school into a vibrant hub celebrating local rice culture and the natural environment. Our design harmonizes the village’s agricultural heritage with sustainable practices, preserving its charm while introducing modern functionality. Our architectural strategy focuses on restoration, utilizing materials like steel reinforcements and locally sourced elements to create a cohesive roof that serves as a lookout and communal space. This fosters a seamless connection between indoor and outdoor areas, with key features such as an infinity pool and terraced layout enhancing the relationship with the surrounding landscape. By prioritizing local labor and materials, Commune STORE engages the community and promotes sustainability. The project aims to revive traditional rice farming and empower youth, celebrating the village’s cultural spirit while forging a sustainable future where nature and community thrive together.	See detailed description	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-04-18 13:00:31.097334	2026-04-18 13:00:31.097334	P139	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
842aabac-b113-47f1-a01a-5d1ea17f21b5	HOV	David Raponi	hov@hov.it	FLOLONY (Float-On/Float-Off/Colony)	IMPLEMENTED	SUBMITTED	SECTION_I	Everywhere	Unknown	\N	\N	FLOLONY is a changeable buoyancy floating housing unit, made up of a mobile naval architecture equipped with autonomous energy and developed on a geometry which enables the vessel to adapt to any marine conditions, even the extreme ones. The structure has a large surface in contact with the open space and the upper part, always out of water, is controlled by systems that can guarantee the maximum supply of vital elements (light and water), useful for the residential/productive metabolism of the colony.	FLOLONY conceives a housing unit in a marine environment, where a community of individuals chooses to live a short or long part of their lives on the open sea. As for the essential services for life the unit is autonomous and, according to its potential configurations and equipments, it can be independent (therefore with no need of external supplies) for periods varying from a few months to several years. Moving along marine routes within the temperate/equatorial zones and following the direction of the main streams, the colony maintains its energy balance using Ocean Thermal Energy Conversion – OTEC, sun energy, wave power and the methods of collection and use of high temperature waters originating from deep thermal sources.\r\nFLOLONY is a structure made of double and triple steel layers and aluminum. Its changeable buoyancy is regulated by compensation basins that permit a float-on/float-off range of about 120ft (36.5m). This allows it to face extreme marine conditions and, in the same way, to keep its buoyancy on the surface level when there are optimum marine conditions.\r\nThe unit is divided into 19 main decks and 10 secondary (or partial) decks, for a total amount of 29 levels. In the immersed section, besides the compensation basins, there are fish farming basins, habitats for farming products, systems for the collection and treatment of precipitations, a desalination plant, storages of  potable water and fuel, emergency diesel/electric engine-generators, an electric propulsive system, a stock area for the converters of wave power, technical special areas, etc.\r\nAccommodation units, cultural and entertaining spaces, schools, scientific and medical laboratories, pilot house areas, bridges, technical and navigation instruments, mechanical plants for air change/treatment, production workshops and laboratories, green areas, play and sport areas, etc. are situated in the changeable buoyancy section and in the emerging section.\r\n\r\nTechnical Sheet\r\n\r\nLength: 395.33 m (1,297 ft)\r\nBeam: 269.65 m (885 ft)\r\nHeight: 180.75 m (593 ft)\r\nVolume: 6,107,742.00 m3\r\nEstimated construction cost: $ 2.97 billion\r\nDraft: 98.45 (323 ft) to 134.72 m (442 ft)\r\nDecks: 29\r\nInstalled power:\r\n2 diesel generators × 15,200 kW = 30.4 MW\r\n2 diesel generators × 11,400 kW = 22.8 MW\r\n4 strips (with 7 oscillating sensors each) x 6,700 kW = 26.8 MW\r\nHigh Concentration Photovoltaics Panels x 2,600 kW  = 2.6 MW\r\n2 OTEC Systems (Ocean Thermal Energy Conversion) x 10,500 kW = 21 MW\r\nTotal power: 103.6 MW on-board electricity supply	In this project simulation a realistic social model is applied to the structure: the building cost of the colony is divided into shares per person according to the number of inhabitants, as well as the costs for maintenance, services, crew, etc. Nevertheless, the structure of the colony does not exclude the implementation of more supportive social models, in which the participation to livelihood activities and services is equally distributed among the occupants, if a crew is not present, and the professional activities are carried out by the inhabitants themselves (doctors, pilots, engineers, on board and production technicians, teachers, instructors, operators, etc.)\r\nIn both cases the colony represents a complex organism and activates a system of relationships among the inhabitants that is typical of small and tightly connected groups, and it also represents an alternative to the social models characterized by collective intelligence. Both models, which are antithetical ones according to the bifurcation theory, could be the ongoing result of the IT era.	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	IFF6	David Raponi_HOV	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
202400b1-def8-40e2-90f5-6adf99906981	Freelance Architect	Sümeyye Özelçi	13126719720@163.com	Yuanbo Building: Hub of Rural Art Teachers	IMPLEMENTED	APPROVED	SECTION_IV	Zhuhai	China	22.271	113.5767	Zhuhai, situated in southern China's bustling 'Greater Bay Area', stands as a beacon of development. The Zhuhai Campus of Beijing Normal University provides funded education for students from disadvantaged regions, with over 70% of enrollees being female. These students receive education and then return to their hometowns as educators in rural schools. Our project entails the renovation of the Yuanbo building, which will serve as the teaching facility for the School of Design and as an educational hub for rural art teachers. In the era of virtual reality, the project attempts to bring design education back to humanity and nature. The continuous roof loop offers spaces for feeling nature and exchanging ideas. The atrium with big stairs is the exhibition and show space for students. The square courtyard with the original tree can be used as outdoor exhibition space. The round courtyard offers a stage with lights where students can hold small concerts. Students find inspiration from the building in the design studios. Make best use of original structure and prefabricated components. Yuanbo Building occupies a key location in the linear plan of the campus. Originally constructed in 2005, this old teaching building was damaged during a super typhoon in 2017. Its rundown appearance detracted from the beautiful campus landscape. The client wanted to transform it into a landmark that harmonized with the surrounding environment at low costs. The main construction process is strictly limited during the summer and winter vacations. Instead of tearing anything down, we developed a dry-hanging brick wall system and an aluminum window casing system. This new facade has limited connection points with the original structure. Prefabricated components could be installed very quickly.  The new facade maximizes natural light and ventilation, enhancing indoor environment quality. By strategically placing openings in the atrium walls and installing triangular scuttles on the platform, sunlight is directed into previously dark areas. Additionally, the redesigned window casing system blocks excess heat and direct sunlight, promoting energy efficiency. These measures create a healthier indoor environment while reducing energy costs. A continuous "hiking" loop on the rooftops provides safe and beautiful exercise spaces, ideal for female students. The campus playground's distant location prompted us to repurpose unused roof areas into exercise spaces. We introduced an innovative continuous loop of stairs and corridors, seamlessly connecting roofs, courtyards, and indoor areas. At each intersection, elevated platforms with grass or wooden flooring create dynamic spaces of various sizes and heights. These once-neglected roof spaces now offer stunning views of the surrounding nature, transformed into ideal exercise areas. A loop lighting system ensures safety for nighttime use, resembling a hiking trail above the rooftops, reminiscent of local mountain hikes, a popular city exercise activity. The design preserves original trees and integrates the building seamlessly into the stunning natural landscape. Surrounded by lush mountains and a central lake, Yuanbo Building stands as a campus landmark at its heart. We've safeguarded all existing trees and added two courtyards within the building. The square courtyard provides a new resting area around a preserved tree, doubling as a temporary outdoor exhibition space. The round courtyard serves as a venue for student concerts. Both courtyards, along with the main entrance, are linked by an art path, harmonizing the buildings with nature and the campus. The new design sparks innovation in education. Yuanbo Building has become a vibrant center for communication. In the era of virtual reality and digital media, we are attempting to bring art and design back to humanity and nature. A glass roof was put above the center open- air cube. Stairs were reconnected inside. This atrium has been exhibition and show space for students. Abandoned classrooms are joined together to form a multi-functional exhibition hall. The courtyards and outdoor corridors can hold exhibitions, ceremonies, and even open-air markets. Through our design, the Yuanbo building has transformed from a closed, dilapidated structure into the vibrant hub of the entire campus. The indoor environment is now healthier, with a rooftop exercise space catering to users, particularly female students, for exercise in a natural setting. Moreover, the building is open to both campus and community, maximizing the impact of art education and healthy spaces.	Zhuhai, situated in southern China's bustling 'Greater Bay Area', stands as a beacon of development. The Zhuhai Campus of Beijing Normal University provides funded education for students from disadvantaged regions, with over 70% of enrollees being female. These students receive education and then return to their hometowns as educators in rural schools. Our project entails the renovation of the Yuanbo building, which will serve as the teaching facility for the School of Design and as an educational hub for rural art teachers. In the era of virtual reality, the project attempts to bring design education back to humanity and nature. The continuous roof loop offers spaces for feeling nature and exchanging ideas. The atrium with big stairs is the exhibition and show space for students. The square courtyard with the original tree can be used as outdoor exhibition space. The round courtyard offers a stage with lights where students can hold small concerts. Students find inspiration from the building in the design studios. Make best use of original structure and prefabricated components. Yuanbo Building occupies a key location in the linear plan of the campus. Originally constructed in 2005