4cacbf90-8ae3-4634-b4f1-9d1df6fa9a30	Pieris.Architects, HELLENIC REPUBLIC ATTICA REGION	Pieros Pieris, Stella Pieri, Constantinos Pieris, Antonia Kolozi, Katerina Kalogridi, Alexandros Mimidis, Evi Katsikoudi	info@pierisarchitects.com	Antonis Tritsis Metropolitan Park	PLANNED	APPROVED	SECTION_I	Athens	Greece	37.9838	23.7275	The redevelopment of Antonis Tritsis Park marks a pivotal urban intervention in the heart of western Athens—one that seeks to revitalize one of the city’s largest public green spaces into a model of inclusive, adaptive, and environmentally conscious urban design. Currently at the design stage, the project reimagines the park not simply as a site for leisure, but as a living system that fosters community resilience, ecological regeneration, and new forms of social and cultural interaction.  The 1,200-acre park occupies a unique position within the urban fabric, offering both ecological value and social potential. The redevelopment proposal builds upon the park’s existing natural assets—wetlands, lakes, native woodland areas, and open meadows—while introducing a cohesive spatial strategy that enhances accessibility, functionality, and ecological coherence. A redesigned circulation system connects key entrances to diverse zones of activity and engagement, encouraging users to move fluidly between quiet natural areas and dynamic programmatic nodes.  The masterplan envisions a series of thematic zones, each catering to different user needs and experiences. Recreational areas include a range of facilities that support active lifestyles—multi-use sports courts, cycling paths, walking trails, parkour routes, and nature play spaces. Restorative environments such as sensory gardens, shaded groves, and tranquil lakeside clearings promote mental well-being and social inclusivity, particularly for children, seniors, and individuals with limited mobility.  One of the project’s key innovations lies in its adaptive reuse strategy. Disused buildings within the park—most notably the former INEDIVIM structures—are being repurposed into co-working hubs, studios, and community workshops. These spaces will support local entrepreneurship, digital work, and cultural programming, transforming the park into a productive landscape that bridges nature and contemporary forms of work and learning. In this way, the redevelopment introduces a hybrid typology for urban parks: not just spaces for relaxation, but also platforms for creativity, collaboration, and knowledge exchange.  Cultural infrastructure is another essential component. The plan integrates outdoor cinemas, amphitheaters, and flexible performance areas that can host events ranging from concerts and film screenings to community forums and educational activities. These interventions are envisioned as low-impact, open-air structures that blend into the landscape, offering a year-round program of events while minimizing environmental disruption.  Sustainability and environmental performance are foundational principles across all phases of the project. The landscape strategy emphasizes native planting, drought-resistant species, and the reestablishment of natural habitats to support local biodiversity. Rainwater harvesting systems, permeable paving, and passive cooling design techniques are incorporated to reduce the park’s environmental footprint. Low-impact materials, solar-powered amenities, and energy-efficient lighting will be implemented to ensure long-term sustainability with minimal maintenance demand.  The project also recognizes the role of the park as an educational and civic resource. Interpretive trails, community gardens, and participatory workshops will offer visitors the opportunity to learn about ecology, urban farming, climate resilience, and sustainable living. A strong emphasis is placed on community involvement throughout the implementation process, with local residents, schools, and civic organizations actively engaged in shaping the programming, design decisions, and stewardship of the park.  Accessibility and equity are at the forefront of the spatial reorganization. The new design prioritizes barrier-free circulation, inclusive play areas, and dedicated zones for vulnerable user groups. Every aspect of the park’s redevelopment has been guided by a commitment to universal design, ensuring that it can be enjoyed and used by all members of the community—regardless of age, ability, or background.  The implementation will proceed in structured phases, beginning with upgrades to core infrastructure, hydrology, and circulation networks. Subsequent phases will focus on ecological restoration, cultural programming, and the activation of innovation zones. A monitoring framework will accompany each stage, allowing for the evaluation of social, environmental, and economic impacts over time.  In its totality, the redevelopment of Antonis Tritsis Park represents a shift in how public space is conceived and delivered. It positions urban nature not as a backdrop, but as an active agent in the production of health, creativity, and social resilience. As a prototype for nature-based urbanism, the project demonstrates how multifunctional public landscapes can address the complex challenges of 21st-century cities while fostering a deeper connection between people and place.	The redevelopment of Antonis Tritsis Park marks a pivotal urban intervention in the heart of western Athens—one that seeks to revitalize one of the city’s largest public green spaces into a model of inclusive, adaptive, and environmentally conscious urban design. Currently at the design stage, the project reimagines the park not simply as a site for leisure, but as a living system that fosters community resilience, ecological regeneration, and new forms of social and cultural interaction.  The 1,200-acre park occupies a unique position within the urban fabric, offering both ecological value and social potential. The redevelopment proposal builds upon the park’s exist