a backdrop, but as an active agent in the production of health, creativity, and social resilience. As a prototype for nature-based urbanism, the project demonstrates how multifunctional public landscapes can address the complex challenges of 21st-century cities while fostering a deeper connection between people and place.	See detailed description	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-04-18 13:00:39.923528	2026-04-18 13:00:39.923528	P160	Pieros Pieris, Stella Pieri, Constantinos Pieris, Antonia Kolozi, Katerina Kalogridi, Alexandros Mimidis, Evi Katsikoudi	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
071814f8-7a96-4eba-b6f7-5aaa22633daf	Pieris.Architects	Stella Pieri, Pieros Pieris, Romina Routsi, Aggeliki Chronopoulou	info@pierisarchitects.com	Athletic & Cultural Park	PLANNED	APPROVED	SECTION_I	Athens	Greece	37.9838	23.7275	The Athletic & Cultural Park in Ayia Paraskevi, Athens, is a transformative urban project that combines athletic, cultural, and recreational facilities within a green, sustainable environment. Designed to serve as a model for sustainable urban living, the park integrates various United Nations Sustainable Development Goals (SDGs) to promote health, inclusivity, innovation, climate action, and biodiversity.  Central to the park’s concept is SDG 3: Good Health and Well-Being. It offers a range of sports and recreational amenities such as football pitches, skateparks, yoga zones, outdoor gyms, and playgrounds that encourage physical activity across all age groups. Beyond fitness, the park’s extensive greenery—with shaded areas, tree groves, and quiet corridors—supports mental health by providing peaceful spaces for relaxation and reflection. This holistic approach fosters both physical and psychological well-being for visitors.  The park also advances SDG 9: Industry, Innovation, and Infrastructure by incorporating innovative urban design elements that connect its different sections through pedestrian and cycling paths. These promote sustainable transportation and reduce car dependency, benefiting both the environment and public health. Features like elevated wooden walkways and artistically designed treehouses encourage creativity and community involvement. Additionally, historic military buildings have been adaptively reused as workshops and cultural centers, blending heritage preservation with contemporary needs and supporting sustainable infrastructure.  In line with SDG 11: Sustainable Cities and Communities, the park prioritizes social inclusion and accessibility. It creates a welcoming environment where people from diverse backgrounds can gather, interact, and engage in outdoor activities. The design emphasizes walkability, cycling, and outdoor fitness, reducing carbon emissions and promoting a stronger sense of community. By offering cultural and recreational amenities, the park contributes to building a resilient and inclusive urban space that meets the needs of local residents.  The park addresses SDG 13: Climate Action through sustainable practices such as green landscaping that mitigates the urban heat island effect and natural stormwater management via permeable surfaces and green roofs. Reusing existing structures reduces the environmental impact associated with new construction. These efforts enhance the park’s resilience to climate challenges and demonstrate how urban design can contribute to environmental sustainability.  Lastly, the park supports SDG 15: Life on Land by emphasizing biodiversity and ecological preservation. Native plant species and green corridors create habitats for local wildlife and reduce the need for irrigation, fostering a healthier ecosystem. This connection to nature encourages visitors to appreciate and protect the environment.  Overall, the Athletic & Cultural Park exemplifies how urban spaces can address global challenges through sustainable design, health promotion, cultural engagement, and environmental stewardship. It stands as a vibrant community hub that enriches the quality of life for all its visitors while serving as a replicable model for future urban development.	The Athletic & Cultural Park in Ayia Paraskevi, Athens, is a transformative urban project that combines athletic, cultural, and recreational facilities within a green, sustainable environment. Designed to serve as a model for sustainable urban living, the park integrates various United Nations Sustainable Development Goals (SDGs) to promote health, inclusivity, innovation, climate action, and biodiversity.  Central to the park’s concept is SDG 3: Good Health and Well-Being. It offers a range 