es and demonstrate how urban design can contribute to environmental sustainability.  Lastly, the park supports SDG 15: Life on Land by emphasizing biodiversity and ecological preservation. Native plant species and green corridors create habitats for local wildlife and reduce the need for irrigation, fostering a healthier ecosystem. This connection to nature encourages visitors to appreciate and protect the environment.  Overall, the Athletic & Cultural Park exemplifies how urban spaces can address global challenges through sustainable design, health promotion, cultural engagement, and environmental stewardship. It stands as a vibrant community hub that enriches the quality of life for all its visitors while serving as a replicable model for future urban development.	See detailed description	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-04-18 13:00:39.923528	2026-04-18 13:00:39.923528	P162	Stella Pieri, Pieros Pieris, Romina Routsi, Aggeliki Chronopoulou	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
7a74a9d5-950b-4c31-a5ca-b1172d2dcbcb	Beijing Uiniversity of Civil Engineering and Architecture; OnEarth Studio; Xi'an University of Architecture and Technology	Jun Mu, Wei Jiang, Tiegang Zhou, Sharon Show, Zhuqing Chang, Qiangqiang Li, Weiwei Lu, Zengfei Liang, Yan Huang, Zhengyang Wang	mujunmail@163.com	Macha Village Community Center	IMPLEMENTED	APPROVED	SECTION_IV	Huining	China	35.6854	105	1.Demands for a Village Community Centre When asking villagers about their feelings regarding the developed rammed-earth houses, the team sometimes received responses such as, “It is very strong and comfortable, but it still looks ‘earthy’…” In their minds, their traditions often seem like something only the poor must endure. Further studies and demonstrations are needed to showcase what earth architecture and rural living could become in the future. Macha is a representative poor village in the core region of the Loess Plateau, characterized by the world’s largest loess deposit, low economic levels, and a fragile ecological environment. Earth, the most abundant local resource in the region, has been widely used for constructing various farming facilities and dwellings, exemplified by the rammed-earth dwelling courtyard with a bare yard and an underground cellar for collecting and storing rainwater. Like many poor villages in China, Macha has been declining over the years. Most adult men work away from the village, leaving their children and fields to women and the elderly. In this context of a “hollow village,” the village’s traditions and original spirit are being lost. In late 2012, through collaboration between the team and Macha’s village committee, a sub-project for a village community centre was launched on a sloping wasteland beside the crossroads, offering a good view facing the eastern valley and serving all community groups. 2. Design In response to villagers’ demands, the centre combines a Chinese medicine clinic, nursery, library, stage, shop, and a multi-functional hall, organized according to the local traditional concept of a “three-section courtyard.” This design ensures each functional block has maximum exposure to daylight, a good view of the eastern valley, cross-ventilation in summer, and protection from cold winds in winter. By following the sloping topography facing the valley, all outdoor and indoor spaces are carefully arranged on three terraced levels. The design considers both the villagers’ current needs and reasonable flexibility for future sustainable development. The 0.5-meter-thick rammed-earth walls serve as thermal mass, effectively balancing indoor temperature and humidity. Enhanced waterproofing eliminates the need for plastering, allowing the unique texture of rammed earth to be felt and seen, expressing its natural aesthetic. Upgraded structural elements, such as roofing and window systems, are designed to fulfill their functions while serving as a demonstration for craftsmen and professionals. The rammed-earth technology was further developed through architectural design to provide better spatial experiences. The local tradition of rainwater collection has been preserved and enhanced with a roof-ground-based system. A wind turbine system harnesses valley winds to meet the centre’s daily electricity needs. 3. Performance Through two summer workshops involving over 80 student volunteers and 30 villagers, the centre was constructed and began operating in April 2016. The two-year construction process also served as a training and education opportunity for villagers and university students from mainland China, Hong Kong, and overseas. The village centre, primarily built with on-site resources, now stands harmoniously, as if it grew from the ground. It functions as a community hub and a demonstration and training base for the central government in upgraded rammed-earth technology. Using a DIY manual as a guide, the team and well-trained Macha villagers have trained over 300 craftsmen from the region. The centre has also facilitated programs to bring resources and training in agriculture, handicrafts, and education to Macha, fostering sustainable self-promotion and development through various activities. In the past year, with support from a team social worker and the new public space, the original leather-silhouette drama group, composed of twelve elders and dissolved ten years ago, was revived. The 78-year-old Chinese medicine doctor in Macha was invited to the clinic to serve villagers with the assistance of his grandson, his last student. A young family returned from the city to operate the shop, using internet resources to provide e-shopping services for villagers. Children now regularly play and read in the library after school. In the multi-functional hall, women enjoy weekly self-organized activities, such as dancing, embroidery, and movie screenings. As one elder remarked, the original soul of Macha seems to be returning.	1.Demands for a Village Community Centre When asking villagers about their feelings regarding the developed rammed-earth houses, the team sometimes received responses such as, “It is very strong and comfortable, but it still looks ‘earthy’…” In their minds, their traditions often seem like something only the poor must endure. Further studies and demonstrations are needed to showcase what earth architecture and rural living could become in the future. Macha is a representative poor village in the core region of the Loess Plateau, characterized by the world’s largest loess deposit, low economic levels, and a fragile ecological environment. Earth, the most abundant local resource in the region, has been widely used for constructing various farming facilities and dwellings, exemplified by the rammed-earth dwelling courtyard with a bare yard and an underground cellar for collecting and storing rainwater. Like many poor villages in China, Macha has been declining over the years. Most adult men work away from the village, leaving their children and 