he two-year construction process also served as a training and education opportunity for villagers and university students from mainland China, Hong Kong, and overseas. The village centre, primarily built with on-site resources, now stands harmoniously, as if it grew from the ground. It functions as a community hub and a demonstration and training base for the central government in upgraded rammed-earth technology. Using a DIY manual as a guide, the team and well-trained Macha villagers have trained over 300 craftsmen from the region. The centre has also facilitated programs to bring resources and training in agriculture, handicrafts, and education to Macha, fostering sustainable self-promotion and development through various activities. In the past year, with support from a team social worker and the new public space, the original leather-silhouette drama group, composed of twelve elders and dissolved ten years ago, was revived. The 78-year-old Chinese medicine doctor in Macha was invited to the clinic to serve villagers with the assistance of his grandson, his last student. A young family returned from the city to operate the shop, using internet resources to provide e-shopping services for villagers. Children now regularly play and read in the library after school. In the multi-functional hall, women enjoy weekly self-organized activities, such as dancing, embroidery, and movie screenings. As one elder remarked, the original soul of Macha seems to be returning.	See detailed description	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-04-18 13:00:39.923528	2026-04-18 13:00:39.923528	P163	Jun Mu, Wei Jiang, Tiegang Zhou, Sharon Show, Zhuqing Chang, Qiangqiang Li, Weiwei Lu, Zengfei Liang, Yan Huang, Zhengyang Wang	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
6e1ff324-3017-4e7c-b83c-9c007bacd645	Pieris.Architects, A.P Christou & Associates, MITSIDES, SAMUEL + ASSOCIATES, Dr. Matthaios Santamouris, Alexandros Vlachopoulos, G & N SCHUBERT CONSULTANTS, MDA CYPRUS LLC	Pieris.Architects	info@pierisarchitects.com	Cynergy Bank HQ	PLANNED	APPROVED	SECTION_I	Nicosia	Cyprus	35.1856	33.3823	The design for the Cynergy Bank Headquarters in Nicosia responds to the evolving role of financial institutions in the 21st century—where cultural heritage, environmental responsibility, and human well-being are as important as economic performance. Conceived for an international competition, the proposal received an Honorable Mention for its innovative integration of the United Nations Sustainable Development Goals (SDGs), delivering an architecture that is both visionary and grounded. From its agricultural roots to its urban future, the bank’s identity is deeply embedded in the building's architecture. The white, faceted aluminum façade, patterned with delicate perforations resembling a wheat field, reflects the bank's origins and pays homage to its emblem, Demeter—the goddess of agriculture. More than a visual motif, this façade acts as a responsive skin, filtering light and reducing solar heat gain, setting the stage for a holistic approach to sustainability. At the heart of the building, a sculptural concrete and glass volume houses a 500-seat concert hall and convention center, opening the bank’s presence to the wider public and reinforcing its civic role. This multifunctional cultural hub aligns with SDG 9 (Industry, Innovation, and Infrastructure), by promoting resilient infrastructure that serves both business and community functions, creating spaces that are adaptable, inclusive, and forward-thinking. The building’s spatial organization supports SDG 3 (Good Health and Well-being) through biophilic design and human-centered planning. Six levels of open-plan offices are arranged around a central atrium filled with native Cypriot plants and vertical garden panels. These green elements improve air quality, reduce stress, and establish a daily connection with nature, enhancing both the health and productivity of employees. The internal plaza, accessible from multiple levels, becomes a living landscape that supports informal interaction and movement—fostering both social cohesion and well-being. Above the atrium, a dramatic energy roof integrates transparent photovoltaic panels and light diffusers. This sculptural feature maximizes the use of natural light while generating renewable energy on-site, reducing reliance on fossil fuels and lowering operational carbon emissions. This design strategy directly supports SDG 7 (Affordable and Clean Energy) and SDG 13 (Climate Action) by actively incorporating clean energy production into the building's infrastructure and reducing environmental impact through passive design. The project's mechanical and structural systems were designed with long-term sustainability in mind, following the principles of SDG 12 (Responsible Consumption and Production). The design team prioritized the use of low-impact materials, high-efficiency HVAC systems, and a modular layout that allows for future adaptability. Rainwater harvesting, greywater recycling, and the use of native landscaping minimize resource consumption and ensure the building operates with ecological sensitivity. The flexible, collaborative workspaces also respond to SDG 8 (Decent Work and Economic Growth) by promoting a healthy and adaptable work environment that encourages innovation, transparency, and equity. The workplace strategy avoids rigid hierarchies, instead favoring open, daylit spaces that foster inclusivity, creativity, and professional growth—creating a setting in which both people and ideas can thrive. Finally, the project's commitment to SDG 15 (Life on Land) is evident in its landscape design and integration of biodiversity. Indigenous plant species populate the central plaza and vertical gardens, supporting local ecosystems and reducing the need for artificial irrigation. This ecological sensitivity strengthens the building’s connection to place, creating a meaningful relationship between the built and natural environments. Developed in collaboration with an expert team—including A.P Christou & Associates (Structural Study), MITSIDES, SAMUEL + ASSOCIATES (Mechanical Study), Dr. Matthaios Santamouris (Sustainability Consultant), Alexandros Vlachopoulos (Specialized Consultant), G & N Schubert Consultants (Acoustics), and MDA CYPRUS LLC (Quantity Surveying)—the Cynergy Bank Headquarters offers a comprehensive and actionable blueprint for future-ready institutional architecture. By uniting design excellence with the principles of the SDGs, the Cynergy Bank Headquarters transcends the conventional office typology. It is not only a place of work but a cultural, ecological, and social catalyst—anchored in heritage, shaped by innovation, and committed to the well-being of both people and the planet.	The design for the Cynergy Bank Headquarters in Nicosia responds to the evolving role of financial institutions in the 21st century—where cultural heritage, environmental responsibility, and human well-being are as important as economic performance. Conceived for an international competition, the proposal received an Honorable Mention for its innovative integration of the United Nations Sustainable Development Goals (SDGs), delivering an architecture that is both visionary and grounded. From its agricultural roots to its urban future, the bank’s identity is deeply embedded in the building's architecture. The white, faceted aluminum façade, patterned with delicate perforations resembling a wheat field, reflects the bank's origins and pays homage to its emblem, Demeter—the goddess of agriculture. More than a visual motif, this façade acts as a responsive skin, filtering light and reducing solar heat gain, setting the stage for a holistic approach to sustainability. At th