eb0dc93c-c571-4c60-8e8b-39c6f5d5558f	Pieris.Architects, Theodosiou Engineers, ConAP	Pieros Pieris, Alexandros Mimidis	info@pierisarchitects.com	Gaia	PLANNED	APPROVED	SECTION_I	Athens	Greece	37.9838	23.7275	The Gaia Office Building, currently in the preliminary design stage, is envisioned as more than a headquarters—it is a statement of intent. Located along Athens’ Sigrou Avenue, Gaia is a next-generation workplace that aligns corporate identity with global responsibility. From its inception, the project has been designed to advance a number of the United Nations Sustainable Development Goals (SDGs), weaving them into its material, spatial, environmental, and social DNA.  At the core of Gaia’s vision is SDG 3: Good Health and Well-being. The project redefines the office as a place that promotes holistic health—physical, mental, and emotional. In a post-pandemic context, Gaia addresses this through enhanced air quality systems, generous circulation, and restorative spaces such as the indoor “Garden in the Sky.” Access to greenery, natural light, and quiet zones is not a luxury in Gaia’s vision, but a foundation for a healthier, more productive daily experience.  Supporting SDG 8: Decent Work and Economic Growth, Gaia is designed to cultivate a resilient, inclusive, and future-ready working environment. The spatial layout encourages diverse modes of working—individual focus, collaborative teamwork, and informal interaction. Adaptability is built into the floorplates and infrastructure, allowing the workplace to evolve as technologies and organizational needs change. By fostering creativity, learning, and well-being, Gaia aims to attract and retain top talent, and contribute to long-term economic vitality.  Underpinning Gaia’s technical design is SDG 9: Industry, Innovation and Infrastructure. Smart building systems, performance-oriented engineering, and high-quality, low-impact materials demonstrate a commitment to innovation. The collaboration between Civil Premises Design – Theodosiou Engineers (structural) and ConAP (mechanical) ensures that technical excellence is integrated from the ground up. These systems are not only efficient—they are scalable, designed for longevity, and capable of responding to new demands over time.  SDG 11: Sustainable Cities and Communities is also a central consideration. Gaia contributes positively to the urban fabric of Sigrou Avenue by introducing green spaces, enhancing the pedestrian experience, and creating a more vibrant and socially engaging public realm. Rather than an isolated corporate entity, the building aspires to be a civic asset—offering spaces for dialogue, cultural activity, and informal exchange, all of which help knit the project into the life of the city.  Gaia’s environmental strategy reflects a deep commitment to SDG 13: Climate Action. The use of laminated wood as a primary structural material reduces embodied carbon, while passive design strategies, efficient mechanical systems, and provisions for renewable energy help reduce operational emissions. These decisions reflect not only a regulatory compliance mindset, but a proactive stance toward climate resilience and environmental responsibility.  Finally, SDG 15: Life on Land is embedded through the project’s commitment to biodiversity. The building integrates multiple planted zones—both indoors and out—which foster urban ecosystems and provide habitats for pollinators and other species. The rooftop garden and the landscaped pond offer microenvironments that reconnect city dwellers with nature, enhancing ecological awareness in daily life.  While Gaia is still in development, its ambitions are clear. It seeks to redefine the role of the office in the 21st century—not just as a space for productivity, but as a driver of social value, environmental stewardship, and long-term resilience. By aligning design and engineering decisions with the SDGs, Gaia aspires to become a meaningful prototype for sustainable urban development—not only in Athens, but as part of a broader global conversation.	The Gaia Office Building, currently in the preliminary design stage, is envisioned as more than a headquarters—it is a statement of intent. Located along Athens’ Sigrou Avenue, Gaia is a next-generation workplace that aligns corporate identity with global responsibility. From its inception, the project has been designed to advance a number of the United Nations Sustainable Development Goals (SDGs), weaving them into its material, spatial, environmental, and social DNA.  At the core of Gaia’s vision is SDG 3: Good Health and Well-being. The project redefines the office as a place that promotes holistic health—physical, mental, and emotional. In a post-pandemic context, Gaia addresses this through enhanced air quality systems, generous circulation, and restorative spaces such as the indoor “Garden in the Sky.” Access to greenery, natural light, and quiet zones is not a luxury in Gaia’s vision, but a foundation for a healthier, more productive daily experience.  Supporting SDG 8: Decent Work and Economic Growth, Gaia is designed to cultivate a resilient, inclusive, and future-ready working environment. The spatial layout encourages diverse modes of working—individual focus, collaborative teamwork, and informal interaction. Adaptability is built into the floorplates and infrastructure, allowing the workplace to evolve as technologies and organizational needs change. By fostering creativity, learning, and well-being, Gaia aims to attract and retain top talent, and contribute to long-term economic vitality.  Underpinning Gaia’s technical design is SDG 9: Industry, Innovation and Infrastructure. Smart building systems, performance-oriented engineering, and high-quality, low-impact materials demonstrate a commitment to innovation. The collaboration between Civil Premises Design – Theodosiou Engineers (structural) and ConAP (mechanical) ensures that technical excellence is integrated from the ground up. These s