 13:00:39.923528	P167	Pieros Pieris, Alexandros Mimidis	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
28c3001d-6221-4703-88d3-006f13131c35	Independent Researcher (Graduation Project, Bilkent University – Department of Architecture)	Elif Duru Alkazan	durualkazan18@gmail.com	The Ecological Victory: Resilient Rural Redevelopment in İkizköy	PLANNED	APPROVED	SECTION_II	Milas	Turkey	37.3168	27.7839	The Ecological Victory" is a conceptual architectural proposal aimed at reversing the ecological destruction and social displacement caused by decades of open-pit coal mining in the Akbelen Forest region of İkizköy, Muğla, Turkey. The project offers a comprehensive, interdisciplinary approach to post-mining recovery that restores not only the land but also the community and culture that once thrived there. Developed as a graduation project at Bilkent University, it addresses themes of ecological justice, rural resilience, innovative construction, and sustainable design thinking.  The region has long suffered from extractive operations, especially following the establishment of the Yeniköy (1986) and Kemerköy (1994) thermal power plants. Entire villages—including Hüsamlar, Çakıralan, and İkizköy’s Işıkdere neighborhood—have been evacuated to make way for expanding coal fields. Forests were razed, olive groves uprooted, and underground water sources jeopardized. Residents, often unaware of their rights, were displaced without sufficient planning for resettlement. Despite years of protests and public resistance—particularly to save the Akbelen Forest—the expansion of the coal mine has continued to threaten local ecosystems and rural livelihoods.  This proposal envisions a future in which the forest is saved, and the displaced community of İkizköy is provided with a sustainable, dignified, and locally rooted way of life. The core of the design is a new village, master-planned around the principles of modularity, community engagement, and ecological integration. Drawing from the structure of traditional Turkish rural settlements, it restores a collective sense of space through a centrally located mosque, coffeehouse (kahvehane), Turkish bath (hamam), and village square—elements intended to rebuild not only infrastructure, but social cohesion and belonging.  The housing typology is centered around 3D-printed concrete cores, designed to be affordable, scalable, and adaptable. Each unit includes connection points for attachable modules such as barns, coops, or additional living spaces—accommodating varying household needs and economic activities. The curvilinear geometry of the structures enhances print efficiency and references vernacular architecture. The project explores the use of low-carbon materials and local resources to minimize the environmental footprint and enhance construction feasibility.  Ecological restoration plays a major role in the proposal. It is informed by research from the Ege Forestry Research Institute and Dr. Hidayet Karakurt’s studies on post-mining soil conditions. The reforestation strategy includes species such as Pinus brutia, Eleagnus angustifolia, Robinia pseudoacacia, and Cupressus sempervirens—selected for their resilience, ecological value, and potential to regenerate degraded soils. Topsoil recovery and terrain stabilization techniques are applied to prevent erosion and promote long-term vegetation growth.  Local economy revitalization is another pillar of the project. The area was historically known for olive cultivation, pine honey production, fruit farming, and mushroom foraging. By allocating agricultural zones adjacent to residential clusters, the project empowers residents to regain their independence through small-scale farming, food sovereignty, and artisanal production. The integration of cooperative economies is supported by shared infrastructure such as barns, workshops, and storage spaces.  The spatial organization reflects both environmental logic and cultural continuity. Homes are clustered in groups of four, arranged to protect privacy while encouraging interaction. Organic pedestrian paths connect units with public spaces and agricultural fields, creating moments of gathering and fluidity. Water-sensitive design, green corridors, and preserved forest buffers ensure that the development remains climate-adaptive and flood-resilient.  "The Ecological Victory" aligns strongly with several UN Sustainable Development Goals:  SDG 11: Promotes inclusive and resilient rural settlements.  SDG 13: Mitigates climate impact through reforestation and low-carbon construction.  SDG 15: Restores biodiversity through ecological planning.  SDG 6: Safeguards groundwater by protecting forest-fed aquifers.  SDG 12: Encourages circular material use and responsible land management.  SDG 9: Introduces digital fabrication as sustainable infrastructure.  SDG 8: Supports decent work through agriculture and beekeeping revival.  This project serves as a manifesto for architecture’s role in reconciliation between people and nature. Although currently unbuilt, it embodies a realistic and actionable vision for a regenerative future—one that resists extraction and proposes healing, dignity, and agency through design.	The Ecological Victory" is a conceptual architectural proposal aimed at reversing the ecological destruction and social displacement caused by decades of open-pit coal mining in the Akbelen Forest region of İkizköy, Muğla, Turkey. The project offers a comprehensive, interdisciplinary approach to post-mining recovery that restores not only the land but also the community and culture that once thrived there. Developed as a graduation project at Bilkent University, it addresses themes of ecological justice, rural resilience, innovative construction, and sustainable design thinking.  The region has long suffered from extractive operations, especially following the establishment of the Yeniköy (1986) and Kemerköy (1994) thermal power plants. Entire villages—including Hüsamlar, Çakıralan, and İkizköy’s Işıkdere neighborhood—have been evacuated to make way for expanding coal fields.