conventional benchmarks—thanks to its thermally efficient envelope and passive strategies. A 50kWp rooftop solar array offsets 100% of the building’s energy demand, with surplus energy supplied back to the state grid, making it an Energy+ facility. Similarly, a rainwater harvesting system, customized to local rainfall patterns, fulfills all water requirements, ensuring complete water self-sufficiency.  Waste minimization was integral to both design and construction. Leftover site materials were creatively repurposed throughout the building—wooden rafters became light fixtures, purlin sections turned into lamp holders, chisels found new life as door handles, and re-bars were fashioned into wash basin pedestals. This not only reduced construction waste but also celebrated craftsmanship and innovation in reuse.  Beyond sustainability metrics, the project fosters social inclusion and community building. It includes large gathering spaces, such as a terrace for communal activities, underscoring the importance of collective well-being. In both intent and execution, the Lodsi Community Project exemplifies a democratic design process: built by the locals, using local resources, and for the benefit of the local community.  In essence, the Lodsi facility reimagines industrial architecture as a vehicle for ecological regeneration and community development. It challenges the notion that manufacturing facilities must be environmentally taxing or culturally alienating. Instead, it demonstrates how ancient building knowledge, when fused with contemporary sustainability practices, can yield spaces that are both high-performing and deeply humane. As a self-sustaining, net-zero development anchored in place-based design and community empowerment, the Lodsi Community Project stands as a beacon for future-ready architecture in the Global South.	See detailed description	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-04-18 12:59:53.078529	2026-04-18 12:59:53.078529	P1	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
beb271a4-fe8a-445e-a196-00f2c2bc6f5e	Department of Visual Studies, University of Karachi	Kanzul Fatima	wajiha.siddiqui@uok.edu.pk	Sustainable Growth for Fishermen Communities: Architecture for Environment	IMPLEMENTED	APPROVED	SECTION_IV	Karachi	Pakistan	24.89114	67.04658	The project aims to create sustainable and uplifting solutions for the fishing community by enabling architecture to exist in harmony with nature. It seeks to understand design methods that can achieve this goal.	A design program is divided into three parts, including work units for fishermen, a mangrove nursery for researchers, and connecting bridges and ramps for exploration. The design features convertible walls and roofs that allow for adaptable space and the potential to form clusters. The architecture is versatile and can be disassembled and relocated to other sites to restore ecosystems. After 40-50 years, the design anticipates the bridge becoming a natural pathway for eco-tourism.	The materials and design strategies used in a project highlight project's sustainable qualities. The materials were carefully chosen to include bamboo, waste boat wood, plastic, and water drums, all of which contribute to sustainable development and recycling waste. The use of these materials reflects a conscious effort to create an environmentally friendly and socially responsible project.	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	IFF44	Kanzul Fatima and Wajiha Siddiqui	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
4fa797f1-eb59-4595-8fc4-7f75fba742fb	China Architecture Design&Research Group	Kang Kai	329579671@qq.com	The main exhibition hall of Tianfu Agricultural Expo Park	IMPLEMENTED	APPROVED	SECTION_IV	Chengdu	China	30.6599	104.0634	The Tianfu Agricultural Expo Park project is located in Xingyi Town, Xinjin County and Sanjiang Town, Chongzhou City, close to Chengxinpu Expressway and Chengdu Second Ring Expressway, with good landscape and traffic conditions. The main exhibition hall is located in the agriculture exhibition area, north of Chengxin Pu Expressway and west of the Yangma River, with a land area of about 135,000 square meters. It includes the functions of agricultural exhibition hall, conference center, Tianfu Agricultural Civilization Museum, cultural and creative incubation, characteristic commercial neighborhood, outdoor exhibition space and other functions, with a total construction area of about 132,000 square meters. The project uses five arched scaffolding to interpenetrate with the surrounding pastoral landscape, and adopts prefabricated steel and wood structure scaffolding combined with colorful ETFE enclosure system to create a semi-outdoor non-energy consumption space, embodies the concept of green development and environmentally friendly design.	Ecological energy-saving. \r\nThe plan adopts a finger-shaped penetration layout pattern, which is mutually infiltrated with the pastoral landscape. At the same time, in order to reflect the characteristics of the agricultural expo exhibition and take into account the basic needs of wind and rain shelter, it mainly adopts the form of an outdoor exhibition venue with a roof. Through appropriate passive green building technology, the organization of air flow is guided to create a comfortable semi-outdoor activity space. The exhibition part has achieved the goal of near-zero energy consumption, truly realizing the green ecological concept that is in line with the agricultural expo. The design of the building opening effectively organizes the air flow to form a ventilation corridor, so that the indoor temperature can be kept in a more comfortable state for a long time. The microclimate environment of human activities has been greatly improved. In addition, fog spraying additional measures are used at a close range to regulate the micro-environment.\r\nWooden frame. \r\nThe architectural form is a large-span structure, combined with the fact that the project is located in farmland, abandoning the reinforced concrete structure form that causes greater damage to farmland during construction and is not renewable. Laminated wood structure is a negative carbon material that can be carbon-fixed. It can better reflect ecological and agricultural characteristics and is all factory-processed. On-site assembly reduces construction errors and ensures completion quality. At the same time, wooden structures originate from nature, with simple colors and in line with agricultural expo characteristics.\r\nColorful film. \r\nETFE film material is light in weight, good in light transmission, easy to color, and can be matched with colorful fields through colorful textures to better reflect agricultural expo concepts.\r\nImplanted nature.\r\n In order to introduce landscape into the arch shed and create an outdoor pastoral feeling indoors, at the boundary, while the building extends into the field, it also extends the external landscape environment into the arch shed to blur and weaken the boundary between architecture and nature and increase opportunities for all-weather contact with nature.	The SDGs are 17 global development goals formulated by the United Nations. These goals will last from 2016 to 2030. The main purpose of these goals is to eliminate poverty, protect the earth and ensure human well-being worldwide. There are extensive interrelationships between the SDGs, and the achievement of one goal may have positive promotion or negative effects on other goals.\r\nIn the 17 global development goals formulated by the United Nations, SDGs2 and SDGs4 have been fully reflected and responded to in the Tianfu Agricultural Expo Park project. The green, open, energy-saving and environmentally friendly architectural landscape design concept provides a solid foundation for the development of sustainable agriculture and provides effective technical models for the construction of agricultural-related infrastructure. The farmland is fertile and vast, and the colorful film arch shed of the main exhibition hall blends with the bright yellow of rapeseed flowers, the oil green of rice seedlings, the golden orange of wheat ears and the deep brown of fertile soil to present seasonal changes. On the west side of the five arch sheds is a demonstration field for scientific agriculture. Farmers spontaneously integrate farmland together, optimize field ridges lines, plant new varieties of crops, and introduce intelligent irrigation equipment to achieve full-cycle automatic monitoring, batching and planting. High-quality agricultural development provides technical support and feasible solutions for eliminating hunger worldwide and achieving food security.\r\nAt the same time, the main exhibition hall of Tianfu Agricultural Expo Park also undertakes important responsibilities for education and scientific research. High-end agricultural research projects and science popularization education exhibitions for students and citizens are all rooted in the park. The construction of the main exhibition hall has become an important platform for citizens to understand modern agriculture and demonstrate sustainable agricultural development. It has great social significance in improving relevant education levels.	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	LDP52	Cui Kai, Kang Kai	130000	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
59149bb0-371b-4622-bc95-91229dc5efd3	steidle architekten	Johannes Ernst	ernst@steidle-architekten.de	Werksviertel Mitte	IMPLEMENTED	APPROVED	SECTION_I	Munich	Germany	48.14156	11.567313	Development of an former industrial area into an independent quarter for living, working, social and cultural use with open public spaces for events and entertainments.	The Werksviertel understands the vitality and complexity of the existing development and uses the positive potential for the emergence of the new quarter. The existing activities are to be gradually cultivated, consolidated and updated, while new developments are initiated at the same time. Urban diversity, spatial events and programmatic innovation are the focus of the design work, which is joint by several european architecture studios.	The Werksviertel is based on economic sustainability through inventory management and the settlement of a highly differentiated range of tenants. This creates a high degree of diversity, which is particularly reflected in a lively and used public space. The careful addition of previously non-existent uses such as hotel/hostel, retail, fitness, offices and, at the end, apartments, generates a wide range of offers for most urban demands and, overall, a differentiated macroeconomic composition.	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	LDP1	Johannes Ernst	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
fb9192ed-9f3c-43be-87a9-cde8b9fbc630	Localworks	Angela Nkurunziza	angela@localworks.ug	AWF Primary Schools in Karamoja	IMPLEMENTED	APPROVED	SECTION_III	Karamoja	Uganda	2.75	34.25	Two primary schools on an area of 2000 sqm located in immediate adjacency to Kidepo Valley National Park in Karamoja/ North-eastern Uganda. One school built in the park buffer zone and another in a farming village nearby, both with the ambition to multiply their influence among each of their 750 school children, their immediate families, and their surrounding communities.\r\n\r\nIn total, 21 buildings across 2 schools, each with 9 classrooms reinforce the vision of AWF to integrate stunning landscapes within the schools, create beautiful that are friendly to the environment on which they are placed and elevate the perceptions of indigenous materials.	Due to the remoteness of the sites and the associated high transport costs, building materials were carefully selected to be sourced locally and built with local labour wherever possible. The Kidepo area has beautiful local stone which was utilised for near-carbon-neutral foundations and plinth walls. The stones were gathered by the locals within a 3km radius of the site and arranged in semi-dry-stack formations creating a water-mitigating substructure. Walling utilises fair-faced, manually compressed stabilized soil blocks (CEBs) formed on site, a material that presents a much more ecological alternative to the commonly used “village brick” which is a main cause of deforestation in Uganda. \r\nThe steel roof trusses were designed using very thin steel profiles, of the size more commonly used for windows and doors; the idea was to optimise the design so much that the entire primary roof structure of two schools would fit into a single truck. The idea was not only to minimise transport costs but also to reduce the weight of each truss to such an extent that they can be hoisted in place by muscle power. Sliding and top-hung steel louvre panels form windows and doors, multicoloured as inspired by the local jewelry design, provide a sturdy, maintenance-efficient response to shading and security requirements.	Special care was given to the landscape design which was seen as the key to fostering a better relationship between people and nature. Existing trees and shrubs were protected to an extraordinary extent, local species added and innovative forms of appropriate agriculture introduced in the form of demonstration farms and gardens. While the school in Geremech was designed in the image of a ‘savannah school’, the Sarachom school reflects its location within an agricultural zone in the structure of a demonstration garden.\r\nIn total, 21 buildings across two schools, each with nine classrooms reinforce the vision of AWF to integrate stunning landscapes within the school that are friendly to the environment on which they are placed and elevate preexisting perceptions of indigenous materials. Each building is completely dependent on passive ventilation to achieve indoor thermal comfort. A combination of thermal mass and building orientation used to minimise direct ingress of sun has proven to be an effective passive strategy to avoid overheating without deploying high-tech energy intensive equipment. Appropriate technologies include a semi-centralised rainwater harvesting, solar power, fuel-efficient wood stoves and 'aquaprivy' toilets.	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	LDP25	Allan Semakula, Arthur Baleeta, Charles Ssegirinya, Deborah Tusiime, Edson Agume, Emma Mugisha, Felix Holland, Jeroen Van Roie, Juliana Achi, Philip Matovu, Robert Mugisha, Sandra Mudondo, Valerie Rubombora	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
b9e76f2b-addf-4193-8e8b-cc55bdd5a2f3	The Architectural Society of China	Yehao Song	sup_atelier@supatelier.com	Yunzhai Community Center	IMPLEMENTED	APPROVED	SECTION_IV	Changyuan	China	35.2125	114.735	With integrated design of both interior and exterior spaces, a “multi-dimensional Chinese garden” has been formed. For locals, it’s an auditorium for celebrations, films and lectures, as well as a leisure space for seniors and children. For visitors, it’s a tourist center for tourist reception, services and cultural activities.	With relatively small site area and building area, as well as a limited budget, the project aims to make much difference with little intervention. A series of design approaches have offered diverse options for villagers’ activities, including the ground-level courtyard, the roof terrace and interior areas. To save operation and maintenance cost, the community center’s management is both time-dependent and zone-dependent. People of all ages from surrounding villages can come here at any time of the day for recreation or gathering, rediscovering the village’s long-lost vitality.	Time & zone-oriented management facilitates the 24-7 operation of the community center\r\n    To weaken the sense of full enclosure of traditional courtyard system, various openings are planned on the walls to make the boundaries permeable rather than closed and solid. The boundaries, with their original function of enclosure preserved, provide easy access for people and bring landscape on both sides of the walls together, making the community center highly open and sharable.\r\nThe enclosed interior spaces, the exterior courtyards and the roof platform are connected with multi travelling routes and managed separately, so that during periods when interior spaces are closed, visitors can still enjoy the multi-dimensional exterior garden at any time of the day, thus saving operation and maintenance costs while maximizing the utility of available spaces.	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	LDP12	Yehao Song, Xiaojuan Che, Dan Xie, Jingfen Sun, Yingnan Chu, Tianyu Kuang, Zhihao Huang, Yuyan Xia, Wenbo Yue	635	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
0ccd174b-cc5d-4f83-b46e-a62f98d55272	SUP Atelier of THAD	Yehao Song	sup_atelier@supatelier.com	Village Lounge of Shangcun	IMPLEMENTED	APPROVED	SECTION_IV	Shangcun Village	China	29.945833	118.748056	Through invigoration and utilization of the ruined courtyard, the design has presented a roofed space with 6 bamboo umbrellas for local people’s gatherings and leisure activities, doubling as an exhibition hall of local culture and history.	Make use of old and local materials\r\nThe team encouraged the villagers to collect usable black bricks, black tiles, stones. and timber for construction. \r\nOpen up the space to the public\r\nThe walls of the family house have been partially torn down, turning the private courtyard behind the walls into a public joint.\r\nForm a set of "umbrellas” with bamboo and integrate with the nature\r\nThe design team picked bamboo as the main material for construction. The bamboo canopies were made to be easily dissembled and upcycled.	"Village Economic Cooperative" "Migrant Association" "Rice Hoarding Association" were held to implement social protection system.\r\nThose organizations bring the villagers together to boost future development projects, such as operation hostels, the renovation for local homestays, the upgrading of landscape and infrastructure, and the promotion of cultural and tourism programs, which can raise their incomes and share the benefits equally\r\nAn open roof could boost natural ventilation. The lounge could serve as a community school for villagers.	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	LDP21	Yehao Song, Jingfen Sun, Yingnan Chu, Dan Xie, Xiaojuan Chen, Haowei Yu	150	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
1b76df1f-a678-4e0e-9377-4cc62f27d23c	SJK Architects	Sarika Shetty	sarika@sjkarchitect.com	JSW Sanjeevani Hospital, Aibaugh	IMPLEMENTED	APPROVED	SECTION_IV	Alibaug	India	18.640548	72.872215	JSW Sanjeevani Multispeciality Hospital offers high quality healthcare to a 50-km stretch in rural Raigad area with limited healthcare infrastructure; designed to express compassion, wellness, and beauty to enable physical and psychological well-being.	The intervention of JSW Sanjeevani Multispeciality Hospital has changed a previously slag-filled, barren site into a lush, green zone. Landscaped greens on the south facilitate connection with nature. Balconies, terraces, and corridors bring in natural light and air, while common areas offer opportunities for rejuvenation and interaction. A bio-diverse micro-climate promotes healing and calmness which is crucial for patient recovery. Clear planning adjacencies and circulation ensure ease of movement for staff, patients, and families even during times of distress.	The JSW Sanjeevani hospital's strategic location on the Mumbai-Goa highway helps address accidents. This intervention has 100% rainwater harvesting and other eco-friendly features and also uses AAC blocks for better insulation and nearby steel plant slag for plinth filling.The hospital prioritises natural ventilation and wide corridors to reduce airborne disease transmission and incorporates balconies and indigenous vegetation to promote patient engagement and recovery. As an initiative of the JSW Foundation, it offers 13+ specialised consultancies with competitive rates and free services under government schemes, while employing 99% of its staff from a 25-km radius.	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	LDP28	Shimul Javeri Kadri, Sarika Shetty, Sapna Rohra, Harshini Yohee, Bhavin Patel, Rishit Jain.	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
8f1eef77-99ac-410a-ba7b-43828c1a8ad1	Architectural Society of China	Wei ZHANG	zw1998@vip.163.com	Kuyangshu Biathlon Center	IMPLEMENTED	APPROVED	SECTION_IV	Chongli	China	40.998857	115.261397	Kuyangshu Biathlon Center is one of the main competition venues in Zhangjiakou Zone of the Beijing 2022 Winter Olympic Games. It is the venue with the largest number of gold medals.	Sustainable design with minimum influence on nature and equal quality design for disabled athletes and spectators are the two main concepts. During the games, it will undertake all competitions of the biathlon of the Winter Olympic Games and the biathlon and cross-country ski of the Winter Paralympic Games, setting a total of 11 gold medals of the Winter Olympic Games and 38 gold medals of the Winter Paralympic Games. It will become the training base of the national team after the Games.	The venue covers an area of 132ha, with only 8795㎡ permanent building area.Facilities unnecessary after Olympics were built with cabins or tents. Walls in building are flexible and removable. Instead of a big reservoir on the mountain, we created five small lakes among the courses, minimizing the influence on nature. Gravel pavement courses can be changed into mountain bike courses or just melt into nature after the Games. Special design for disabled spectators and athletes are made in the venue.	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	LDP43	Architect In Charge: Weimin ZHUANG, Wei ZHANG, Hong ZHANG Design Team: Jingxian ZHAO, Jiazhen GONG, Xiangyi LI, Sisi LIANG, Haiyang HUANG, Siyu LEI, Zhonglin GONG, Yuan JIA	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
912b73e9-8376-47b6-a88c-31d4ba41a75e	Vijay Gupta Architects	Saurabh Gupta	media@vga.co.in	Euro School	IMPLEMENTED	APPROVED	SECTION_IV	Bengaluru	India	12.97422	77.593185	The design for Euro School, Bannerghatta aims to break the conventional school model with an organic built morphology that weaves in nature with the manmade, fostering a respect for nature among students.	The school’s design incorporates the site’s natural topography into its built mass, retaining all existing trees on site. Play areas and outdoor classrooms encourage students to spend more time outdoors – also reflected in the school’s curriculum. The zero-discharge campus employs pragmatic planning to minimally harm the site’s terrain such as using the natural swale to replenish the groundwater table. Employing local/recycled materials in the design also reduces the project’s carbon footprint.	A student’s holistic development must foster sustainable values in them from an early age. The school employs strategies to provide outdoor learning opportunities where teaching takes place with and through nature. The school aims to be a model that considers the natural environment and built habitat as mutual entities countering the disconnect between the two in most metropolitan cities. By establishing a connection with the natural site at different levels, the school’s objective is to foster respect for and curiosity towards the natural world.	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	IFF24	Vijay Gupta, Saurabh Gupta, Akanksha Gupta	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
de858a10-ae31-4bdc-9c0c-ff27019a6149	Craft Narrative	Yatindra Patil	info@craftnarrative.com	Vaulted School	IMPLEMENTED	APPROVED	SECTION_IV	Pune	India	18.518909	73.856116	Vaulted school the initiative from the founder of Nabhangan foundation & an artist Rajshri Deshpande. Foundation working in the fields of rural regeneration & community building to empower villages to self reliance.\r\n \r\nVaulted school is built just minutes away from Dhorkin Tanda, a hamlet in Maharashtra inhabited by sugarcane-cutting labour near Paithan, Aurangabad. The hamlet had one school accommodating a total of 30 students, which was dilapidated.\r\n \r\nWhat the old structure lacked, the new structure had it hacked: ample lighting and ventilation achieved with the help of vaulted roofs, stand-alone sanitation facility, a kitchen for mid-day meals, and an overall conducive environment for knowledge to reside in and foster with the ‘play and learn’ ideology.\r\n \r\nThe vaulted school is designed to evoke and satisfy the curiosities children are capable of, and answers them in the most natural way possible: the breeze on their faces that flows because of the Venturi effect, the green buffer zones that cut off the glare, and the importance of planting native flora and fauna in and around the school.\r\n \r\nThe planning provides ample space for one of the most essential needs of a school—the playground, tucked on one side of the site.	Vaulted school the initiative from the founder of Nabhangan foundation & an artist Rajshri Deshpande. Foundation working in the fields of rural regeneration & community building to empower villages to self reliance.\r\n \r\nVaulted school is built just minutes away from Dhorkin Tanda, a hamlet in Maharashtra inhabited by sugarcane-cutting labour near Paithan, Aurangabad. The hamlet had one school accommodating a total of 30 students, which was dilapidated.\r\n \r\nWhat the old structure lacked, the new structure had it hacked: ample lighting and ventilation achieved with the help of vaulted roofs, stand-alone sanitation facility, a kitchen for mid-day meals, and an overall conducive environment for knowledge to reside in and foster with the ‘play and learn’ ideology.\r\n \r\nThe vaulted school is designed to evoke and satisfy the curiosities children are capable of, and answers them in the most natural way possible: the breeze on their faces that flows because of the Venturi effect, the green buffer zones that cut off the glare, and the importance of planting native flora and fauna in and around the school.\r\n \r\nThe planning provides ample space for one of the most essential needs of a school—the playground, tucked on one side of the site.\r\n \r\nThe overall site of 305sq. m. offers a classroom equipped with storage shelves for books and educational toys, a staff room for the teachers, designed with storage units for examination papers and academic journals, and lastly, multi-purpose hall which doubles up as an additional classroom or a dining hall if and when need be.\r\n \r\nIn the foresight, an additional floor can be added by dismantling the vaulted roof temporarily for construction. The same can be assembled as a roof for the next level and the central gutter beam can unfold to extend the slab floor. Even with these changes the dynamics will only be affected positively.\r\n \r\nAll the current spaces are carefully designed in the 102 sq. m. built-up area the premise offers. The classroom’s orientation responds evidently to the breeze pattern and sun path. Considering the soil conditions present, a pile foundation is constructed to strengthen the substructure on which the load-bearing brick walls find their ground. The process is furthered with the vaulted metal sheet roof that minimizes the heavy structural cost and makes the form structurally rigid with minimal support.\r\n \r\nAs one looks deeper into the shape of the structure and the design of the classrooms, the semi-circular volumes serve as noise buffers to the disturbances caused by vehicles passing by on the adjacent side of the road.\r\n \r\nA free path for ventilation and light is created by the high ceilings, which on the outer side are made up of non-reflective roofing material to reduce heat gain.\r\n \r\nEach and every wall is painted with pieces of information the child will imbibe even while sitting idly; one of the prominent being a depiction of The Big Dipper on the classroom’s low-height ceilings which is a craft intervention made by inserting an acrylic rod within the slab.\r\n \r\nYellow glossy coloured epoxy flooring added additional layer of fun and are painted with mathematical learnings and traditional floor games to utilise the flooring area at its best. Moreover, the playground, just like the classroom, is a product of psychologically backed design thinking, subtly introducing the concept of an amphitheatre to its tiny users. The steps under the overhang double up as seats for when the school is to conduct a recreational activity that requires staging and audience areas. The superstructure revolves around local bricks & traditional pattern as infill materials to bridge the gap between technicalities and rooted aesthetics.	A school built minutes away from Dhorkin Tanda, Hamlet, in Maharastra. It is inhabited by sugarcane-cutting labourers in Paithan, Aurangabad. The children had adapted to the fallible condition of their previous school, where they didn't have proper access to light and ventilation. The school was in the vicinity of an alcohol brewery, which had a  furnace nearby. The school had dingy rooms and unhygienic toilets. Another factor affecting education was parents that expected their children to accompany them for their labour work, which instilled even less desire among children to attend school. The challenge was to design a school where children could feel a safe and fun place with a tight pocket and harsh climatic conditions. \r\n\r\nA school is anticipated to be holistic learning for students, which will help them grow physically, emotionally and socially. Our main ideology was 'play and learn'. The school is a profound design for children to explore their curiosity amidst learning their native environment and craft. The spaces mould according to anthropometry and children's usage, making them the first priority. The play in open and closed spaces provided noise buffers and adequate sunlight for learning and protected from the harsh climate of Dhorkin. The spaces are carefully designed in the 102 SQM build-up area to leave a colossal chuck as a playground. Learning being the central idea of the school, the design revolves around grasping knowledge from the surroundings and architectural elements such as roofs, walls and even floors. Introduction to modern methods like cognitive learning and social and intellectual development have been assimilated for overall child development.\r\n\r\nA free path for ventilation and light is created by the high ceilings, with non-reflective roofing material to reduce heat gain. The classroom orientation, vaults and openings respond to the breeze to keep comfortable temperatures for students. This takes a step towards the green initiative, helps students concentrate and is cost-effective. Clean toilets and kitchen facilities are designed for the students. \r\n\r\nThe vaults made of metal sheets are a cost-effective material that provides classroom volume for holistic and focused learning. The structure is made of local bricks and traditional patterns to continue the rooted aesthetics and create a cost-effective building with a grounded feeling to the elevation. The budget was a major constraint in the project; materials like epoxy for flooring, corrugated sheet and brick, which were readily available around the site, were used. Learning is central to the idea; the playground also becomes a classroom and vice-versa. The subtle introduction of the amphitheatre, which faces the playground, helps students pick the concepts of sports.	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	LDP17	Yatindra Patil & Vijay Kharade	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
a8908d37-be3f-47c5-a7f6-1bbc9964bd31	Craft Narrative	Yatindra Patil	info@craftnarrative.com	Library Pod	IMPLEMENTED	APPROVED	SECTION_IV	Pune	India	18.518909	73.856116	“It all started with my father, saying when there is bus stops in each village then there should be a library stop too.”\r\nThis is the vision shared by our patron, an artist  Rajshri Deshpande. She is also the founder of  Nabhangan  foundation.\r\n \r\nThe design conceived as Knowledge pod. A place to learn, contemplate & play all around.\r\nPod has potential to form communal space, where villagers with diverse age can gather, accomplish  the reading habit and also a perfect setting  for storytellers  too.\r\n \r\nA deliberate attempt to insert  the library pod within the existing rural school & our intent is to shape it as part of the school &  surrounding.\r\nPod amidst existing rain tree, pipal  tree and also encircled by graffiti art works created by local artist & students. It creates the colourful and shaded foreground.\r\n \r\nThis inserted library pod serves as the two parallel worlds, A one being introverted book shelf  & other as vibrant scribble or black board.\r\nBook shelf positioned to create intimate seating possibilities with existing steps around and rubber wood bench as part of the pod. The large overhang serves the purpose for seating area.\r\n \r\nBlack board oriented  towards larger shaded open space, Creates the place under shade to serve as outdoor classroom.\r\nA backdrop for early morning gatherings & lunch time play activities.\r\n \r\nLibrary pod Insert  accomplishes the multifaceted activities for students and villagers.	As we trace back our academic culture to the gurukul system while evolving into a society that focuses on technology in education, the Indian demographical context cannot be ignored. The quest for knowledge doesn’t know restrictions, it is where the willingness is— across age groups and interests, and it has to be addressed at the grassroots level in order to excel collectively. What better way to address it than to start from the villages of India, where natural inquisitiveness thrives, despite proper infrastructure and resources.\r\n \r\n“When there are bus stops in each village, there should be a library stop too.”\r\n \r\n This was the thought behind Rajshri Deshpande’s initiation for Library Pod—an arena for knowledge that has the potential to form a communal space where villagers of diverse ages can gather, and accomplish the reading habit and also a perfect setting for storytellers too. The crux of the project lies in its location—it is a deliberate architectural intervention that utilizes only 17.16 sqm of space in a rural school that has an area of 220 sqm. The pod is built where knowledge resides—a school in the village of Aurangabad, Maharashtra. It takes up a lot less space as compared to the impact it puts on the virtue of education. The structure is strategically built under a peepal tree, in a space encircled by graffiti artworks created by local artists & students. It consists of a storage shelf and a projecting metal roof designed to shield the users from extreme weather conditions, made up of thin steel plate rafters and purlin that taper towards the edges to express the lightness against the visually heavy bookshelf. The entire unit in metal doubles up as water-tight bookshelves and as blackboards on the other side, which cater to the outdoors, making it suitable to conduct a class under the peepal tree as well.  Since it is outside the built school structure and open to sky, the bookshelves had to be made water and dust-free by using rubber gaskets to seal them and GI sheets to make up their framework and shutters. The bookshelves were made by the manufacturers of streetside electrical distribution board boxes, who have prefabricated the unit and assembled it at the location to maintain workmanship and quality. An extension of this unit is made by adding a rubber wooden bench beside it. The flooring for this pod is constructed with bricks, in a way that they start from level zero and up to the pod’s level by creating small steps in between, also serving as a place to sit. The brick base is covered by the overhang which is supported by 80mm*80mm M.S. box sections as columns. The pod also serves as a backdrop for early morning gatherings and lunchtime play activities in the school while successfully accomplishing multifaceted activities for students and villagers alike. With that being stated, the Libray Pod is an example of how the biggest of achievements start with the smallest of inventions.\r\n \r\nThe pinnacle of mankind can be understood by the way inventions are made. It is in the bigger achievements that the technological advancements are measured, however, the smallest of interventions making the biggest of differences are worth paying attention to. Completed in December 2021, the Library Pod is a successful initiative by Nabhangan Foundation, which now serves as a place to learn, contemplate and play around.	A school in the rural boundaries of Pimpal Gaav Pandhri, in Aurangabad, has students who are curious to read and discover the world through books but needed motivation. The school had donations of books each year, which disappeared within a year as a system of using these books needed to be adopted. The library pod began as an experiment. \r\nThe significance of having a library in schools cannot be under-emphasized. It encourages the development of the students and villagers, assists in developing the vocabulary, increases comprehension, instils the habit of reading in silence, and encourages a problem-solving approach in students, especially at a young age.\r\nThe intent is to shape it as part of the school and cultivate a community of readers. The pod has a rural setting amongst the rain and pipal trees, surrounded by artwork by local artists and students. \r\nThe design is envisioned as a Knowledge Pod—a place to learn, contemplate and play around. The pod is like a coin, revealing its two sides, one the introverted, where reading is the main activity under the comfortable shade of trees. In contrast, the other is the extroverted side, which brings together a class.  \r\n\r\nThe pod has a unique design where it borrows shade and seatings from trees and the buildings around it and offers its own. The library is designed as a quiet space with a bookshelf and seater. The back of these bookshelves turns into a blackboard that caters to several activities, provides an under-the-tree outdoor classroom, and caters for activities like storytelling and morning assembly. The library pod is positioned as a pause point for the school as well as villagers, to take their quiet time to read. It also provides a welcoming seater for anyone from the village who wishes to cultivate a habit or gain knowledge. \r\nThe material is mostly steel sections used for electric boards with an interlocking mechanism. The roofing was a simple corrugated sheet with a paint finish. The structure is kept light and according to the child's anthropometry. \r\nThe library helps students understand their own culture and exposes them to other cultures, gives them the most recent information, and exposes students to fresh ideas, literature, and ideas, making their awareness of the history and geography of both the near and far regions. An intervention like the Library pod holds the potential to administer a thought and a change of wave.	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	LDP20	Yatindra Patil & Vijay Kharade	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
81f5d72d-ea8c-45f3-acda-a613491c2deb	Hoang Thuc Hao & 1+1>2	1+1>2 Architects	amedia@112.com.vn	Highland School System	IMPLEMENTED	APPROVED	SECTION_IV	Hanoi	Vietnam	21.031477	105.844719	Since 2014, 52 schools have become operational. Many more are in the process of construction in every region of the country. Every school aims to serve its community, support teachers and students	School designs are inspired by the everyday, design cues can come from the rhythm of Thai dance, or a forest flower inspires roof shapes. The school design is based on four core principles: respect the surrounding environment; promote the indigenous spirit and traditional culture; take advantage of local materials and hire local workers; combine design suitable for modern education with traditional methods.	Though varied in context and design, schools sprung up like “flowers of the soil”, representing justice, the spirit of integration and inspiration. They served to build strong social consciousness, contribute educational significance, and safeguard indigenous traditions. Just as importantly, they motivated disadvantaged communities to raise their voices and contribute to humanity’s rich and diverse culture.	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	LDP67	Hoang Thuc Hao & 1+1>2	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
16b4c688-1ac3-45c5-bb66-7d4a03d52ab7	One University One Village team, The Chinese University of Hong Kong	Li Wan	wanli@cuhk.edu.hk	Sustainable Rural Development Program: One University One Village	IMPLEMENTED	APPROVED	SECTION_IV	Southwest China	China	26	104	The One University One Village (1U1V) Initiative was launched by Prof. Edward NG and Dr. Li WAN at The Chinese University of Hong Kong (CUHK) in 2014. It aspires to bring together the expertise, knowledge and human resources of “a university” to improve the livelihood of “a village” and its needy villagers in a strategic, systematic and sustainable manner. In 2015, 1U1V team conducted a post-earthquake reconstruction project in Yunnan, China to demonstrate the use of “high-science-low-technology” strategies with the “local materials, local labour, and local technology” principle of rural construction, and to encourage endogenous development in rural China. The project and the holistic strategy behand it creatively mended the environmental, economic, and social sustainable development of poor rural areas. Since 2017, the team started to scale up the work, and to continue the work more systematically, with the building of the Terra Centre in Kunming as the working base in China to research, promote, train and knowledge transfer. With funding support from the Chan Cheung Mun Chung Charitable Fund, 60 more village houses have been rebuilt and more than 70 houses are under construction in Southwest China.	Sustainable rural development is a significant issue in China, which has more than 40% of its population living in rural areas. The development of poor rural areas in mountainous regions of Southwest China has been relatively slow and unsustainable. The crucial support that poor rural areas of China require is not only funding but also innovative ideas and systematic strategies. Rammed earth construction has a long history in China. Raw earth is the main material used in traditional architecture because it is inexpensive, accessible and exhibits remarkable thermal performance. However, under the impact of urbanization, rural residents tend to think that earthen buildings are associated to poverty and backwardness. Moreover, improving the seismic performance of earth buildings is a big challenge since many of them are located in earthquake-prone areas. To provide a suitable and sustainable solution for rural reconstruction in Southwest China, our team explores the research and innovates rammed earth building technology to provide a safe, economical, simple, and sustainable reconstruction strategy that the rural residents can afford, own, and disseminate.\r\nTo ensure systematic and sustainable rural reconstruction work with innovative ideas, scientific research is essential to understand the context, identify the problem, and find a proper solution. To empower the rural residents and encourage endogenous development, “high-science-low-technology” strategies and “local labour, local materials, and local technology” principle was applied in poor rural areas in Southwest China. Instead of promoting the benefits of imported brick and concrete, our team determined whether the shortfalls of traditional rammed earth technology and the fragility of village life could be addressed in situ. The implementation of this strategy was a simple step in rebuilding the lives of the people. Since 2014, our team has started to build rural houses to demonstrate a comprehensive and systematic construction system and resulting substantially high building quality. Meanwhile, the residents were empowered through the demonstration projects with craftsman training and co-construction. Through this long-term cooperation and learning-by-doing process, we established mutual trust with the villagers and convinced them that the innovative, anti-seismic rammed earth building was a good solution. \r\nOur rural programme provides an interdisciplinary, innovative and sustainable solution for poor rural areas in China. This solution has been generated by multidisciplinary partnerships and networking platforms. We also hope this knowledge database can also inspire and lead the work of the local governments and other NGOs in China and other underprivileged areas in less-developed countries, and eventually create a knowledge value chain that helps build a better future for rural communities around the world. More than 60 village houses have been rebuilt and more than 70 houses are under construction in Southwest China. More than 6 villager craftsman construction teams (including a women construction team) were established. Moreover, the innovative rammed earth building technology can be replicated for the improvement of poor rural areas where there are similar natural and social conditions to those in the poor rural areas of Southwest China, for example, in the rural regions of Nepal and India.	The 1U1V program helps villagers find local employment, increase their skills and incomes, and improve building safety to avoid poverty caused by earthquakes. This responds to SDG 1 (End poverty in all its forms everywhere)\r\nOur craftsman training plan and construction organization have a comprehensive and positive impact on the psychological needs of villagers at all levels. It responds Target 4.4 (substantially increase the number of youth and adults who have relevant skills, including technical and vocational skills, for employment, decent jobs and entrepreneurship) of SDGs.\r\nWe engaged women into construction to promote gender equality. Furthermore, a women construction team with a female leader and half of women workers has been established after this project. Men and women get equal pay for equal work. This strategy is aligns with SDG 5 (Achieve gender equality and empower all women and girls).\r\nAt least 6 village construction teams were established. With the formwork and rammer donated from our team, villagers can own this technology and pass it on. Supporting productive activities, decent job creation, entrepreneurship, creativity and innovation, and encourage the formalization and growth of micro- and small-sized enterprises is also emphasized in Target 8.3 of SDGs.\r\nPreferential use of local and natural materials minimized the embodied energy and respond to the target 12.2 (Achieve the sustainable management and efficient use of natural resources.)of SDGs.\r\nThe esteem needs and self-actualization needs of villager craftsmen are also considered and valued in this project. This process changed the attitude of the villagers towards rammed earth buildings. They became interested in switching back from brick-concrete houses because this method protected their traditional technology and lifestyle. Such a shift is consistent with the Target 12.8 (ensure that people have the relevant information and awareness for sustainable development and lifestyles in harmony with nature) of SDGs\r\nOur team not only provide design as architects but also worked with the villagers throughout the process as partners. Besides, we established effective network of academics, professionals, students and volunteers who share the same aspiration to generate academic and societal impact by intervening practical projects, to build a knowledge community. Local government is also involved to coordinate and explore this new sustainable way of rural reconstruction. This model not only benefits the villagers, but also has a positive impact on other participants and contributes. It responds the Target 17.16 (Enhance the Global Partnership for Sustainable Development, complemented by multi-stakeholder partnerships that mobilize and share knowledge, expertise, technology and financial resources, to support the achievement of the Sustainable Development Goals in all countries) and Target 17.17 (Encourage and promote effective public, public-private and civil society partnerships, building on the experience and resourcing strategies of partnerships) of SDGs.	\N	\N	\N	\N	