405d173b-e292-419a-a7b2-3c1810676bcd	TecTo Arhitectura	Sergiu C. Petrea	office@tecto.ro	FIRST CLT MULTI COMFORT OFFICE BULDING	IMPLEMENTED	APPROVED	SECTION_II	Reci	Romania	45.85	25.933	The project was designed as the first large scale project with CLT and GLT structure in S-E Europe as flagship two-levels office building, based on utmost ecological and long-term sustainability. The building acts as a visual interface between two antagonistic spaces – an industrial platform used for production and a natural landscape with strong horizontal lines.	The design workflow followed four major objectives: Sustainable prefabricated CLT and GLT construction, Healthy and Inclusive Working Spaces: individually room-controlled comfort and high-quality work environment, increased noise protection, passive construction for insulation and air-tightness, heat recovery ventilation system; Ecology: use of geothermal energy, high efficiency biomass co-generation plant for heating and electricity, optimization of utilities costs, green roofs, enhanced daylight autonomy, increased degree of recyclable building; High quality architecture and landscape.	The main challenge was to create an office building for around sixty people that had to provide healthy lives and promote well-being for all at all ages and achieve gender equality through operational use. The owner aimed to achieve full and productive employment and decent work for all through a sustainable building. The green roofs and the surrounding landscape collect and filter rainwater ensuring availability and sustainable management of water. Moreover, it restores to nature the built footprint and promotes sustainable use of terrestrial ecosystems, enhancing local biodiversity. The building has a heating and cooling system based on a well with enhanced heat collection and a heat pump with hot/cold puffer system and a biomass co-generation plant for heating and electricity while the ventilation system uses heat recovery to minimize consumption. This ensures sustainable consumption and production patterns and acts as an example of fighting against climate change. The project strategy uses resilient infrastructure and promotes inclusive and sustainable industrialization. Finally, it is an example of good architectural practice to show how built environment may become inclusive, safe, resilient and sustainable, its awards in several competitions backing up the idea.	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	LDP11	PhD. arch. Sergiu-Cătălin Petrea, arch. Sabrina Ene-Butnariu, arch. Cristina Mototolea, arch. Sebastian-Ștefan Apostol, arch. Dan - Alexandru Roșu, arch. Tania-Victoria Băncilă, arch. Diana-Elena Fusea, arch. Ovidiu-Ion Bălășoiu	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
81045e49-2aef-48ad-b0ef-0f4b200ca7e3	IAP - Institute of Architects Pakistan	Amina Qayyum Mirza	aaomd2@gmail.com	Product Development & Marketing Offices, Khurrianwala, Punjab, Pakistan | Creating Equality/Inclusiveness in the Workplace-A Catalyst for Change	IMPLEMENTED	APPROVED	SECTION_IV	Khurrianwala	Pakistan	31.51722	73.26667	The project is located in peri-urban area in an industrial estate. The project- product development & marketing offices are connected to a production facility. The design is conceived as an open plan inclusive and a non-discriminatory workplace.	The locality of this project is important as the preconceived notion of women’s subservient status is prevalent in society as a whole. \r\n\r\nThe new offices were designed to create gender equality in the workplace in an open-plan by placing women with ease next to their male colleagues, thus normalizing the feminine presence. The shared workspaces were interspersed with occasional meeting areas to encourage collaboration; cultivating gender interaction. \r\n\r\nThe open-plan fostered communication between various management levels. Facilitating the rightful candidate to rise in the hierarchal order in the company. \r\n\r\nGender-specific spaces were created to give women privacy, security, and comfort. The new building incorporated principles of biophilia, passive design and energy conservation.	Pakistan is the fifth most populated country in the world, with more than 50% female population. (Pakistan population 2022). \r\n\r\nThe engagement of women workforce benefits the country’s economy and help alleviate poverty.\r\n\r\nAt a micro level in the peri-urban area, these projects act as a catalyst for a change in the perception of built space and work environment. It created an enabling equitable non-discriminatory environment lessening the gender divide.\r\n\r\nThe project had significant impact on the company’s policy for inclusion and recognition of gender-specific needs. Leading to women empowerment as an integral part of Vision 2025. \r\n\r\nAt a macro level, women empowerment benefits the country as women prioritize wellbeing of their families and invest all their earnings in improving the future prospects of their children.	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	LDP59	Amina Qayyum Mirza	1858.0608	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
10acb640-93c5-420a-a8c2-e10642a29416	The Chinese University of Hong Kong and Kunming University of Science and Technology	Li Wan	wanli@cuhk.edu.hk	Terra Centre	IMPLEMENTED	APPROVED	SECTION_IV	Kunming	China	25.03926	102.718887	Through the cooperation with Kunming University of Science and Technology (KUST), One University One Village team have improved the construction technology and seismic performance of the earth construction in Southwest rural China. In order to carry out long-term artisans training, to provide space for conducting experiments, research and practical study, and to showcase the technologies and achievements of new seismic earth construction, the 1U1V team built the Terra Centre in KUST campus with funding support from the Chan Cheung Mun Chung Charitable Fund.\r\nThe project design is highly based on the local climate condition of Kunming. Appropriate passive design strategies guaranteed low operating energy consumption. All the materials used in the wall are natural materials. No industrial stabilizers were added in the earth wall. The wall is 100% recyclable, degradable, and pollution free. \r\nThe Terra Centre is not only a building but a research and education tool. The team trained and employed villagers to build the Terra Centre and thus transfer to them a way to make their livings economically later. The result verified an appropriated solution of the local reconstruction that provides references for national rural construction policies and earth building seismic standards.	Research shows that socioeconomic value is crucial in sustainable rural development. The environmental load of vernacular houses in poor rural areas is low already. The key issue is how to improve the safety, quality and dignity of the living environment without adding substantial environmental load. Earth building has a very long history in China. Terra Center as a research centre for earthen architecture and rural sustainable development, applied “high-science and low-technology” strategy with “local materials, local labour and local technology” principle to encourage endogenous and sustainable development in poor rural areas in China.\r\n    The building design is highly based on local climate condition so that proper passive design strategies can be selected. Kunming has a moderate climate with abundant sunshine and large temperature difference between day and night. With good thermal mass, rammed earth wall is a very suitable material. We designed a semi-outdoor space with top lighting in the middle of the building to provide a comfortable multifunctional space for multiple training and academic activities. Passive design strategies including passive solar heating, natural ventilation, and shading guaranteed high indoor environmental quality and low operating energy consumption. No active cooling and heating equipment has been used in this project.\r\n    To minimize the impact to the local environment, 89% of the building materials (by weight) are local natural materials (raw earth, gravel, sand, and bamboo). No industrial stabilizer was added to the wall, i.e., the wall is 100% recyclable and pollution-free. The roof structure is made of bamboo that is a fast-growing material with low embodied energy. No decoration material was used on the building façade and interior walls. Industrial materials, such as cement and steel, are limited and efficiently used in key structural parts to ensure building safety and building environmental quality.\r\n    We meet the safety needs of people by improving the building seismic performance. To improve wall strength and reduce cracks, we analyzed the basic properties of the soil and optimized the proportion by adding gravel and sand. The air compressed rammers and the aluminum alloy formwork are applied to Improving the compressive strength of the wall. In terms of structural design, reinforced concrete tie columns, ring beams, foundation and floor slabs are applied to enhance the structural integrity. The result of mechanical property tests and shaking table tests corroborates that the seismic performance of the rammed earth building significantly is improved, thereby meeting the local seismic codes perfectly.\r\nThe Terra Centre is not only a building but a research and education tool. We trained and employed villagers to build the Terra Centre and thus transfer to them a way to make their livings economically later. 33 villagers (including 5 women) joined this project and passed the craftsmen training. The project changed the attitude of the villagers towards rammed earth buildings. They became interested in switching back from their brick-concrete houses because the project protected their local traditional construction method and lifestyle. The project result provides references for national rural construction policies and earth building seismic standards.	Our craftsman training plan and construction organization have a comprehensive and positive impact on the psychological needs of villagers at all levels. It responds Target 4.4 (substantially increase the number of youth and adults who have relevant skills, including technical and vocational skills, for employment, decent jobs and entrepreneurship) of SDGs.\r\nWe engaged women into construction to promote gender equality. Furthermore, a women construction team with a female leader and half of women workers has been established after this project. Men and women get equal pay for equal work. Accordingly, the equipment has been improved to make them more convenient to control for women. This strategy is aligns with SDG 5 (Achieve gender equality and empower all women and girls).\r\n    At least 5 village construction teams were established after completion of the Terra Centre. They can use their knowledge of such new construction technology as their livelihood. With the formwork and rammer donated from our team, villagers can own this technology and pass it on. Supporting productive activities, decent job creation, entrepreneurship, creativity and innovation, and encourage the formalization and growth of micro- and small-sized enterprises is also emphasized in Target 8.3 of SDGs.\r\n    Preferential use of local and natural materials minimized the embodied energy and respond to the target 12.2 (Achieve the sustainable management and efficient use of natural resources.)of SDGs.\r\n    No industrial stabilizer was added in the wall, i.e., the wall of this building is 100% recyclable and pollution-free. This project reduces the construction waste caused by building construction, responding to the Target 12.5 (Substantially reduce waste generation through prevention, reduction, recycling and reuse) of SDGs.\r\n    The esteem needs and self-actualization needs of villager craftsmen are also considered and valued in this project. This process changed the attitude of the villagers towards rammed earth buildings. They became interested in switching back from brick-concrete houses because this method protected their traditional technology and lifestyle. Such a shift is consistent with the Target 12.8 (ensure that people have the relevant information and awareness for sustainable development and lifestyles in harmony with nature) of SDGs.\r\n    Our team not only provide design as architects but also worked with the villagers throughout the process as partners. Besides, we established effective network of academics, professionals, students and volunteers who share the same aspiration to generate academic and societal impact by intervening practical projects, to build a knowledge community. Local government is also involved to coordinate and explore this new sustainable way of rural reconstruction. This model not only benefits the villagers, but also has a positive impact on other participants and contributes. It responds the Target 17.16 (Enhance the Global Partnership for Sustainable Development, complemented by multi-stakeholder partnerships that mobilize and share knowledge, expertise, technology and financial resources, to support the achievement of the Sustainable Development Goals in all countries) and Target 17.17 (Encourage and promote effective public, public-private and civil society partnerships, building on the experience and resourcing strategies of partnerships) of SDGs.	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	LDP6	Edward Ng, Li Wan, Lucia Cheung, Xinan Chi, Wenfeng Bai, Marc Auzet, Juliette Goudy, Fang Tian, Xiaoxue Liu, Lai Zhou, Shan Dai, Changzhuan Shao	1328.5	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
cb69fae8-a8c0-40b9-9430-5c30ae0cac43	IAB - Institute of Architects Bangladesh	Razib Hassan Chowdhury	silt.studio@gmail.com	বোতলবাড়ি' - Community hub and wash facilities for women	IMPLEMENTED	APPROVED	SECTION_IV	Kuakata	Bangladesh	21.815347	90.140874	A resilient community hub providing friendly space for women and adolescent girls with access to proper toilets and bathing facilities- A space to foster inquisition, collaboration, and self-reliance.	A water-starved, Cyclone prone community in kolapara , kuakata hosts this structure where local women commune to identify, discuss and find solutions to their constraints. A low-cost and easily replicable solution for resilient shelters is achieved by utilizing waste plastic bottles, bamboo posts, old fishing nets and mud. In addition to addressing the lack of sanitation the structure also houses a repurposed underground bunker as a communal strong room for valuables during cyclones.	A safe space for women to engage, build a resilient community, and gain access to hygiene facilities in an area prone to water scarcity and natural disasters. The combination of locally available materials with repurposed waste in an easily replicable technique keeps carbon the footprint and construction costs to a minimum. Women's active participation in learning the techniques and building the shelter empowers them with new skills while also fostering a sense of ownership of the space.	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	LDP72	SILT	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
1ba30dc8-27ba-4bf4-9581-f71bf3cf83fc	Kuee Architecture	Ar Shyuan Kuee	shyuan@kueearch.com	1 Lasam	IMPLEMENTED	APPROVED	SECTION_IV	Ipoh	Malaysia	4.59342	101.087676	Taking 10 years to conceptualize, 1 Lasam is the first GBI Platinum Building in Perak. Its V-shape footprint designed to maximize the footprint, with a courtyard carved out in the centre for natural ventilation throughout. Fully built with exposed red-bricks and concrete, this green building is also entirely powered by solar panel. Lush greenery occupies breakout spaces for the worker who to enjoy views out to the nature. Double layered brick walls at the west facing facade cut down heat gain substantially.\r\nBeing the first building in the country to win PAM Awards in SDGs category, 1 Lasam has fulfilled eight category in this United Nation's standard. It is a bold addition to Ipoh's cityscape and contributes positively to the country's sustainability scene.	1 Lasam was conceptualised more than eight years ago by the owner Dato Lim, when GBI rating tool was new and there was still no other green buildings in Perak. The amicable and ambitious client wanted to build the first ever GBI Platinum building in the state, to resonate with the group’s motto of being a pioneer in many of the businesses they have ventured in since decades ago.\r\n\r\n¬ A central courtyard was carved in the centre, to allow more daylighting into the office spaces. Nako windows were installed at high levels of all office spaces for natural cross and stack ventilation through the central courtyard, so that during a cool day no air conditioning would be required. \r\n\r\nMeasuring about 30,000sf of office space, the 5-story office block comes with majority workspaces with ancillary spaces e.g. conference room, gallery space etc.The design team explored the concept of floating boxes which further developed into box-in-box geometry. The higher floors were lifted up supported by a bold V-shape column, to allow for vehicle circulation on the street level. With the neighbouring army camp, many restrictions in building design were imposed. The west facing double layered wall installed with dense louvres not only eliminated direct view to the camp, it also blocked the heat and sunlight to the office spaces in the evening. On this gesture, the Architect managed to kill two birds with one stone.\r\nEight categories for United Nation’s Sustainable Development Goals were achieved. The complying categories included Responsible Consumption and Production, as relatively high percentage of construction material was used and many construction waste being recycled. Clean Water and Sanitisation also played an important role in the design of the building. While both rainwater harvesting and greywater recycling led to high reduction in portable water, storm water control was also catered for, with a bioswales constructed on site for effective water drainage.\r\n\r\nOther green features included maximising electricity generation from the solar panels, rainwater and grey water harvesting, tinted glass, grasscrete for lowering heat island effect, and bioswales on site for effective storm water drainage etc. \r\n\r\nMaterials were selected carefully to reflect the client’s intention to keep the building as “raw” as possible. Exposed bare concrete, red bricks applied with waterproofing solution, simple aluminium framed tinted glass, exposed ceiling throughout, and to many’s surprises, not a single drip of paint was used in the entire building. \r\n\r\nTo resonate further the V-shape land and V-shape column, V-shape balustrades were designed to emphasise the strong alphabet presence of the client’s mother company name “BVH”.\r\n\r\n1 Lasam was perhaps one of the boldest new addition to Ipoh’s low profile skyline. It’s head-turning architecture has attracted interests from professionals and the public in general since it’s completion. With Dato’s intention to allow public access on the ground floor for green building education, we believe this building will contribute positively to the local sustainable architecture scene in many years to come.	3 3.9 1. Waterproofing sealant with no formaldehyde 3.A 1. 10 m of outdoor building smoking area away from building openings 6 6.3 1. Storm water control meeting MSMA requirements 6.4 1. Rainwater harvesting leads to 51% reduction in portable water 1. Greywater recycling leads to 12.03% reduction in portable water 1. Potable water for ALL landscape irrigation is NOT needed 1. Reduced annual potable water consumption by 67.55% 7 7.2 Solar PV panels for renewable energy (40kWp) 11 11.C Up to 37.10% of the total material cost are regional materials 12.1. Up to 26.40% of total material cost to have recycled content 1. Dedicated recycling bins during construction stage 1. At least 75% of construction waste is diverted to recycling centre 12.6 1. Dedicated recycling bins during construction stage 1. At least 50% of construction waste is diverted to recycling centre 12.8 1. Real time energy and water usage display 13 13.1 Use zero ODP products 14 14.1 Storm water control meeting MSMA requirements 15 15.1 Project complies with local town planning requirements 15.2 1. 100% of all timber products (mainly doors) were certified by MTCC/ FSC	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	LDP2	Ar. Shyuan Kuee	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
e48c80de-5e5a-45d3-be9e-508b9126eab6	MA Arch	Morohoshi	morohoshi@maruarchi.com	Hanaju Renovation	IMPLEMENTED	SUBMITTED	SECTION_IV	Tokyo	Japan	35.726	139.7673	This is a renovation project for an old flower shop “Hanaju”, located at the entrance of Yanaka Cemetery. Established in 1877, the traditional townhouse had undergone numerous additions over time. Rather than restoring it to a fixed past, the project aimed to create a “living preservation” by embracing the building’s evolving history. The renovation connected structures from different eras and gradually opened them to the outside. A new steel frame extended the existing structure, designed to transcend time like the traditional wooden frames. New elements were offset to blur the boundaries between old and new, creating a dynamic, continuous space that evolves with use.	This is a renovation project for an old flower shop “Hanaju”, located at the entrance of Yanaka Cemetery. Established in 1877, the traditional townhouse had undergone numerous additions over time. Rather than restoring it to a fixed past, the project aimed to create a “living preservation” by embracing the building’s evolving history. The renovation connected structures from different eras and gradually opened them to the outside. A new steel frame extended the existing structure, designed to transcend time like the traditional wooden frames. New elements were offset to blur the boundaries between old and new, creating a dynamic, continuous space that evolves with use.	See detailed description	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-04-18 13:00:15.086189	2026-04-18 13:00:15.086189	P101	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
1ebbded5-9a1d-4883-8378-ca8431290760	Architectural Society of China	Yehao Song	sup_atelier@supatelier.com	Wastewater Resource Recovery Plant of Yixing	IMPLEMENTED	APPROVED	SECTION_IV	Yixing	China	31.36	119.815	The Concept WRRF Yixing, is a future-oriented Water Resource Recovery Facility & factory. The aim of the project is to upgrade conventional sewage treatment plants to environmental-friendly and re-cycling-oriented plants. Alleviating the Not-in-my-backyard effect, the upgrade will transform a closed pollution-control plant into a sustainable and future-oriented infrastructure project that is environmental-friendly, open to the public, harmonious with its neighborhood and available for sci-ence education.	The overall planning of the plant is implemented in pursuit of an intensive layout, the efficient use of land, the integration of landscape & buildings, and the care for human. \r\nThe waste water will be treated into clean water , fertilizers and energies, such as biogas and thermal energy. The clean water will irrigate farmland and return to nature. The fertilizers and energies are sustainable products from waste resources.\r\nA special “Tank Cafe” clings to the southern wall of a secondary sedimentation tank. The specially designed space can be also transformed into a muti functional conference hall or exhibition hall, serving for both professional and popular science activities. Several small courtyards scattered in the coffee shop has optimized views and positions of openings while covering structural elements and separating different zones. \r\nHere people can percept, experience or even play with its features, enjoying the changes of nature, the diversity of ecological environment. Through the project, the conservation of resources, the care for environment and the respect for humanity are spread to the public\r\nThe core value of the project lies in creating a conceptual plant that not only meets industrial de-mands, but also serves as a public space that draws people close to it. Here people can percept, ex-perience or even play with its features, enjoying the changes of nature, the diversity of ecological environment and the ever-changing patterns of light. Through the delicate spatial experience, con-cepts of the plant are conveyed to people, raising their awareness for the conservation of resources, the care for environment and the respect for humanity.\r\nThe overall planning and architectural design of the plant area respect and integrate the design of sewage and sludge treatment processes, and basically achieve the four goals of "water quality sus-tainability, resource recycling, energy self-sufficiency, and environmental friendliness".	The Concept WRRF Yixing, is a future-oriented Water Resource Recovery Facility & factory. The aim of the project is to upgrade conventional sewage treatment plants to environmental-friendly and re-cycling-oriented plants. Alleviating the Not-in-my-backyard effect, the upgrade will transform a closed pollution-control plant into a sustainable and future-oriented infrastructure project that is environmental-friendly, open to the public, harmonious with its neighborhood and available for sci-ence education.\r\nThe overall planning of the plant is implemented in pursuit of an intensive layout, the efficient use of land, the integration of landscape & buildings, and the care for human. \r\nThe waste water will be treated into clean water , fertilizers and energies, such as biogas and thermal energy. The clean water will irrigate farmland and return to nature. The fertilizers and energies are sustainable products from waste resources.\r\nThe overall planning and architectural design of the plant area respect and integrate the design of sewage and sludge treatment processes, and basically achieve the four goals of "water quality sus-tainability, resource recycling, energy self-sufficiency, and environmental friendliness".	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:0