70b431fb-0f42-42d4-a031-38a1623c369b	Bangladesh University of Engineering and Technology (BUET)	Aqib Mohammad Nibir	aqibnibir1659@gmail.com	Repurposing The Barisal Riverport – For Socially Inclusive and Sustainable Urban Life	PLANNED	APPROVED	SECTION_IV	Barishal	Bangladesh	22.701	90.3535	Once known as Gird-e-Bhandar in Mughal period, the Barisal Riverport, Bangladesh's second-largest transit port, is gradually losing its prominence following the inauguration of the Padma Bridge. Previously, travel between Barisal and Dhaka by river took 7–8 hours, but the new road connection has reduced that to just 3 hours. As a result, most commuters have shifted to road transportation for their time efficiency slowly deserting the main driving force of this port.  Despite being surrounded by dense commercial activity, the riverport is at risk of becoming obsolete and consumed by unregulated commercial sprawl. This proposal seeks to reimagine the port’s role not only as a transit hub but also as a civic and cultural landmark, preserving its 154-year-old legacy and adapting it to Barisal’s evolving urban landscape. With growing economic development around the Payra Power Plant and an international tourism vision for Kuakata in the south, the riverport holds strategic importance for both regional stakeholders and visitors.  Integrating the Urban Fabric-  Currently, a buffer of heavy commercial and administrative zoning isolates the riverfront from nearby residential areas. The project aims to break this urban barrier and return valuable riverfront space to the people—while retaining its operational port functions. By reconnecting key urban activity nodes with the river, the design weaves the riverport back into the city's fabric. To encourage sustainable mobility, dedicated cycle lanes run alongside pedestrian walkways, linking active city areas to a rooftop riverfront promenade. This promotes healthier lifestyles, reduces future traffic congestion, cuts carbon emissions, and enhances air quality. By making the waterfront part of daily life not just an economic asset, the city cultivates a deeper appreciation for the river and promotes a collective sense of stewardship.  Reimagining the Riverport  A critical challenge is balancing public access with uninterrupted port operations. The design addresses this by introducing a three-layer system:  1. Rooftop Level: Connected to major urban activity zones, this level features a riverfront restaurant, open promenade, continuous pedestrian and cycle lanes, gathering spaces, and shaded seating areas—activating the riverfront as a vibrant public realm.  2. Port Building Level: Ensures seamless transitions between roadways and pontoons, facilitating smooth boarding and cargo handling without disrupting port functions.  3. Lower Liminal Level: Designed as a landscaped, accessible zone that welcomes the public to engage with the waterfront through boat rides, swimming, and other water-based leisure activities, linked to adjacent riverfront areas.	Once known as Gird-e-Bhandar in Mughal period, the Barisal Riverport, Bangladesh's second-largest transit port, is gradually losing its prominence following the inauguration of the Padma Bridge. Previously, travel between Barisal and Dhaka by river took 7–8 hours, but the new road connection has reduced that to just 3 hours. As a result, most commuters have shifted to road transportation for their time efficiency slowly deserting the main driving force of this port.  Despite being surrounded by dense commercial activity, the riverport is at risk of becoming obsolete and consumed by unregulated commercial sprawl. This proposal seeks to reimagine the port’s role not only as a transit hub but also as a civic and cultural landmark, preserving its 154-year-old legacy and adapting it to Barisal’s evolving urban landscape. With growing economic development around the Payra Power Plant and an international tourism vision for Kuakata in the south, the riverport holds strategic importance for both regional stakeholders and visitors.  Integrating the Urban Fabric-  Currently, a buffer of heavy commercial and administrative zoning isolates the riverfront from nearby residential areas. The project aims to break this urban barrier and return valuable riverfront space to the people—while retaining its operational port functions. By reconnecting key urban activity nodes with the river, the design weaves the riverport back into the city's fabric. To encourage sustainable mobility, dedicated cycle lanes run alongside pedestrian walkways, linking active city areas to a rooftop riverfront promenade. This promotes healthier lifestyles, reduces future traffic congestion, cuts carbon emissions, and enhances air quality. By making the waterfront part of daily life not just an economic asset, the city cultivates a deeper appreciation for the river and promotes a collective sense of stewardship.  Reimagining the Riverport  A critical challenge is balancing public access with uninterrupted port operations. The design addresses this by introducing a three-layer system:  1. Rooftop Level: Connected to major urban activity zones, this level features a riverfront restaurant, open promenade, continuous pedestrian and cycle lanes, gathering spaces, and shaded seating areas—activating the riverfront as a vibrant public realm.  2. Port Building Level: Ensures seamless transitions between roadways and pontoons, facilitating smooth boarding and cargo handling without disrupting port functions.  3. Lower Liminal Level: Designed as a landscaped, accessible zone that welcomes the public to engage with the waterfront through boat rides, swimming, and other water-based leisure activities, linked to adjacent riverfront areas.	See detailed description	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-04-18 13:00:15.086189	2026-04-18 13:00:15.086189	P81	Aqib Mohammad Nibir	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
3a1074f2-e312-4245-9f38-9d6787194c03	SUP Atelier of THAD	Yehao Song	sup_atelier@supatelier.com	Xuhui Demonstrative Project	IMPLEMENTED	APPROVED	SECTION_IV	Beijing	China	39.912433	116.401033	Located in Xuhui No.26 Block in Shunyi District of Beijing, the project was commissioned by Xuhui Group to create a small-scale sharing space in a leisure park. Powered by the sharing economy in vogue, the space can be booked by residents through an intelligence system. Moreover, through collaboration with BREEAM system in UK and LEED system in the US, the project serves as a zero-energy consumption demonstrative project in cold areas of North China, aiming to reduce energy consumption, improve thermal comfort, and promote sustainability through theme activities of mitigating the increasingly severe environmental problems.\r\n\r\nMain structures of prefabricated timberwork and louvers of prefabricated carbonized wood correspond to the zero-carbon concept from perspectives of materials and construction. Architectural elements of the 3 units were classified into various groups of standardized modules with green technology. Through modification and combination, these modules can adapt to various spaces and facilitate comparative studies and promotion of sustainable technologies.\r\n \r\nThe buildings are equipped with intelligence control systems. Through real-time monitoring of the environmental indicators (temperature, humidity, illumination, CO2, PM 2.5, infrared rays)， the energy system can be controlled automatically to save energy and reduce emission. The public can view the real-time indicators, too.	Located in Xuhui No.26 Block in Shunyi District of Beijing, the project was commissioned by Xuhui Group’s Beijing office to create a small-scale sharing space in a leisure park. Powered by the sharing economy in vogue, the space can be booked by residents through an intelligence system. Moreover, through collaboration with BREEAM system in UK and LEED system in the US, the project serves as a zero-energy consumption demonstrative project in cold areas of North China, aiming to reduce energy consumption, improve thermal comfort, and promote sustainability through theme activities of mitigating the increasingly severe environmental problems. \r\n\r\n The project borders a community playground on the south. Unlike the centralized layout often seen in sustainable projects, the main building consists of 3 similar units that are scattered among trees as small-scaled landscape buildings: a fitness center, a lounge and a book cafe (doubling as a showroom of popular science), which can be operated separately. The 3 units center on a sunken courtyard paved with permeable gravel. Users can enter this small building cluster via a wooden walkway through the rain garden. The overhead wooden walkway and the pipe trenches underneath connects the 3 units with a half-earthed energy & smart control center, forming a “3 driven by 1” mode. \r\n\r\nMain structures of prefabricated timberwork and louvers of prefabricated carbonized wood correspond to the zero-carbon concept from perspectives of materials and construction. Architectural elements of the 3 units were classified into various groups of standardized modules with green technology. Through modification and combination, these modules can adapt to various spaces and facilitate comparative studies and promotion of sustainable technologies.\r\n \r\nAs an experimental platform for prefabricated buildings with zero energy consumption, the project has established an integrated mechanism of “design-construction-test-feedback” process. With the help of information technology, the analysis of sustainable indicators can bring forth implementation methods, which can fit in newly built and renovated buildings in cold areas, or serve as prototypes in both public and housing projects. \r\n\r\nThis project is located in a cold area, where heating and cooling energy consumption are both huge. High-performance envelopes with thermal indicators greatly outperforming the minimum code. Passive design strategies, such as projected roofs with air-ducting devices and composite façades with photovoltaic double glazing and prefabricated double-layered wooden envelope, which can boost natural ventilation. \r\n\r\nThe applications of renewable energy include film glass, photovoltaic power generation, and a hybrid heating system powered by both solar thermal power and air-source heat pump. Sustainable drainage strategies have been integrated into the landscape, too: Green roofs and a permeable courtyard can purify and retain rainwater. \r\n\r\nThe buildings are equipped with intelligence control systems. Through real-time monitoring of the environmental indicators (temperature, humidity, illumination, CO2, PM 2.5, infrared rays)， the energy system can be controlled automatically to save energy and reduce emission. The public can view the real-time indicators, too.	SDGs 3: Ensure healthy lives and promote well-being for all at all ages\r\nConnection: The project was to create a small-scale sharing space in a leisure park. \r\nThe main building consists of 3 similar units that are scattered among trees as small-scaled landscape buildings: a fitness center, a lounge and a book cafe (doubling as a showroom of popular science), which can be operated separately. Powered by the sharing economy in vogue, the space can be booked by residents through an intelligence system.\r\n\r\nSDGs 6: Ensure availability and sustainable management of water and sanitation for all\r\nConnection: The 3 units center on a sunken courtyard paved with permeable gravel. The overhead wooden walkway and the pipe trenches underneath connects the 3 units with a half-earthed energy & smart control center, forming a “3 driven by 1” mode. Sustainable drainage strategies have been integrated into the landscape too: Green roofs and a permeable courtyard can purify and retain rainwater.\r\n\r\nSDGs 7: Ensure access to affordable, reliable, sustainable and modern energy for all\r\nConnection: The applications of renewable energy include film glass, photovoltaic power generation, and a hybrid heating system powered by both solar thermal power and air-source heat pump.\r\nThe buildings are equipped with intelligence control systems. Through real-time monitoring of the environmental indicators (temperature, humidity, illumination, CO2, PM 2.5, infrared rays)， the energy system can be controlled automatically to save energy and reduce emission. The public can view the real-time indicators, too.\r\n\r\nSDGs 13: Take urgent action to combat climate change and its impacts\r\nConnection: Main structures of prefabricated timberwork and louvers of prefabricated carbonized wood correspond to the zero-carbon concept from perspectives of materials and construction. Architectural elements of the 3 units were classified into various groups of standardized modules with green technology. Through modification and combination, these modules can adapt to various spaces and facilitate comparative studies and promotion of sustainable technologies.\r\nThis project is located in a cold area, where heating and cooling energy consumption are both huge. High-performance envelopes with thermal indicators greatly outperforming the minimum code. Passive design strategies, such as projected roofs with air-ducting devices and composite façades with photovoltaic double glazing and prefabricated double-layered wooden envelope, which can boost natural ventilation. \r\nAs an experimental platform for prefabricated buildings with zero energy consumption, the project has established an integrated mechanism of “design-construction-test-feedback” process. With the help of information technology, the analysis of sustainable indicators can bring forth implementation methods, which can fit in newly built and renovated buildings in cold areas, or serve as prototypes in both public and housing projects.	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	LDP18	Yehao Song , Xiaojuan Chen, Dan Xie, Zhenghao Lin	157	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
59ee9feb-02ff-480a-b078-f0f6dc55bdae	SUP Atelier of THAD	Yehao Song	sup_atelier@supatelier.com	The indoor playground of the rural middle school	IMPLEMENTED	APPROVED	SECTION_IV	Yueyang	China	29.1446	113.1161	Located in central rural China, the project creates an indoor playground and lecture hall with natural ventilation and natural lighting, and invigorates the regularly planned campus.	Located in central rural China, the project accommodates an indoor playground and lecture hall and invigorates the regularly planned campus. The building stretches across the altitude of the site with the main space at the higher part and service room at the lower part. Natural ventilation and lighting serve as major sustainable strategies to improve thermal comfort. Prefabricated materials and construction methods are chosen to reduce the cost of equipment and maintenance of the project.	The project is being used as a shared teaching facility for villagers and students to reduce poverty, improve education quality and creates sustainable communities. It retains the trees of the current land, uses recyclable and prefabricated materials for construction, and integrate innovative passive design strategy to reduce construction cost and energy consumptions. The color puzzle façade design originates from the local lake and popularizes the concept of sustainable architecture in daily use.	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	LDP19	Yehao Song, Xiaojuan Chen, Dan Xie, Jingfen Sun, Suritu Bai, Yingnan Chu, Dongchen Han, Haowei Yu.	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
b3129b1f-9c33-4b2c-a452-d8caa49069c2	SUP Atelier of THAD	Yehao Song	sup_atelier@supatelier.com	Gaobeidian Railway City sustainable demonstration pavilion	IMPLEMENTED	APPROVED	SECTION_IV	Gaobeidian	China	39.28486	115.954605	The project is an exhibition pavilion with passive house certification, within which the sustainable architecture strategies and the edge-cutting building techniques could be introduced to the public.	The pavilion is targeted at PHI standard combined with sustainable strategies and architectural interests of the team. The basic prototype is made of two wedges, an atrium inserted into the main body improving interior ventilation and a terraced atrium connecting exterior and interior. The north side is sheltered with earth merging into landscape, highly reducing the thermal losses. The curtain wall on south side works as a solar collector in winter and helps to prevent interior from overheat with an automatic sun-shading system. As for landscape, traditional Chinese garden features are adopted to create interesting experience outdoors.	The project aims to create a healthy, comfortable and eco-friendly nZEB building using passive strategies and active strategies and introduce a low-carbon lifestyle to the public. The project is also an experimental platform for scientific research-practice linkage to promote the development of sustainable building, cultivating high-quality contractors and workers, practicing design strategies and edge-cutting techniques and laying the foundation of carbon neutrality. During the whole process of the project, female participants play important roles in each decision-making process.	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	LDP22	Yehao Song, Jingfen Sun, Dan Xie, Yingnan Chu, Xiaojuan Chen, Dongchen Han, Zhenghao Lin	1400	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
f1b4b845-4720-4b38-b7db-c56d9c08bfdb	Architectural Society of China	Yehao Song	sup_atelier@supatelier.com	THE-Studio (Tsinghua Eco Studio)	IMPLEMENTED	APPROVED	SECTION_IV	Guian New Area	China	26.4688	106.4831	THE-Studio(Tsinghua Eco Studio) is both a practical demonstration case which deeply integrates sustainable design strategies with ecological technologies,and an experimental platform for sustainable, aiming to building technologies can truly suit to the local conditions of climate and culture.	In THE-Studio timber frameworks are employed in the large-space exhibition hall and the prefab light-steel modules are used to at both sides. Sustainable service systems are mostly plugged into the cavity of facades.The modular double-skin facade system is a unique integration of vernacular rattan-weaving craftsmanship with industrial prefabrication technology,highly expressing site-specific characteristics.\r\nThe passive design methods responding to local climatic factors of natural wind,solar radiation and daylight are further contrived by the design team.The design team highly encourages usage of renewable materials and promote the employment of vernacular materials and craftsmanship which can decrease the carbon footprint during .	THE-Studio can provide a high-quality research space for both men and women to enhance their professional competence.The design team placed great emphasis on passive design strategies that respond to local climate factors.First,the double-skin facades consisting of double-glazed and the rattan-weaving double skin are typical climate responsive design.Second,the use of renewable energy has greatly reduced the waste generation.Building adopts the passive air-conditioning system.It also combines Rainwater recycling and ecological landscape together.Using renewable materials can both decrease the carbon footprint during whole life span.In the construction process,the design team mobilized the local people,provided a large number of jobs,and brought opportunities and development to the industry.In the future,local people can replace the rattan weaving on the facade by themselves.	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	LDP62	Song Yehao,  Sun Jingfen,  Chen Xiaojuan,  Lin Zhenghao, Han Dongchen, Xie Dan	701	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
1be86df9-91c4-483e-bfb7-e00c932563e4	Juri Troy Architects	Prof. Arch. Mag. Juri Troy	office@juritroy.at	VELUX Sunlighthouse	IMPLEMENTED	APPROVED	SECTION_I	Vienna	Austria	48.182288	16.075958	The Sunlighthouse is the first CO²-neutral single-family-house in Austria. The challenge was to develop an energy and ecological concept that would eliminate the ecological footprint for the next thirty years.	The building equipment includes a high performing heat pump, 48 m² mono crystalline photovoltaic roof panels, 9 m² thermal solar panels for hot water and a controlled air system with heat recovery. The roof and facade windows were strategically positioned to maximize passive solar energy, to enable optimal, natural ventilation during summer and to minimize the thermal losses during winter. The Sunlighthouse will produce more energy than the construction as well as the usage of the house consumes.	Our team took the big challenge to create a house that will produce more energy in 30 years than it will need for building, transport, heating and electrical use all together. That means that after this period it will produce even more energy as it ever consumed and will therefore be some kind of a small power station. We also focused on the use of new well performed materials that need very few ore non CO² to be produced.	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	LDP8	Prof. Arch. Mag. Juri Troy, DI Matthias Hein	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
4ebdb9d1-194f-438f-9de6-a7eb49b42109	SUP ATELIER OF THAD	Yehao Song	sup_atelier@supatelier.com	Tea Leaf Market of Zhuguanlong	IMPLEMENTED	APPROVED	SECTION_IV	Fujian	China	26.484	117.925	Zhuguanlong Township of Shouning County, Ningde City of Fujian Province, where the Tea Leaf Market is located, is a township fertile in tea leaf yet to be lifted out of poverty at the time of the project’s planning phase. Zhuguanlong Tea Leaf Market featured a multi-functional tea leaf market, aiming for a boost in tea leaf economy and better public spaces for local people..\r\n\r\nA large-span space was proposed for various functions at different times of the year based on earlier bamboo construction experience, fundamental functions of the market and other demands by the public. Apart from seasonal tea leaf trading, the market can be used for farm product trading, villagers’ short stay and children’s sports activities. On special occasions such as weddings and funerals, people can also gather under the market’s roof for a feast. \r\n\r\nThe project‘s structural form inspired by a sort of traditional woven arch structure built with local raw bamboo. Locally obtained natural materials and recycled building materials such as soil, wood and stone were all used for construction, motivating local craftsmen to wisely “turn wastes into treasures” with refined local building technologies, presenting a well-utilized public building to the villagers.	Zhuguanlong Township of Shouning County, Ningde City of Fujian Province, is a township fertile of tea leaf yet to be lifted out of poverty at the time of the project’s planning phase. A multi-purpose large-span space was proposed as a tea market in the town. Apart from seasonal tea leaf trading, the market can be used for farm product trading, villagers’ short stay and children’s sports activities. On special occasions such as weddings, funerals and the local beggar festival, people can also gather under the market’s roof for a feast. \r\n\r\nThe design team thoroughly studied building technologies of “rainbow bridge”, a sort of traditional wooden arch bridge achieved with ancient people’s wisdom, searching for solutions. The team found that the shelters could both be built with simple traditional building methods as the rainbow bridge with refined bamboo construction technologies. Finally, through craftsmen’s simple processing of raw bamboo, which Zhuguanlong township was richly endowed with, a woven bamboo structure with an 18-meter span was completed\r\n\r\nThe project built with locally obtained and recycled materials, which is people-centered, low-carbon and innovative. The design team thoroughly studied the possibility of recycling local materials. Field study showed that red soil on site was frequently used on local rammed-earth walls; bamboo woods prosper in mountainous lands along the site; dilapidated houses, which were being demolished at that time, could provide rubble from wall foundations and wood pieces from pillars and beams. As a result, recycled rubbles were used on newly built walls, while red soil on site was rammed into walls by local craftsmen; moso bamboo, through anti-corrosion treatment by the bamboo contractor, was assembled into large-span structures; recycled wood pieces was processed into wooden couches or wood bricks within rammed-earth walls. \r\n\r\nThe design team also visited a stone processing factory to collect stone leftovers from processing, which were later cut into smaller pieces on both exterior and interior pavement. Those recycled materials, usually seen as wastes and thus coming at very low costs, were re-utilized by local villagers and craftsmen and extended their life in a new place, bearing our respect for people’s wisdom and labor. \r\n\r\nZhuguanlong Tea Leaf Market is one project of the team’s series of sustainable practices and can be viewed as sustainable from environmental, social and economic perspectives. \r\nTo achieve environmental sustainability, the project was built with locally obtained and recycled materials with low innate carbon footprint. Besides, it has made full use of natural ventilation, daylighting and rain-water landscapes, achieving harmony with surrounding natural lands. \r\n\r\nTo achieve economic sustainability, the planning of the project was established under the premise of boosting local agricultural economy, enriching daily life in the community and involving local people in construction to make profits for their families. To achieve social sustainability, the market was positioned as a space of the people, by the people and for the people. Besides, through the use of local materials and refined traditional building technologies, local features were showcased throughout the building, celebrating the township’s unique culture and history.	Goal 1: No Poverty (1.3 1.4)\r\nThe project was built to equal the local Tea leaf trade economy resources, provide the villagers with a quality public space for sharing business opportunities instead of decentralized tealeaf transaction.\r\n\r\nGoal 2: Zero Hunger (2.3)\r\nThe small scale vegetable farmers has raised their incomes. The Market provides them a better place and chance to sell their products.\r\n\r\nGoal 3: Good Health and Well-being (3.3)\r\nAn open roof could boost natural ventilation and daylighting, reducing operational costs. Against COVID-19 pandemic, it could be used for pandemic prevention coordination, nucleic tests and medical observation.\r\n \r\nGoal 4: Quality Education (4.7) \r\nThe project sometimes serves as a community school for villagers.\r\n\r\nGoal 5: Gender Equality (5.5) \r\nThe township head is a lady, who participated in decision-making of the project. 30%-40% architects, engineer, artisan, who involved in this project are women.   \r\n\r\nGoal 6: Clean Water and Sanitation (6.6)\r\nThe rainwater drainages are well organized and all rainwater above the roof were imported either to the Greenland or to the canal to mountain stream.    \r\n\r\nGoal 7: Affordable and Clean Energy (7.3)\r\nThe design has made full use of sunlight for indoor lighting and natural ventilation in summer for better environment. The passive strategies save lots of energy consumption, use the minimum energy consumption lights up 500sqm.\r\n\r\nGoal 8: Decent Work and Economic Growth (8.1 8.8 8.9)\r\nThe project improves the tealeaf trade, makes the local economic growth, promotes safe and healthy working environment for tea famers. The iconic architectural design enhances the local tourism popularity.  \r\n\r\nGoal 9: Industry, Innovation and Infrastructure (9.2 9.B)\r\nThe project encourages the bamboo construction industry, the local rammed earth construction industry, which are the sustainable industrialization. The special bamboo construction technology is distinctive and domestic.\r\n\r\nGoal 10: Reducing Inequality (10.1 10.2)\r\nThe market is an open space for all tea farmers to share the trade information and resources, to reduce the income inequalities. It’s also a covered square, where the community activities, public meetings, discussions, could be held to promote universal social, economic and political inclusion.  \r\n\r\nGoal 11: Sustainable Cities and Communities (11.C 11.4 11.6)\r\nThe project is constructed by the local people with recycled materials, local technologies, so the cost is extremely affordable. Bamboo and rammed earth are local materials. The rest construction materials such as rubble and woods from the demolished ruins, roadside abandoned slates, and waste from stone factory, are recycled near the site. They are processed and reused in the project. The construction technologies such as Woven bridge technology is listed in the UNESCO’s Intangible cultural heritage, and the rammed earth technology is learned from the World Cultural Heritage Tulou building. These construction strategies with recycled and local materials, with vernacular technologies and by the local craftsmen, support the least developed area in sustainable and resilient building.\r\n\r\nGoal 12: Responsible Consumption and Production (12.2 12.5 12.8)\r\nThe main materials of the project are bamboo and rammed earth from natural resources, which could be get from the surroundings environment easily. The recycled materials are appropriate used in the project, reduced the waste generation, and universal understanding of sustainable lifestyles.\r\n\r\nGoal 13: Climate Action (13.3)\r\nThe project are built by the biodegradable low-carbon material such as bamboo and earth, in low-carbon maintenance and operation. It’s a good case for the public to build knowledge and capacity, that natural material construction could be a solution for climate change.\r\n\r\nGoal 16: Peace, Justice and Strong Institutions (16.7)\r\nThis project is a results of democratic decision-making. The bamboo roof construction is supported by local villagers and governments. Using the recycled materials were proposed by villagers and supported and approved by architects and local craftsmen, The Multi-functional mode of use are suggested by local residents. \r\n\r\nGoal 17: Partnerships for the Goals (17.1 17.6 17.9)\r\nThe project served as tealeaf market, which brings more trade resources and popular tourist scenic spot, brings more local income and benefits, also more revenue collections for the township. During the whole process, the Design team from the best University in China had a chance to lean and share the traditional woven arch bridge technology, rammed earth technology from local, and innovative improve those technology to make them used in modern construction. The Knowledge sharing and cooperation between local craftsmen and scholars and engineers from university, made the special construction innovation.  \r\nThe whole project proved, that with the appropriate method, Appropriate technology, natural resources, the SDG capacity in developing countries could be enhanced and distinctive.	\N	\N	\N	\