486ff423-3fd5-476f-b040-8a4be25c267f	Manasaram Architects	Ar. Neelam Manjunath	mansarch@gmail.com	Bamboo Symphony	IMPLEMENTED	APPROVED	SECTION_IV	Bengaluru	India	12.97422	77.593185	Bamboo Symphony, the office of Manasaram Architects is a beacon for a new era of office design. The building embodies the core principles of the firm being a zero energy sustainably built development.	Wrapping around the RWH pond spread across multiple levels the open office layout fosters collaboration. The structural system was developed by experimentation, research and working on site with artisans and employing vernacular knowledge. Illustrating use of Bamboo Reinforced Concrete, & slant bamboo columns, the project showcases Bamboo as a 21st CE construction material. Protected yet open to the exteriors the office is well ventilated, & cooler employing bio-climatic design to its fullest.	SDG 8:The built work is a beacon for collaborative invigorating workplaces.\r\nSDG 9(9.5 & 9.b):The project was constructed upon research into local knowledge & serves as a beacon in the context of developing countries.\r\nSDG 11(11.a):Ventilation, daylight, RWH & closed loop systems, the project promotes sustainable communities.\r\nSDG 12(12.2, 12.7, 12.8 & 12.a):Using leftover materials & employing bamboo as the primary structural material, this design illustrates the practice of responsible construction.	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	LDP45	PRINCIPAL ARCHITECT: Ar. Neelam Manjunath  TEAM: Ar. Sanjita Harwalker   CHIEF MASON: Gopal Prasad Tanti  BAMBOO ARTISAN:Anand Lal Marandi  Consultants:  Building material & Technology             – Center for Green Building Material & Technology, Bangalore. Rainwater Harvesting                            – Prof. A.R.Shivkumar, IISc, Bangalore. Waste Water Treatment                        – CDD Society, DEWATs, Bangalore. Compressed Stabilized Earth Blocks    – Dr.Yogananda, Mrinmayee, Bangalore.	210	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
e594556c-ca7e-48dc-8299-bb97f2ef4301	Studio Lotus	Harsh Vardhan	media@studiolotus.in	Krushi Bhawan	IMPLEMENTED	APPROVED	SECTION_IV	Bhubaneswar	India	20.296059	85.824539	Krushi Bhawan is a government facility that transcends the typical closed office campus morphology by integrating governmental functions with direct community engagement and education.	Krushi Bhawan engenders community participation with the ground floor designed as a free-flowing public space supporting numerous public functions, including workshops and haats (weekly markets). The terrace features urban farming exhibits and crop samples to educate farmers. The patterned brick façade draws on the region's famed ikat dyeing techniques and the design integrates passive, low-tech climate mechanisms to limit mechanical air-conditioning to only 20% of the built areas.	The project involved over 100 artisans to create a contemporary narrative of traditional Odia craft at an unprecedented architectural scale, promoting craftsmanship and regional scopes of employment. The intervention also demonstrates how public institutions can support regional crafts and sustain the communities built around them. Krushi Bhawan thus seeks to embody the idea of truly inclusive architecture — created for and built by the people and representing their collective cultural identity.	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	LDP30	Design Team: Ambrish Arora, Sidhartha Talwar, Raman Vig, Sachin Dabas	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
a34274d1-f5c9-4b55-a16e-e952a59ac87a	Studio Cardenas Conscious Design	Arch. Mauricio Cardenas Laverde	m.cardenas@studiocardenas.it	Energy Efficient Bamboo House	IMPLEMENTED	APPROVED	SECTION_IV	Baoxi	China	28.00611	118.76028	Energy Efficient Bamboo House confirms that using natural materials for construction, as bamboo, is the most viable means to reduce embodied carbon in buildings, inspiring new architectural languages.	The Energy Efficient Bamboo House, built for the first International Bamboo Architecture Biennale, stands out for its golden proportions and modular design, facilitating assembly of the bamboo canes even by unskilled workers. It is an excellent illustration of BooTech construction system, using mechanically applied joints to connect the bamboo canes. Unlike mainstream approach, which uses cement as a filler, BooTech leaves the cane intact making it possible to replace when needed.	Bamboo plant tackles 7 SDGs, using it for construction with a proper technique, as BooTech, offers a truly expendable alternative to the use of polluting steel and concrete, enabling us to rethink architecture in eco-friendly ways, in keeping with the SDGs. Energy Efficient Bamboo House is a resilient architecture that promotes inclusive and sustainable industrialization and sustainable use of terrestrial ecosystems, fosters innovation, combats climate change and can be globally implemented.	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	LDP55	Arch.Mauricio Cardenas Laverde	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
f0c719cf-96a5-4161-a167-472ccb29dd91	WM Creative Studio - Relab	Muhammad Nafeel Qureshi	nafeel@wmcreativestudio.com.pk	Development Delirium: how architecture nurtures inequality	IMPLEMENTED	APPROVED	SECTION_IV	Karachi	Pakistan	24.89114	67.04658	A Retrofit housing in Gujjarnalla Karachi slums, Pakistan, an equitable and ethical design solutions to negotiate with the existing building/structure/system to improve inhabitants’ life.	With more than 55% of the world's population living in cities, and half of the metropolis citizen lives in informal settlements, it is fundamental to explore design by means of bilateral negotiations and architecture which fulfill citizens’ needs. Retrofit Housing typology is explored based on residents’ needs, cost-effectiveness and encourages communities to rebuild their homes to improve community engagement through design to improve livability.	The project will address GOAL 10 & 1 to reduce inequalities and end poverty by improving livability by implementing resilient & safe retrofit housing solution GOAL 11. Further providing school, community center & clinic promoting opportunity to quality education and well-being will satisfy GOAL 4 & 5. Improving the dying need of the neighborhood and city by implementing wetland to improve sanitation and improve city ecology will support GOAL 6.	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	IFF52	Muhammad Nafeel Qureshi, Wajiha Siddiqui Mehdi, and Muhammad Mehdi	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
40ad1721-95e2-4944-9f83-855dbbf0ea5f	WM Creative Studio - Relab	Wajiha Siddiqui	wajiha@wmcreativestudio.com.pk	The Baitussalam School	IMPLEMENTED	APPROVED	SECTION_IV	Jacobabad	Pakistan	28.2793	68.43727	A primary school in Jacobabad, Pakistan, conceptualized to counter education system vulnerabilities & climate emergencies with sustainable modular design, bamboo framework, and child-centric spaces.	It is a reimagining of schools in a significantly challenged education system in Jacobabad, one of the hottest rural regions of Pakistan, which was also severely affected by the catastrophic floods of 2022. The adaptable module comprises two rooms and a courtyard, facilitating integration for flexible indoor/outdoor, formal/informal learning spaces. The school also features a step farm, renewable energy rainwater harvesting /solar energy, and an emergency refuge double roof covered with fabric.	This school will address Goal 17 through partnerships with the local community and organizations to create a sustainable and affordable learning environment. It will support Goal 13 by utilizing sustainable construction materials and step farming to promote climate action. Job creation in construction and permaculture will satisfy Goals 8 and 2. Goals 10 and 4 will be supported by reducing inequalities in education and designing secure child-centric learning spaces.	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	IFF56	Muhammad Mehdi, Wajiha Siddiqui Mehdi, Muhammad Nafeel Qureshi, Nihal Ahmed Barry & Muhammad Bilal	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
55328833-0302-41d8-a5ac-49d6e1465dbe	Centre for Green Building Materials Technology	Ar. Neelam Manjunath	mansarch@gmail.com	Flexi San Shell	IMPLEMENTED	APPROVED	SECTION_IV	Bengaluru	India	12.97422	77.593185	The uniqueness of these prefabricated toilets lies in their ability to completely collapse on themselves, manufactured and stored, ready for emergencies, deployed with great speed and unskilled labor.	Giving back to society, Flexi San Shell was developed by CGBMT in collaboration with the local community. A rapidly deployable toilet with portability at its heart, the structure a lightweight & collapsible. Ideal for use in disaster stricken or remote locations, the structure can create a small shell for sanitation use. The structure serves as a blueprint for community level initiatives for rapid fabrication. A small group of unskilled labour can assemble up to 50 of these toilets per day.	SDG 3: Prevent the spread of diseases by providing a safe and hygienic sanitation solution in areas without proper toilet facilities.\r\nSDG 6:We can provide access to basic sanitation facilities in areas without proper sanitation infrastructure. \r\nSDG 10:We can help to reduce inequalities in access to basic sanitation facilities, particularly for marginalized and vulnerable communities.	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	LDP44	Architect : Ar. Neelam Manjunath Artisans  : Mr.Anandi Lal Marandi                                    Mr.Gopal   Students : Smt. Neha Hegde                                    Sri. Vinya Kotle                                   Smt. Devina Agarwal	1.1	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
c3902c85-78a3-4f11-a250-a2ce56db2ac2	JP za PUP	Filip Joveski	fjoveski@gmail.com	Kindergarten Tocila, Prilep, N. Macedonia	IMPLEMENTED	APPROVED	SECTION_II	Prilep	North Macedonia	41.347	21.55695	The Kindergarten in Tocila, Prilep, N.Macedonia, is a two story building, with a capacity for 252 children (aged 9 months to 6 years). The plot is 5030m2, of which 1530m2 is under the ground floor, and the rest is green open space (playground) and parking plots for bikes and cars (regulations). The design of the facility incorporates simple, yet powerful superposition of volumes, shapes and accented colors. The design is: innovative (following the principles of Neuro Architecture for children); inclusive (without architectural barriers in and outside the buildings); green and sustainable (passive solar design, energy efficiency, environmentally friendly, renewable energy sources), beneficial to the overall well-being of all occupants and economically viable	The main idea was to design a projects that is green, sustainable, inclusive and adapted to the needs of every child. The building makes maximum use of the natural benefits offered by the sun. The location of the building within the boundaries of the site allows maximum use of the sun from the south side. All playrooms and nurseries (as well as the open-air playrooms) are with east, south-east, south and south-west direction, and have the possibility of natural ventilation and cooling throughout the year. The design of the facility incorporates simple, yet powerful superposition of volumes, shapes and accented colors (in the design of the floor plans, as well as in its spacial conception). All spaces are designed to benefit memory, improve cognitive capacity and improve mental stimulation of the children. The building has clear floor plans and clear visible circulation - central space and gallery halls that directly lead to each classroom on the ground and on the first floor. It provides landmarks for better orientation (colors and shapes), social spaces, enriched environments, natural light and open views to the green landscape surrounding the kindergarten.	The building design promotes good health and well-being (Goal 3) by providing a healthy indoor climate (natural ventilation/cooling and natural lighting, good acoustics and open views), which is very important for buildings with vulnerable users, such as children at their early age. It provides quality preprimary education (Goal 4) and a quality early childhood development and care, by enabling a productive learning environment (by creating spaces that benefit memory, improve cognitive capacity and improve mental stimulation by incorporating neuro architecture design principles), that is accessible and inclusive for all children (no architectural/physical barriers in or outside, with sensory room), which directly reduces inequalities (Goal 10) for the children with disabilities. Minimum energy consumption Is achieved by implementing passive solar system design (Goal 13 – Climate action) and implementation of renewable energy sources (Goal 7 - Affordable and Clean energy): orientation of building that offers max use of sun; compact form of building for reducing heat loss; building envelope elements that enable highest possible energy class; air source heat pump (with heat recovery) that is connected to the HVAC system (underfloor central heating system with time controls and separate thermostats for each room); PV panels that produce renewable electricity on site connected to the electrical installation and the air heat pump; water- and energy-efficient devices; No light pollution; Sanitary hot water (central generation) provided through solar water heating with solar collectors; Green roof for thermal insulation, sound absorption, purification of the air, and temperature reduction- reduction of 'urban heat island effect'.	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	LDP50	Filip Joveski	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
ef7b58cf-3b19-4ba9-8907-036821df1bbc	CP KUKREJA ARCHITECTS	Keshav Tomar	keshav.tomar@cpkukreja.com	Central Vista Redevelopment	IMPLEMENTED	APPROVED	SECTION_IV	New Delhi	India	28.635773	77.224433	The Redevelopment of Central Vista, New Delhi, is a historically and culturally significant project proposing the redevelopment over 440 Hectares of prime land. Reimagining New Delhi as a Garden City, the redevelopment proposal offers a possibility of bestowing it with an international iconic stature and creating a state-of-the-art futuristic and livable vision of urban development.	The Redevelopment of Central Vista, New Delhi, is a historically and culturally significant project proposing the redevelopment over 440 Hectares of prime land.\r\n\r\nUrban Context\r\nLocated in the heart of New Delhi, the capital of India, the design concepts are centred on restoration, adaptive re-use, intelligent conservation, upgradation, retrofitting and reconfiguration of the existing edifices to preserve the celebrated historic value of the area, along with creation of some landmark edifices. The site comprises of highly coveted buildings such as the Presidential Residence (Rashtrapati Bhawan), the North and South Blocks, the Indian Parliament, Ministerial Complexes, various Secretariat buildings besides the National Archives, few National Museums and a National Stadium.\r\n\r\nMaster Planning Concept\r\nThe overall master planning integrates elements of harmony, balance and rhythm to ideate a concept which is a comprehensive understanding of the challenges of the present times while leaving ample area for unhindered future expansion. The axis of the Vista extends more than 2 kms in length and is developed as a mixed-use cultural district. A natural stream balances the overall site and is flanked by extensively landscaped avenues and pedestrian spine on either side. By restricting vehicular movement on the outer roads, this street is kept pedestrian-friendly, becoming an eco-conscious zone. The design also proposes a monorail concealed under the terraced landscape which links all buildings in the precinct & integrates with city mass transit significantly reducing vehicles in this district. Technological advancement is utilised to its fullest with features such as high-end security systems, display screens to help guide pedestrians with movement in and around the site, well-regulated parking for vehicles etc.\r\n\r\nVernacular design\r\nThe architectural design strives for a responsible concept development through an understanding of conservation, sustainability and holistic approach. The offices are proposed as mixed-use spaces and inspired by the mohallas, chowks and bazaars of Chandni Chowk (one of the oldest area in New Delhi), accommodate retail areas, restaurants, lounging spaces etc. in their central courtyards. Entrance of these buildings use Gopurams and Toranas as inspiration, giving an abstract and magnificent look to the whole Complex. \r\n\r\nClimatologically responsive Design \r\nThe offices would be able to symbolically represent India through use of jaalis, louvres, accommodating semi-shaded central courtyards and creation of double skin façade by extending slabs (chhajjas) supported by colonnaded corridors around the Secretariat edifices. These architectural elements and techniques work well in the Indian landscape and establish a climatologically responsive design. Stone panels with different traditional Indian architectural motifs become the patterns for jaalis which celebrate art and architectural history of India while synchronising with the existing Lutyens’ character. \r\n\r\nRe-defining urban character\r\nThe proposal also integrates high-level technology through automation and artificial intelligence systems in the buildings for increased security. North and South Blocks, already existing and highly prominent offices, are proposed to be restored instead of using them as museums. At one end of the axis, a precinct of Museums has been created around India Gate, a national memorial monument, which proposes adaptive reuse of historical Indian princely estates. \r\n\r\nReimagining New Delhi as a Garden City, the redevelopment proposal offers a possibility of bestowing it with an international iconic stature and creating a state-of-the-art futuristic and livable vision of urban development. \r\n\r\nThe Redevelopment of Central Vista, New Delhi, is a historically and culturally significant project proposing the redevelopment over 440 Hectares of prime land. Reimagining New Delhi as a Garden City, the redevelopment proposal offers a possibility of bestowing it with an international iconic stature and creating a state-of-the-art futuristic and livable vision of urban development.	Transforming India’s capital for the 21st Century \r\n\r\nCentral Vista is the seat of the Government of India and lies at the heart of New Delhi. Inaugurated nearly a century ago, in 1931, this precinct and New Delhi were envisioned by British architects Edwin Lutyens and Herbert Baker as the central administrative zone for the country. The area houses many important legislative, administrative and cultural buildings, including the Rashtrapati Bhawan (Presidential Residence), the Indian Parliament House, the North and South blocks, the secretariat buildings, National Archives, National Museum, and the India Gate. The Central Vista holds immense historical, political and cultural significance for Indians and it is amongst the country’s most well-known precincts.\r\n\r\nIn 2019, the Government of India initiated the redevelopment of the Central Vista in order to strengthen and modernise the existing governance infrastructure and re-envision Rajpath (now Kartavya Path), the central avenue, which runs from the Rashtrapati Bhawan in the west to the India Gate in the east. Refurbishment of the central avenue, supported by the latest amenities and infrastructure, would also ease distress and overuse of the existing facilities, while opening up an opportunity to rethink the avenue’s connection to people and the environment. \r\n\r\nThe redevelopment proposal by CP Kukreja Architects, designed in association with Benoy Ltd., United Kingdom, was selected amongst the top six competition entries and was presented to the Central Public Works Department (CPWD) and the Ministry of Housing and Urban Affairs (MoHUA), Government of India. \r\n\r\nThe proposal aims to carve a new identity for the capital by creating an inclusive, ecological and cultural precinct that is rooted in history and yet showcases India’s emergence as a force to be reckoned with in the 21st century. The design creates a people-centred, sustainable development plan supported by technology, that respects and responds to the historical, environmental and architectural contexts.\r\n\r\nThe site can be divided into three parts. On the west are the Rashtrapati Bhavan and the North and South Blocks that house the Defence and Finance ministries. The central part comprises the Kartavya Path, envisaged as a wide, landscaped public avenue with the new secretariat buildings proposed on its either side. Finally, a cultural hub is envisaged around the India Gate in the east, culminating in the Independence Tower, a new-age observatory, near the National Stadium. Guesthouses of princely states surrounding the lawns of the India Gate, including Jaipur House and Hyderabad House, and other structures of historical significance are proposed to be reused as museums and art galleries.  \r\n\r\nA CELEBRATION OF INDIA'S MYRIAD HISTORIES\r\nA significant idea proposed at the Central Vista is to extend the central axis till the banks of the river Yamuna in the east and to the reserved forest at the Delhi Ridge in the West, beyond the Rashtrapati Bhavan. This will revive the historical connection between the neglected river waters and the city by integrating it into the site's landscape through long canals running along the Kartavya Path.  \r\n\r\nDesign elements for the new secretariat buildings are inspired by traditional Indian and Lutyens’-era architecture. For example, large monumental gateways punctuating the facade(s) are a contemporary reinterpretation of the Torana (sacred gateway) and the Gopuram (a monumental tower at a temple's entrance), both of which are prominent features of Indian temple architecture. Other elements include jaalis (traditional perforated screens), chajjas (protruding slabs for shading), and central courts. The courtyards are shaded partly through pergolas, whose members are arranged to form an Ashoka Chakra, a Buddhist symbol that symbolises the Wheel of Time and is a part of the Indian Tricolour. In addition, red and beige sandstones are proposed for the facade to maintain the visual vocabulary of the existing Lutyens’-era architecture. \r\n\r\nCREATING A CITY FOR THE PEOPLE \r\nThe transit plan opens up the central avenue as a completely pedestrian boulevard by diverting traffic through new roads running through the secretariat buildings. These new semi-public roads will be connected to the lateral roads on the avenue, which have been reimagined as underpasses for unobstructed pedestrian movement. \r\n\r\nRoads running in the east-west direction are proposed at the concourse level of the Secretariat buildings and the lateral roads running across the central avenue are reimagined as underpasses. All parking for the secretariat buildings is proposed on the ground and basement levels.  \r\n\r\nAn underground monorail connects the administrative and cultural buildings to Delhi’s Metro network, thereby easing access and reducing the need for motorised vehicles. Moreover, it increases accessibility to the central avenue for the public without obstructing the flow of the flourishing natural landscape. \r\n\r\nLANDSCAPE FOR URBAN RENEWAL, RECREATION, AND REJUVENATION\r\nAt the western end of the site, tree-lined avenues extend from the foot of Raisina Hill and merge into the central avenue where natural landscape reigns supreme. The verdant landscape features ghats (steps that lead to a water body) at the edge of the water canals, with trees densely populated on either side. Terraced levels extend from the central axis onto the front of the Secretariat buildings, adding to the three-dimensionality of the landscape and providing citizens with the opportunity to relax and gaze at the picturesque views.\r\n\r\nThe landscape on the east, surrounding the India Gate and the National War Museum, is focused on restoring existing parkland, lined with scrubs and meadows and interspersed with zones for social interaction, thereby rejuvenating the region's biodiversity.    \r\n\r\nFurther up east, a 194.7 metres tall watchtower, the Independence Tower, is proposed to allow people to view never-before-seen panoramas of the capital city. Its height alludes to India’s independence in the year 1947, and hence bears an emotional significance. The tower's form is a symbolic representation of folded hands, as the Indian greeting 'Namaste'.\r\n\r\nCLIMATE-SENSITIVE DESIGN INTERVENTIONS FOR A SUSTAINABLE FUTURE \r\nSeveral active and passive sustainable design strategies are proposed to ensure the buildings have minimal environmental impact. \r\n\r\nAt the master planning level, the dense vegetation acts as a heat sink, and the water channels have a cooling effect on the local microclimate. At the building level, the passive design strategies are centred around efficient channelling of air, water, and sunlight to create suitable indoor environments, thus reducing the dependence on artificial HVAC and lighting systems. Compact volumes enable mutual shading at the building level and minimise the solar heat gain. Planned around a series of courtyards, the secretariat buildings receive ample daylight and natural ventilation. The regular misting of courtyards in the summers helps reduce the ambient local temperature by 10-12 degrees celsius. These courtyards are integrated with pergolas for shading, water bodies for evaporative cooling, and roof gardens that act as heat sinks and thermal barriers. Double-skin facades with jaalis enable shading while serving as chutes for natural ventilation. Double-wall construction, insulated roofs and high-performance reflective glass further help in minimising the overall heat gain in the building.\r\n\r\nSunlight is used to generate electricity in the buildings through solar panels on rooftops, parking lots and walkways. Solar thermal energy powers the air conditioning system, and biogas is generated on the site through organic waste treatment. The design also proposes a smart waste management system with automated pneumatic waste collection and provision of waste segregation and collection points at regular intervals. All the rainwater from the site is proposed to be recycled and reused for flushing and irrigation. The design also proposes an integrated high-level automation technology system and artificial intelligence systems that enable efficient energy use and increased security in the secretariat buildings.\r\n\r\nThe proposal revamps and adds to the administrative and political infrastructure needed for the functioning of a rapidly progressing nation of 1.38 billion people. It takes on the underlying present-day urban planning challenges, from the dominance of car-oriented land use to the forsaken waters of the Yamuna. And finally, the design facilitates the creation of a lively urban public space, respectful of the local context and seamlessly integrated with the natural landscape, setting an example for how to create a city for the people at the very heart of Indian democracy.	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	IFF14	Dikshu C Kukreja	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
8e0d80a1-558e-404d-afc2-3eed8d09e44a	Tsinghua Architectural Design and Research Institute	Guande Wu	thad_international@thad.com.cn	Entrance Pavilions of Old Neighborhood in Beijing	IMPLEMENTED	APPROVED	SECTION_IV	Beijing	China	39.912433	116.401033	Our project is a series of shelters located at the entrance of low-income communities, designed to promote a sustainable and child-friendly environment over the past three years of the pandemic.	The entrances of the old neighborhood were in a state of disrepair, with crude tents providing the only cove. The architects and local residents collaborated to engage over a hundred children in the design of the public spaces. The architects utilized recyclable paper tubes and beer crates as the building material, resulting in a quick-to-build, prefabricated, reconfigurable structure that is waterproof, fireproof, and does not damage the foundation. These places have now become iconic symbols.	Over 100 children have participated in this project to decorate bicycle parking spaces and showcase their drawings. The project uses sustainable, environmentally friendly, and recyclable construction materials, drawing inspiration from traditional construction patterns to achieve rapid construction without burdening the environment. The project is creating quality spaces at the entrances of old neighborhoods, aiming to reduce the inequality of environmental decay caused by low income.	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	LDP54	Sisi Liang, Wei Zhang, Guande Wu, Yue Wang	123	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
e1fc233a-8440-4559-a74d-cb036f7a0765	TecTo Arhitectura	Sergiu C. Petrea	office@tecto.ro	FOREST-LAND MUSEUM (Pădureni Museum)	IMPLEMENTED	APPROVED	SECTION_II	Plosca	Romania	44.033	25.117	For project targets the construction of a museum that will gather and represent as faithfully as possible the characteristics of the region, highlighted in the form of a local traditional household. The future Forest-Land Museum (Pădureni Museum) will comprise of two buildings- a larger building conformed to the shape of the local churches’ typology, that contains the museum and a smaller building, following the shape of the local dwellings containing a study center.	The design team followed the principles stated by F. Schumacher in the book "Small Is Beautiful". Instead of a major ordering gesture, the museum benefits from the community's contribution, both as a supplier of labour and materials. Old wood and stone elements, artifacts and personal items are combined with modesty to outline a familiar, yet modern space, open to contemporary experiences. The use of local materials, saving of resources and the close association between what was built, and the natural environment were all important goals established by the community and the partner NGOs.	Among the villages threatened with extinction, it was proposed to build a commemorative space, to bring together the elderly people who are still in the area, the young people who return to develop small sustainable businesses and the researchers interested in the cultural, ethnological, and anthropological peculiarities of the place. It aims to build resilient infrastructure, promote inclusive and sustainable building methods and be an example of safe and resilient human settlements.\r\nFaithful to the "cradle to cradle" principle, the project uses elements recovered from abandoned buildings and natural materials, sustainably exploited from local sources ensuring healthy lives and well-being for all at all ages. Reinterpreted traditional elements, arising from the use of local craftsmen shape a natural background for cultural and manufacturing activities that address inclusive and equitable quality education and promote lifelong learning opportunities for all. The project aims to give back to the community a certain territory, a location between familiar limits by using iconic shapes and familiar materials, achieving gender equality, productive employment, and decent work for all. Locally sourced and produced sustainable and reliable energy empowers the building systems ensuring low consumption that tries to combat climate change effects. The built assembly and the surrounding landscape restores to natural environment and promotes sustainable use of terrestrial ecosystems, enhancing local biodiversity.	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	IFF9	PhD. arch. Sergiu-Cătălin Petrea, arch. Sabrina Ene-Butnariu, arch. Cristina Mototolea, arch. Sebastian-Ștefan Apostol, arch. Dan - Alexandru Roșu, arch. Tania-Victoria Băncilă, arch. Diana-Elena Fusea, arch. Ovidiu-Ion Bălășoiu	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
943f786d-e356-4d15-bb6d-658601dc4410	Architectural Society of China	Yehao Song	sup_atelier@supatelier.com	Central Canteen of Tsinghua University	IMPLEMENTED	APPROVED	SECTION_IV	Beijing	China	39.912433	116.401033	To improve the living quality of the campus, a new building is built with multi-functions as canteens for students and professors, lecture hall and exhibition hall for the campus, office and service hall for the Tsinghua Career Center and food storage for all the canteens at the center of the campus of Tsinghua University.	The core idea of design is to repair the urban texture in the campus context, to improve the fluency of the site, to make it easy to get in for the public from all directions. The section design takes the full advantage of the terrain of the site, creates a three-dimensional indoor street for the public, through ground floor on east and B1 floor on west. The entrance floor of the building on the one hand is functional and solid and on the other hand is a kind of cluster of open public space.	The project transformed the site of former canteen and integrated as a convenient and complete public place for the campus. The terrain of the site is in good use for easy accessibilities in all directions. The trees and vegetation are preserved to keep the continuity and sustainability of the environment. Sustainable strategies, especially passive design strategies are adopted in the project to make the space more comfortable and reduce the cost and energy consumption in operation.	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	LDP35	Yehao Song, Jingfen Sun, Dan Xie , Xiaojuan Chen, Lina Wang	21000	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
f770dca8-3a4e-4dd8-96f3-6bbfda667477	Beijing Jiaotong University, China	Xi Pan	panxi.thu@gmail.com	IUCN-Wuzhiqiao Community-based Environmental Education Centre	IMPLEMENTED	APPROVED	SECTION_IV	Fengning	China	41.2	116.65	IUCN-Wuzhiqiao Community-based Environmental Education Centre is a public welfare project conducted by a team of university student volunteers. The project is located in a village in northern China named Xiaowopu. The village, as the water source of Beijing, is a site of the project “Mega-cities and their Watersheds: Nature-based Solutions for Sustainable Drinking Water Sources” funded by EU China. Since 2017, over 200 volunteers have worked in this village. Taking “Architecture as Social Process” as the principal idea, the project has built a series of public spaces and facilities including a school, an open-air theatre, a public square, a community kitchen, a bridge, a water-taking facility and barrier-free structures, and provided various social services, such as environmental education, clean energy promotion, medical consultation, smartphone using skill training and craftsmen training, in order to improve the living environment and social vitality of the community, and enhance its sustainable development.	As a rural community development project led by architects, the principal idea of this project is "Architecture as a Social Process", which means to establish positive social relationships through public building activities. Just like throwing a stone into calm water, building, as an event, can activate the community and promote its development.\r\n\r\nThe project is located in Xiaowopu, a village in North China. In 2015, the village was included into EU China’s project “Mega-cities and their Watersheds: Nature-based Solutions for Sustainable Drinking Water Sources” as the water source of Beijing. Our team has been working in this village since 2017, and over 200 university students have served as volunteers for the village. We have built a series of public spaces and facilities, including a school, an open-air theatre, a public square, a community kitchen, a bridge, a water-taking facility and barrier-free structures. And we have also provided various social services, such as environmental education, clean energy promotion, medical consultation, smartphone using skill training and craftsmen training.\r\n\r\nThe most significant strategy of this project is to apply a series of unique modes of work, which include:\r\n\r\n1)\tMulti-participation Organization: The villagers and student volunteers, as the most important participants, always work together through the whole process of the project, including planning, design, construction and maintenance. While the village committee and NGO provide financial support and coordination. Everyone contributes, and everyone benefits. \r\n2)\tSneaking Time in the Busy Year: Working all year-round on the farm, the villagers only have free time for construction in slack seasons. And the students are only available during weekends and holidays. Therefore, the project is divided into different stages, which are embedded and conducted in slack seasons and holidays. In other words, the project is distributed in different periods of the year.\r\n3)\tThe Interweaving of Construction and Use: Different from the linear working pattern of other building projects, this project applies a rolling pattern, interweaving the construction and use of facilities. Once a new facility is built, the benefit it brings encourages the villagers and volunteers to work harder and better on the next one. Thus, a “compound interest” mode is achieved.\r\n\r\nWhat’s more, various strategies are also used in the design process, including the reordering of spaces, preservation of collective memory, emphasis of ritual space, identity shaping of water source village.\r\n\r\nThe project has brought significant benefits in three ways:\r\n\r\n1)\tFirst, through the provision of public space, facilities and social service, the living condition of the villagers is improved, and the public life of the community is more active.\r\n2)\tSecond, through the provision of environmental education, awareness of environmental protection in the village has been enhanced.\r\n3)\tThird, through the provision of opportunities of social practice for the students, potential experts for rural development in the future are cultivated.	The project involves 12 SDGs. SDG6、7、12、13、15 focus on the environment, and are positively correlated with each other. SDG3、4、5、8、10 center around the community members and can be realized through shared means such as education provision and facility building. \r\n\r\n1.\tSDGs for the environment\r\nSDG 6：Clean Water and Sanitation\r\nChallenge-The villagers had to take drink water in an unhygienic and unsafe way.\r\nContribution- The project built a water-taking facility that allows multiple villagers to get water in a hygienic, convenient and safe way.\r\n\r\nSDG 7 Affordable and Clean Energy\r\nChallenge- Under the government's rural revitalization strategy, lots of construction activities were going on and consumed a large amount of energy.\r\nContribution- The project provided examples for reducing energy consumption in construction, such as renovating existing buildings, designing flexible facilities to meet multiple needs, using solar panels and solar lighting, introducing energy-efficient cookers in the community kitchen.\r\n\r\nSDG 12 Sustainable Consumption and Production\r\nChallenge- Chemical and plastic products were widely used in village, but the villagers had no awareness of proper waste disposal.\r\nContribution- The project encouraged less use of plastic packaging and chemical products harmful to the environment, promoted environmental-friendly alternatives, and built garbage incinerators.\r\n\r\nSDG 13 Climate Action \r\nChallenge- Droughts occurred frequently due to climate change, which increased villagers' anxiety about farming.\r\nContribution- The project repaired the open-air theatre for the rain-praying ceremony and relieved the villagers' anxiety in a cultural way.\r\n\r\nSDG 15 Life on Land\r\nChallenge- The biodiversity of the environment was threatened by construction and agricultural activities.\r\nContribution- The project established natural resource archives and a digital museum for the village, and gave lectures to enhance villagers' awareness of environmental protection.\r\n\r\n2.\tSDGs for the community members\r\nSDG 3 Good Health and Well-Being\r\nChallenge-The health knowledge and medical condition of the villagers were poor.\r\nContribution- Through giving health knowledge lectures and introducing doctor volunteers to serve the village, the situation was improved.\r\n\r\nSDG 4 Quality Education\r\nChallenge-Most of the villagers had little access to education after the age of 15 (graduation from junior high school).\r\nContribution- The project not only provided diverse learning materials for children, but also advocated lifelong learning and offered knowledge and skill training to villagers of all ages.\r\n\r\nSDG 5 Gender Equality\r\nChallenge- Due to the traditional conception of genders, women were in a disadvantaged position in the village.\r\nContribution- The project cultivated women's organizations through collective activities such as square dancing and cooking, and asked the women to help run the community kitchen and environmental education center, which increased women's participation in public affairs.\r\n\r\nSDG 8 Decent Work and Economic Growth\r\nChallenge- The villagers could only earn low income from agriculture, and lacked other sources of income.\r\nContribution- The project provided employment opportunities in construction activities, and increased the villagers’ income.\r\n\r\nSDG 10 Reduced Inequalities\r\nChallenge- Due to the urban-rural dual structure in China, the rural population, especially the elderly, women and children, were neglected in development.\r\nContribution- The project encouraged women to participate in public affairs, provided barrier-free facilities for the elderly, and offered learning materials to children.\r\n\r\nSDG 11 Sustainable Cities and Communities\r\nChallenge- Due to the loss of young population, the community’s vitality was decreasing.\r\nContribution- By providing public space, reviving traditional activities, and encouraging young people to return, the community’s sustainability was improved.\r\n\r\n3.\tSDG 17 Partnerships for the goals\r\nChallenge- The development of the community requires multi-disciplinary collaboration.\r\nContribution- In addition to young architect volunteers, NGOs were introduced to provide financial support, and volunteers majored in agriculture, medicine, anthropology are organized to work together.	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	LDP7	Xi Pan, Zhongyuan Liu, Shun Lu, Xinchen Guo	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
f1b3c46e-d873-4064-95ba-56c1c949b4c7	Tongji University	Philip F. Yuan	philipyuan007@tongji.edu.cn	‘The Light of Internet’ World Conference Center	IMPLEMENTED	APPROVED	SECTION_IV	Wuzhen	China	30.742453	120.488833	In order to meet the functional requirements of the World Internet Conference and future diversified operation requirements; the pavilion is divided into four exhibition halls from south to north. The space can be used separated or merged.	The site is located in the northwest corner of the heart of Wuzhen, surrounded by farm houses, tourism projects and the first stage project of the exhibition pavilion area.\r\nThe space can be used in series at large exhibitions or it can be opened in parallel to accommodate various activities. Considering the space experience and applicability of the space of the independent exhibition hall, each section of the exhibition halls is high in the center and low along the edge. The string beams are placed in the middle of the exhibition hall to form the big open space for the special function requirement. At the same time, there are openings at the top to introduce the skylight to improve the space quality.\r\nIn order to achieve rapid construction of the entire pavilion, the dynamic modular system and the logic of the full prefabrication are applied to the overall skin construction of the entire pavilion project.	The space can be used separated or merged, so it is possible to be used in series at large exhibitions or it can be opened in parallel to accommodate various activities. In order to achieve rapid construction of the entire pavilion, the dynamic modular system and the logic of the full prefabrication are applied to the overall skin construction of the entire pavilion project.	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	LDP16	Philip F. Yuan	19446	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
405aa0d4-4048-41ea-a737-eb97564e0fc5	PS_Architetture	Pedone Working s.r.l.	pedoneworking@gmail.com	HEMP REGENERATION_Urban regeneration programme	IMPLEMENTED	APPROVED	SECTION_I	Bisceglie	Italy	41.229019	16.495083	Natural construction and bioclimatism are the elements of the project. Solar greenhouses and sunshades design the facades of the buildings. Public and private green spaces redesign the neighbourhood.	“HEMP REGENERATION”, Urban regeneration project, Bisceglie, Puglia.\r\nAn abandoned market area with environmental problems is reclaimed with a system of public and private green spaces and new NZeb residences.\r\nThe project develops research themes in the Mediterranean area with passive bioclimatic contributions; solar greenhouses and a natural ventilation system mitigate the temperature of the flats made of hemp and lime materials, subtracting -800,000 kg of CO2 and reducing -3,000,000 lt H2O.	Houses with natural hemp materials for the healthiness of the occupants. The cultivation of hemp results in a circular economy. Production reduces -3,000,000 litres H2O and -800,000 kg CO2. High insulation, solar greenhouses, natural ventilation, photovoltaic and solar systems for affordable and clean energy. Permeable surfaces and rainwater recovery for water saving and groundwater recharge. Green spaces and Mediterranean scrubland for bee and insect repopulation.	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	LDP29	Ing. Pietro Pedone, Arch. Pantaleo Pedone, Arch. Massimo Pedone, Arch. Eleonora Pedone	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
c692dc6b-60de-49d6-a33e-45fd4f3bf061	EFFEKT Architects	Liv Elbirk	le@effekt.dk	Living Places Copenhagen	IMPLEMENTED	APPROVED	SECTION_I	Copenhagen	Denmark	55.679521	12.567034	Living Places Copenhagen demonstrates a new way of building homes with record low carbon foot print and delivers best in class indoor climate.	The vision of Living Places Copenhagen is to lead the way within the building industry and show how rethinking buildings can help solve some of the global climate and health challenges. The concept holds the lowest CO2 emissions in Denmark, demonstrating that we do not have to wait for future technology to build homes that benefit both people and the planet. Designed with a strong focus on creating a healthy indoor climate using daylight and fresh air. SDG: 3, 9, 11, 12, 13, 17	Living Places concept holds the lowest CO2 emissions in Denmark and a first-class indoor climate. The concept is based on five key principles: homes should be healthy, affordable, simple, shared over time and scalable. A complete Life Cycle Assessment has been carried out. The green transition is a team sport that requires close cooperation through all phases towards a common goal between all parties of construction projects. Living Places Copenhagen is the result of such a partnership.	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	LDP32	EFFEKT, The VELUX Group, Artelia and Enemærke & Petersen. Design group: Sinus Lynge, Kasper Reimer, Tina Lund Hansen, Daniel Veenboer, Marco Antonio Ravini, Juan Pablo Herrero Gil, Yulia Kozlova, Evgeny Markachev, Joel Brynielsson	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
ae3b0bb6-813e-4254-9aa5-102bbc09f4a3	Sumito TAKASHINA Architects inc.	Sumito TAKASHINA	sumito@starchitects.jp	URAKUSATSU TOU	IMPLEMENTED	APPROVED	SECTION_IV	Kusatsu	Japan	35.01748	135.955594	A project to upcycle and revitalize a 60-year-old hotel completed in 1961 to provide for the next 60 years. A large amount of CO2 emissions from demolition and new construction were reduced.	Rather than scrap-and-build a large reinforced concrete hotel built 60 years ago with an enormous environmental burden, we revitalized it for the next generation in this location that enjoys the benefits of the earth in the form of hot springs. The existing frame was reinforced to withstand earthquakes, and the interior and exterior were finished with an abundance of natural materials that have a low environmental impact. This is an attempt to go carbon neutral for the next 60 years.	This project aims to achieve Goal 12 of the SDGs by reducing the amount of material resources, waste, and CO2 emissions by upcycling existing buildings, i.e., reusing existing structures without demolition or new frame work, and also contributes to Goal 15 by protecting hot spring and wood resources. \r\n This method is not only effective in significantly reducing construction costs and time, but is also desirable from an ESG investment perspective.	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	LDP53	Sumito TAKASHINA	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
49a533eb-fe01-4b7c-bbf6-a66548dafbbe	Studio Cardenas Conscious Design	Arch. Mauricio Cardenas Laverde	m.cardenas@studiocardenas.it	BooTech EcoDome	IMPLEMENTED	APPROVED	SECTION_I	Milan	Italy	45.464654	9.188315	BooTech Ecodome explores the use of bamboo, recycling one of the natural materials most suitable for construction, with a contemporary language and technique, following the UN 2030 Agenda SDGs.	BooTech EcoDome, a geodesical bamboo dome designed for Interni Magazine event at 2009 Milan’s Design Week. Bamboo was reused from a previous pavilion, cut into slats and assembled using mechanical connections using no cement and specialized manpower, unlike mainstream approach. A disrupting construction system in a time of environmental crisis, designed with a precise geometry in harmony with the proportions of the Statale University’s renaissance main courtyard. Tradition vs Innovation.	BooTech EcoDome refers to a physical transformation of the built environment asserting that the most viable means to radically reduce embodied carbon in buildings is to use natural materials for construction such as bamboo. Other than combat climate change, using bamboo properly for construction can tackle several SDGs by generating a new value chain, promoting inclusive and sustainable industrialization, foster innovation, protecting ecosystems, bringing near agriculture and architecture.	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	LDP66	Arch. Mauricio Cardenas Laverde	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
f77d4d2d-a89d-43e6-9f63-425254b91415	Juri Troy Architects, Caravan Atelier	Prof. Arch. Mag. Juri Troy	office@juritroy.at	Straw flea	IMPLEMENTED	APPROVED	SECTION_I	Murstetten	Austria	48.2333	15.8167	The project is conceived as a one-room house. It stands as a solitaire self-confidently and naturally in the midst of the historical remains.	In the southern, lower part is the living room with large, completely openable glazing to the garden and the small stream crossing the property. The building is entered via the northern part, where there is also a small sanitary unit and a sleeping gallery. The large panorama windows are aligned with the historical and landscape references and offer an unrestricted view towards the church, into the valley or to the remains of historical statues in the park.	The project follows a holistic sustainable concept in planning, use and implementation. The house is elevated and only touches the terrain via the eight screw foundations. This means that no ground surface is sealed. Most of the materials used come from the immediate surroundings. The wood, both for the structural elements and for the surfaces, comes from the client's own forests and was processed in the neighbouring sawmill. Heat and energy are generated by the photovoltaic system on the roof.	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	LDP9	Prof. Arch. Mag. Juri Troy	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
db92d397-3591-4e79-be1a-f0767b47d719	ARB (UK)	Joshua Bolchover	jpbarch@hku.hk	Incremental Development Manual for Mongolia	IMPLEMENTED	APPROVED	SECTION_IV	Ulaanbaatar	Mongolia	47.898009	106.910015	The concept is an in-situ upgrading strategy for the ger district residents of Ulaanbaatar, Mongolia that integrates affordable energy efficient housing and key sanitation and sewage infrastructure.	Over 840000 people live in the ger districts of Ulaanbaatar, Mongolia without basic infrastructure, and use an average 4.1t of coal for heating as temperatures drop below -30°C. Current plans require residents to exchange their own land for an apartment. We want to allow people to stay on their land via  a mechanism to regenerate plots using infrastructure that promotes densification and value creation for resident landowners, as well as building energy efficient houses that does not use coal.	The proposed idea integrates energy efficient housing and in-situ infrastructural provision. Improved insulation, and eliminating use of raw fuels will reduce carbon emissions. Improved air quality, and access to sanitation and sewaging will improve the health and wellbeing of communities by having direct access to drinking water, and reduced sickdays. More people will be living in sustainable, durable homes, whilst site densification reduces unsustainable growth of informal settlements.	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	IFF25	Joshua Bolchover, Jersey Poon	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
5e1a91ab-6ca0-430b-a82b-cf82cf8463a7	AUTH School of Architecture	Angelos Saltidis (Author), Anastasios Tellios (Supervisor)	ttellios@arch.auth.gr	2 km: "Roof" of Agricultural Growth and Innovation in Thessaloniki Plain	IMPLEMENTED	APPROVED	SECTION_I	Thessaloniki	Greece	40.63741	22.94096	The project investigates the redefinition of the Greek countryside, aiming to become a model for the development of a new generation of farms where production, research and recreation are in balance.	The proposal transforms 50 hectares of agricultural land into an alternative agricultural typology, offering cultural and community facilities developed around farming and food production. Thus, it makes this new structure an active economic and social center, forming a new model of the relationship between consumer and producer. The resulting program variety reflects the entire food chain, from research, education, cultivation, and harvesting, to storage, sale, and consumption.	The project studies new methods of cultivation and food production, suggesting the creation of a new model of farms placed in the Greek countryside, along the main highways. New experimental crops are created around the structure adopting the pixel cropping model. Architecturally, the proposal is based on the typology of the elongated pitched roof allowing for easy future expansion of the structure, or even its transfer to a new plot, leaving the minimum possible footprint on the environment.	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	IFF11	Angelos Saltidis	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
9d6a513e-43cd-40b2-a554-8e5241e1994d	Studio Cardenas Conscious Design	Arch.Mauricio Cardenas Laverde	m.cardenas@studiocardenas.it	BooTech Innovative Bamboo Construction System	IMPLEMENTED	APPROVED	SECTION_I	Milan	Italy	45.464654	9.188315	BooTech construction system is a balance between nature and artifice, applicable without cement nor specialized manpower unlike mainstream approach, makes it, when in commerce, the first of its kind.	The symbiosis between nature and technology is the original characteristic of BooTech, a disruptive sustainable construction system in a time of environmental crisis. BooTech innovates through the dry-mounted application of bamboo, a natural product of nature, to achieve beautiful, cost-effective, low carbon architectural solutions of different geometrical forms and sizes. The elegant designed system can host bamboo poles of various available species that can vary from 50mm to 140mm diameter.	Introducing BooTech into the building chain will promote shaping a circular industry ecosystem, a value network that will challenge the existing construction industry supporting life-cycle thinking. BooTech is a conscious, innovative and strategic choice to radically reduce embodied carbon in buildings supporting the mitigation of climate change in line with the SDGs of the United Nations 2030 Agenda.	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	LDP49	Arch. Mauricio Cardenas Laverde	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
7f0e0f7c-26d7-4cc3-94ab-2350559fb7e4	Brac University	Emmat Ara Khanam Ema	khanam.ema@bracu.ac.bd	Zero Carbon Bamboo Building with Active Participation of Marginalized Community	IMPLEMENTED	APPROVED	SECTION_IV	Jhenaidah	Bangladesh	23.633841	89.066856	A communal space where community members can congregate for various official or informal activities that will promote community building and a sense of unity and connections.	The aim was to inspire local people to develop a space on their own, which would create a sense of ownership, and pride in the community while encouraging sustainable living through the eco-friendly structure that produces no carbon emissions. The structure is made of affordable, local materials, with the help of student volunteers, locally-trained artisans, and community members to support and strengthen capacity in the communities ultimately advancing sustainability's long-term goals.	Bamboo Architecture offers a potential solution to the environmental, economic, and social issues that society is currently confronting in Bangladesh. In addition, the involvement of locals enriches practicality and efficiency in the use of community resources, as well as a strengthening strategy for sustainable eco-buildings. Their active involvement in every project phase, from project conception to design to implementation, will also help sustainability's long-term goals.	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	LDP69	Zainab Faruqui Ali, Emmat Ara Khanam Ema	31.22	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
4a7dbfe0-6910-4fee-9db1-5e767f7d822a	China Architecture Design & Research Group (CADG)	Jiayin Wei	2019332@cadg.cn	The main pavilion of the 11th Jiangsu Horticultural Expo	IMPLEMENTED	APPROVED	SECTION_IV	Nanjing	China	32.053418	118.776849	The main pavilion of the 11th Jiangsu Horticultural Expo is a large-scale public building group with highly complex and diversified functions composed of 43 individual buildings. The original industrial building has a construction area of 12,500 ㎡, and the total construction area after activation and expansion is 52,000 ㎡.\r\n\r\nThe design takes the site of an abandoned private cement factory as the construction base. Restoring environment, repairing urban functions, creating a new public green space in the city and respect for "ecology" and "heritage" are the primary value orientation during the planning and architectural design process of the main pavilion.	The new building adopts the "light intervention" design strategy, in which groups of small architectural groups are placed in the open space between the reserved buildings, creating a strong contrast between the old and the new, and regenerating the ruins into modern horticultural pavilions full of greenery.\r\n\r\nLight intervention, reflected in the "light structure" - the use of prefabricated steel structure system to achieve environmental protection and rapid construction process; "Light image" - slender structural components combined with climbing vertical greening to create a light architectural image, contrasting with the roughness and thickness of industrial buildings; "Light attitude" - boundless green gardens permeate the industrial site, allowing the building to dissolve its image and disappear from nature.\r\n\r\nFrom a lime-burning factory to a space that carries new life, the design and construction of the main pavilion is not to erase the past and forget history, but to leave traces and let history speak. Between the old and the new, today's thinking and creation are also passers-by, and more reverie about beautiful cities and spaces belongs to the future.	The main pavilion of the 11th Jiangsu horticultural Expo is built on the site of an abandoned cement factory, focusing on creating a science popularization platform with the theme of industrial heritage protection. The design strategy of light intervention also gives the building greater flexibility to meet the needs of multiple functions and types of spaces, while also taking into account post exhibition renovation and reuse. The design of the main pavilion intends to rely on the diverse industrial architectural relics and rich elevation differences within the site, using a slender steel structure system to achieve a lightweight modern exhibition hall community, making the green art garden diffuse and linger between the rough industrial factories, and using green space to bridge the damage caused by industrial production to the mountains and nature. Using a modular strategy to handle and adapt to complex sites, the prefabricated system enables pre planting of greenery, integrating horticulture and architecture. After the exhibition, the main exhibition hall park will serve as a public education base and a children's forest experience place, continuously promoting plant and horticultural knowledge to citizens.	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	LDP13	Cui Kai	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
9196757a-1456-4139-acec-ce85ce87dcc7	SUP Atelier of THAD	Yehao Song	sup_atelier@supatelier.com	Waterfowl Pavilion of Beijing Zoo	IMPLEMENTED	APPROVED	SECTION_IV	Beijing	China	39.910309	116.365435	Waterfowl Pavilion is a net-zero energy building located on an island with high ecosystem diversity, and serves as a multi-functional building for bird breeding, exhibition and science advocacy.	To create a demonstration net-zero energy building under the limit budget is the initial target. Since the pavilion is a habitat for birds, the environmental quality is more complicated. The sustainable strategies need to be refined into specific goals for each engineering discipline.\r\nThe design emphasizes being 'invisible' in the natural environment, which is not only reflected in visual level, but also the minimization of interferences to ecological system and wild environment of the island.	The pavilion employs PV, PVT and Solar heating system to produce clean energy onsite. By combining passive design methods and active technologies together, the energy consumption during operation is minimized.(Goal 7)\r\nThe original micro-ecosystem is intactly preserved with the site handling strategies. An integrated wetland system is employed through a minimally invasive reform of the site section, which creates an excellent habitat for the waterfowl and the vegetation.(Goal 15)	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	LDP26	Yehao Song, Lina Wang, Jingfen Sun, Dan Xie, Xiaojuan Chen, Yifan Bai, Zhenghao Lin， Junjie Li	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
b987f085-1090-4ace-a43a-52e3780d81a9	China Architecture Design & Research Group	Xinyi Zhao	zxy5153@gmail.com	The Future Garden of Jiangsu 11th Horticultural Expo	IMPLEMENTED	APPROVED	SECTION_IV	Nanjing	China	32.053418	118.776849	The project is located on Kongshan mountain in Nanjing, where quarrying caused ecological damage. A botanical garden, outdoor theaters and a hotel are built to restore ecosystem and bring life back.	Respecting and reusing existing resources, we chose ecological restoration as our strategy. The old transport channel is reconstructed to provide a path to garden and blankets of fog at the pit bottom build a poetic landscape while adjusting temperature and humidity. The roof of botanical garden, a 16000㎡ artificial lake covers the entire secondary mine pit, creating a special "underwater" experience. Then, open-air stages are set up against the cliff to project a huge light show and the hotel is elevated at the east end overlooking the whole park.	By light intervening strategy, innovative technology and adaptive vegetation, we avoided new damage to the site and restore degraded forest and ecosystem. The abandoned quarry reshaped into a garden showcased new chances of sustainability, as well as offering a platform for public to look into biodiversity and eco-restoration. Restoring is not only recompensing, but also creating a new nature where human learn to coexist with our planet, and our architecture - when its water turns green with algae and its steel is covered with moss - will eventually be a part of it too.	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	LDP41	Kai Cui, Fei Guan, Qin Ma, Ling Yang, Xi Chen	98000	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
f36f534c-bf9f-4205-8062-b1b58235c547	Group of Architects and Thinkers (GOAAT)	Md. Rabiul Islam	goaatmail@gmail.com	Bangabandhu Memorial Ghat	IMPLEMENTED	APPROVED	SECTION_IV	Gopalganj	Bangladesh	23.013014	89.822405	The project's notion to knit the community while keeping the natural setting, comes from commemorating the visions of 'The father of the nation' who fought for the liberty of the people of Bangladesh.	The Project is situated on the bank of Madhumati River which has been left unutilized without development for decades with mono functional activities like boat docking and river-based transportation of goods which over the years caused the site to decay from extensive flooding and erosion.\r\nThe design proposal transforms the entire riverfront with an Indoor information center, an outdoor public space as a contemplation zone that extends towards the river and terminates as a natural slope. The outdoor gathering area around the shallow pond is vegetated with the national flower of Bangladesh “The Lily” enclosed by a curved walkway linking the building mass with the river. \r\nThe main aspect of the project is its adaptability with seasonal changes of water levels and vegetation and inclusivity of nature within a public space. Proposed contours adapt with flooding and inundation of the site during monsoon that brings fertile soil, amplifies native vegetation growth, and attracts numerous shore birds. The safety enclosure of the curved walkway is formed with slender poles made of metal at different height that also acts as a perching zone for shore birds.	The project ensures equal accessibility to people of all races, gender, age and religion. It works as a recreational space with well thought out inclusion for the elderly and specially abled and gives everyone the opportunity to connect with nature. Thus, it plays a vital role in maintaining the mental health of the inhabitants. It prevents the site from soil erosion which previously was a major threat to the mono-functions of this area. The proposed contours adapt to the site's floods and inundation during the monsoon, which delivers fertile soil, amplifies natural flora development, and attracts a large number of shore birds. The circular walkway's safety perimeter is built by thin metal poles of varying heights that also serve as a perching zone for coastal birds.	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	LDP60	Md. Rabiul Islam , Nehleen A Chowdhury, Utsha Zaman	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
7d852ebb-78bf-4c91-94f8-174bc559727b	Vincenzo Bernardi Architect	Vincenzo Bernardi	vincenzo.bernardi@gmail.com	Parish building in Maida  [Italy]	IMPLEMENTED	APPROVED	SECTION_I	Maida	Italy	38.859613	16.3637	Under Construction parish building in Maida (CZ) consists of two bodies containing the parish hall and classrooms for catechism separated by a courtyard that metaphorically recalls the street of an ancient village.	Hospitality and a sense of community are the principles that guided the design of the building whose shape recalls the archetypal village of houses with sloping roofs and which seeks a formal dialogue with the historic center.\r\nThe building aims to be a point of reference for the entire community and its orientation along the east/west axis, as well as allowing it to open onto the panorama of the Gulf of Sant'Eufemia, ensures that the main entrances are easily identifiable from the street.	The building houses rooms for meetings and gatherings for the formation and catechism of the Catholic religion which has inclusion and hospitality among its founding values. Hospitality and a sense of community are the principles that guided the design of the building whose shape recalls the archetypal village of houses with sloping roofs and which seeks a formal dialogue with the historic center.	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	IFF45	Vincenzo Bernardi	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
3846899a-e331-42af-ad98-2d6da5311eec	CSCAE	Primitivo González	noa@primitivogonzalez.com	Burgos Art School	IMPLEMENTED	APPROVED	SECTION_I	Burgos	Spain	42.34106	-3.70184	An art school with character and presence within its surroundings, designed to maximize contact among disciplines and students, but also with the city.	An art school with “character” where functionally different areas are structured with a courtyard system, but where students are familiar with all the activities taking place in the building, feeling they are part of the whole school, not only doing activities from their own specialist area. The maximum visual and physical openness possible, as a key part of the learning and training process. Mies van der Rohe Award Nominee (2013)	The property requirements, according to the official educational program, reserved little space for areas without a “specific” use. In the teaching of art, personal exchange, relationships and non-regulated information are all a vital part of the maturing process. Space where this can occur were implemented. Also visual connections among areas were encouraged.\r\nFor example, the double height area in the “entrance hall” is crossed over the top with the walkway which closes off the circle of hallways on the first floor. This has allowed the teaching team to organize a catwalk for fashion students to show their work.	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	LDP34	Primitivo González	6915.89	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
0aec3739-78fa-4a32-aa0e-f599cbc441cc	CSCAE	Primitivo González	noa@primitivogonzalez.com	Justice Palace in Burgos	IMPLEMENTED	APPROVED	SECTION_I	Burgos	Spain	42.34106	-3.70184	An obsolete and old building, presenting an image of being inaccessible, is transformed into a contemporary courthouse, with a sense of closeness to the citizens.	There are public buildings that transmit a feeling of being “inaccessible”. This renovation of a 19th century courthouse in a neo-classical style, represents a radical change in the access and layout of the building. The entrance steps have been removed, and the semi-basement floor converted into the ground floor of the building, housing all public services. The result is an accesible building, with enough space for its use, well comunicated as placed in the city centre and giving a modern image of the Justice institucion.The project achived an Honorable Mention in the UIA Award “Friendly Spaces Accesible to All” (2014)	Faced with the common alternative of moving the courts from the building to a purpose built campus on the outskirts of the town and making them less convenient to get to,  the Ministry of Justice addressed the possibility of renovating the old building. The project firmly celebrates and supports this option, presenting strategies for adapting the building’s characteristics to current needs. We have managed to secure the survival of a building which is important in itself as a part of the urban landscape. The creation of an accessible, pleasant "new building” is conveyed in the image of the building, that brings closer the institution closer to the citizens	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	LDP36	Primitivo González	13.226	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
58f6514b-da20-4a32-b8c4-7b178b65b834	WM Creative Studio - Relab	Wajiha Siddiqui Mehdi	wajiha@wmcreativestudio.com.pk	Tranquil Abode	IMPLEMENTED	APPROVED	SECTION_IV	Uthal	Pakistan	25.8039	66.61949	Tranquil Abode: A housing prototype located in rugged terrain adjacent to a farm in Uthal, Balochistan, Pakistan, created in response to the devastating floods of 2022.	The Tranquil Abode is a culture-specific housing prototype in Uthal, Balochistan, designed in response to the 2022 floods in Pakistan. Its introverted empathetic design prioritizes privacy for women & employs simple construction techniques that can be easily adapted by the community. The prototype utilizes affordable, local materials. Given the catastrophic loss of life during these floods, a double roof has been incorporated to provide temporary refuge in the face of future climate emergencies.	GOAL 17 has been achieved through a local NGO's partnership with the locals & architecture students, which guided the project towards sustainable practices & adaptability benefiting GOAL 13 & 11 by mitigating the impact of climate change. Providing training in neo-vernacular building techniques to the locals, creating jobs & economic growth, satisfies GOAL 8. The participatory design, prioritizing privacy for women & utilizing regional materials, furthers GOAL 10's aim of reducing inequalities.	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	LDP39	Muhammad Mehdi, Wajiha Siddiqui Mehdi, Muhamad Nafeel Qureshi, Ilsa Ahmed, Muhammad Bilal, and Nihal Ahmed Barry	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
1b1dbfd0-1ed7-401b-9122-243c20cb2cea	Sir Syed University Of Engineering & Technology	Nihal Ahmed Barry	nihalahmed212@gmail.com	Redefining Religious Spaces - Mosque as a Social Catalyst	IMPLEMENTED	APPROVED	SECTION_IV	Uthal	Pakistan	25.804807	66.62028	The mosque in Baluchistan, Pakistan aims to redefine traditional religious structures by implementing sustainable development goals. The goal is to design a sustainable and communal space that promotes a sense of ownership through place-making strategies..	Mosques in Pakistan are now limited to prayer, but in early Islam, they were community centers for social cohesion without discrimination. This project aims to design a sustainable place using a neo-vernacular approach respecting regional materials & construction with an open, nature-connected layout that is inclusive for all ages. The program promotes community programs like community kitchens, bazaars, and safe spaces for play to increase visibility on the street.	Goal 2 has been achieved by implementing a program, community kitchen and farming, to address food scarcity. Goal 5 is achieved by designing an inclusive space that discourages discrimination and promotes gender equality. Goals 6 & 13 mitigate climate change by incorporating rainwater harvesting, sanitation practice and use of vernacular materials Additionally, the project provides opportunities for local businesses to thrive, such as a bazaar, to uplift the regional economy in line with Goal 8.	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	IFF58	Nihal Ahmed Barry, Wajiha Siqqdiqui & Muhammad Mehdi,	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
6a1600e0-e62d-4dc1-903d-13df878b5864	Studio Cardenas Conscious Design	Arch. Mauricio Cardenas Laverde	m.cardenas@studiocardenas.it	Microclimatic Pavilion	IMPLEMENTED	APPROVED	SECTION_I	Milan	Italy	45.464654	9.188315	Microclimatic Pavilion is a first of its kind sustainable dry mounted bamboo bearing structure designed, unlike mainstream approach, to be easily assembled without the need of specialized manpower.	Is in the Fabbrica del Vapore where is possible to experience the Microclimatic Pavilion, built in 2006 in the context of Milan’s Salone del Mobile for DAGAD Association. An exhibition space, a comfort point for people and technology to meet and enjoy the pleasant effects of microclimate control where apparently distant worlds coexist: high tech metallic joints and low tech of bamboo. An urban oasis to protect against the effects of the heat island phenomenon, in line with the 2030 Agenda SDGs.	The Microclimatic Pavilion’s objective, other than holding exhibitions, is that of contributing to reduce the urban heat island effect. Studies have found that local warming caused by this phenomenon significantly increases temperatures in addition to global warming. The project, as an urban oasis, promotes sustainable use of bamboo as a construction material, tackling at least 7 SDGs, and takes action to combat climate change ensuring health and well-being for a sustainable development.	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	LDP63	Arch. Mauricio Cardenas Laverde	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
72e17f51-be36-45d6-b9ed-0eefa52cc9b3	Hoang Thuc Hao and 1+1>2 Architects	1+1>2 Architects	amedia@112.com.vn	Village System	IMPLEMENTED	APPROVED	SECTION_IV	Hanoi	Vietnam	21.031477	105.844719	Globalization has brought the world together but it has obliterated and vanished identities. The purpose of the project is to create a relevant living environment for each specific community.	In order to bring happiness to the users and the society, protect the cultural architecture diversity in general and particularly in residential architecture, we advocate research and practices according to the "1+1>2" philosophy, which is vernacular core values incorporate with vanguard academic knowledges. All together towards enhance and acculturate local identity, contribute to shaping lifestyle, inspire people and permeate vernacular culture. Crucially, architects must comprehend which core values and innovations are appropriate for each particular community.	Practicing in settlement architecture has help us reveal the beauty of local lifestyles, it also shows us the unlimited ability of architecture to connect and support people, raise happiness for the users, for the buildings and for the architects themselves. Sustainable environment is essential, but more important is to create a sustainable lifestyles respecting history and future. That is the motivation in our creativity.	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	LDP68	Hoang Thuc Hao and 1+1>2 Architects	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
ddd00346-7ea0-4e31-a292-31b5d6e51e66	College of Architecture and Urban Planning, Tongji University, Shanghai, P.R.CHINA	YI Wenjing	923086411@qq.com	Mending the City- Shanghai Railway Station Metro Station Analysis	IMPLEMENTED	SUBMITTED	SECTION_IV	Shanghai	China	31.222934	121.461763	Located in the inner ring of Shanghai, Shanghai Railway Station is the second largest railway station in the city. The train tracks have brought about a great fragmentation of urban space and urban life, while the metro station has to some extent mended the rift and witnessed the rise and fall of the urban environment around Shanghai Railway Station.	Built in 1986 on the site of the former Shanghai East Railway Station, Shanghai Railway Station is the second largest railway station in Shanghai, adjacent to the Shanghai Long Distance Passenger Terminal, and together with Shanghai Hongqiao Station and Shanghai South Railway Station, it forms the largest railway hub in the eastern coastal region of China - the Shanghai Railway Hub. From 1995 to 2005, three underground lines and two underground stations were built at Shanghai Railway Station. The opening of the underground has enhanced the connection between intercity and urban transport in Shanghai, and the underground passages between the stations have to a certain extent weakened the fragmentation of urban ground space caused by the railway tracks. The subway, as part of the urban transport construction, is closely related to the tides of development in the surroundings of Shanghai railway stations over the past 30 years.	The train tracks passing through the Shanghai Railway Station also divide the city into two parts, creating spatial barriers to movement and, to some extent, leading to a difference in urban life and function between the north and south of the station. The connection of the metro station to the north-south square offers the possibility of sustainable development of the urban environment around the station in terms of infrastructure, and stimulates further consideration of the spatial design of the station-city integration. In addition, the urban development around the railway station is closely linked to the construction of the metro, which flourished in the 1990s but has now become a low-end wholesale and retail cluster with less commercial activity than other urban sub-centres, exploring the possibilities of sustainable consumer development in terms of the current situation and outlook of the metro network and urban connectivity.	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	IFF39	Shanghai Lab, Tongji University	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
81ce9d34-d551-4768-9c46-2e63c36bb3d7	CSCAE	Primitivo González	estudio@primitivogonzalez.com	Municipal Archive of San Agustín	IMPLEMENTED	SUBMITTED	SECTION_I	Valladolid	Spain	41.65351	-4.72378	The church of San Agustin, part of a Monastery, was abandoned and in ruins. However, the ruins were still able to evoke its past. The introduction of a new use within them, the city’s archive, allows a new live to the building.	The use of heritage links us to our past, while allowing us to look to the future. The church of San Agustin, part of a Monastery of the Augustinian order, founded at the beginning of the 15th century, was abandoned and in ruins. However, the ruins were still able to evoke its past.  The restoration of the existing ruins together with the introduction of new use through superposed structures, has made possible the recovery of this monument for the City Archive of Valladolid.	During the 1960s it was contemplated the demolition of the ruins of the church. However this ruins evoke the past of the building and city, and connect the citizens to its past. The new program introduced in the building, respectful with the existing fabric, shows a resilient infrastructure, that can be adapted again in the future if needed. Furthermore, the project generates an open, friendly and accessible space, bringing the archive institution closer to all citizens.	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	EFP2	Primitivo González, Gabriel Gallegos	4303	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
378cb2b2-2105-42a2-bfa0-20c93217212b	College of Architecture and Urban Planning, Tongji University, Shanghai, P.R.CHINA	WU Xiaoyu	1807234699@qq.com	Shanghai Jing'an Temple Metro Station Analysis	IMPLEMENTED	SUBMITTED	SECTION_IV	Shanghai	China	31.222934	121.461763	Jing'an Temple Metro Station is one of the most important and densely populated stations in Shanghai's metro network. It is located in the Jing'an Temple business district, the core of Shanghai, and has not only a high density of urban construction above ground, but also the most dense underground space system within the metro station area.	A large number of high-density urban buildings are located in and around the Jing'an Temple Subway Station in Shanghai, and a large number of underground spaces have been developed with the construction of underground rail transit, resulting in a large number of underground interchange channels, underground streets and underground commercial spaces. This study analyzes and evaluates the above-ground and underground station public spaces, analyzes the problems of underground station public spaces, and proposes targeted strategies to improve the quality and vitality of underground station public spaces, to further link the underground space with the life of citizens, and to promote sustainable urban development.	The above-ground station area public space of Jing'an Temple metro station well combines the transportation facilities used for daily commuting with people's daily life through public spaces such as plazas, green areas and pedestrian streets, which provides good protection for the physical and psychological health of urban residents and can be benchmarked against  SDG 3. The reliable underground urban transportation infrastructure construction can be benchmarked against SDG 9, which provides great convenience for people to travel. The integrated development of above- and below-ground space within the station area is an excellent model for promoting urban sustainability in Shanghai, which can be benchmarked against SDG 11. Although the latter two indicators still have obvious flaws and shortcomings in the current study, the strategies proposed in this study will hopefully provide some reference value.	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	IFF30	Shanghai lab, Tongji University	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
7d4b129c-61b0-4d42-aa5c-2a859bf73369	College of Architecture and Urban Planning, Tongji University, Shanghai, P.R.CHINA	DIAO Yingjie	diaoyj0729@163.com	City in the Sky:Shanghai ZiKaWei Metro Station Analysis	IMPLEMENTED	SUBMITTED	SECTION_IV	Shanghai	China	31.222934	121.461763	Zikawei Metro Station is an important public activity, commercial and transportation core in western Shanghai,  and is one of the important representatives of Shanghai's excellent planning.	The rail transit and underground space in Zikawei area form the basis of Xujiahui's urban space, and the newly built two-story sky platform system connects the entire Xujiahui core area building as a whole, and the three-dimensional urban development strategy provides citizens with rich public space and also constructs a framework for sustainable urban development.	For hundreds of years, the Zikawei area has gone through a long stage of development, from the water town market, to the religious center, and then to the current urban hub, it has always carried a large number of urban public life, and the attention to public space has ensured the physical and mental well-being of the people. The far-sighted urban planning after the chinesereform and opening up has also provided Zikawei with a solid foundation for sustainable development.	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	IFF22	Shanghai Lab, Tongji University	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
398c068a-90f0-438b-a4e4-421e03dd914f	College of Architecture and Urban Planning, Tongji University, Shanghai, P.R.CHINA	RUI Dian	tim_rui@163.com	Urban Network Under the Park - Shanghai People's Square Metro Station	IMPLEMENTED	SUBMITTED	SECTION_IV	Shanghai	China	31.222934	121.461763	People's Square Metro Station is a political, cultural, tourist and transport hub in the centre of the city of Shanghai, with three interchange lines, a huge flow of people and many public spaces.	As one of the busiest metro stations in the centre of Shanghai, People's Square Station has undergone historical changes and renewal. The station is surrounded by many public and cultural buildings, commercial offices, tourism and leisure resources. The extended underground space with numerous entrances and exits organises huge crowds and meets the activities and lives of people of all ages in a three-dimensional space. People's Square still has space and opportunities for future development.	People's Square is the result of the people's struggle for fairness and justice. With the construction of the metro, more and more people were able to reach it and enjoy the central public space of the city, reducing inequalities. Meanwhile, People's Square Station has undergone several renovations and renewals. Public transport is brought together, cultural buildings are diverse and event facilities are abundant, promoting the sustainability of the city and the community.	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	IFF23	Shanghai Lab, Tongji University	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
66e4a60d-0196-4979-b4c5-1c86a8f5aedb	College of Architecture and Urban Planning, Tongji University, Shanghai, P.R.CHINA	XIE Shuting	2243270539@qq.com	A Metro Network Stitched Together by Commerce——Responsible Consumption and ProductionA Metro Network Stitched Together by Commerce——Responsible Consumption and Production	IMPLEMENTED	SUBMITTED	SECTION_IV	Shanghai	China	31.222934	121.461763	Subway stations in the city bring great convenience for people to travel quickly, but also open up underground space, connecting every node in the city into a network.，giving all people access to basic public services and improve the quality of life. The completion of the IAPM Shopping Mall above the Shaanxi South Road subway Station in Shanghai integrates the subway station with large commercial and urban public Spaces. While improving people's living quality, this construction mode reduces resource consumption, environmental degradation and pollution of the city and increases the net welfare income of economic activities through the highly integration of resources and functions, as well as the increase of urban green space. It is a sustainable pattern of consumption and production.	Subway stations in the city bring great convenience for people to travel quickly, but also open up underground space, connecting every node in the city into a network and give all people access to basic public service and improve the quality of life.\r\nShaanxi South Road belongs to Huangpu District of Shanghai, and is located at the junction of Jing 'an District, Huangpu District and Xuhui District. It is also the intersection of two main traffic arteries, Huaihai Middle Road and Shaanxi South Road. Huaihai Road near it is the second most prosperous commercial street in Shanghai after Nanjing East Road, where many department stores such as Printemps, Parkson, Huating Isetan and 200 Yongxin gather together to form the Huaihai Road business circle.\r\nShaanxi South Road Hub station is the transfer station