d for use by vulnerable people  and at the same time are inclusive so that all people can enjoy safe, green urban spaces.	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	IFF31	Shanghai Lab, Tongji University	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
56df0450-688f-4d05-88a5-5dda76a34100	Project: As If	Leroy Cheng	leroy.cheng@proj-as-if.com	Crafted Prosumption – Adopting Doma for Sustainable Urban Strategies in Prosumption Model	IMPLEMENTED	SUBMITTED	SECTION_IV	Hong Kong	China	22.296807	114.161627	Giving up the old urban strategies, this project proposes Doma as the spatial device to set up a new sustainable linkage between places and people in response to the uptrend of prosumption economy.	An abrupt change in living habits and meaning in places is widely observed after the pandemic. Accompanying the increasing prosumption behaviors under the customization fad, the current urban strategies in assigning homogenized programs to places become unfit under both micro- and macro-perspective. After study, Doma, a versatile and adaptable component in Japanese houses, may be the solution for its potential to cultivate sustainability and synergize future development in the built environment.	Curating programs for placemaking has been downplayed in urban planning due to the rise of individualized prosumption behaviors and increasing contactless interactions in the post-pandemic era. To encourage physical interactions, an adaptable spatial device down to the household scale being able to constantly transform and cope with the new changes, including the new form of cultural hierarchy, social interactions and economic structures become more important to sustain our future development.	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	IFF33	Leroy Cheng	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
ae3c426d-41bb-49e8-8257-993e38839ba6	Centre for Green Building Materials and Technology	Ar. Neelam Manjunath	cgbmtblr@gmail.com	Let’s Build with Bamboo	IMPLEMENTED	SUBMITTED	SECTION_IV	Bengaluru	India	12.97422	77.593185	At the COP27, Bamboo has been named as one of future technologies to tackle climate change. Let’s Build with Bamboo is the first comprehensive book on Bamboo Construction curated for a wide audience.	A traditional, eco-friendly, & cost-effective construction material, Bamboo offers a sustainable alternative to most manufactured materials. Let’s Build with Bamboo is the world’s first comprehensive guidebook about bamboo construction informed by vernacular knowledge and on site practical application illustrating the modern usage of this material. By sensitising architects, engineers and academicians, the book will instil confidence in readers world over to adopt bamboo as material of choice.	SDG 4(4.4 & 4.7): Spread knowledge of bamboo construction at grassroots \r\nSDG 8(8.2 & 8.3): Bamboo based construction has economic & social benefits, spurring green economy\r\nSDG 9: Support to industry, innovation & infrastructure supporting development \r\nSDG 11(11.1, 11.3 & 11.b): A beacon for sustainable communities by green construction\r\nSDG 12(12.7, 12.8 & 12a): Responsible construction by use of sustainable materials\r\nSDG 13: Bring awareness about bamboo playing a major role in climate change.	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	IFF38	BOOK CONCEPT, DESIGN AND AUTHOR: Ar. Neelam Manjunath   COVER PHOTO AND DESIGN: Ar. Neelam Manjunath   BLURB: Ar. Anand D K, Dr. Sanjeev Singh   CURATOR AND CO-EDITORS: Ar. Neelam Manjunath, Ar. Prof Anand D K, Dr. Sanjeev Singh, Dr. Jagadish Vengala   LINE EDITORS: Ar. Neelam Manjunath, Ar. Rajesh Advani   TEXT REFERENCING: Ar. Radhika Gopinath, Ar. Sagar Jayaram, Veronica, Nayana Badiger     PRINTED BY Judge press Grafi print private limited W.Q. Judge Press, 97,Residency Rd, Bengaluru. Karnataka 560025   FORWORD BY N. Sivasailam , IAS (R) Arun Kr Bansal. IFS( R)   DESIGN CREDITS Concept and Layout by Ar. Neelam Manjunath   Graphic Design by Karthik Burra   PICTURE RESEARCH: Ar. Sagar Jayaram, Vivek Cheekoti, Shreya Gaikwad, Veronica   IMAGE/PHOTO REFERENCING: Vivek Cheekoti, Shreya Gaikwad, Veronica   COMPILATION: Ar. Sagar Jayaram, Ar. Sowmya, Ar. Sonali Srivastava   FORMATTING: Ar. Mogilisetty, Nikhil Prasanth , Vivek Cheekoti,  Nayana Badiger	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
8351d9e3-59b2-4d48-a4e9-3968ebc0d3c0	College of Architecture and Urban Planning, Tongji University, Shanghai, P.R.CHINA	Xiong Yixuan	dnjchz@gmail.com	Hanzhong Road Metro Station	IMPLEMENTED	SUBMITTED	SECTION_IV	Shanghai	China	31.222934	121.461763	Hanzhong Road Station, located in Jing'an District, Shanghai, China, is the interchange station of Shanghai Metro Line 1, Line 12 and Line 13, put into use on April 10, 1995 with the opening of Line 1; Passed Line 12 and Line 13 on December 19, 2015.	In the 1990s, there were large areas of low-rise residential buildings and little high-rise apartments and office buildings near Hanzhong Road Station. Along with the construction of the subway, the old residential buildings were gradually replaced by high-rise commercial complexes, office buildings and new residential communities.\r\nCircumstance:Hanzhong Road Station is a five-story island-platform. For the platforms of Line 12 and 13 are arranged upward-and-downward counterpoint, there is no need to transfer through the station hall; The station hall of Line 12 and 13 connects to the hall of Line 1 through an underground passage. As an interchange station, the station has multiple floors with high pedestrian flow during peak hours, but clear flow lines ensure its traffic efficiency.  \r\nThe station has ten entrances distributed in three street blocks. Entrance 1-4 are located above the station hall of Line 1 and Entrance 5-10 above the station hall of Lines 12 and 13. Entrance 5 and 10 lead to underground commercial space and the accessible elevator is located near Entrance 10. The entrances lead to five roads. Among them, Hengfeng Road and Hengtong Road are traffic arteries. \r\nBuildings around the station are mainly high-rise commercial and office buildings. Residential areas are further on the north and southeast sides. The station hall area of Line 12 and 13 is now covered by a Shopping Center whose underground part is directly connected with the station.   \r\nThe station is relatively close to Suzhou River and adjacent to Hengfeng Road Bridge on the west side. Entrances 3, 7, 8, and 9 are only one block from the Suzhou River along which is waterfront landscape green space.\r\nQuestions and Optimization:Entrance 1-4 are located above the hall of Line 1. Due to its early construction period, the vertical transportation facilities are crude. Heat map shows the north side (commercial-office area) of Hanzhong Road Station has a higher pedestrian flow compared to the south side (residential area). Entrance 1 in this area has a dense flow of people during rush hours with a narrow stairs and no two-way escalator; The barrier-free elevator near entrance 10 is hidden behind the street greening whose accessibility and visibility need improving.\r\nPassengers entering and exiting the station are mainly office staff and residents nearby with a high demand for small restaurants, fresh food, convenience stores, etc. However, except for entrance 5 and 10 leading to the shopping mall. There is only one bakery next to entrance 1 and no small commercial service facilities near the other entrances. A temporary building near Suzhou River at Entrance 2 and 3 currently serve as a food market, indicating a lack of community oriented commercial support. \r\nThe station is near Suzhou River. However, along Hengfeng Road and Meiyuan Road which connect the station and landscape area are warehouses and parking lots. Sight is squeezed by Hengfeng Road Bridge, lacking direct visual connection and prompts. The pedestrian experience can be optimized by renovating local streets, connecting subway stations with landscape spaces.	According to existing studies, Hanzhong Road Station is seen as an interchange station whose traffic efficiency and the experience of underground space are mainly concerned. But it is located in a mixed-functional area in the central city of Shanghai. Which means the circumstance is complex and the station serves a large quantity of passengers getting out and in every day. Therefore it should not only transfer but also be an infrastructure connecting to the city or the community and more accessible to the citizens. \r\nBased on data collection and field research, this study analyses the relation between the station and its circumstance, including roads, buildings, city landscape as well as urban activities around it, and  proposes ideas-from the aspects of convenient facilities and spatial experience-to help make it a more positive and active part of the city in which it deeply roots. The goal is to improve transportation efficiency, enhance the convenience of city lives and increase the vitality of urban public space，creating a sustainable city and community.	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	IFF40	Shanghai Lab, Tongji University	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
8f64f63d-c0a9-4723-b442-061aebfa102e	euZen Architecture / Theodora Kyriafini - Fotini Lymperiadou & Co L.P. / Architects: T. KYRIAFINI, F. LYMPERIADOU, K. DESPOTIDIS, A. EFTHIMIADOU / Associates: I. DESPOTIDIS, C. SAXONI, E. MALEZI, A. IOSIFIDOU, P. GALANIS, I. KEFALONITI, A. LYMPERIADOU, M.	Theodora Kyriafini - Fotini Lymperiadou & Co L.P.	info@euzenarchitecture.com	Innovative Bioclimatic European School in Crete	IMPLEMENTED	SUBMITTED	SECTION_I	Heraklion	Greece	35.339887	25.141917	1st prize of the 2012 International Architectural Competition organized by UIA & School Buildings Organization. European School is addressed to 780 pupils aged 5 to 18 years old. Construction is planned to start in 2024.	Bringing nature to the heart of the school is the catalyst for users to experience joy and freedom, promoting health.\r\nCourtyards surrounded by small scaled buildings and their arcades embrace pupils and foster the feeling of community while improving the microclimate.\r\nPassive heating and cooling methods are adopted incorporating design principles of ancient and vernacular local architecture.\r\nLocal, low embodied energy clean materials achieve a high-quality indoor air, resulting in the well-being for the users.	The school through education acts as a prototype for experiential lifelong learning in environmental awareness, involves local community and nearby university, promoting good health & the well-being of its users.\r\nSmall scaled buildings and inner courtyards surrounded by arcades are formed as natural environments, adjacent to south facing classrooms. Nature’s rhythms are observed and respected.\r\nAchieving almost zero energy consumption, it presents an affordable and clean energy example of bioclimatic design.	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	IFF50	Theodora Kyriafini, Fotini Lymperiadou	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
516f0e05-52ca-4a14-bc95-baad1901cb94	Unknown	Unknown	lrx06@126.com	Dingzhou Cultural and Sports Center	IMPLEMENTED	SUBMITTED	SECTION_IV	Dingzhou	China	38.5138	114.9899	Dingzhou City, historically lauded as the "the throat of the nation" and designated a "Millennium County" by the UN, is experiencing continuous population loss. The city 's lack of attraction and sense of belonging is the main problem. The project is located at the junction of urban and rural areas in Dingzhou City, surrounded by 6000 students of middle schools and several kindergartens. Dingzhou Cultural and Sports Center is committed to providing a pleasant place for healthy sports and learning for Dingzhou city, especially for the surrounding children. It comprises five core buildings: Theater, Cultural Center, Stadium, Fitness Center, and Exhibition Center. These are complemented by supporting facilities like the Roaming Tower and children courtyards. The design adequately incorporates modern concepts including public co-design, low-carbon sustainability, resilience to local climate, and intelligent construction. City-Park Integration The project employs an integrated north-south site planning approach. Building forms adopt a posture of "embracing the gardens," creating a seamless city-park integration. The main structures are set back to the northeast, dedicating the central public space to landscape, fully connecting with the southern park.  Wandering Cloud Roofscape A parametrically gradient "wandering cloud" roof and second-floor connective spaces bridging indoors and outdoors, link the five parts into a cohesive whole. This creates multi-layered, multi-scaled, and multi-functional urban spaces, encouraging free movement through non-consumptive areas and redefining public life. Large-span planar grid structures support by tree-like steel columns. Lightweight aluminum roof panels and mesh ceilings featuring parametric variations in color and perforation rates, generate a natural, organic texture paying homage to the millennia-old Dingzhou white porcelain.  Public Co-Design Facing the fading vibrancy of Dingzhou's older cultural buildings, we chose "co-design" as our approach. We invited the future stewards of this land – students from Dingzhou No.1 High School – to paint their vision of an ideal space. This transcends mere spatial renewal; it's a practice in fostering "belonging. Empowered by Technology The project emphasizes intelligent design, production, and construction. Parametric design modeled the complex curved surfaces' triangular fractals and perforation gradient variations, enabling precise division and optimized layout of curtain wall unit panels. Digital craftsmanship facilitated human-machine collaboration and coordinated intelligent construction. Furthermore, the project utilizes renewable energy sources like solar power and air-source heat pumps, supplying over 80% of domestic and pool hot water. This reduces carbon emissions by approximately 22.41 tons annually compared to natural gas. Energy-saving lighting reduces emissions by about 204.99 tons per year. With a green area of approximately 46,459 sqm, the site sequesters an estimated 166.83 tons of carbon annually. Operation Vitality Since its opening in 2024, the Dingzhou Cultural and Sports Center has become a hotspot for leisure activities for citizens in Dingzhou and surrounding areas. The National Fitness Center became Dingzhou's second-largest membership gym within two months of opening. It became the training place for teenagees of basketball, pingpang ball, swimming, etc. The Stadium hosted the 2024 CBA Club Cup group stage and the 2024-2025 Chinese Women's Volleyball Super League.	Dingzhou City, historically lauded as the "the throat of the nation" and designated a "Millennium County" by the UN, is experiencing continuous population loss. The city 's lack of attraction and sense of belonging is the main problem. The project is located at the junction of urban and rural areas in 