, and construction. Parametric design modeled the complex curved surfaces' triangular fractals and perforation gradient variations, enabling precise division and optimized layout of curtain wall unit panels. Digital craftsmanship facilitated human-machine collaboration and coordinated intelligent construction. Furthermore, the project utilizes renewable energy sources like solar power and air-source heat pumps, supplying over 80% of domestic and pool hot water. This reduces carbon emissions by approximately 22.41 tons annually compared to natural gas. Energy-saving lighting reduces emissions by about 204.99 tons per year. With a green area of approximately 46,459 sqm, the site sequesters an estimated 166.83 tons of carbon annually. Operation Vitality Since its opening in 2024, the Dingzhou Cultural and Sports Center has become a hotspot for leisure activities for citizens in Dingzhou and surrounding areas. The National Fitness Center became Dingzhou's second-largest membership gym within two months of opening. It became the training place for teenagees of basketball, pingpang ball, swimming, etc. The Stadium hosted the 2024 CBA Club Cup group stage and the 2024-2025 Chinese Women's Volleyball Super League.	See detailed description	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-04-18 13:00:15.086189	2026-04-18 13:00:15.086189	P86	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
6f13e8a6-db58-4bec-9194-aa519da4eab1	Sir Syed University of Engineering and Technology	Muhammad Bilal	muhammadbilal199720@gmail.com	A SELF SUSTAINING TECHNICAL SCHOOL: A MODULAR DESIGN APPROACH TO EVOLVE A RESILIENT COMMUNITY	IMPLEMENTED	SUBMITTED	SECTION_IV	Karachi	Pakistan	24.89114	67.04658	Not bounded by the site, a low cost modular approach towards skill development center in pakistan to improve lives of youth.	As fastest growing population yet limited opportunities, Economic deprivation, Pakistan is grappling with illiteracy that accelerating rate of children out of school ended up in child labor which effects health and personal development. Low cost skill development center can be an indispensable contribution for youth to learn, develop and explore by means of architecture.	This project implement goal 4 by giving skill development quality in underprivileged areas of Pakistan through modular approach by implementing on less time constraints further empowering the region through different possible economic growth which will help the region to self sustain and counter poverty by this this project is implementing goal 8 and 1 and ensuring reduction of inequality in the country through empowerment which covers the goal no 10.	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	IFF60	Muhammad Bilal and Muhammad Mehdi	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
7e3b8fa9-7bfb-487f-bec6-47c1c135e028	Arlind Dervishaj architecture & innovation workshop	Arlind Dervishaj	arlindd@kth.se	Grattacortina – a concept accounting for growing density in Cities	IMPLEMENTED	SUBMITTED	SECTION_I	Turin	Italy	45.085719	7.705418	Grattacortina is a sustainable urban regeneration model that addresses the increasing density in cities. Its organic design integrates public spaces and repurposes unused plots without demolition.	Grattacortina is a concept designed to address the growing density in cities, specifically in Turin, Italy. Unlike traditional high-rises that require the demolition of existing structures, this concept uses plots that would otherwise remain unused while combining real needs of cities into a new urban model that includes public spaces, and adaptable and flexible structures. It incorporates sustainable principles including daylighting strategies at the urban scale and in the design of facades.	It contributes to SDG 11 as a new urban model to address densification, supports SDG 12 through the reuse of empty plots instead of outward city expansion, SDG 13 through design for adaptability reduces lifecycle GHGs, SDG 3 with optimal access to daylight for all buildings, SDG 7 by integrating renewable energy sources, and SDG 8 to create new jobs and investments. Lastly, the creation of new public spaces from urban regeneration aligns with multiple SDGs including SDG 11, SDG 3, and SDG 8.	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	IFF8	Arlind Dervishaj	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
f85e2f58-d7a7-4166-9eb2-0855043b289b	TecTo Arhitectura	Sergiu C. Petrea	office@tecto.ro	DSBU (Deutsche Schule Bukarest) - New School Campus	IMPLEMENTED	SUBMITTED	SECTION_II	Bucharest	Romania	44.43268	26.10201	A new school campus containing educational spaces for children of all ages, focused on pupils’ integration, belonging and well-being. The general concept follows principles from all aspects of sustainability and represents EU principles: democracy, equality, unity, diversity, and mutual learning.	As a European school, DSBU gathers pupils from many European countries in a new place where the European principles such as democracy, education, equality, learning together from each other are brought together. The buildings are placed around a central square, accessible from all directions, that connects every empty space between buildings, creating a coherent urban composition that responds to functional connectivity and aesthetic purposes. The functional layout helps children to guide themselves easily inside the school, facilitating education through art, space, light and emotion.	All spaces ensure healthy activity and promote well-being for all at all ages. The colorful architecture and common spaces support the indoor and outdoor activities and ensure inclusive and equitable quality education and promote lifelong learning opportunities for all. The school has many secure places of different kinds, that encourage movement and social interaction, gender equality, productive employment, and decent work for all. The project uses sustainable materials and affordable and reliable energy efficient systems in a compact shape that proves that it is possible to imagine an architectural vocabulary that is both aesthetically harmonious and capable to give valuable answers to economic and sustainable constraints (environmental, social, economic). The general architecture image establishes a significant link with nature based on a resilient infrastructure as part of an inclusive, resilient, and sustainable new part of the city. Overall, the project strives to become a manifesto for contemporary sustainable architecture, designed to meet educational, cultural, and economic needs, with emphasis on energy efficiency and responsible use of natural resources, protecting biodiversity and taking urgent action to combat climate change. The campus has been pre-certified with the grade Excellent for the Green Schools category by ROGBC - Romania Green Building Council, thus confirming the care for the environment and the commitment for a sustainable and green future.	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	LDP10	PhD. arch. Sergiu-Cătălin Petrea, arch. Sabrina Ene-Butnariu, arch. Cristina Mototolea, arch. Sebastian-Ștefan Apostol, arch. Dan - Alexandru Roșu, arch. Tania-Victoria Băncilă, arch. Diana-Elena Fusea, arch. Ovidiu-Ion Bălășoiu	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
a5694e95-add3-49fe-a056-cbfe757c753d	CSCAE	Primitivo González	noa@primitivogonzalez.com	Art School in Valladolid	IMPLEMENTED	SUBMITTED	SECTION_I	Valladolid	Spain	41.653293	-4.724193	The new Art School of Valladolid, respectful of its historical context, is built as an architecture of patios, where education and creativity can meet.	The new Art School of Valladolid is adjacent to the convent of Las Carmelitas Descalzas. The plot used to be part of the convent's orchards, this condition has characterised the project. Towards the city, the buildings shows itself as an architecture of walls; towards the inside, an architecture of patios. The project strives to be respectful of its historical context. However, it houses a space for creativity, youth and dreams. The essence of the project is the materialization of this duality.	The Art School, placed in the former orchards of the adjacent convent, shows a brick façade, respectful to the historical context. However the internal structure is designed to promote a better education, allowing teachers and students to appropriate the space. It also intends to create an environment that provokes the interaction between different disciplines and students, an to encourage them to be active part of their education.	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	LDP33	Primitivo, Noa and Ara González	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
307dd0e8-2841-4228-90c6-5b2830cd1e5c	Architectural Society of China	Wei ZHANG	zw1998@vip.163.com	Yuanbo Building	IMPLEMENTED	SUBMITTED	SECTION_IV	Zhuhai	China	22.274046	113.57223	Yuanbo Building is the teaching building for School of Design in Zhuhai Campus of Beijing Normal University. It is a renovation project. The design encourages communication and experiencing nature.	Yuanbo Building is attempting to bring design education back to humanity and nature. The building has been transformed into the most popular and dynamic space on the campus. Different design teaching activities such as exhibitions, performances, and even fashion shows were set in motion. A newly built continuous loop of stairs and corridors connects the roofs, courtyards and indoor spaces tightly together, creating opportunities for exchanging ideas and engendering social interactions.	In the era of virtual reality, the project attempts to bring design education back to humanity and nature. The continuous roof loop offers spaces for feeling nature and exchanging ideas. The atrium with big stairs is the exhibition and show space for students. The square courtyard with the original tree can be used as outdoor exhibition space. The round courtyard offers a stage with lights where students can hold small concerts. Students find inspiration from the building in the design studios.	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	LDP42	Architect In Charge: Wei ZHANG, Jingxian ZHAO Design Team: Haiyang HUANG, Xiangyi LI, Yue WANG, Xiaoqian ZHANG, Mingcheng CAI, Sisi LIANG, Yuben ZHANG, Ruoxing LI, Shiqi LI	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
8b7591f8-0135-49de-a719-2291710a85de	Chocarro y Urmeneta S.L.P. / Arquitectos	Patxi Chocarro	arquitectos@chyurm.com	REUSED BOTTLE CHRISTMAS TREE	IMPLEMENTED	SUBMITTED	SECTION_I	Pamplona	Spain	42.81687	-1.64323	Simple, austere, contemporary, reusable and low energy consumption were the premises for the Christmas tree promoted by the “Mancomunidad de la Comarca de Pamplona”. (Pamplona’s Common Region is an entity which manages urban waste collection and recycling thereof, among other competences, for 355.000 inhabitants)\r\n\r\nDue to Christmas celebrations and with the aim of sensitizing the citizens about recycling, a tree with reused and reusable glass bottles was projected and has been installed continuously since 2012. The structure of the tree consists of a cone-shape steel structure. This cone has four quadrants, screwed to each other. This fact allows a comfortable assembly and dismantling of the structure, as well as its transportation and storage. This means that the reusability of the structure and of the bottles is guaranteed throughout the years.	Simple, austere, contemporary, reusable and low energy consumption were the premises for the Christmas tree promoted by the “Mancomunidad de la Comarca de Pamplona”. (Pamplona’s Common Region is an entity which manages urban waste collection and recycling thereof, among other competences, for 355.000 inhabitants)\r\n\r\nDue to Christmas celebrations and with the aim of sensitizing the citizens about recycling, a tree with reused and reusable glass bottles was projected and has been installed continuously since 2012. The structure of the tree consists of a cone-shape steel structure. This cone has four quadrants, screwed to each other. This fact allows a comfortable assembly and dismantling of the structure, as well as its transportation and storage. This means that the reusability of the structure and of the bottles is guaranteed throughout the years.\r\n\r\nA 3.300 kg counterweight has been projected to support wind’s push and suction which can also be dismantled.\r\n\r\nThe tree is 6m high and has 4,80m diameter on the base.\r\nSince 2012 it has been located in “Baluarte’s Auditorium” Square during Christmastime.\r\n\r\nThe number of the bottles used is of 2.328. The 90% of them are green glass, and the 10% transparent glass.\r\n\r\nThe illumination has been carried out by Waterproof LED luminaire.\r\n\r\nThe lights are arranged radially into three circular rings in parallel planes to the base. The light is projected towards the cone’s vertex illuminating the bottles.\r\n\r\nAn explanatory panel was located next to the tree with a message about the responsible attitude of the citizens in terms of recycling. The 2.328 bottles involved the glass recovery of 13 families of Pamplona’s region along a year.	Since 2012, without interruption, the reused bottle tree has been installed during the Christmas period. The public entity organizes educational activities with children to raise awareness about the reuse of glass bottles. It is a reference event in the city of Pamplona.\r\n\r\nThe tree was awarded in 2013 at the awards organized by the Basque-Navarre Official College of Architects and won first prize at the WAN AWARDS 12, LIGHTING INSTALLATION OF THE YEAR.	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	LDP46	Patxi Chocarro and María Urmeneta	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
24e64e67-d02e-49a7-bd3a-b20955413035	Zuby Design Collective	Zohaib Zuby	zohaib.zuby@ivs.edu.pk	Wallah's House	IMPLEMENTED	SUBMITTED	SECTION_IV	Karachi	Pakistan	24.89114	67.04658	Wallah’s House is an experiment in Affordable Housing in an urban slum in Karachi. The project was co-financed (home-owners and donors), and co-designed (home-owners, contracting team), while sourcing technical design expertise on a pro-bono basis.	Wallah’s House is a precedent for Affordable Housing in the Urban Slum context. Financing was through Zakat donations, which prove to be a sustainable source for financing construction. Reinforced Cement Concrete is employed offering labour ease and cost efficiency, while giving structural integrity and sense of dignity for homeowners in slums. Vernacular elements (courtyards & screens) were employed offering culturally appropriate user-experience and passive cooling. The family had an empowered role in the entire layout of spaces, making it a thoroughly participatory design process.	Wallah’s project worked with SDG 11.1 “Affordable Housing”. The project was co-financed (homeowners and donors), and co-designed (home-owners, contracting team). The construction makes use of local materials, technology and skill. The project is sensitive to its wider cultural ethos and immediate context, in terms of architectural devices and aesthetic. It works on a small footprint, with ample semi-open flexible spaces. The project is also an incremental housing project, where the metaphor of making “half a good house” has been achieved, and additional levels can be made in the future.	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	LDP5	Zohaib Zuby	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
b29909e7-beb3-42d5-be68-be4451c197b3	Unknown	Unknown	mujunmail@163.com	Wanjian Village Children's Library	IMPLEMENTED	SUBMITTED	SECTION_IV	Qianshan	China	30.6333	116.5667	The adobe house, originally constructed as a bamboo paper workshop, had long been abandoned prior to its renovation. It was located within Wanjian village, bordered by a bamboo forest to the south and a former drying terrace to the east. The house retained load-bearing earthen walls and a simple timber truss roof structure, but prolonged neglect had rendered the timber structure unsafe. Its interior was subdivided into four cramped rooms with low ceilings, inadequate ventilation, and minimal natural light.  The project aimed not only to provide a multifunctional space that supports daily extracurricular learning for rural children and accommodates diverse community activities, but also to serve as a demonstration that offers replicable strategies for the adaptive reuse of abandoned vernacular dwellings common across traditional villages in China.  Guided by principles of simplicity, efficiency, safety, and practicality, the renovation approach—informed by the building’s condition and programmatic needs—can be summarized in three aspects. First, the necessary replacement of the roof structure served to reinforce and optimize the structural system, ensuring safety and long-term stability. Second, the new structural system was fully integrated into the spatial reconfiguration of the interior, enhancing spatial quality and flexibility for reading, learning, play, and community use. Third, apart from necessary door and window replacements, exterior interventions were kept to a minimum in order to preserve the building’s original appearance and material texture, maintaining the physical traces of collective memory shared by villagers over the past three decades.  At the heart of the renovation was the insertion of a concrete frame within the original adobe envelope, replacing deteriorated interior partitions. This strategy transformed the original load-bearing system—which had relied on adobe perimeter walls—into a hybrid structure combining a central concrete frame with stabilized earthen walls. The frame, shaped like a four-legged table, provided seismic resistance and overall structural integrity, especially critical in areas where parts of the adobe walls were visibly compromised. Beyond its structural role, the frame was conceived as a spatial device: its columns and half-slab defined a series of interior zones with varied width, height, and lighting. The area beneath the “table” can be flexibly divided with curtains, forming adaptable spaces for teaching, play, exhibitions, or community meetings. On the south side, a built-in bookshelf doubles as a staircase, leading to a quiet mezzanine for reading and reflection. In this way, the structure served not only as a reinforcement strategy but also as an organizing element for a richly layered spatial experience.  Working within the constraints of a relatively rudimentary rural construction context, the design team deliberately pursued simple, buildable solutions to address complex needs and support adaptable space. To overcome the limitations of daylight and interior height, the original roof was rotated and raised to accommodate clerestory windows. These modifications significantly improved natural lighting and ventilation, while also creating an elevated mezzanine that offers tranquil views of the surrounding bamboo forest and distant mountains. A bubble window inserted into the new roof resolves stair clearance and offers playful views into the forest. From a construction standpoint, these strategies were tailored to local conditions. Given the lack of timber construction traditions in the area and restrictions on local forest resources, conventional cast-in-place concrete was chosen for the structural frame for its durability and local workability. For the existing adobe walls, a 3 cm-thick layer of cement plaster reinforced with mesh was applied to the interior surfaces, to stabilize without altering the exterior. This combination of technical feasibility and cultural sensitivity allowed the project to maintain the original character of the building while meeting modern safety and performance standards.  The completed project is a low-cost, context-sensitive, and technically sound response that balances tradition and innovation. More than a library, it hosts a variety of community programs—after-school activities, online learning, agricultural training, and summer exchanges between urban and rural families. Its operational model, sustained by local and volunteer collaboration, ensures long-term vitality with minimal financial input. Crucially, the project offers a replicable model for rural revitalization—integrating spatial, cultural, and technical strategies. Through restrained design and thoughtful construction, the Wanjian Village Children’s Library has become a cherished space of learning and care, where children gather after school under filtered sunlight, embraced by bamboo, hills, and shared belonging.	The adobe house, originally constructed as a bamboo paper workshop, had long been abandoned prior to its renovation. It was located within Wanjian village, bordered by a bamboo forest to the south and a former drying terrace to the east. The house retained load-bearing earthen walls and a simple timber truss roof structure, but prolonged neglect had rendered the timber structure unsafe. Its interior was subdivided into four cramped rooms with low ceilings, inadequate ventilation, and minimal natural light.  The project aimed not only to provide a multifunctional space that supports daily extracurricular learning for rural children and accommodates diverse community activities, but also to serve as a demonstration that offers replicable strategies for the adaptive reuse of abandoned vernacular dwellings common across traditional villages in China.  Guided by princ