construction context, the design team deliberately pursued simple, buildable solutions to address complex needs and support adaptable space. To overcome the limitations of daylight and interior height, the original roof was rotated and raised to accommodate clerestory windows. These modifications significantly improved natural lighting and ventilation, while also creating an elevated mezzanine that offers tranquil views of the surrounding bamboo forest and distant mountains. A bubble window inserted into the new roof resolves stair clearance and offers playful views into the forest. From a construction standpoint, these strategies were tailored to local conditions. Given the lack of timber construction traditions in the area and restrictions on local forest resources, conventional cast-in-place concrete was chosen for the structural frame for its durability and local workability. For the existing adobe walls, a 3 cm-thick layer of cement plaster reinforced with mesh was applied to the interior surfaces, to stabilize without altering the exterior. This combination of technical feasibility and cultural sensitivity allowed the project to maintain the original character of the building while meeting modern safety and performance standards.  The completed project is a low-cost, context-sensitive, and technically sound response that balances tradition and innovation. More than a library, it hosts a variety of community programs—after-school activities, online learning, agricultural training, and summer exchanges between urban and rural families. Its operational model, sustained by local and volunteer collaboration, ensures long-term vitality with minimal financial input. Crucially, the project offers a replicable model for rural revitalization—integrating spatial, cultural, and technical strategies. Through restrained design and thoughtful construction, the Wanjian Village Children’s Library has become a cherished space of learning and care, where children gather after school under filtered sunlight, embraced by bamboo, hills, and shared belonging.	See detailed description	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-04-18 13:00:31.097334	2026-04-18 13:00:31.097334	P143	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
d4cb4c97-a1d4-4bec-b093-e843b06d14be	Dvelas Reusail Proyect S.L.	Enrique Kahle	dvelas@dvelas.com	DVELAS Living Sails	IMPLEMENTED	SUBMITTED	SECTION_I	Pamplona	Spain	42.81687	-1.64323	RECYCLED BOAT SAILS – CREATIVE PRODUCTS AND SERVICES\r\nDvelas is an initiative to reuse sails from ships to manufacture shading systems, outdoor furniture, and lighting.	RECYCLED BOAT SAILS – CREATIVE PRODUCTS AND SERVICES\r\n\r\n\r\nAt the end of their useful life sailboat sails are put into storage as until now there has been no available process for restoring them and bring them back to life.   A large quantity of sail material has been put away without any plans for its rehabilitation.   The sails currently used on Maxi Yachts are made of high-tech materials and when they are taken out of service much of their surface is still in perfect condition.  Our project focuses on finding these retired sails and taking full advantage of the technology that has been invested in them.  We do this not only because we can take full advantage of their strength and their durable qualities but also because we think they have enormous, unexplored, aesthetic potential.\r\n\r\nOur projects focus on three main areas of design and production: \r\ntailor-made sun protection\r\noutdoor furniture\r\nlighting systems\r\nRaw materials and consulting services for other proyects.	The business model that Dvelas follows can serve as an exemplary model for society. Starting from a residue that generates a problem, we solve it and create raw material that we offer to third parties and use ourselves to design and produce beautiful and functional products.\r\nThe company has generated stable work directly for 9 people and indirectly for around 15 people. We collaborate with local companies in all our production processes.\r\nWe collaborate with the Lurederra technology center, a technology center that carries out applied technological research and development activities in the fields of nanotechnology, new materials and advanced environment at the service of companies and economic agents both nationally and internationally, including the subsequent implementation of innovations developed in the industrial production centers themselves.\r\nWe are part of the Asociación Cluster Del Sector Del Hábitat Madera Oficina Y Contract (HABIC), it is an activation and linkage engine between the different actors of the habitat industry and it facilitates contact between companies and other agents of the same business to take advantage of the transversality of the sector. It allows us to be in contact with companies and cluster agents, and others, with whom we can exchange knowledge and obtain business opportunities.\r\nWe also collaborate with Ain (Asociación de la Industria Navarra), a private association that, through its specialized knowledge in management and technology, promotes collaboration and the improvement of the competitive position of the industry and the environment. As a result of our collaboration with AIN, our company was included in the catalog of benchmark companies in the circular economy of Navarra.\r\nCollaboration with research centers, the cluster or Ain has given us the opportunity to give talks at different events where we have been able to promote ourselves and teach our way of working.\r\nIn 2018 we were Sustainability partners of the Turn the tide on Plastic team of the Volvo Ocean Race regatta, providing the furniture for the team bases throughout the regatta. We were also invited to participate in the Sustainability presentations at the Volvo Ocean Race Summit in The Hague in June 2018.	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	LDP57	Enrique Kahle, Arraitz Koch, Borja Fuentes, Esperanza Kahle	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
4216b174-7928-4e27-8b3e-4dde9ac75343	the Architectural Design & Research Institute of Tsinghua University	Haiyang Huang	haiyang_arch@163.com	Lakeshore Service Center	IMPLEMENTED	SUBMITTED	SECTION_IV	Zhuhai	China	22.274046	113.57223	The project is about a suburb area renovation in a mountainous college town in Zhuhai, Guangzhou, China. In the north of Fenghuang Mountain, the project is located on the Y104 country road, where two abandoned unfinished buildings had existed for decades. The surrounding environment was quite negative as well: A flood discharge channel on the northwest side of the site was blocked by weeds and silt, which posed a great safety hazard. The surrounding vegetation was lush, the trees were dominated by poinciana, forming a characteristic vegetation landscape.The project renovated the buildings as well as activated the whole site, and eventually succeeded in making the whole abandoned area into a dynamic public place.	Challenge\r\nAfter the COVID-19 pandemic, people are eager to venture outside and rebuild their public social relationships. During China's rapid urbanization process, a large number of urban spaces were left without detailed design and planning, with some even located in important areas for communities and natural environments. By repurposing these areas, we can activate them and create vibrant community spaces. In the era of mobile internet represented by platforms like TikTok, these "small yet refined" urban living rooms will become important face-to-face socializing venues.\r\nContribution\r\nThe project is about a suburb area renovation in a mountainous college town in Zhuhai, Guangzhou, China. In the north of Fenghuang Mountain, the project is located on the Y104 country road, where two abandoned unfinished buildings had existed for decades. The surrounding environment was quite negative as well: A flood discharge channel on the northwest side of the site was blocked by weeds and silt, which posed a great safety hazard. The surrounding vegetation was lush, the trees were dominated by poinciana, forming a characteristic vegetation landscape. The project renovated the buildings as well as activated the whole site, and eventually succeeded in making the whole abandoned area into an activate public place.\r\nThe renovation work was carried out on the basis of respect for the existing elements. The structures of the two unfinished buildings were preserved. The building on the east side was originally designed to have four stories. After evaluating the view of the landscape along the lake side, we persuaded the owner to rebuild the building of two stories or lower, so that it could fit nicely along with the landscape of the valley with a humble gesture.\r\nAs for the landscape design, the features of the site have been largely retained. Specifically, vegetation and trees have been preserved to form landscape nodes. Meanwhile, safety risks were resolved. Taking into account that Zhuhai is often affected by typhoons in the summer, we dredged the originally blocked discharge channel in the process of lakeshore reconstruction. Also, a few landscapes walls were set aside inclined trees to prevent them from collapsing in the wind.\r\nAfter the renovation, the landscape along the lake has once again opened. The revetment was reconstructed with gravel driveway, which often used by locals. All this has created a pleasant hydrophilic space. The outdoor area is particularly vibrant. Activities such as gatherings, photography, outdoor sports are taking place daily. Residents and college students spend their leisure time here meeting friends, chatting, and relaxing. In the study room lectures and salons are held occasionally. The roof platforms are used for rehearsals and BBQs. New memories and stories on the neighborhood are taking place.	The whole project is about an experiment of urban stock renewal. By transferring an abandoned area into an activate place, the project explores how to create a contemporary social space from site characteristics and memories. The original site was separated from its surroundings because of the steep slopes and the triangular space formed by the angle between the buildings and the road. Taking advantage of the slopes of the site, we reconstructed the venue into a space of different heights. Ramps, steps, seats, which are of different height, were used to create different elevations so that the site provides a space that is suitable for a variety of outdoor activities. Meanwhile, a triangular vegetation terrace was used as transition between the building and the road, so that the separated area transformed into a belt space for public use.\r\nIn the final spatial design, we place emphasis on three qualities: vitality, safety, and equality.\r\n1/A PLACE OF VITALITY\r\nThe design of a number of spatial nodes in the area results an "activity catalyst“. These nodes, with no strictly defined function, encourage different types activities happening from time to time.\r\n2/A PLACE OF EUQLAITY\r\nThe original site was featured with a large height difference. The two main plazas in the site are connected to the road with slopes instead of steps. The slopes not only serve as iconic entrances, but also make the public space accessible for people with disabilities.\r\n3/A PLACE OF SAFTETY\r\nThere have been grown weeds along the lake, which blocked the view and the floodway. Through the renovation the weeds were cleaned up and the floodway was unblocked. Considering that Zhuhai is often hit by typhoons in summer, we also constructed landscape walls for the sloping trees to prevent them from being destroyed by the strong winds.	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	LDP64	Wei Zhang, Design Team: Haiyang Huang, Jingxian Zhao, Xiaoqian Zhang, Mingcheng Cai, Sisi Liang (site plan), Xiangyi Li (landscape)	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
0e239a01-a882-43fc-8cd7-b172db5a119f	Studio Cardenas Conscious Design	Arch. Mauricio Cardenas Laverde	m.cardenas@studiocardenas.it	Bamboo Eye	IMPLEMENTED	SUBMITTED	SECTION_IV	Yanqing	China	40.42	116.083336	INBAR Bamboo Eye is a vision of the architecture of the future where the use of natural materials has a crucial impact in the construction process and natural environment, contributing to 10 SDGs.	Bamboo Eye, conceived for the 2019 Beijing International Horticultural Exposition, is a contemporary interpretation of the traditional concept of “Pavilion in the Garden” fusing the pavilion into the garden, creating one single element: a Garden-Pavilion, an innovative sustainable typology where architecture, engineering and landscape melt into each other. Bamboo Eye is 54m in width and 40m in length. Each bamboo arch spans 32m and is 9m tall, is the largest bamboo structure in Northern China.	Using bamboo for construction and the garden, is strategical, as a natural resource contributes to at least 7 SDGs. The bearing structure, 5000 Phyllostachys Pubescens culms, applied with a proper construction technique, enable us to contribute with 3 more SDGs. Bamboo Eye is a resilient healthy architecture representing INBAR by promoting end poverty, provide affordable energy, access to affordable construction, efficient use of natural resources, address climate change and protect ecosystems.	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	LDP56	Arch. Mauricio Cardenas Laverde	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
1c49a8c7-115e-4357-b6b6-8a00ea8d32cb	SUP Atelier of THAD	Yingnan Chu	sup_atelier@supatelier.com	RSC Building in Hainan	IMPLEMENTED	SUBMITTED	SECTION_IV	Chengmai	China	19.7385	110.006767	The project themed “Garden & Courtyard”, is a multi-functional building available for exhibition, creative industries and commercial offices.	The project starting from climatic strategies for subtropical zones, has introduced terraced fields, a series of interconnected courtyards at various altitudes, outdoor atriums and cooling alleys into the building. Taking the abstract prototype of Eastern gardens and courtyards as reference, these spaces are integrated into the multi-functional city hall to from a multi-dimensional public space with gardens and courtyards, where people enjoy various scenes with changing viewpoints through the winding paths.	1.On the basis of the integration of building and landscape, the project’s contribution to society and openness to the public are both highlighted. 2.With an overall energy-saving scheme, different energy plans are applied to non-air-conditioned area (semi-open areas) and air-conditioned area (indoor functional areas). 3.Improvements are made to the cooling alleys and courtyards with better sun-shading and ventilation strategies.4.In air-conditioned areas, a series of strategies are adopted to guarantee energy conservation.	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	LDP75	Yehao Song, Xiaojuan Chen, Dan Xie, Yingnan Chu, Jingfen Sun, Haowei Yu, Mengjia Liu, Yuyan Xia, Zhihao Huang	11198	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
cf73bf65-e8cb-4d1d-896b-9e4086f2d659	Unknown	Unknown	ar.sayedahmed@gmail.com	Adaptive Reuse for Hindu Religious Site: Nag Mohashoy Temple Complex, Narayanganj:	IN_PROGRESS	SUBMITTED	SECTION_IV	Narayanganj	Bangladesh	23.6238	90.4996	The Hindu community is one of the notable minorities in Bangladesh, and historically, they influenced Narayanganj city. Particularly, Saint Nag Mohashoy’s memory that is associated with this place could be felt all over the diaspora and Bengali Hindus’ minds for his life and teachings. That’s why the Narayanganj city corporation took this initiative to protect the “spirit” of his homestead and enhance communal harmony. Collective consent of the local inhabitants found the adaptive reuse principles and associated proposals positive during the field survey, which were later followed in design decisions for the overall temple site. Despite having historic segregation after the partition of Bengal in 1947, the site remained a “socialist tissue” that gives the actual essence of religious tolerance. The design solution wanted to integrate religious aspirations with the past. This might be linked by a “Bridge” to germinate a reflection of the past and prosperity with the future.	The Hindu community is one of the notable minorities in Bangladesh, and historically, they influenced Narayanganj city. Particularly, Saint Nag Mohashoy’s memory that is associated with this place could be felt all over the diaspora and Bengali Hindus’ minds for his life and teachings. That’s why the Narayanganj city corporation took this initiative to protect the “spirit” of his homestead and enhance communal harmony. Collective consent of the local inhabitants found the adaptive reuse principles and associated proposals positive during the field survey, which were later followed in design decisions for the overall temple site. Despite having historic segregation after the partition of Bengal in 1947, the site remained a “socialist tissue” that gives the actual essence 