ab405cc5-f99a-4e23-8c64-6c0db91b6cd2	Pool Arch	Entwicklung	entwicklung@poolarch.ch	Zeughäuser, Kasernenareal Zürich	PLANNED	SUBMITTED	SECTION_I	Zurich	Switzerland	47.3769	8.5417	The project follows an “as found” approach—treating the existing buildings not as obstacles, but as a story to be continued. By layering new elements into the historic structure with care and precision, the Zeughäuser (old armories) are revitalised through minimal intervention, phased construction, and long-term adaptability.	The project follows an “as found” approach—treating the existing buildings not as obstacles, but as a story to be continued. By layering new elements into the historic structure with care and precision, the Zeughäuser (old armories) are revitalised through minimal intervention, phased construction, and long-term adaptability.	See detailed description	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-04-18 13:00:15.086189	2026-04-18 13:00:15.086189	P85	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
1ce8b67b-0ae5-4c27-910d-5422fa9ff5a6	LOCUS	Cruz Dennis Sam Shaju, Nishrin S B, Tanushree H, Srivani Lakshmi K, Monika Valase, Nitesh Ingle	locus@studiolocus.com	Bioregioning MEPZ	PLANNED	APPROVED	SECTION_IV	Chennai	India	13.0827	80.2707	Madras Export Processing Zone (MEPZ), a 262-acre industrial estate established in 1984 is located between the Pachai malai and the Madhuravayol hillocks, in a natural valley forming the lacustrine basin between the Kadaperi and Periya Eri lakes. It forms a part of the Adyar river catchment. Systemic ecological degradation of this lacustrine basin over the last 4 decades resulting from 42% of the campus developments has made MEPZ flood-prone and vulnerable to increasing torrential rainfall. This lack of foresight was compounded by inefficient use of land and natural resources, underutilized industrial infrastructure, fragmented land pockets and aging and structurally unsafe buildings.  Beginning as a vision plan to realise the economic potential of MEPZ in 2023, the project was re-visioned to an powerful ecological regeneration and rechristened Bioregioning MEPZ. Planning strategies The strategies aim at repealing layers of nature-insensitive development, reconnecting work environments with nature, aiming to provide a resilient planet friendly business destination.  Ecologically these include integrating fragmented natural ecosystems, repositioning and repurposing physical infrastructure, using green infrastructure and micro-catchments to alleviate flooding downstream.  Built environment strategies include reducing footprints, agglomerating plots, realigning infrastructure to the periphery to restore land to its pristine state. TOD integrated with multimodal transit systems gears MEPZ to its Net-zero journey.  Ecological interventions Opening the lacustrine by reconnecting three lakes, extends benefits beyond MEPZ to the surrounding 3000 acre Tambaram neighbourhood impacting positively the Adyar river catchment. The existing building footprints and grey infrastructure in the lacustrine are restructured and ecoscapes -softscapes, flood basins, rain gardens, 9 kms of bioswales, deep recharge pits and floodable areas tackling floods and becoming home to a wide array of migratory birds.  Miyawaki forests ring the individual developments adding 150,000 trees to the campus. Green screens woven as a tapestry move vertically into the buildings creating oxy-rich eco-connected spaces adding up 73% of green cover.  Architecture  Utilising available natural resources with a signature wall of high-rise towers featuring breathable buildings, solar farms positioned as veils, vertical green skins provides an imagery inspired by local traditions and aligned with SDGs. An integrated woven mesh of high rise towers forms a signature stretch. This houses covered streets at multiple levels providing a next generation ecosystem across levels. The colourful palette inspired by Tamil temple colours creates a joyous sprinkle for a futuristic MEPZ.  Construction  The breathing built fabric is structured from the traditional weaving styles of the Kancheepuram sarees - a geotagged dresswear of this tropical setting. Inspired by the aerated light sarees, the building fabric aids ventilation in the humid setting. Solar veils draped around the buildings generate 10 MW of energy and a vertical green tropical forest skin provides the nature-connect. An elevated public podium stitches these elements together and connects the blocks in the Signature wall stretch.  Economic  MEPZ’s gain from an increased FAR from 1.5 to 3.65 facilitating a 3- fold increase in the labour force - from a 30,000 to 100,000 workforce drawn from the 300,000 population in the surrounding Tambaram region and beyond. Additional infrastructure targeting a 350% increased export revenue is facilitated by a new trade facilitation center, a new administrative building and social and cultural spaces including a freedom plaza, place making pockets.  Social and Cultural Distributed social and cultural spaces interspersed with green platforms, enhance vibrancy, well-being, safety and inclusivity making MEPZ a resilient, nature-connected workplace and joyous.  Multimodal transport integrate pedestrian walkways with pause points for people to rest, relax and rejuvenate in a 5 min radius. Placemaking pockets designed as shaded open cultural rooms and activities provide a boost inducing happiness hormones, endorphin, serotonin, oxytocin and dopamine in a joyful MEPZ. MEPZ’s metamorphosis is more than a masterstroke in urban ecology—it's a bold declaration of what industrial estates can become when regenerative vision meets resilient design. By fusing tradition with innovation, ecology with economy, and wellbeing with infrastructure, this 262-acre lacustrine haven stands tall as a beacon of sustainable progress. It doesn't just undo human mishandling of nature or reclaim land—it regenerates ecology and hope. A thriving landscape of lakes, forests, breathable architecture and empowered communities, MEPZ now pulses as a nature-connected workplace that’s built for today and prepared for tomorrow.	Madras Export Processing Zone (MEPZ), a 262-acre industrial estate established in 1984 is located between the Pachai malai and the Madhuravayol hillocks, in a natural valley forming the lacustrine basin between the Kadaperi and Periya Eri lakes. It forms a part of the Adyar river catchment. Systemic ecological degradation of this lacustrine basin over the last 4 decades resulting from 42% of the campus developments has made MEPZ flood-prone and vulnerable to increasing torrential rainfall. This lack of foresight was compounded by inefficient use of land and natural resources, underutilized industrial infrastructure, fragmented land pockets and aging and structurally unsafe buildings.  Beginning as a vision plan to realise the economic potential of MEPZ in 2023, the project was re-visioned to an powerful ecological regeneration and rechristened Bioregioning MEPZ. Planning strategies The strategies aim at repealing layers of nature-insensitive development, reconnecting work environments with nature, aiming to provide a resilient planet friendly business destination.  Ecologically these include integrating fragmented natural ecosystems, repositioning and repurposing physical infrastructure, using green infrastructure and micro-catchments to alleviate flooding downstream.  Built environment strategies include reducing footprints, agglomerating plots, realigning infrastructure to the periphery to restore land to its pristine state. TOD integrated with multimodal transit systems gears MEPZ to its Net-zero journey.  Ecological interventions Opening the lacustrine by reconnecting three lakes, extends benefits beyond MEPZ to the surrounding 3000 acre Tambaram neighbourhood impacting positively the Adyar river catchment. The existing building footprints and grey infrastructure in the lacustrine are restructured and ecoscapes -softscapes, flood basins, rain gardens, 9 kms of bioswales, deep recharge pits and floodable areas tackling floods and becoming home to a wide array of migratory birds.  Miyawaki forests ring the individual developments adding 150,000 trees to the campus. Green screens woven as a tapestry move vertically into the buildings creating oxy-rich eco-connected spaces adding up 73% of green cover.  Architecture  Utilising available natural resources with a signature wall of high-rise towers featuring breathable buildings, solar farms positioned as veils, vertical green skins provides an imagery inspired by local traditions and aligned with SDGs. An integrated woven mesh of high rise towers forms a signature stretch. This houses covered streets at multiple levels providing a next generation ecosystem across levels. The colourful palette inspired by Tamil temple colours creates a joyous sprinkle for a futuristic MEPZ.  Construction  The breathing built fabric is structured from the traditional weaving styles of the Kancheepuram sarees - a geotagged dresswear of this tropical setting. Inspired by the aerated light sarees, the building fabric aids ventilation in the humid setting. Solar veils draped around the buildings generate 10 MW of energy and a vertical green tropical forest skin provides the nature-connect. An elevated public podium stitches these elements together and connects the blocks in the Signature wall stretch.  Economic  MEPZ’s gain from an increased FAR from 1.5 to 3.65 facilitating a 3- fold increase in the labour force - from a 30,000 to 100,000 workforce drawn from the 300,000 population in the surrounding Tambaram region and beyond. Additional infrastructure targeting a 350% increased export revenue is facilitated by a new trade facilitation center, a new administrative building and social and cultural spaces including a freedom plaza, place making pockets.  Social and Cultural Distributed social and cultural spaces interspersed with green platforms, enhance vibrancy, well-being, safety and inclusivity making MEPZ a resilient, nature-connected workplace and joyous.  Multimodal transport integrate pedestrian walkways with pause points for people to rest, relax and rejuvenate in a 5 min radius. Placemaking pockets designed as shaded open cultural rooms and activities provide a boost inducing happiness hormones, endorphin, serotonin, oxytocin and dopamine in a joyful MEPZ. MEPZ’s metamorphosis is more than a masterstroke in urban ecology—it's a bold declaration of what industrial estates can become when regenerative vision meets resilient design. By fusing tradition with innovation, ecology with economy, and wellbeing with infrastructure, this 262-acre lacustrine haven stands tall as a beacon of sustainable progress. It doesn't just undo human mishandling of nature or reclaim land—it regenerates ecology and hope. A thriving landscape of lakes, forests, breathable architecture and empowered communities, MEPZ now pulses as a nature-connected workplace that’s built for today and prepared for tomorrow.	See detailed description	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-04-18 13:00:08.127452	2026-04-18 13:00:08.127452	P62	Cruz Dennis Sam Shaju, Nishrin S B, Tanushree H, Srivani Lakshmi K, Monika Valase, Nitesh Ingle	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
5e19f15c-4b2d-423b-9bb8-f86a9b8585ac	IMK Architects	Rahul Kadri, Harish Vyas, Bhumika Ganjawala, Heena Sheikh, Pooja Satam, Pramod Shelar & Anjan kurtadkar	Preeti.v@imkarchitects.com	MALABAR HILL ELEVATED NATURE TRAIL	IMPLEMENTED	APPROVED	SECTION_IV	Mumbai	India	19.076	72.8777	In the heart of Mumbai, the Malabar Hill Forest Trail reclaims 12 acres of inaccessible, ecologically sensitive urban forest to create a public space that prioritizes coexistence over control. Designed as a 482-meter-long elevated walkway, the project merges architecture, ecology, and landscape to revive one of the city’s last natural terrains. In a metropolis where accessible green public spaces are rare, the trail offers not just a route through nature, but a reimagined model of urban infrastructure one that is inclusive, resilient, and regenerative.  The structure is built without cutting a single tree. Low-impact concrete pile foundations preserve underground root systems and soil permeability. Cylindrical, epoxy-coated steel columns and beams offer modularity, durability, and weather resistance. Steel joists support a deck made of Merbau Indonesian teak wood, chosen for its strength, minimal upkeep, and natural harmony with the forest environment. These materials were prefabricated off-site and rapidly assembled on-site, minimizing disruption and ecological damage.  The walkway gently rises from 2 to 10 meters above ground, responding to terrain without altering it. It allows stormwater to flow naturally and wildlife to move freely beneath. The defined trail prevents informal paths that caused soil erosion and ecological degradation. By lifting pedestrian activity off the ground, the trail ensures accessibility while safeguarding the forest from human impact.  Along the route, small yet thoughtful interventions enhance experience while respecting ecology. Warm LED lighting embedded into the balustrades reduces light pollution, maintaining nocturnal rhythms. Interpretive signage educates visitors about local flora and fauna, transforming the trail into an open-air learning corridor. Seating bays, waste bins, and CCTV cameras ensure safety, cleanliness, and comfort. The trail widens at intervals to accommodate rest points and viewing decks, encouraging pause and reflection.  The Malabar Hill Forest Trail is not only a design achievement but it is a product of participatory governance. Initiated by the Nepeansea Road Citizens’ Forum and supported by the JSW Foundation, the trail was funded by the Brihanmumbai Municipal Corporation (BMC). This civic partnership exemplifies a new model of urban development, one shaped by collaboration between local communities, public agencies, and private institutions. The result is a civic space deeply rooted in context, shared ownership, and long-term ecological stewardship.  Rather than functioning as an ornamental park, the trail restores natural systems and redefines public space as essential civic infrastructure. It avoids spectacle and over-programming, instead offering a quiet, sustained engagement with nature. The design shows that ecological sensitivity can be an architectural act restraint, not dominance, becomes the gesture.  The trail provides a replicable model for how Indian cities can embed nature into the public realm. It reimagines landscape architecture as fundamental to urban infrastructure on par with roads, water networks, and transport systems. In a city known for its density and fragmentation, this project reconnects land, people, and systems in a subtle yet powerful way.  It also advances multiple Sustainable Development Goals:  SDG 11 by creating inclusive, safe, and accessible public space  SDG 15 by preserving forest ecology and biodiversity  SDG 16 through cross-sectoral collaboration  Today, this restored forest is a breathing space for Mumbai’s citizens. Morning walkers, school groups, elderly visitors, and nature lovers alike share the trail. It’s more than just a walkway it’s a bridge between the urban and the natural, the past and the future, and between the people and the land they live on.	In the heart of Mumbai, the Malabar Hill Forest Trail reclaims 12 acres of inaccessible, ecologically sensitive urban forest to create a public space that prioritizes coexistence over control. Designed as a 482-meter-long elevated walkway, the project merges architecture, ecology, and landscape to revive one of the city’s last natural terrains. In a metropolis where accessible green public spaces are rare, the trail offers not just a route through nature, but a reimagined model of urban infrastructure one that is inclusive, resilient, and regenerative.  The structure is built without cutting a single tree. Low-impact concrete pile foundations preserve underground root systems and soil permeability. Cylindrical, epoxy-coated steel columns and beams offer modularity, durability, and weather resistance. Steel joists support a deck made of Merbau Indonesian teak wood, chosen for its strength, minimal upkeep, and natural harmony with the forest environment. These materials were prefabricated off-site and rapidly assembled on-site, minimizing disruption and ecological damage.  The walkway gently rises from 2 to 10 meters above ground, responding to terrain without altering it. It allows stormwater to flow naturally and wildlife to move freely beneath. The defined trail prevents informal paths that caused soil erosion and ecological degradation. By lifting pedestrian activity off the ground, the trail ensures accessibility while safeguarding the forest from human impact.  Along the route, small yet thoughtful interventions enhance experience while respecting ecology. Warm LED lighting embedded into the balustrades reduces light pollution, maintaining nocturnal rhythms. Interpretive signage educates visitors about local flora and fauna, transforming the trail into an open-air learning corridor. Seating bays, waste bins, and CCTV cameras ensure safety, cleanliness, and