452	2026-04-18 13:00:08.127452	P64	Rahul Kadri, Harish Vyas, Bhumika Ganjawala, Heena Sheikh, Pooja Satam, Pramod Shelar & Anjan kurtadkar	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
274da34c-6a74-44da-a41f-69bf092bd4a0	KIRK	Richard Kirk, Brendan Pointon, Andrew Magub, Catherine Liu, Fedor Medek	cm@kirk.studio	UQ Soundshell	IMPLEMENTED	APPROVED	SECTION_IV	Brisbane	Australia	-27.4698	153.0251	The UQ Soundshell is a vaulted diagrid timber pavilion that acts as a pivotal element within the recently revitalised Lake and Ampitheatre at the University of Queensland St Lucia precinct.  The Soundshell responds to its sensitive and historically important site through simplicity of form and use of considered details and finishes. It enriches the on-campus experience and provides a new multi modal performance venue accommodating both small to large-scale events.  Versatile in its design, the timber diagrid structure offers a shaded, functional space outside of performance times. Climate and acoustic analysis were integrated to deliver optimal performance quality while maintaining weather protection and lakeside views. Performers can hear themselves and others clearly, a key challenge to overcome for outdoor performances.  The thin shell copper clad form blends into the surrounding landscape with a soft vaulted form and natural material palette. Thoughtfully crafted details result in a timeless and memorable structure.  9. Industry, innovation and infrastructure.   The project’s structure was comprised of Engineered Timber with GL21 spotted gum glue-laminated members forming the vaulted diagrid shell. The project utilises locally sourced timber in lieu of globally sourced timber. Timber was sourced and fabricated locally in Maryborough. As a local species, its use also supports regional forestry supply chains and reduces embodied transport energy.  The engineered GL21 spotted gum glulam is unique to the Australian Timber industry and the singular product available for external weather exposure. The product offers exceptional strength, durability, and dimensional stability, making it ideal for the complex curved geometry of the vaulted shell. Its high strength-to-weight ratio allows for slender, elegant structural members that minimise material use without compromising performance. The precision of glulam fabrication enabled complex junctions and consistent quality across prefabricated components.  Prefabrication additionally minimised site disturbance, and significantly reduced construction time and waste. The off-site fabrication and assembly process required less on-site labour, improved safety, and lowered emissions associated with transport and construction sequencing.  10. Reduced Inequalities  The project supports engagement by all members of the public, with access remaining open to the broader public and not exclusively within the University body. The stage design was carefully considered to not include any steps that may cause ambulatory impediment.   12. Responsible consumption and production.  Materials were selected based on structural performance, lifecycle durability, low embodied carbon, and end-of-life recyclability.  The GL21 Spotted Gum Glue Laminated timber was specified for its ability to achieve equivalent structural loadings and member depth as steel at a significantly reduced embodied energy. The engineered timber selected was the best suited product for external exposure without the need for over-cladding or continual maintenance. Careful consideration was placed on how the spotted gum species would age to ensure the material would meet ambitious life cycle goals for the project. The selected timber ages gracefully over time in an exposed environment, softening to a patina grey.   The diagrid system forms an entirely vaulted geometry, eliminating the need for internal columns and enabling a generous and clear span over the stage. The structure was designed to evolve with changing event demands. The stage design accommodates a broad range of event sizes and formats, structural nodes were included in the vaulted diagrid for elements to be attached and flexible hard and soft infrastructure were integrated for future utilisation.   The design leverages the existing context’s topography as natural infrastructure for spectators, negating the need to construct a material amphitheatre. The materiality and construction strategy enables end of life recyclability for the project and the capacity for disassembly or reuse, further extending the lifecycle of the materials used.   13. Climate Action  The UQ Soundshell achieves meaningful sustainability outcomes through the strategic use of mass-engineered timber. The primary structure comprises prefabricated GL21 spotted gum glue-laminated (glulam) timber, a renewable, low-embodied-carbon material that actively stores carbon over its lifecycle. By replacing a fully steel structure with locally sourced timber, the project significantly reduces its carbon footprint.   The vaulted diagrid structure is inherently passive, providing extensive shade, ventilation and protection from subtropical weather conditions, allowing for open-air use year-round without mechanical conditioning. Computational design tools informed the geometry of the structure, optimising performance across acoustic reflection, daylight access, and ventilation. This results in a high-performing space with minimal operational energy demand.	The UQ Soundshell is a vaulted diagrid timber pavilion that acts as a pivotal element within the recently revitalised Lake and Ampitheatre at the University of Queensland St Lucia precinct.  The Soundshell responds to its sensitive and historically important site through simplicity of form and use of considered details and finishes. It enriches the on-campus experience and provides a new multi modal performance venue accommodating both small to large-scale events.  Versatile in its design, the timber diagrid structure offers a shaded, functional space outside of performance times. Climate and acoustic analysis were integrated to deliver optimal performance quality while maintaining weather protection and lakeside views. Performers can hear themselves and others clearly, a key challenge to overcome for outdoor performances.  The thin shell copper clad form blends into the surrounding landscape with a soft vaulted form and natural material palette. Thoughtfully crafted details result in a timeless and memorable structure.  9. Industry, innovation and infrastructure.   The project’s structure was comprised of Engineered Timber with GL21 spotted gum glue-laminated members forming the vaulted diagrid shell. The project utilises locally sourced timber in lieu of globally sourced timber. Timber was sourced and fabricated locally in Maryborough. As a local species, its use also supports regional forestry supply chains and reduces embodied transport energy.  The engineered GL21 spotted gum glulam is unique to the Australian Timber industry and the singular product available for external weather exposure. The product offers exceptional strength, durability, and dimensional stability, making it ideal for the complex curved geometry of the vaulted shell. Its high strength-to-weight ratio allows for slender, elegant structural members that minimise material use without compromising performance. The precision of glulam fabrication enabled complex junctions and consistent quality across prefabricated components.  Prefabrication additionally minimised site disturbance, and significantly reduced construction time and waste. The off-site fabrication and assembly process required less on-site labour, improved safety, and lowered emissions associated with transport and construction sequencing.  10. Reduced Inequalities  The project supports engagement by all members of the public, with access remaining open to the broader public and not exclusively within the University body. The stage design was carefully considered to not include any steps that may cause ambulatory impediment.   12. Responsible consumption and production.  Materials were selected based on structural performance, lifecycle durability, low embodied carbon, and end-of-life recyclability.  The GL21 Spotted Gum Glue Laminated timber was specified for its ability to achieve equivalent structural loadings and member depth as steel at a significantly reduced embodied energy. The engineered timber selected was the best suited product for external exposure without the need for over-cladding or continual maintenance. Careful consideration was placed on how the spotted gum species would age to ensure the material would meet ambitious life cycle goals for the project. The selected timber ages gracefully over time in an exposed environment, softening to a patina grey.   The diagrid system forms an entirely vaulted geometry, eliminating the need for internal columns and enabling a generous and clear span over the stage. The structure was designed to evolve with changing event demands. The stage design accommodates a broad range of event sizes and formats, structural nodes were included in the vaulted diagrid for elements to be attached and flexible hard and soft infrastructure were integrated for future utilisation.   The design leverages the existing context’s topography as natural infrastructure for spectators, negating the need to construct a material amphitheatre. The materiality and construction strategy enables end of life recyclability for the project and the capacity for disassembly or reuse, further extending the lifecycle of the materials used.   13. Climate Action  The UQ Soundshell achieves meaningful sustainability outcomes through the strategic use of mass-engineered timber. The primary structure comprises prefabricated GL21 spotted gum glue-laminated (glulam) timber, a renewable, low-embodied-carbon material that actively stores carbon over its lifecycle. By replacing a fully steel structure with locally sourced timber, the project significantly reduces its carbon footprint.   The vaulted diagrid structure is inherently passive, providing extensive shade, ventilation and protection from subtropical weather conditions, allowing for open-air use year-round without mechanical conditioning. Computational design tools informed the geometry of the structure, optimising performance across acoustic reflection, daylight access, and ventilation. This results in a high-performing space with minimal operational energy demand.	See detailed description	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-04-18 13:00:08.127452	2026-04-18 13:00:08.127452	P65	Richard Kirk, Brendan Pointon, Andrew Magub, Catherine Liu, Fedor Medek	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
91a7eff8-8e70-4a9d-90c0-af71a935460b	BRAC University, Dhaka University of Engineering & Technology (DUET)	Mahia Mustary Nushin, Aqib Mohammad Nibir	mahiamustary@gmail.com	SHAKO – COMMUNITY INFRASTRUCTURE FOR RESILIENT LIVING	PLANNED	APPROVED	SECTION_IV	Chandpur	Bangladesh	23.2335	90.6626	The site is in Chandpur 10, Dhaka, Bangladesh, home to over 90 households from a water nomad community, evenly split between boat dwellers and stilt house residents. Due to past practices involving unconventional medicine and lifestyle, the community remains socially marginalized. Seasonal monsoon flooding submerges the entire area, disrupting daily life by eliminating usable spaces for fishnet repair, children’s play, and other activities. Limited income opportunities contribute to poor living standards, pushing residents to engage in small-scale gardening on raised porches and yards that can endure flooding but are insufficient to meet their ends.   WASH (Water, Sanitation, and Hygiene) infrastructure including pit latrines and bathing areas is severely impacted by rising water levels. Though Oxfam Bangladesh has provided floating WASH units, a past accident during a storm involving a boat house has made the community wary of using them. The lack of awareness, training and anchoring skills makes these units unreliable. During monsoon, movement becomes difficult, requiring boats for even short distances or access WASH facilities or city market.   In response, interviews and site surveys reveal the undeniable need for year-round accessibility. A raised walkway, SHAKO (access bridge), is proposed six feet above ground with a one-foot safety margin during heavy monsoon. This main spine links the city bazar to all household types (stilt and boat) extending to the WASH zone. It slopes down to meet the river, allowing boat access. In the dry season, it serves as a shaded playscape and tea stalls underneath. In monsoon, it becomes the primary mobility route, ensuring safe access to homes, WASH facilities, and enabling small-scale commerce and recreation, supporting both present needs and future community development.   The proposal is envisioned as an evolving solution, continuously tailored to the community’s needs with a focus on accessibility. Active community participation through the construction process empowers residents to understand, adapt, and customize the intervention according to their specific requirements.	The site is in Chandpur 10, Dhaka, Bangladesh, home to over 90 households from a water nomad community, evenly split between boat dwellers and stilt house residents. Due to past practices involving unconventional medicine and lifestyle, the community remains socially marginalized. Seasonal monsoon flooding submerges the entire area, disrupting daily life by eliminating usable spaces for fishnet repair, children’s play, and other activities. Limited income opportunities contribute to poor living standards, pushing residents to engage in small-scale gardening on raised porches and yards that can endure flooding but are insufficient to meet their ends.   WASH (Water, Sanitation, and Hygiene) infrastructure including pit latrines and bathing areas is severely impacted by rising water levels. Though Oxfam Bangladesh has provided floating WASH units, a past accident during a storm involving a boat house has made the community wary of using them. The lack of awareness, training and anchoring skills makes these units unreliable. During monsoon, movement becomes difficult, requiring boats for even short distances or access WASH facilities or city market.   In response, interviews and site surveys reveal the undeniable need for year-round accessibility. A raised walkway, SHAKO (access bridge), is proposed six feet above ground with a one-foot safety margin during heavy monsoon. This main spine links the city bazar to all household types (stilt and boat) extending to the WASH zone. It slopes down to meet the river, allowing boat access. In the