4a2e2a22-2439-4927-91d8-954e23655532	Unknown	Unknown	hrshl.jg@gmail.com	Nepal Seva School	PLANNED	SUBMITTED	SECTION_IV	Nepal	Nepal	28	84	A replicable, disaster-resilient school prototype for Karmayog Foundation, Seva School supports rural Nepali communities through incremental growth. Centred on courtyards, it expands with classrooms, an orchard, and health spaces. Using bamboo trusses, earthbag foundations, and CSEB walls, it is monsoon- and earthquake-resilient, built with local skills and materials.	A replicable, disaster-resilient school prototype for Karmayog Foundation, Seva School supports rural Nepali communities through incremental growth. Centred on courtyards, it expands with classrooms, an orchard, and health spaces. Using bamboo trusses, earthbag foundations, and CSEB walls, it is monsoon- and earthquake-resilient, built with local skills and materials.	See detailed description	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-04-18 13:00:31.097334	2026-04-18 13:00:31.097334	P135	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
6e8c6df6-a61d-4957-99b6-c6a569863886	Unknown	Unknown	lorenzoabate93@gmail.com	the garden of studies	IMPLEMENTED	SUBMITTED	SECTION_I	Bassano del Grappa	Italy	45.7656	11.7346	The innovation lies in the practical application of sustainability in the design and construction process, in a context that is clearly behind the current urban qualitative meaning of "study center". The analysis of the current state has led to a redesign of the spaces, first for cars, in favor of that for people, characterizing the surfaces through green areas, draining pavements and street furniture. The project had two phases of construction with different work times and areas, however following a general vision of the master plan. In two years, about 4400 m2 of bituminous conglomerate were removed, which was recovered by becoming milled asphalt. For greater soil permeability and enrichment of the aquifer, 1950 m2 of draining concrete, 1990 m2 of green lawn with seeding, 220 m2 of area with herbaceous and creeping plants and 120 m2 of pavement in prefabricated grid plates for the bike area were laid. This determined greater soil permeability of about 60%. To encourage the presence of users in the area and suggest moments of outdoor socialization and education, 120 trees and 680 herbaceous and creeping plants were planted, in order to guarantee greater shade and sensory well-being. In addition, 244 m of road-type kerbs were laid, creatively reused to form seats and 35 ml of seats and 18 ml of tables in painted steel, for a total of about 470 seats. The intervention has led to a considerable decrease in the urban heat island effect in the area and an increase in comfort in the vicinity and inside the school buildings, ensuring higher learning standards.	The innovation lies in the practical application of sustainability in the design and construction process, in a context that is clearly behind the current urban qualitative meaning of "study center". The analysis of the current state has led to a