f0423043-92ad-41be-87ae-783839ca9de8	Unknown	Unknown	daher.arquitetura@gmail.com	Butanta HIS - Social Housing	IN_PROGRESS	SUBMITTED	SECTION_V	São Paulo	Brazil	-23.5505	-46.6333	The HIS Butantã project is part of a series of projects developed for a private investor that aims to create developments with greater construction potential, combining the interest in democratizing access to high-quality, sustainable, and bioclimatic architecture for the population with lower purchasing power.  In this project, all dimensions are modularised in 30 cm with a maximum span of 6 m  The project combines 11 identical modular units in different variations that follow a rule of offering the best sunlight and ventilation for the development	The HIS Butantã project is part of a series of projects developed for a private investor that aims to create developments with greater construction potential, combining the interest in democratizing access to high-quality, sustainable, and bioclimatic architecture for the population with lower purchasing power.  In this project, all dimensions are modularised in 30 cm with a maximum span of 6 m  The project combines 11 identical modular units in different variations that follow a rule of offering the best sunlight and ventilation for the development	See detailed description	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-04-18 13:00:08.127452	2026-04-18 13:00:08.127452	P69	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
1cf6d37a-dcdd-4e5d-9c1d-4f27e76d14c6	NIVASA	Akhila Ramesh, Anitha Mahendra, Vishal	nivasaworks@gmail.com	Project Suitcase – Transitional Shelter for a Displaced Tribal Community	IMPLEMENTED	APPROVED	SECTION_IV	Chikkaballapur	India	13.4346	77.7274	Existing Scenario:  A small tribal community consisting of 19 number of families, lived on a lake bank, in the remote Rayanakallu village of Manchenahalli Gram Panchayat. These families lived in dismal thatched roof dwellings, disconnected from the world in many ways. The living conditions were abysmal, with exposure to the cold winters, harsh summers, heavy rains, with a perpetual threat of snakes and fire. The flashpoint for action came in an unfortunate manner: a family lost their 3-month-old baby in a fire. This galvanized the government authorities into action. The DC allotted land for the families and the tribal welfare department of Chikkaballapur district approached Nivasa to build temporary homes for the community, till such time as when the government was able to allocate permanent housing for them. This scenario is indicative of the fact that 99% of India’s nearly fifty thousand architects are serving the top 10% elite population, leaving the poor communities to shelter in devastatingly unhealthy conditions. Nivasa’s Intervention: We decided to adapt our PROJECT SUITCASE model to cater to the various challenges this particular site presented. Project Suitcase is what we have dubbed our humane dignified solution for urban landless homeless, which we had derived after extensive studies. Why the name Suitcase? To denote an ease of portability and reuse: a system that enables easy and fast installation, easy to dismantle and carry to the next location to install again. Over the course of many surveys of existing conditions in various informal settlements, we felt the need for a housing concept that would address the ever-shifting, ever-changing dynamic lifestyle: a versatile material that would not necessitate skilled knowledge, was easy to source, use and reuse multiple times, easy to transport, easy to adapt to various requirements when the families grew. These questions became the guiding force for our quest for an impactful solution. Our design options led to extensive market research, rounds of prototyping design and material options. Always the outcome was checked for structural stability, climatic and user response. After a series of experiments, we zeroed in on slotted angle palette racks for walls. These storage units clad with a bison board on the exterior doubled up for thermal comfort as well. The basic layout gives segregated space for sleeping, kitchen and veranda. The modularity of the design and the material completely supports expansion, adaptation of different layouts based on usage of space. The materials such as the sheets can be upgraded in thickness and quality as per local availability and affordability.	Existing Scenario:  A small tribal community consisting of 19 number of families, lived on a lake bank, in the remote Rayanakallu village of Manchenahalli Gram Panchayat. These families lived in dismal thatched roof dwellings, disconnected from the world in many ways. The living conditions were abysmal, with exposure to the cold winters, harsh summers, heavy rains, with a perpetual threat of snakes and fire. The flashpoint for action came in an unfortunate manner: a family lost their 3-month-old baby in a fire. This galvanized the government authorities into action. The DC allotted land for the families and the tribal welfare department of Chikkaballapur district approached Nivasa to build temporary homes for the community, till such time as when the government was able to allocate permanent housing for them. This scenario is indicative of the fact that 99% of India’s nearly fifty thousand architects are serving the top 10% elite population, leaving the poor communities to shelter in devastatingly unhealthy conditions. Nivasa’s Intervention: We decided to