fec8c8cf-adf9-4e20-baf6-fbe23e513c1a	Weber Thompson	Aswair	aswain@weberthompson.com	Solis	IMPLEMENTED	SUBMITTED	SECTION_V	Seattle	United States of America	47.6062	-122.3321	Solis was designed as both proof of concept and as a replicable model for energy-efficient multifamily development. The team took an underutilized parcel of land in a high-energy urban neighborhood and built a Passive House-certified apartment building that celebrates their drive to prove that deep-green buildings are achievable at a multifamily scale, in urban environments, with industry standard practices, at market rate prices. The end goal is to inspire more buildings like Solis and provide a roadmap to a more sustainable future.   When construction was completed in May of 2020, Solis was certified as the largest Passive House (PH) multifamily building in Washington State, with a dramatic 50% energy reduction from a U.S. multifamily baseline, and a perfect EnergyStar 100 score. It achieves these dramatic reductions in energy use for a mere 5% cost above conventional construction by using conventional materials in innovative and multi-faceted ways, including pairing an enhanced building enclosure with a top-notch mechanical system for exceptionally comfortable and healthy units.	Solis was designed as both proof of concept and as a replicable model for energy-efficient multifamily development. The team took an underutilized parcel of land in a high-energy urban neighborhood and built a Passive House-certified apartment building that celebrates their drive to prove that deep-green buildings are achievable at a multifamily scale, in urban environments, with industry standard practices, at market rate prices. The end goal is to inspire more buildings like Solis and provide a roadmap to a more sustainable future.   When construction was completed in May of 2020, Solis was certified as the largest Passive House (PH) multifamily building in Washington State, with a dramatic 50% energy reduction from a U.S. multifamily baseline, and a perfect EnergyStar 100 score. It achieves these dramatic reductions in energy use for a mere 5% cost above conventional construction by using conventional materials in innovative and multi-faceted ways, including pairing an enhanced building enclosure with a top-notch mechanical system for exceptionally comfortable and healthy units.	See detailed description	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-04-18 12:59:53.078529	2026-04-18 12:59:53.078529	P4	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
eab2a4f0-9486-46a4-82e1-867b44ad0789	Insitu	F Quandt	f.quandt@insitu.ch	Markthalle	PLANNED	SUBMITTED	SECTION_I	Basel	Switzerland	47.5596	7.5886	Constructed in 1929, the Markthalle was once the third-largest reinforced concrete dome structure in the world. Today, it is a heritage listed building. For decades, it served as Basel’s principal commercial hub. However, as distribution logistics evolved, the cooperative operating the hall returned it to the city. The City of Basel subsequently sold the property to a real estate investor, who undertook refurbishment and conversion works between 2009 and 2011. On two floors, areas were created for fashion retail, gastronomy, a mountain sports store, and a computer shop. Additionally, a twelve-storey residential tower was integrated into the existing structure. The high-end fashion stores failed to attract sufficient clientele—despite the hall’s central location in town, it lacked significant pedestrian traffic. In 2013, the owner approached the newly founded Markthalle AG Basel to pilot a new concept. Through the slow and sure introduction of market stalls and food vendors, retail outlets, festivals, and tasting events all centered around food, drink, and enjoyment, the revitalized Markthalle quickly became a popular destination. Architecturally, the challenge lay in reactivating the space with minimal investment and reversible interventions. Retail modules clad in cherry wood veneer were painted with lime wash; concealed cameras and ventilation systems were exposed; furnishings were assembled from surplus stock and some interesting finds. A warm patina started to appear over time. Infrastructure for thirty stands including electricity meters, water supply points, and ventilation were installed. A relatively new dishwashing facility acquired from the now-closed Markthalle in Bern was incorporated, and shared crockery was procured to reduce waste volumes. At the back four professional kitchens were installed, to be shared by six stands each. Originally conceived as a restaurant, Space F now serves as an event venue hosting conferences, concerts, theatrical performances, and other cultural formats. From Sunday to Sunday, the hall is filled with office workers at lunchtime and in the evening with families. The 30 food stands, run mainly by chefs with an immigrant background, collectively serve over 1,500 meals per day. Especially from Thursday to Saturday in the evenings, three bars and a curated selection of food stands invite visitors to unwind by candlelight. Whether gathered at communal tables, enjoying an intimate tête-à-tête at charming bistro tables, or relaxing in cozy lounge areas and sofas, the softly illuminated Markthalle dome reveals its atmospheric potential every evening. Cultural programming—ranging from concerts and dance or holding night flea markets—frequently run side by side at the evenings operations. The Markthalle is a consumption-free zone.  The shops offer Demeter-certified products. On Sundays, a popular mix of brunch, flea market, and children’s activities attracts primarily families. The slide between the escalators has become a beloved attraction for children.	Constructed in 1929, the Markthalle was once the third-largest reinforced concrete dome structure in the world. Today, it is a heritage listed building. For decades, it served as Basel’s principal commercial hub. However, as distribution logistics evolved, the cooperative operating the hall returned it to the city. The City of Basel subsequently sold the property to a real estate investor, who undertook refurbishment and conversion works between 2009 and 2011. On two floors, areas were created for fashion retail, gastronomy, a mountain sports store, and a computer shop. Additionally, a twelve-storey residential tower was integrated into the existing structure. The high-end fashion stores failed to attract sufficient clientele—despite the hall’s central location in town, it lacked significant pedestrian 