18f64191-a3e3-471e-b209-7dd4e25e0cbb	Insitu	F Quandt	f.quandt@insitu.ch	Werkstadt Areal with Halle Q	PLANNED	SUBMITTED	SECTION_I	Zurich	Switzerland	47.3769	8.5417	Werkstadt Zürich is a 42,000 m² former SBB industrial site transforming into a hub for urban production, innovation, and culture. As part of Zurich’s “Werkplatz Zürich” strategy, a forward-looking district is emerging. Denkstatt Sàrl leads the site’s transformation and usage strategy, while baubüro in situ handles the architecture and sensitive heritage renovation. Both offices work on-site, fostering an agile, user-centered development. The listed Building Q is being adapted to provide flexible spaces for productive uses while respecting its historic fabric.	Werkstadt Zürich is a 42,000 m² former SBB industrial site transforming into a hub for urban production, innovation, and culture. As part of Zurich’s “Werkplatz Zürich” strategy, a forward-looking district is emerging. Denkstatt Sàrl leads the site’s transformation and usage strategy, while baubüro in situ handles the architecture and sensitive heritage renovation. Both offices work on-site, fostering an agile, user-centered development. The listed Building Q is being adapted to provide flexible spaces for productive uses while respecting its historic fabric.	See detailed description	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-04-18 13:00:08.127452	2026-04-18 13:00:08.127452	P52	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
06355328-8f4f-48d2-a4aa-a7c418525af4	Group DCA	Unknown	media@groupdca.in	groupDCA Studio	IMPLEMENTED	SUBMITTED	SECTION_IV	Gurugram	India	28.4595	77.0266	Located in Gurugram, the groupDCA Studio is a human-centric workspace that reflects the firm’s eco-conscious design values. Moving away from conventional cubicle-oriented office typologies, its nature-integrated design encourages employee well-being and collaboration. The design scheme utilises locally sourced materials, pays homage to traditional craftsmanship, and retains all existing trees on site. Elements from the previous studio, including furniture, fixtures, and key plant species, have been thoughtfully repurposed, reinforcing an ethos of continuity and reuse. Additionally, passive design strategies and an integrated landscaping model shape a grounded, materially honest workplace.	Located in Gurugram, the groupDCA Studio is a human-centric workspace that reflects the firm’s eco-conscious design values. Moving away from conventional cubicle-oriented office typologies, its nature-integrated design encourages employee well-being and collaboration. The design scheme utilises locally sourced materials, pays homage to traditional craftsmanship, and retains all existing trees on site. Elements from the previous studio, including furniture, fixtures, and key plant species, have been thoughtfully repurposed, reinforcing an ethos of continuity and reuse. Additionally, passive design strategies and an integrated landscaping model shape a grounded, materially honest workplace.	See detailed description	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-04-18 13:00:00.604992	2026-04-18 13:00:00.604992	P49	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
291305b6-326a-4247-b590-a73e5f925de9	UCA	L Rodriguez	lrrodriguez@uca.edu.sv	NZEB Laboratory	IMPLEMENTED	SUBMITTED	SECTION_V	San Salvador	El Salvador	13.6929	-89.2182	A net zero energy building, NZEB, by definition, produces, through renewable sources, all the energy required for its operation within the constructive building's footprint. This is a concept widely researched internationally, but modestly explored in the Central American region. The research project that provided the foundation for the present work included the design, construction, and monitoring of a 100 m2 laboratory with an energy performance that exceeds ASHRAE 90.1 Standard, requirements by 42%. The data collected during the three phases are the foundation for a global life cycle assessment over NZEB El Salvador, under the standard of ISO 14044 which establishes that the analysis of the life cycle of a building, requires the evaluation of each one of the building's life stages, from the extraction of raw materials, the production and distribution of energy, to the use, reuse and final disposal. The NZEB El Salvador building contemplates different construction systems, which have Wood as a base construction technology, and is comparable with other construction technologies. Therefore, functional units have been considered to compare these construction systems. The budget base and part of the contractual documents were considered to calculate these impacts.	A net zero energy building, NZEB, by definition, produces, through renewable sources, all the energy required for its operation within the constructive building's footprint. This is a concept widely researched internationally, but modestly explored in the Central American region. The research project that provided the foundation for the present work included the design, construction, and monitoring of a 100 m2 laboratory with an energy performance that exceeds ASHRAE 90.1 Standard, requirements by 42%. The data collected during the three phases 