14c4a23c-4c6a-43e9-93cb-b3ce9a745b91	Unknown	Arperag	arparag@gmail.com	Reclaiming the Al-Cazaba Of Guadix	PLANNED	SUBMITTED	SECTION_I	Guadix	Spain	37.2978	-3.1372	"Reclaiming the Al-Cazaba Of Guadix" is an urban design proposal aiming to regenerate a historic Spanish citadel and its surroundings. It transforms the area into a vibrant cultural and religious hub by creating a network of public plazas connected by pedestrian access. The design emphasizes preserving cultural heritage while fostering sustainable urban integration and economic growth through a Funduque-inspired tourist-hub, creating local job opportunities. This project envisions a more livable and economically viable future for Guadix, aligning strongly with SDG 11 (Sustainable Cities & Communities) by revitalizing public spaces, safeguarding heritage, and promoting inclusive urban development.	"Reclaiming the Al-Cazaba Of Guadix" is an urban design proposal aiming to regenerate a historic Spanish citadel and its surroundings. It transforms the area into a vibrant cultural and religious hub by creating a network of public plazas connected by pedestrian access. The design emphasizes preserving cultural heritage while fostering sustainable urban integration and economic growth through a Funduque-inspired tourist-hub, creating local job opportunities. This project envisions a more livable and economically viable future for Guadix, aligning strongly with SDG 11 (Sustainable Cities & Communities) by revitalizing public spaces, safeguarding heritage, and promoting inclusive urban development.	See detailed description	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-04-18 13:00:15.086189	2026-04-18 13:00:15.086189	P99	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
ba645ec2-e559-4595-9c19-81fea9dddec3	Unknown	Unknown	aminaqmirza@gmail.com	Eco-Friendly Development - Industrial Facilities	IMPLEMENTED	SUBMITTED	SECTION_IV	Khurrianwala	Pakistan	31.5172	73.2667	Design works commencing from 2013 to 2019. The Client, Interloop Limited, Pakistan, is a leading hosiery manufacturer and exports globally. The projects are located in the Industrial Park of Khurianwala, a peri-urban area, near the agricultural plains of Punjab, specifically in the vicinity of Faisalabad, Pakistan. The climate is semi-arid with minimal annual rainfall.  In 2013, Interloop Limited sought services for offices located at the Industrial Park.  At the time Project 1, Unordinary: Quality Assurance and Product Development Laboratory was under construction and it was transformed into a memorable place of work and joy. This laboratory is connected to the FYF production facility. This project that led to a series of projects in the future.  Project 2, Catalyst for Change: Product Development and Marketing Offices and the Landscape/Parking project was completed in 2015. Success of the new Product Development and Marketing Offices and Landscape/Parking. This led to Project 3. Anecdotes: Merchandising Offices, the two buildings are interconnected via a pedestrian bridge and connected to the Main VSF Production Facility. Project 4 Luncheonette: Cafeteria is a low-cost staff dining area that was completed in 2019 Project 5 Regeneration Upcycling: Eco-Park and a Botanical Garden, a fully sustainable off-the-grid project, was completed in 2019.  Significance of the Project:  The People:   Project 2 was a catalyst for change; it changed the culture of the work environment, creating a place of democracy and social inclusion.   The open plan workspaces cultivated gender interaction by placing women with ease next to their male colleagues in the workplace. The shared workspaces, interspersed with occasional meeting which cultivated interaction, dispelling gender barriers. People had control over the environment and connected to nature.   Project 3, merchandising offices, was layered in an anecdotal analogy of our current time. The essence of locale, the everyday transitory experience of pop culture, politics, is juxtaposed and expressed in the exterior and the interior of the contemporary architectural form.   The open plan layout fostered communication between various management levels. The staff and executives are placed in a common space that yields connectivity to various elements, people, work, and curated views of nature.    Project 4, Luncheonette - Cafeteria, form and materials are juxtaposed to harmonize with the surrounding buildings. Curated views for the diners, low-cost and low-maintenance finishes, daylight capture, and natural ventilation.    Project 5, Regeneration Upcycling - Eco-Park Botanical Garden. The project features a native 5-Tier Plantation, Information Center, Water Reservoir, and Renewable Energy. The information center is to disseminate ancient knowledge of native plant species. A walking track is created for the residents of staff housing in the vicinity.  Accessibility: Designed with accessibility considerations: accessible ramps and toilets.   Integrated Passive Design: The orientation of the buildings was of prime consideration while allocating functions. The plantation was done accordingly. These measures saved energy costs. In Project 2 alone, 20 tons of energy consumption were reduced just in HVAC loads. Similarly, in Projects 3 & 4, approx. 45 tons of energy.  Building Envelope:  Exterior Walls: Cavity walls form an insulating envelope in local clay burnt bricks. Glass Curtain Wall: Frameless double-glazed curtain wall & windows, consisting of low-e tinted glass on the outside and local clear glass on the inside. The curtain wall has operable windows with fly netting. The buildings are designed with local materials, and the local industry is primarily engaged to create a modern vernacular.  Energy Conservation: Low-energy-consuming light fixtures reduced energy loads. Eco-friendly, low water consumption fittings are used. Further recyclable materials are used.   Natural Daylight Use: The building design incorporates the use of abundant daylight by channeling it through various means. Sky lights are north-facing. Lighting load is reduced.  Microclimate: There were no trees at the site. Local flowering evergreen trees were proposed around the building perimeter, which would enhance the environment while helping to lower the ambient temperature.   Landscape Design: The contemporary landscape design around the building complex is based on low-cost and low-maintenance principles, echoing universal symbols. Local trees, native plants, and shrubs nurturing flora and fauna while consuming fewer resources were recommended.   Eco-Park Botanical Garden. Up-cycled industrial waste and by-products are used to achieve Carbon Credits.   Challenges: Remote location, low-cost, high design, and a lack of project execution expertise. Juxtaposition of different materials and detailing for extreme temperature fluctuations.	Design works commencing from 2013 to 2019. The Client, Interloop Limited, Pakistan, is a leading hosiery manufacturer and exports globally. The projects are located in the Industrial Park of Khurianwala, a peri-urban area, near the agricultural plains of Punjab, specifically in the vicinity of Faisalabad, Pakistan. The climate is semi-arid with minimal annual rainfall.  In 2013, Interloop Limited sought services for offices located at the Industrial Park.  At the time Project 1, Unordinary: Quality Assurance and Product Development Laboratory was under construction and it was transformed into a memorable place of work and joy. This laboratory is connected to the FYF production facility. This project that led to a series of projects in the future.  Project 2, Catalyst for Change: Product Development and Marketing Offices and the Landscape/Parking project was complete