c599b266-5f24-469f-8255-aa634f902a2f	Unknown	Unknown	haiyang_arch@163.com	Hybrid Yard——Courtyard No.7 of Xizongbu Hutong	IMPLEMENTED	SUBMITTED	SECTION_IV	Beijing	China	39.9042	116.4074	Courtyard No. 7, located in Xizongbu Hutong, Beijing, represents a thoughtful renovation of a historic residential compound dating back to the Qing Dynasty. Initially, this traditional courtyard had deteriorated due to severe overcrowding, fragmented ownership, and unauthorized or incompatible extensions. Situated merely 2.0 kilometers from the Forbidden City, Courtyard No. 7 had accommodated up to 15 households, with each family averaging only 26.1 square meters of living space. This overcrowding resulted in inadequate daylight, poor ventilation, and substandard living conditions. Additionally, infrastructural deficiencies, such as insufficient drainage and lack of accessible amenities, posed safety and health risks to residents. The renovation focused on transforming the overcrowded, dark, and isolated courtyard into a vibrant, livable, and community-oriented environment. Nonessential structures and extensions were carefully removed, reclaiming valuable open space. This dramatically improved natural light penetration and ventilation, significantly enhancing the indoor environmental quality and resident comfort. Modern amenities, notably indoor bathrooms, replaced dependency on distant public toilets, further elevating daily living standards. A significant aspect of the renovation addressed physical accessibility. Prior to renovation, the courtyard’s entrance featured a height difference of approximately 0.7 meters, complicating entry for elderly residents and those with mobility issues. The project introduced gentle ramps and levelled pathways, ensuring seamless access for elderly residents, wheelchairs, bicycles, and pedestrians, thus promoting inclusive usage. Additionally, lowered window sills were designed specifically to facilitate interaction between residents, particularly children, and their neighbors, fostering a sense of belonging and community engagement. Environmental resilience was also a cornerstone of the project. Originally, drainage problems regularly resulted in flooding during heavy rains. Regrading and discreetly installing modern drainage solutions successfully mitigated these issues. Additionally, the careful preservation of mature trees previously threatened by unplanned construction greatly contributed to improving the courtyard’s microclimate. The design cleverly integrates a new lightweight steel-framed corridor, whose roof gently curves around these preserved trees, symbolically intertwining built heritage with the natural environment. Furthermore, Courtyard No. 7 adopted adaptive reuse as a guiding sustainability principle. Original building materials, particularly the traditional grey bricks and roof tiles, were salvaged and reused to maintain the historical integrity of the architecture. New construction employed minimal, durable materials like steel and glass to minimize future maintenance needs, reduce construction waste, and preserve the site’s original character. To enhance community engagement while safeguarding residential privacy, the front section of the courtyard was converted into a tenant-operated cultural space, serving as a community living room. This mixed-use area hosts cultural activities and gatherings, creating vibrant interactions among residents and visitors, yet carefully maintains privacy for the primary residential spaces deeper within the compound. The original metal gate was replaced with a welcoming traditional wooden entry, inviting community interaction without compromising residents’ security. Throughout the renovation, residents actively participated in the design process, ensuring the project directly responded to their real-world needs and concerns. Decisions regarding spatial arrangement, amenity inclusion, and accessibility were made collaboratively, resulting in a highly tailored living environment. Ultimately, Courtyard No. 7 exemplifies an innovative approach to urban heritage revitalization, successfully balancing modern living standards, cultural preservation, environmental sustainability, and social inclusivity. By thoughtfully integrating community-oriented spaces, carefully enhancing physical accessibility, and adopting resilient, sustainable design practices, the project demonstrates a replicable model for improving quality of life within historical urban contexts, benefiting both residents and the broader community.	Courtyard No. 7, located in Xizongbu Hutong, Beijing, represents a thoughtful renovation of a historic residential compound dating back to the Qing Dynasty. Initially, this traditional courtyard had deteriorated due to severe overcrowding, fragmented ownership, and unauthorized or incompatible extensions. Situated merely 2.0 kilometers from the Forbidden City, Courtyard No. 7 had accommodated up to 15 households, with each family averaging only 26.1 square meters of living space. This overcrowding resulted in inadequate daylight, poor ventilation, and substandard living conditions. Additionally, infrastructural deficiencies, such as insufficient drainage and lack of accessible amenities, posed safety and health risks to residents. The renovation focused on transforming the overcrowded, dark, and isolated courtyard into a vibrant, livable, and community-oriented environment. Nonessential structures and extensions were carefully removed, reclaiming valuable open space. This dramatically improved natural light penetration and ventilation, significantly enhancing the indoor environmental quality and resident comfort. Modern amenities, notably indoor bathrooms, replaced dependency on distant public toilets, further elevating daily living standards. A significant aspect of the renovation addressed physical accessibility. Prior to renovation, the courtyard’s entrance featured a height difference of approximately 0.7 meters, co