, inviting community interaction without compromising residents’ security. Throughout the renovation, residents actively participated in the design process, ensuring the project directly responded to their real-world needs and concerns. Decisions regarding spatial arrangement, amenity inclusion, and accessibility were made collaboratively, resulting in a highly tailored living environment. Ultimately, Courtyard No. 7 exemplifies an innovative approach to urban heritage revitalization, successfully balancing modern living standards, cultural preservation, environmental sustainability, and social inclusivity. By thoughtfully integrating community-oriented spaces, carefully enhancing physical accessibility, and adopting resilient, sustainable design practices, the project demonstrates a replicable model for improving quality of life within historical urban contexts, benefiting both residents and the broader community.	See detailed description	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-04-18 13:00:00.604992	2026-04-18 13:00:00.604992	P45	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
c436cae1-7102-4ab4-a99c-564c0da0471e	Pieris Architects	Unknown	info@pierisarchitects.com	“(A).Maze” Residential Development	IMPLEMENTED	SUBMITTED	SECTION_I	Athens	Greece	37.9838	23.7275	The “(A).Maze” residential development in Glyfada, Greece, is a thoughtful and forward-looking architectural intervention that transforms a 1980s polikatoikia into a model for sustainable urban living. Commissioned by ΑΤΚΕ or GKD DEVELOPMENT MON. AE, the project exemplifies the potential of adaptive reuse in addressing key urban and environmental challenges. Rather than opting for demolition and new construction, the design team chose to preserve and upgrade the existing structure, a decision that anchors the project’s sustainability credentials and reflects a deep commitment to the United Nations Sustainable Development Goals (SDGs). At the core of the design is the ambition to align architecture with global efforts toward environmental responsibility, social wellbeing, and urban resilience. The project specifically contributes to SDG 11 (Sustainable Cities and Communities) by demonstrating how existing urban structures can be repurposed to meet modern living standards without further contributing to land use, material waste, or environmental degradation. Through this approach, “(A). Maze” maintains the original building’s embodied energy and avoids the carbon-intensive processes associated with demolition and new construction, thereby supporting SDG 13 (Climate Action). The architectural language of the development is one of restraint, clarity, and calm. The building’s dated exterior was replaced with a minimalist façade, characterized by a neutral palette of whites and greys that reflects the Mediterranean light while lending a timeless elegance. Vertical white shutters add both rhythm and functionality, acting as passive shading devices that reduce solar gain and improve energy efficiency—supporting SDG 7 (Affordable and Clean Energy) through passive design strategies. The integration of rooftop solar panels further reduces dependence on non-renewable energy sources, contributing to the transition toward clean energy infrastructure in urban environments. Internally, the project promotes wellbeing through careful spatial planning, natural light, ventilation, and access to shared outdoor amenities—directly addressing SDG 3 (Good Health and Well-being). A communal pool at the ground level acts as a sensory and social threshold, encouraging interaction among residents while offering a tranquil space for relaxation and physical activity. This feature not only enhances quality of life but also reflects an understanding of how built environments can positively influence mental and physical health. From a technological and engineering standpoint, the project aligns with SDG 9 (Industry, Innovation and Infrastructure) by applying innovative refurbishment strategies and advanced building systems to an existing structure. The collaboration between MV PC for structural analysis and Konstantinos Sourilas for mechanical systems ensured that the development met modern standards of performance without sacrificing the integrity or character of the original building. These partnerships enabled precise interventions that elevated the project’s structural and environmental capabilities. Material selection and construction methods were guided by the principles of SDG 12 (Responsible Consumption and Production). Instead of using newly manufactured materials for an entirely new build, the project reused what was already available, reducing demand on natural resources and limiting construction-related waste. All added materials and systems were chosen based on their durability, energy performance, and environmental impact, with a focus on longevity and low maintenance. The project’s urban impact also reinforces these sustainability goals. By maintaining the original footprint in an already dense neighborhood, “(A).Maze” avoids contributing to urban sprawl and supports a compact city model—one that prioritizes efficiency, walkability, and proximity to infrastructure. This approach is essential in cities like Athens, where land is limited and the environmental cost of unchecked growth is high. In summary, the “(A).Maze” residential development is more than just a design upgrade; it is a comprehensive statement on how architecture can respond intelligently and responsibly to global challenges. By choosing adaptive reuse over demolition, integrating renewable energy systems, and enhancing quality of life for its occupants, the project actively supports six key SDGs: SDG 3 (Good Health and Well-being), SDG 7 (Affordable and Clean Energy), SDG 9 (Industry, Innovation and Infrastructure), SDG 11 (Sustainable Cities and Communities), SDG 12 (Responsible Consumption and Production), and SDG 13 (Climate Action). Through its careful balance of form, function, and environmental ethics, “(A).Maze” offers a replicable model for sustainable residential development in urban contexts. It challenges the conventional notion that progress requires starting from scratch and instead illustrates how innovation and sustainability can emerge from thoughtful transformation of the existing built environment.	The “(A).Maze” residential development in Glyfada, Greece, is a thoughtful and forward-looking architectural intervention that transforms a 1980s polikatoikia into a model for sustainable urban living. Commissioned by ΑΤΚΕ or GKD DEVELOPMENT MON. AE, the project exemplifies the potential of adaptive reuse in addressing key urban and environmental challenges. Rather than opting for demolition and new construction, the design team chose to preserve and upgrade the existing structure, a decision that anchors the project’s sustainability credentials and reflects a deep commitment to the United Nations Sustainable Development Goals (SDGs). At the core of the design is the ambition to align architecture with global efforts toward environmental responsib