ucture. The collaboration between MV PC for structural analysis and Konstantinos Sourilas for mechanical systems ensured that the development met modern standards of performance without sacrificing the integrity or character of the original building. These partnerships enabled precise interventions that elevated the project’s structural and environmental capabilities. Material selection and construction methods were guided by the principles of SDG 12 (Responsible Consumption and Production). Instead of using newly manufactured materials for an entirely new build, the project reused what was already available, reducing demand on natural resources and limiting construction-related waste. All added materials and systems were chosen based on their durability, energy performance, and environmental impact, with a focus on longevity and low maintenance. The project’s urban impact also reinforces these sustainability goals. By maintaining the original footprint in an already dense neighborhood, “(A).Maze” avoids contributing to urban sprawl and supports a compact city model—one that prioritizes efficiency, walkability, and proximity to infrastructure. This approach is essential in cities like Athens, where land is limited and the environmental cost of unchecked growth is high. In summary, the “(A).Maze” residential development is more than just a design upgrade; it is a comprehensive statement on how architecture can respond intelligently and responsibly to global challenges. By choosing adaptive reuse over demolition, integrating renewable energy systems, and enhancing quality of life for its occupants, the project actively supports six key SDGs: SDG 3 (Good Health and Well-being), SDG 7 (Affordable and Clean Energy), SDG 9 (Industry, Innovation and Infrastructure), SDG 11 (Sustainable Cities and Communities), SDG 12 (Responsible Consumption and Production), and SDG 13 (Climate Action). Through its careful balance of form, function, and environmental ethics, “(A).Maze” off