5bd8221b-4a31-4c4d-8dc3-5097892e241d	Pieris Architects	Unknown	info@pierisarchitects.com	“Eco-city” Office Building	PLANNED	SUBMITTED	SECTION_I	Athens	Greece	37.9838	23.7275	The “Eco-city” Office Building, located in Marousi, Athens, is a cutting-edge development that redefines the role of the workplace in the 21st century. Designed with a total gross floor area of 53,260 m², the project integrates sustainability, advanced digital technologies, and human-centered design into a single architectural statement. Conceived as a landmark for innovation and environmental responsibility, Eco-city supports the transformation of the office from a functional space into a resilient and regenerative environment. The project’s design approach directly supports key Sustainable Development Goals (SDGs): SDG 3 (Good Health and Well-being), SDG 7 (Affordable and Clean Energy), SDG 9 (Industry, Innovation and Infrastructure), and SDG 13 (Climate Action). The building’s form is shaped to optimize daylight, air flow, and thermal comfort. Stepped facades on the northwest and northeast sides allow for the creation of accessible terraces and visual connections to surrounding green spaces. These design gestures establish a strong relationship between interior and exterior environments, creating a continuous experience of light, space, and nature. Generous glazing and open floor plates enhance transparency and flexibility, contributing to a workplace that promotes well-being, productivity, and collaboration. In line with SDG 3, these spatial qualities support mental health, comfort, and healthy routines for building users. A defining feature of Eco-city is the implementation of Information-Driven Design (IDD). This approach uses environmental data and digital simulation to shape the building’s orientation, envelope, and systems performance. By studying factors such as sun path, prevailing winds, and temperature fluctuations, the design team optimized energy efficiency and thermal behavior. These insights allowed for a passive design strategy that significantly reduces energy demand for lighting, heating, and cooling. Parametric modeling tools were employed to refine the building form for maximum performance. Real-time simulations tested ventilation patterns, daylight access, and material performance across the building’s lifespan, enabling the team to make well-informed, resilient design decisions. This data-driven, iterative design process ensures the building adapts to environmental conditions with precision—maximizing natural comfort and minimizing the need for artificial energy use. These efforts are fundamental to SDG 7, ensuring clean energy use through both passive strategies and the integration of efficient mechanical systems. Mechanical systems developed by ConAP complement the passive design with smart technologies, optimizing energy performance while maintaining user comfort. Responsive ventilation, heating, and cooling systems are designed to adjust dynamically to occupancy and weather conditions. The building structure, engineered by Civil Premises Design – Theodosiou Engineers, emphasizes efficiency, modularity, and minimal material waste, supporting long-term adaptability and ease of maintenance. Together, these systems reflect the goals of SDG 9, demonstrating how digital innovation and integrated engineering can elevate the sustainability and functionality of commercial buildings. In alignment with SDG 13, climate action is embedded into every layer of the project. The building’s carbon footprint is reduced through a careful selection of low-impact materials, energy-efficient systems, and passive environmental strategies. The green terraces and planted zones not only provide outdoor spaces for relaxation and informal meetings but also support local biodiversity and urban cooling. Rainwater management and landscape integration further contribute to the site’s ecological value, reinforcing the building’s role as a sustainable urban intervention. Beyond its physical features, Eco-city is designed to accommodate the future of work. Its flexible floor layouts support multiple working models—from collaborative hubs to quiet zones—adapting easily to evolving organizational needs. The planning strategy allows for modular leasing, future reconfiguration, and long-term operational sustainability. Ultimately, the Eco-city Office Building exemplifies the convergence of technology, ecology, and architecture. It is a model for how office buildings can be designed not just to meet current demands, but to anticipate and support the needs of future generations. Through the integration of bioclimatic design, advanced data tools, and a deep commitment to sustainability, Eco-city sets a new standard for intelligent, human-centered, and environmentally responsible urban development.	The “Eco-city” Office Building, located in Marousi, Athens, is a cutting-edge development that redefines the role of the workplace in the 21st century. Designed with a total gross floor area of 53,260 m², the project integrates sustainability, advanced digital technologies, and human-centered design into a single architectural statement. Conceived as a landmark for innovation and environmental responsibility, Eco-city supports the transformation of the office from a functional space into a resilient and regenerative environment. The project’s design approach directly supports key Sustainable Development Goals (SDGs): SDG 3 (Good Health and Well-being), SDG 7 (Affordable and Clean Energy), SDG 9 (Industry, Innovation and Infrastructure), and SDG 13 (Climate Action). The building’s form is shaped to optimize daylight, air flow, and thermal comfort. Stepped facades on the northwest and northeast sides allow for the creation of accessible terraces and visual connections to surrounding green spaces. These design gestures establish a strong relationship between interior and exterior environments, creating a continuous experience of light, space