c6bc7f1f-287c-4657-a1e8-1795f5e40df8	Pieris Architects	Unknown	info@pierisarchitects.com	“Gazi Vision”, Urban Hotel	IMPLEMENTED	SUBMITTED	SECTION_I	Athens	Greece	37.9778	23.7163	The Gazi Vision Urban Hotel is a contemporary reinterpretation of the city hotel—rooted in adaptive reuse, environmental consciousness, and a bold architectural identity. Located in the culturally rich and ever-evolving neighborhood of Gazi in central Athens, the project is a direct response to the changing dynamics of urban life. Once a disused and outdated office building, the structure has been transformed into a fully renovated hotel comprising 20 compact, thoughtfully designed studio and one-bedroom flats, intended to accommodate short- and medium-term stays for travelers, digital nomads, and professionals.  Gazi, a district with deep postindustrial roots, is now a thriving hub for arts, nightlife, and creative industries. The neighborhood’s dense mix of industrial relics, contemporary culture, and vibrant street life offered the ideal context for a hospitality project that could capture and reinterpret the area’s raw, energetic character. Gazi Vision does not merely insert a building into this urban narrative—it contributes to it, establishing a dialogue between the past and the future, tradition and reinvention.  The architectural intervention begins with a commitment to reuse. Rather than demolishing the existing building, the design strategy centered on preserving the original structure and adapting it to a new program. This approach not only minimized waste and carbon emissions but also respected the embodied energy of the original construction—offering a powerful example of sustainable urban regeneration in practice. The new exterior features stacked, fluid volumes wrapped in a barcode-inspired aluminum façade. This distinctive skin, at once abstract and referential, reinforces the building’s identity and establishes a bold presence within the urban fabric. It offers a striking visual contrast while subtly referencing the coded systems of contemporary consumer culture and digital connectivity, both of which characterize modern urban life.  Internally, the hotel prioritizes comfort, acoustic insulation, daylight, and spatial efficiency. Each unit is designed to optimize its compact footprint while offering a high standard of living—equipped for self-sufficiency yet tied into the social and cultural landscape outside. Common areas are minimized in favor of maximizing private comfort, while certain shared amenities and rooftop access provide moments of communal interaction and urban views. The interiors employ neutral, durable materials and clever storage solutions, creating a sense of calm amid the bustling environment of Gazi.  Energy performance and sustainability are integral to the project. The mechanical design, developed by KHM Ltd, utilizes efficient HVAC systems tailored to the building’s occupancy patterns, reducing operational energy use. Thermal insulation, natural ventilation strategies, and efficient glazing all contribute to a comfortable indoor environment while lowering the need for artificial conditioning. The structure, reviewed and upgraded by structural engineer Alexandros Karageorgos, was reinforced and adapted to meet current safety and performance standards without full reconstruction.  Construction, carried out by REKAT Constructions, followed a tight urban logistics plan, minimizing disruption to the surrounding neighborhood—a key factor given Gazi’s pedestrian-oriented streets and constant activity. The hotel’s compact footprint, limited vehicle access, and support for walkability tie it into larger urban strategies for density, mixed-use development, and sustainable mobility.  While not conceived as a statement on sustainability alone, the project aligns naturally with a number of global development goals. It supports SDG 11 (Sustainable Cities and Communities) by repurposing existing infrastructure and enhancing urban quality without contributing to sprawl. By conserving embodied carbon and reducing waste through adaptive reuse, it contributes to SDG 13 (Climate Action). The use of smart building systems and efficient materials reflects the aims of SDG 9 (Industry, Innovation and Infrastructure), while the healthy, well-lit, and acoustically comfortable indoor spaces promote SDG 3 (Good Health and Well-being)—particularly relevant in dense, noisy urban centers.  In an era where cities face increasing pressure to grow sustainably, Gazi Vision provides a replicable model of urban transformation. It demonstrates that even small-scale projects can have a meaningful impact—revitalizing a single building while contributing to a broader narrative of environmental responsibility, cultural continuity, and design innovation. The project merges architectural expression with practical functionality, elevating the idea of the city hotel into something more than temporary accommodation: a compact urban home that engages with its context and envisions a more adaptive, sustainable future.	The Gazi Vision Urban Hotel is a contemporary reinterpretation of the city hotel—rooted in adaptive reuse, environmental consciousness, and a bold architectural identity. Located in the culturally rich and ever-evolving neighborhood of Gazi in central Athens, the project is a direct response to the changing dynamics of urban life. Once a disused and outdated office building, the structure has been transformed into a fully renovated hotel comprising 20 compact, thoughtfully designed studio and one-bedroom flats, intended to accommodate short- and medium-term stays for travelers, digital nomads, and professionals.  Gazi, a district with deep postindustrial roots, is now a thriving hub for arts, nightlife, and creative industries. The neighborhood’s dense mix of industrial relics, contemporary culture, and vibrant street life offered the ideal context for a hospitality project that could capture and reinterpret