environment while lowering the need for artificial conditioning. The structure, reviewed and upgraded by structural engineer Alexandros Karageorgos, was reinforced and adapted to meet current safety and performance standards without full reconstruction.  Construction, carried out by REKAT Constructions, followed a tight urban logistics plan, minimizing disruption to the surrounding neighborhood—a key factor given Gazi’s pedestrian-oriented streets and constant activity. The hotel’s compact footprint, limited vehicle access, and support for walkability tie it into larger urban strategies for density, mixed-use development, and sustainable mobility.  While not conceived as a statement on sustainability alone, the project aligns naturally with a number of global development goals. It supports SDG 11 (Sustainable Cities and Communities) by repurposing existing infrastructure and enhancing urban quality without contributing to sprawl. By conserving embodied carbon and reducing waste through adaptive reuse, it contributes to SDG 13 (Climate Action). The use of smart building systems and efficient materials reflects the aims of SDG 9 (Industry, Innovation and Infrastructure), while the healthy, well-lit, and acoustically comfortable indoor spaces promote SDG 3 (Good Health and Well-being)—particularly relevant in dense, noisy urban centers.  In an era where cities face increasing pressure to grow sustainably, Gazi Vision provides a replicable model of urban transformation. It demonstrates that even small-scale projects can have a meaningful impact—revitalizing a single building while contributing to a broader narrative of environmental responsibility, cultural continuity, and design innovation. The project merges architectural expression with practical functionality, elevating the idea of the city hotel into something more than temporary accommodation: a compact urban home that engages with its context and envisions a more adaptive, sustainable future.	See detailed description	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-04-18 13:00:39.923528	2026-04-18 13:00:39.923528	P158	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
014580ae-2320-43bf-bbda-3100309506f5	Design Guidelines Research, Development and Implementation Association	Burcu Büken Cantimur; Doğa Erdem; İnci Olgun; Z. Hande Kayan; Kumru Çılgın; Özge Türkü Mert; N. Papatya Seçkin; Serim Dinç	inci.olgun@gmail.com	Dumlupinar Urban Design Guide	IMPLEMENTED	APPROVED	SECTION_II	Balikesir	Turkey	39.6484	27.8826	The Urban Design Guide prepared for Dumlupınar Neighborhood represents a place-based strategy for open public spaces and architecture, positioning urban design as a critical framework for shaping resilient, inclusive, and culturally grounded built environments. Focusing on the historic center of Balıkesir Province, the guide advances an urban design approach that integrates architectural heritage, microclimatic sensitivity, and participatory place-making within a holistic framework aligned with the Sustainable Development Goals (SDGs). At its core, the project centers on the reinterpretation of open spaces and neighborhood fabric through architectural typologies and street interface design. By analyzing building orientation, typological continuity, and parcel-scale uses, the guide introduces design principles that maintain morphological coherence while adapting to contemporary sustainability imperatives. Prioritizing passive climate control strategies, the integration of local materials, repair-oriented techniques and architectural sensitivity to energy performance, the Guide assumes a guiding role in the restoration of historic buildings and their adaptation to evolving functions. The Guide emphasizes the critical role of architecture in enhancing the quality of public spaces through rich spatial interfaces. Ground-floor active facade strategies are designed to animate street views, support small-scale economic activities, and promote neighborhood-level resilience. In doing so, the built environment is approached not as a static heritage asset, but as a dynamic, evolving cultural entity capable of supporting climate-adaptive and socially inclusive urbanism. Through the preservation and revitalization of historic facades, the enhancement of walkability, and the visibility of local businesses, the Guide aims to increase the cultural and spatial visibility of Dumlupınar, preserving neighborhood identity through the display of architectural heritage and enabling community-based cultural tourism that supports the local economy. Urban design interventions focus on the creation of legible, human-scaled public spaces through the coordination of architectural rhythms, street sections, vegetated landscapes, and microclimate-responsive materials. The Guide aims to encourage spatial ownership by integrating shaded gathering areas and edible landscaping with the built environment. Design principles are articulated through a set of "codes" that prioritize the adaptive reuse, restoration, and passive conservation of historic buildings, alongside small-scale architectural gestures that harmonize with broader urban systems.  In conclusion, the Dumlupınar Urban Design Guide offers a replicable model that seeks to reconcile environmental, cultural, and spatial priorities. It serves as a reference that strengthens cross-scalar integration among architects and urban designers. It demonstrates how the careful design of the built environment— from architectural detail to urban form—can serve as an effective tool for advancing the SDGs within dense, heritage-rich urban contexts.	The Urban Design Guide prepared for Dumlupınar Neighborhood represents a place-based strategy for open public spaces and architecture, positioning urban design as a critical framework for shaping resilient, inclusive, and culturally grounded built environments. Focusing on the historic center of Balıkesir Province, the guide advances an urban design approach that integrates architectural heritage, microclimatic sensitivity, and participatory place-making within a holistic framework aligned with the Sustainable Development Goals (SDGs)