tion of historic buildings, alongside small-scale architectural gestures that harmonize with broader urban systems.  In conclusion, the Dumlupınar Urban Design Guide offers a replicable model that seeks to reconcile environmental, cultural, and spatial priorities. It serves as a reference that strengthens cross-scalar integration among architects and urban designers. It demonstrates how the careful design of the built environment— from architectural detail to urban form—can serve as an effective tool for advancing the SDGs within dense, heritage-rich urban contexts.	See detailed description	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-04-18 13:00:00.604992	2026-04-18 13:00:00.604992	P46	Burcu Büken Cantimur; Doğa Erdem; İnci Olgun; Z. Hande Kayan; Kumru Çılgın; Özge Türkü Mert; N. Papatya Seçkin; Serim Dinç	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
f755967f-44f8-489c-8823-de85fccfea7d	Pieris.Architects	Constantinos Pieris, Stella Pieri, Valentinos Skiadas	info@pierisarchitects.com	“Casa Solace” Residence	PLANNED	APPROVED	SECTION_I	Kythnos	Greece	37.3833	24.4167	Casa Solace is situated on the serene island of Kythnos, Greece, and is designed to blend the island’s rich architectural traditions with minimalist principles. Drawing inspiration from the island’s historic barns and cells, the residence harmonizes with its natural surroundings and promotes a deeper connection to the land. Crafted from local stone and wood, the house evokes a sense of timelessness, rooted in the region’s heritage, while incorporating modern design to meet the needs of today’s sustainable lifestyle. The design prioritizes simplicity and functionality, with the home built primarily from locally sourced stone and timber. The thick stone walls, typical of Kythnian architecture, provide thermal mass, naturally regulating the temperature inside the home and reducing the need for artificial heating and cooling. This passive design strategy is a key feature of the home, supporting sustainability and minimizing its environmental impact. Casa Solace embraces a minimalist design ethos that creates a calm and undistracted living space. Large wooden pergolas extend from the main structure, creating shaded outdoor areas for relaxation while preserving the sense of openness and connection to the environment. These pergolas invite a lifestyle centered around outdoor living, enabling residents to engage with the landscape while enjoying panoramic views of the hills and the Aegean Sea. Windows and doors are strategically placed to optimize natural light and offer unobstructed views of the surrounding landscape. Traditional wooden shutters are used to control light and airflow, further promoting natural ventilation. The design allows for a seamless flow between interior and exterior spaces, reinforcing the connection to nature. Every element, from the architectural layout to the materials used, serves to deepen the occupants’ engagement with the natural world, promoting mindfulness and fostering a sense of peace. Sustainability is embedded throughout Casa Solace. The use of recycled and reused materials, alongside responsibly sourced local stone and wood, reduces the carbon footprint of construction. The passive solar design, which takes full advantage of natural light and the island’s climate, minimizes energy consumption. Solar panels will also be incorporated to generate renewable energy, further enhancing the home’s energy efficiency. These efforts not only reduce the environmental footprint but also support the local economy by utilizing local materials and labor. In addition to these sustainable practices, water management strategies are a key part of the design. Rainwater harvesting and water-efficient fixtures will reduce the home’s water consumption, contributing to a more sustainable living environment. The residence’s landscaping also enhances local biodiversity, with green roofs and permeable paving that encourage the growth of native plants and support the local ecosystem. The design of Casa Solace aligns with several United Nations Sustainable Development Goals (SDGs). SDG 3 (Good Health and Well-being) is promoted through the home’s serene and natural environment, which encourages mental and physical well-being. SDG 9 (Industry, Innovation, and Infrastructure) is supported by the integration of innovative, energy-efficient technologies and sustainable building practices. The residence’s minimalist design and the use of locally sourced materials also reflect SDG 12 (Responsible Consumption and Production), ensuring that the project minimizes waste and energy consumption throughout its construction and lifespan. By creating a home that promotes a deeper connection to nature, Casa Solace embodies the principles of SDG 11 (Sustainable Cities and Communities). The project contributes to sustainable development by using local materials and resources responsibly, fostering a sustainable community that aligns with the natural rhythms of the island. Finally, SDG 15 (Life on Land) is addressed through the landscaping, which supports local biodiversity and integrates seamlessly with the natural surroundings, ensuring that the residence complements and enhances the environment. In conclusion, Casa Solace is a residence that goes beyond simple architecture—it is a space designed to foster mindfulness, well-being, and a deep connection to the natural world. By combining local traditions with sustainable practices, the project creates a living space that is in harmony with its surroundings, offering its occupants not just a home, but a sanctuary. The careful integration of passive design, natural materials, and eco-friendly technologies ensures that the residence is not only a retreat for the present but also a model for future-conscious living.	Casa Solace is situated on the serene island of Kythnos, Greece, and is designed to blend the island’s rich architectural traditions with minimalist principles. Drawing inspiration from the island’s historic barns and cells, the residence harmonizes with its natural surroundings and promotes a deeper connection to the land. Crafted from local stone and wood, the house evokes a sense of timelessness, rooted in the region’s heritage, while incorporating modern design to meet the needs of today’s sustainable lifestyle. The design prioritizes simplicity and functionality, with the home built primarily from locally sourced stone and timber. The thick stone walls, typical of Kythnian architecture, provide thermal mass, naturally regulating the temperature inside the home and reducing the need for artificial heating and cooling. This passive design strategy is a key feature of the home, supporting sustainability and minimizing its environmental impact. Casa Solace embraces a minimalist design ethos that creates a calm and undistracted living