41d6f08d-1c24-488f-8cc6-defde2cc813e	Pieris.Architects, Liontos & Associates, IT KV CONSULTING ENGINEERS, NeaPolis Lighting	Constantinos Pieris, Stella Pieri, Pieros Pieris, Margarita Varla, Ilektra Kefalloniti, Romina Ruci	info@pierisarchitects.com	“Olivia Eterna” Urban Hotel	IN_PROGRESS	APPROVED	SECTION_I	Athens	Greece	37.9848	23.7283	Olivia Eterna is an urban hospitality project underway in the historic heart of Omonia, Athens. Designed as a small-scale but forward-thinking hotel, the project repurposes a disused office building into a sustainable, community-conscious destination. Through this adaptive reuse, Olivia Eterna aims to revitalize neglected infrastructure while supporting a broader shift toward responsible, integrated urban tourism.  The hotel emerges as a response to a pressing urban need: how to accommodate growing tourism without contributing to gentrification, loss of local identity, or environmental degradation. Positioned at the intersection of tradition and innovation, Olivia Eterna proposes a model for hospitality that is rooted in context, inclusive by design, and grounded in ecological responsibility.  A central inspiration behind the project is the olive tree—long associated with Athens and the goddess Athena. This symbol of peace, wisdom, and continuity is interpreted both materially and metaphorically in the building’s design. The façade features wooden laser-cut panels engraved with olive leaf motifs. These serve not only as symbolic ornamentation but as shading devices that reduce solar gain and soften the building’s presence on the street. The motif carries through to the interiors, where organic textures and natural materials offer a sense of grounding and calm.  Instead of demolishing and rebuilding, the design team has opted for an adaptive reuse strategy that preserves the existing structure. This reduces construction waste, retains the embodied carbon of the original building, and reflects an ethical commitment to reuse over replacement. The hotel retains its urban footprint while significantly improving energy performance and visual character, demonstrating how thoughtful architectural intervention can be both sustainable and inspiring.  Inside, the spatial arrangement reflects biophilic principles—inviting daylight, fresh air, and greenery into the guest experience. Materials have been selected for their sensory richness and environmental performance, creating a restful atmosphere that contrasts with the intensity of the city outside. The limited number of rooms allows for an intimate guest experience, with personal attention and quiet luxury replacing the anonymity of larger hotel formats.  Sustainability extends beyond structure and materials. Olivia Eterna’s operational systems include energy-efficient HVAC, smart lighting, water-saving fixtures, and responsible waste management. Many furnishings are either repurposed or locally crafted, while amenities and products are chosen with a focus on ecological footprint. This approach aligns the project with contemporary circular economy principles and reinforces its long-term commitment to responsible consumption and production.  Olivia Eterna also engages proactively with the social context of Omonia. Rather than isolating itself from its surroundings, the hotel integrates into the local economy by sourcing goods and services from neighborhood artisans, vendors, and partners. This strengthens community ties and encourages cultural exchange between guests and residents. Guests are invited to explore the area through curated local experiences, promoting a deeper, more respectful kind of tourism.  Unlike unregulated short-term rentals that often strain housing supply and alter neighborhood dynamics, Olivia Eterna operates within a formal hospitality framework. It contributes to the regulated growth of the city’s tourism sector while preserving housing for locals and upholding municipal planning standards. In this way, it supports a healthier urban ecosystem and reflects a more sustainable trajectory for city-based accommodation.  The hotel also incorporates intelligent technologies that improve energy management without compromising ambiance. NeaPolis Lighting has designed a scheme that supports circadian rhythms, promotes rest, and reduces energy consumption. Smart systems automate lighting and climate control, maintaining comfort efficiently and discreetly.  What sets Olivia Eterna apart is its holistic integration of design, culture, and sustainability. It demonstrates that even modest-scale developments can drive meaningful urban transformation when guided by clear values and thoughtful planning. The project leverages design to create connection—between past and present, building and street, traveler and place.  As Athens continues to redefine its urban core, Olivia Eterna positions itself as a new type of city hotel: one that honors its setting, nurtures its guests, and contributes to the collective vitality of the neighborhood. By working with, rather than against, the rhythms and textures of its environment, the project serves as a quiet but confident model for future hospitality development in dense, heritage-rich urban areas.	Olivia Eterna is an urban hospitality project underway in the historic heart of Omonia, Athens. Designed as a small-scale but forward-thinking hotel, the project repurposes a disused office building into a sustainable, community-conscious destination. Through this adaptive reuse, Olivia Eterna aims to revitalize neglected infrastructure while supporting a broader shift toward responsible, integrated urban tourism.  The hotel emerges as a response to a pressing urban need: how to accommodate growing tourism without contributing to gentrification, loss of local identity, or environmental degradation. Positioned at the intersection of tradition and innovation, Olivia Eterna proposes a model for hospitality that is rooted in context, inclusive by design, and grounded in ecologica