t to responsible consumption and production.  Olivia Eterna also engages proactively with the social context of Omonia. Rather than isolating itself from its surroundings, the hotel integrates into the local economy by sourcing goods and services from neighborhood artisans, vendors, and partners. This strengthens community ties and encourages cultural exchange between guests and residents. Guests are invited to explore the area through curated local experiences, promoting a deeper, more respectful kind of tourism.  Unlike unregulated short-term rentals that often strain housing supply and alter neighborhood dynamics, Olivia Eterna operates within a formal hospitality framework. It contributes to the regulated growth of the city’s tourism sector while preserving housing for locals and upholding municipal planning standards. In this way, it supports a healthier urban ecosystem and reflects a more sustainable trajectory for city-based accommodation.  The hotel also incorporates intelligent technologies that improve energy management without compromising ambiance. NeaPolis Lighting has designed a scheme that supports circadian rhythms, promotes rest, and reduces energy consumption. Smart systems automate lighting and climate control, maintaining comfort efficiently and discreetly.  What sets Olivia Eterna apart is its holistic integration of design, culture, and sustainability. It demonstrates that even modest-scale developments can drive meaningful urban transformation when guided by clear values and thoughtful planning. The project leverages design to create connection—between past and present, building and street, traveler and place.  As Athens continues to redefine its urban core, Olivia Eterna positions itself as a new type of city hotel: one that honors its setting, nurtures its guests, and contributes to the collective vitality of the neighborhood. By working with, rather than against, the rhythms and textures of its environment, the project serves as a quiet but confident model for future hospitality development in dense, heritage-rich urban areas.	See detailed description	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-04-18 13:00:39.923528	2026-04-18 13:00:39.923528	P155	Constantinos Pieris, Stella Pieri, Pieros Pieris, Margarita Varla, Ilektra Kefalloniti, Romina Ruci	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
29467343-b447-463d-9c42-21c7eb1b9b92	Pieris.Architects, Elissaios Papatzanakis, G. ARCHONTAKIS TECHNIKI IKE, Dr. Agis M. Papadopoulos, GREENWAYS Landscape Architecture Chanikian ltd, NeaPolis Lighting, Homes S.A.	Constantinos Pieris, Stella Pieri, Pieros Pieris, Lydia Sklavou, Myrto Gatou, Evi Katsikoudi	info@pierisarchitects.com	“Tella Thera” Nature-inspired Resort	IN_PROGRESS	APPROVED	SECTION_I	Chania	Greece	35.5138	24.018	Tella Thera is an intimate eco-resort currently under construction in the rolling hills near Chania, Crete. Designed as a refuge for mindful living and deep connection to nature, the resort embodies a new paradigm of hospitality—one that blends environmental respect, cultural sensitivity, and architectural subtlety. With just 21 thoughtfully designed villas and suites, it offers guests a private, tranquil setting in harmony with the rugged Mediterranean landscape.  The project embraces the terrain’s natural features, carefully embedding the buildings within the hillside to minimize environmental disturbance and visual impact. The architecture adopts a restrained, elegant language inspired by local building traditions but expressed through contemporary techniques and materials. Locally sourced stone and timber provide authenticity and durability, while lime-based renders and natural finishes contribute to healthy indoor environments and sustainability. The low-density site planning protects existing vegetation and prioritizes natural drainage patterns, ensuring that the development feels like an extension of the land rather than an imposition on it.  Natural light and ventilation are fundamental design drivers, reducing reliance on energy-consuming mechanical systems. Each villa is oriented to maximize views of the olive groves and Aegean Sea beyond, and large openings facilitate cross-breezes that cool interiors naturally. Green roofs planted with native flora help insulate the buildings and foster biodiversity, allowing the resort to blend seamlessly into the surrounding landscape. These elements create a sensory-rich experience that invites guests to engage with the environment on multiple levels—sight, smell, touch, and sound—evoking a calm and restorative atmosphere.  Beyond the architectural and landscape design, the resort offers a holistic approach to wellness and hospitality. Programs focused on mindfulness, yoga, and traditional healing practices will be available to guests, encouraging physical, mental, and emotional renewal. These activities, paired with the peaceful setting and thoughtful spatial layout, create an environment that promotes relaxation and balance, counteracting the stresses of modern life. Interiors are designed with natural materials and simple, elegant detailing that prioritize comfort and longevity over fleeting trends.  The resort’s operational model is built around sustainability and resource efficiency. Advanced energy systems—including solar panels, high-performance insulation, and earth-coupled ventilation—help minimize the carbon footprint and reduce energy demand. Water conservation strategies are rigorously applied through rainwater capture, greywater recycling, and efficient irrigation systems, which are critical given the region’s semi-arid climate. Waste management follows strict protocols to reduce landfill contributions, incorporating composting and recycling alongside policies that eliminate single-use plastics. Building automation and smart technologies optimize resource use while ensuring guest comfort and convenience.  Tella Thera places strong emphasis on supporting and integrating with the local community. Construction and furnishing utilize regional craftsmen and suppliers, reinforcing traditional skills and reducing transport emissions. An on-site organic garden provides fresh produce for the resort’s kitchens, complemented by close relationships with nearby farmers and food artisans. These connections foster a farm-to-table approach that honors local culinary heritage and offers guests authentic gastronomic experiences.  In addition to its environmental and operational goals, the resort serves as a cultural hub that connects visitors with Crete’s rich traditions. Workshops, exhibitions, and events will provide opportunities for guests to explore local crafts, music, and cuisine, deepening their understanding of the island’s heritage and fostering respectful cultural exchange. This engagement is designed to create lasting memories and encourage stewardship of the place rather than superficial tourism.  Throughout construction, care is taken to safeguard the site’s ecological integrity. Measures are in place to prevent soil erosion, protect native species, and limit noise and dust pollution, ensuring the surrounding environment remains undisturbed. The project team works closely with local authorities and environmental experts to maintain compliance with best practices and regional sustainability objectives.  Tella Thera represents a forward-looking example of Mediterranean tourism development that seeks to balance guest experience with ecological and cultural responsibility. Rather than pursuing growth for its own sake, the project aims to regenerate the land, support local livelihoods, and offer visitors an experience grounded in place and purpose. It is a living model for the future of luxury travel—one where elegance and environmental stewardship coexist, creating spaces that heal both people and planet.	Tella Thera is an intimate eco-resort currently under construction in the rolling hills near Chania, Crete. Designed as a refuge for mindful living and deep connection to nature, the resort embodies a new paradigm of hospitality—one that blends environmental respect, cultural sensitivity, and architectural subtlety. With just 21 thoughtfully designed villas and suites, it offers guests a private, tranquil setting in harmony with the rugged Mediterranean landscape.  The project embraces the terrain’s natural featu