ar panels, high-performance insulation, and earth-coupled ventilation—help minimize the carbon footprint and reduce energy demand. Water conservation strategies are rigorously applied through rainwater capture, greywater recycling, and efficient irrigation systems, which are critical given the region’s semi-arid climate. Waste management follows strict protocols to reduce landfill contributions, incorporating composting and recycling alongside policies that eliminate single-use plastics. Building automation and smart technologies optimize resource use while ensuring guest comfort and convenience.  Tella Thera places strong emphasis on supporting and integrating with the local community. Construction and furnishing utilize regional craftsmen and suppliers, reinforcing traditional skills and reducing transport emissions. An on-site organic garden provides fresh produce for the resort’s kitchens, complemented by close relationships with nearby farmers and food artisans. These connections foster a farm-to-table approach that honors local culinary heritage and offers guests authentic gastronomic experiences.  In addition to its environmental and operational goals, the resort serves as a cultural hub that connects visitors with Crete’s rich traditions. Workshops, exhibitions, and events will provide opportunities for guests to explore local crafts, music, and cuisine, deepening their understanding of the island’s heritage and fostering respectful cultural exchange. This engagement is designed to create lasting memories and encourage stewardship of the place rather than superficial tourism.  Throughout construction, care is taken to safeguard the site’s ecological integrity. Measures are in place to prevent soil erosion, protect native species, and limit noise and dust pollution, ensuring the surrounding environment remains undisturbed. The project team works closely with local authorities and environmental experts to maintain compliance with best practices and regional sustainability objectives.  Tella Thera represents a forward-looking example of Mediterranean tourism development that seeks to balance guest experience with ecological and cultural responsibility. Rather than pursuing growth for its own sake, the project aims to regenerate the land, support local livelihoods, and offer visitors an experience grounded in place and purpose. It is a living model for the future of luxury travel—one where elegance and environmental stewardship coexist, creating spaces that heal both people and planet.	See detailed description	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-04-18 13:00:39.923528	2026-04-18 13:00:39.923528	P156	Constantinos Pieris, Stella Pieri, Pieros Pieris, Lydia Sklavou, Myrto Gatou, Evi Katsikoudi	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
7f2fb2b2-a377-4f62-b6e3-2424913c2fc8	Pieris.Architects	Pieris.Architects	info@pierisarchitects.com	Metropolitan Seaplane Port, MSPA	PLANNED	APPROVED	SECTION_I	Elefsina	Greece	38.0432	23.54	The Metropolitan Seaplane Port of Attica (MSPA) is a transformative proposal for sustainable infrastructure at the intersection of land, sea, and civic life. Conceived not merely as a transit point but as a regenerative landmark, the MSPA reclaims Elefsina’s industrial waterfront and repositions it as a space of ecological restoration, cultural memory, and civic engagement.  Sited on a prominent pier that extends into the Saronic Gulf, the MSPA redefines the typology of the port terminal. Rather than a corridor of movement and control, it becomes a spatial experience—fluid, intuitive, and welcoming. Its circular building traces an arc along the waterfront, opening toward the horizon and guiding visitors through an architecture that is at once directional and contemplative. This simple geometric form becomes the project’s organizing principle, framing views and creating a rhythm of approach, passage, and arrival.  Instead of relying on monumentality, the MSPA generates presence through atmosphere. At the heart of the terminal, a double-height atrium welcomes visitors with natural light, timber textures, and a floating “sky garden” of native Mediterranean plants. These suspended vessels reference both the maritime history of Elefsina and the healing potential of nature. The garden offers a moment of calm—an oasis that sets the tone for a different kind of travel experience, one rooted in connection rather than haste.  The building’s material palette emphasizes warmth, sustainability, and tactility. Timber, stone, and glass work in concert to blur interior and exterior thresholds. The design employs passive cooling, daylight harvesting, and natural ventilation to reduce environmental impact and enhance user comfort. This commitment to low-energy operation is embedded not only in the technical systems but in the sensory experience of the space—filtered light, natural textures, and the movement of air and water.  Circulation is clear and intuitive, reinforcing a sense of ease. Public and operational zones are seamlessly integrated, allowing for functional flow while offering opportunities for pause and interaction. Shaded terraces, outdoor decks, and planted courtyards create moments of engagement with the sea and the city, making the terminal feel open, breathable, and grounded.  Beyond its architectural language, the MSPA is a civic project. It tells the story of Elefsina’s layered identity—mythic, industrial, and now transitional. The design reclaims a site long associated with degradation and neglect and reframes it as a place of memory, reconnection, and community life. Through this act of transformation, the port becomes a symbol of resilience and reimagining.  Strategically, the MSPA also supports regional mobility and economic development. It links Attica to Greece’s broader island network, enabling intermodal travel that is low-impact, accessible, and well-integrated. Its placement in Elefsina expands the reach of tourism and transportation beyond Athens, helping rebalance economic activity across the region.  Equally important, the port is designed to be used by more than just travelers. It becomes a shared civic space—a place where residents, visitors, students, and families can gather. Walkways, rest areas, event spaces, and gardens invite everyday use, ensuring that the terminal becomes a familiar and inclusive part of Elefsina’s public realm.  Landscape design is woven into the fabric of the project. Plantings are native, drought-tolerant, and ecologically relevant, chosen for their ability to provide shade, scent, texture, and seasonal variation. From the lavender-scented paths to the olive-planted courtyards, nature is experienced as part of the journey, not a backdrop to it.  Finally, the MSPA is conceived with adaptability and long-term resilience in mind. Modular construction techniques, lightweight materials, and flexible internal layouts allow the building to evolve in response to changing technologies, environmental pressures, and community needs.  In sum, the Metropolitan Seaplane Port of Attica presents a new model for infrastructure—one that is human-scaled, ecologically responsive, and socially inclusive. It redefines the port not just as a node of transportation but as a platform for memory, connection, and renewal.	The Metropolitan Seaplane Port of Attica (MSPA) is a transformative proposal for sustainable infrastructure at the intersection of land, sea, and civic life. Conceived not merely as a transit point but as a regenerative landmark, the MSPA reclaims Elefsina’s industrial waterfront and repositions it as a space of ecological restoration, cultural memory, and civic engagement.  Sited on a prominent pier that extends into the Saronic Gulf, the MSPA redefines the typology of the port terminal. Rather than a corridor of movement and control, it becomes a spatial experience—fluid, intuitive, and welcoming. Its circular building traces an arc along the waterfront, opening toward the horizon and guiding visitors through an architecture that is at once directional and contemplative. This simple geometric form becomes the project’s organizing principle, framing views and creating a rhythm of approach, passage, and arrival.  Instead of relying on monumentality, the MSPA generates presence through atmosphere. At the heart of the terminal, a double-height atrium welcomes visitors with natural light, timber textures, and a floating “sky garden” of native Mediterranean plants. These suspended vessels reference both the maritime history of Elefsina and the healing potential of nature. The garden offers a moment of calm—an oasis that sets the tone for a different kind of travel experience, one rooted in connection rather than haste.  The building’s material palette emphasizes warmth, su