d social gap in the implementation of urban public policies, impacting an improvement in the quality of life and comprehensive development of people who exercise their right to the city.	See detailed description	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-04-18 13:00:21.972357	2026-04-18 13:00:21.972357	P119	Arq EFRAIN MIGUEL CALLE SARZURI	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
45b92def-9fbd-4224-a755-8c46875980ab	BiosArqs Estudio de Arquitectura, Habitat para la Humanidad México A.C, ONG Cuidemos.org	Arq. Brenda Guillén, Arq. Rolando Guillén	biosarqs@gmail.com	Casa Melani	IMPLEMENTED	APPROVED	SECTION_V	Cintalapa	Mexico	16.6917	-93.7189	CASA MELANI Chiapas, Mexico  The earthquake of September 7, 2017, one of the most intense recorded in Mexico in the last century, wreaked havoc on society, causing immense emotional and material devastation, leaving thousands of families homeless. In response to this profound crisis, "Casa Melani" emerged from the urgent need to reconstruct a dignified living space for a family of four—a mother, father, and their daughters—who tragically lost their entire home and patrimony. This forced them to seek refuge for several months in an improvised tent, with only a few beds, minimal clothing, and bare necessities, enduring suboptimal conditions and health risks due to harsh weather.  The project is meticulously designed with bioclimatic characteristics that integrate ecotechnological systems, prioritizing the comfort of its inhabitants. The architectural program was carefully adapted to the local way of living and the specific needs of the family, aiming to foster their sense of ownership over the spaces. The resulting identity of the dwelling is characterized by the honest expression of its materials across two distinct structures, connected by an exterior portico that ensures the spaces are well-ventilated and naturally illuminated.  Wind circulation is maximized by the strategic disposition of both buildings and the precise placement of openings at each end, generating effective cross-ventilation. This design intelligently mitigates the extreme local climate, achieving a comfortable interior temperature while maintaining abundant natural light throughout the day.  The formal aesthetic of the project stems from its inherent functionality and the apparent use of materials, which reveal the development and design of its structures. Its constructive system is notable for being replicable, economical, and easy to maintain, making it a highly valuable model for future housing initiatives.  A cornerstone of the Casa Melani project was the active participation of family members—cousins, nieces, nephews, neighbors, and the owners themselves—in the construction process. Guided by a team of professionals, the project utilized an auto-construction method, incorporating technical-practical workshops in masonry, material fabrication, and carpentry. This approach sought to reclaim the concept of "social production of housing," aiming for a profound community impact that fostered collective ownership of this endeavor, transforming it not merely into a house, but into a true HOME.  Currently, the cultivation of corn and squash on the Casa Melani site further strengthens its proposition as a "Productive and Resilient Home," underscoring its capacity to provide not only shelter but also contribute to the family's food security and self-sufficiency.	CASA MELANI Chiapas, Mexico  The earthquake of September 7, 2017, one of the most intense recorded in Mexico in the last century, wreaked havoc on society, causing immense emotional and material devastation, leaving thousands of families homeless. In response to this profound crisis, "Casa Melani" emerged from the urgent need to reconstruct a dignified living space for a family of four—a mother, father, and their daughters—who tragically lost their entire home and patrimony. This forced them to seek refuge for several months in an improvised tent, with only a few beds, minimal clothing, and bare necessities, enduring suboptimal conditions and health risks due to harsh weather.  The project is meticulously designed with bioclimatic characteristics that integrate ecotechnological systems, prioritizing the comfort of its inhabitants. The architectural program was carefully adapted to the local way of living and the specific needs of the family, aiming to foster their sense of ownership over the spaces. The resulting identity of the dwelling is characterized by the honest expression of its materials across two distinct structures, connected by an exterior portico that ensures the spaces are well-ventilated and naturally illuminated.  Wind circulation is maximized by the strategic disposition of both buildings and the precise placement of openings at each end, generating effective cross-ventilation. This design intelligently mitigates the extreme local climate, achieving a comfortable interior temperature while maintaining abundant natural light throughout the day.  The formal aesthetic of the project stems from its inherent functionality and the apparent use of materials, which reveal the development and design of its structures. Its constructive system is notable for being replicable, economical, and easy to maintain, making it a highly valuable model for future housing initiatives.  A cornerstone of the Casa Melani project was the active participation of family members—cousins, nieces, nephews, neighbors, and the owners themselves—in the construction process. Guided by a team of professionals, the project utilized an auto-construction method, incorporating technical-practical workshops in masonry, material fabrication, and carpentry. This approach sought to reclaim the concept of "social production of housing," aiming for a profound community impact that fostered collective ownership of this endeavor, transforming it not merely into a house, but into a true HOME.  Currently, the cultivation of corn and squash on the Casa Melani site further strengthens its proposition as a "Productive and Resilient Home," underscoring its capacity to provide not only shelter but also contribute to the family's food security and self-sufficiency.	See detailed description	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-04-18 13:00:31.097334	2026-04-18 13:00:31.097334	P131	Arq. Brenda Guillén, Arq. Rolando Guillén	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
