ecd69e80-9ad4-4a03-995d-55eb18616c0b	UCA	L Rodriguez	lrrodriguez@uca.edu.sv	Adaptable Habitat Laboratory TC-V-2024	PLANNED	SUBMITTED	SECTION_V	San Salvador	El Salvador	13.6929	-89.2182	High-rise condominium with up to 5 floors, for mixed use, on a plot with an area of 16,818 m2 (1.68 ha) next to another plot of river protection land measuring 19,471 m2 (1.9 ha), separated by public railway land next to a receiving body. A proposal has also been made to expand the Texincal recreational area into a theme park similar to Catalunya en Miniatura, which has been named ‘El Salvador Chiquito’ on a plot of land measuring 36,250 m2. Both proposals, the residential condominium and the park expansion, have been developed through planimetric and altimetric analysis based on the articles of El Salvador's regulatory framework and the application of SUDS (Sustainable Urban Drainage Systems) and RAPS (Safe Pedestrian Environmental Networks) concepts.	High-rise condominium with up to 5 floors, for mixed use, on a plot with an area of 16,818 m2 (1.68 ha) next to another plot of river protection land measuring 19,471 m2 (1.9 ha), separated by public railway land next to a receiving body. A proposal has also been made to expand the Texincal recreational area into a theme park similar to Catalunya en Miniatura, which has been named ‘El Salvador Chiquito’ on a plot of land measuring 36,250 m2. Both proposals, the residential condominium and the park expansion, have been developed through planimetric and altimetric analysis based on the articles of El Salvador's regulatory framework and the application of SUDS (Sustainable Urban Drainage Systems) and RAPS (Safe Pedestrian Environmental Networks) concepts.	See detailed description	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-04-18 13:00:21.972357	2026-04-18 13:00:21.972357	P112	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
399f00da-1249-400e-987e-cc233e6e3b5d	Arquiteta e urbanista	Anna Candida Valentim	annavst29@gmail.com	Cidade Delas: Safer urban spaces for girls and women	IMPLEMENTED	APPROVED	SECTION_V	Manhumirim	Brazil	-20.358367	-41.95892	The booklet Cidade Delas: safer urban spaces for girls and women, seeks to inform about the problems related to the design, uses and occupation of public space that cross the social representations of gender, because like him, the city is also a social construction.	The booklet presents five elements of the right to the city and women's lives and how\r\nthe absence or violation of each element that makes up the right to the city can affect the\r\nwomen's urban experiences, namely:\r\n Right to adequate housing;\r\n Right to quality democratic management;\r\n Right to adequate public services;\r\n Right to urban planning;\r\n Right to urban mobility.\r\nIn addition, articles of the federal constitution are indicated, decrees that guarantee the\r\nwomen's rights to the city, information, curiosities and quotes from authors about the right to the city.	Despite all the achievements of women in society and the advances of their own, the city is still being planned and produced from the perspective of patriarchy. Urban planning does not take into account the demands of the population regarding the inclusion of a plurality of races, genders and social classes, which, in this way, influence the use of space and urban design.\r\nThe urban violence suffered by women goes beyond criminality, these situations are even more reinforced by poorly planned urban spaces, such as abandoned land, precarious public lighting, unsecured parks, poorly planned bus routes, among others. The way the city is planned directly interferes with women's lives, therefore, when the planning does not include them, the space becomes unsafe.\r\nThe city is a reflection of society, which is why it is important to grant inclusive, accessible spaces that encourage feminist struggles in favor of gender equality, that allow the female place in public spaces to be free, circulations and routes to be unlimited and safe.	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	IFF3	Anna Candida Valentim	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
64df8c85-2150-4feb-b9cf-646984b9b113	Secretaria Executiva dos Mananciais	Alonso López	alonsolopez@prefeitura.sp.gov.br	Urbanização Alto da Alegria	IMPLEMENTED	APPROVED	SECTION_V	São Paulo	Brazil	-23.543931	-46.631567	Social housing on Alto da Alegria community by social buildings and urbanization areas of the hydrogaphic system of the main water reservoir of the city of São Paulo.	The intervention in Alto da Alegria community participates in the objectives common to the Program of the Secretarie of Manancial, witch refers to the sanitation of the hydrographics systen of the main water reservoir of São Paulo city but also the urban qualification of precarious settlements and the definitive housing assistance to families removed from areas of geological risk.	The Alto da Alegria community has more than a thousand families with their homes built, over the years, on top of an illegal rubble dump around an environmental protection area in a high-grade geological hazard setting. The removal of these houses will give way to a residential of social interest that solves social issues of access to housing, elimination of risk of landslide and urbanization of environmental protection areas.	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	IFF35	Elisabete França, Maria Teresa Fedeli, Alonso López, Mario Biselli, Arhtur Katchborian	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
609e1260-8498-4bf9-afa1-4b6c9d5943ea	Prefeitura Municipal de Sobral	Yvo Gabriel Sousa Galvão	yvogalvao@sobral.ce.gov.br	Alto do Cristo	IMPLEMENTED	APPROVED	SECTION_V	Sobral	Brazil	-3.670293	-40.314005	The project includes the restoration of the Cristo monument, street urbanization around it and new living spaces for the community, promoting accessibility and appreciation of the neighborhood itself.	Located in an area previously marked by social vulnerability and violence, Alto do Cristo, had its requalification based on the creation of spaces for interaction, accessibility and appreciation of the neighborhood itself. The project, which aimed to reclassify one of the main postcards of the city, benefited not only the surrounding residents, but the entire population of Sobral, which now has 20.500 m² of reclassified public space, with a panoramic view of the entire city.	With the aim of revitalizing the area and bringing more visibility, lighting and security to the local population, the requalification project that transformed the old ravine that housed the Christ monument into a leisure area with more than 20.000 m², also provided an inclusive urbanization and safe housing for surrounding residents by working topography, accessibility and drainage through gardens between its levels, in order to reinforce resilience and adaptation to climate change.	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	LDP71	Antônio Carlos Campelo Costa; Marcely Luíza Barreira Portela; Marília Gouveia Ferreira Lima.	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
181a33e2-c1f3-4494-890a-28aa4c83b7b8	UNISINOS - Universidade do Vale do Rio dos Sinos	Ana Carolina Borile	anacarolina_borile@outlook.com	Agroecological Pavilion - Urban agriculture as an agent of socio-environmental transformation	IMPLEMENTED	APPROVED	SECTION_V	Porto Alegre	Brazil	-30.029726	-51.229265	The agroecological pavilion can be a solution to various problems in cities: it mitigates malnutrition, saves natural resources, generates employment and income, promotes health, and reduces the impact on soil.	In a context of scarcity of natural resources, climate change, and a society heavily hit by food insecurity, broadening access and supply of food with less environmental impact and seeking to reduce waste should be priorities. The pavilion combines the uses of conscious and sustainable urban agricultural production, the commercialization of low-cost food, and uses aimed at education and professionalization in an equipment line on the premises of sustainable architecture, open to the community.	Urban agriculture emerges as a possible solution that answers interrelated issues in urban systems, such as waste management, health, land use, reducing distances between production and consumption, the use of loose spaces in the city, combating food insecurity, and the generation of occupational activity with consequent income generation. In addition, it is able to directly intervene in the adaptation of cities to climate change and sanitary crises, such as the current COVID-19 pandemic.	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	IFF15	Ana Carolina Borile	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
9050edcc-7597-40e1-b6ab-0079d6224dfa	até arquitetura	Henrique Rodrigues Freires de Lima	contato.atearquitetura@gmail.com	An Urban Farm: Architecture and Scarcity	IMPLEMENTED	APPROVED	SECTION_V	São Paulo	Brazil	-23.543931	-46.631567	The project is made up of a network of semi-autonomous units in a steel structure, focused on work, education, research, commerce and culture. The set was designed to be replicated in a scalable way.	"An Urban Farm: Architecture and Scarcity" portrays a problem that had already been resolved and which has abruptly reappeared in the periphery of Brasil: hunger. From the perspective of a marginalized region of São Paulo, hunger is treated as a form of scarcity, social insecurity and a portrait of a period marked by a pandemic that intensified latent inequalities in the global south. In this way, the work proposes multipurpose structures in an unused floodplain area aimed at Jardim Piratininga.	"An Urban Farm: Architecture and Scarcity" seeks to strengthen the local community, support economic growth and ensure effective social assistance, in the form of a self-sustainable, inclusive and replicable management model. In addition, it seeks to provide the necessary tools to face hunger and poverty in the peripheries of Brasil through the community's own means of production, aimed at the community and the city as a whole.	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	IFF4	Henrique Rodrigues Freires de Lima	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
c9a4599b-eec9-4608-928b-b2ab03cb5f73	Natureza Urbana	Breno Pilot	breno@naturezaurbana.net	Lake Jará Urban Park	IMPLEMENTED	APPROVED	SECTION_V	Juriti	Brazil	-2.1528	-56.090733	The project aims the development of public use on the banks of the lake, focusing on controlling the advance of the urban spot over its limits and raising the population's awareness of its relevance.	The project's strategy started with the implementation of an environmental park on a public area, structured in three zones: The Urban Zone, with socio-cultural activities, expands the offer of public spaces in the city. The Connection Zone creates a transition space between the zones, formed by a forest region with the proposition of contemplative uses. In The Lake Zone we proposed uses related to water and ecotourism, in addition to various spaces for contemplation.	The concept of the buildings incorporates elements of vernacular, indigenous and riverside architecture. The proposal of a modular structure using local building techniques, enabled the creation of integrated spaces adapted to the natural environment. The work incorporated renewable materials and local techniques, considering the entire life cycle of the building including its use, maintenance and recycling.	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	IFF16	Pedro Lira (Coordination); Camila Sanches, Giulia Corsi e Victor Navarra (team).	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
73d9f304-e9d6-473e-b7e8-e79cc5e1545e	Univeridad del Bio-Bio, Concepción, Chile	Beatriz Piderit	mpiderit@ubiobio.cl	Future Edu Space(FES) Prototype	IMPLEMENTED	APPROVED	SECTION_V	Concepción	Chile	-36.827393	-73.05037	The Future Edu Space (FES) classroom has been envisaged to promote and inspire the creation of creative, sustainable, and comfortable educational spaces. It has been designed to transform learning experiences, considering many Chilean schools in the Bio-Bío region have deficient infrastructure that critically affects the student community. \r\n\r\nFES used an interdisciplinary approach, linking areas as diverse as architecture, design, education, and engineering. Public and private entities contributed to specific solutions, with the region’s key actors involved In a highly participative process. Teachers, principals, and school boards took part, giving their vision for future classrooms. Psychologists, educators, and specialists in pedagogical innovation provided guidelines about how the space had to foster 21st-century skills. The resulting space acts as a mediator between teaching practices and student learning, with the potential to develop creative and innovative skills while stimulating active participation, interaction, and communication. \r\n\r\nThis prototype has a demonstrational role for the region’s architecture and design offices, wood companies, and builders about schools and technology transfer. It is a result of the project, “Future Edu Space: Generation of Technological Capacities to Build State-of-the-art Sustainable Educational Space from the Biobío Region”, an initiative financed by the Bio-Bío Regional Government’s Innovation for Competitivity Fund (FIC-R).	The Future Edu Space (FES) prototype is an educational space that combines flexibility, adaptability, and variety in its use. Its design was developed based on interdisciplinary and collaborative work involving actors from education, design, architecture, construction, and wood industrialization. The BIM method was used throughout the design process, combined with virtual reality tools.\r\n\r\nTo break with the traditional classroom layout, it has been designed using a square neutral-style floor plan, which allows using the classroom in different senses and creating multiple educational scenarios. It has a total surface area of 100m2, with a central area of 70m2 for 35 students.\r\n\r\nIts structure comprises two active sidewalls to support the pedagogical activities. One holds furniture for individual learning activities, and the other, which can also store furniture, has a large interactive board. It also has an acoustic wall that folds inward to extend activities to an adjoining space. The final wall is glazed, connecting with the outside to take pedagogical activities further still.\r\nPassive strategies are included to generate appropriate environmental conditions: temperature (thermal envelope), air quality (crossed ventilation), acoustics (foldable acoustic doors and partition), and daylight (lucarnes and view windows).\r\n\r\nIt considers the design of flexible furniture to provide an easily adjusted multipurpose learning space. For example, changing from a presentation space to one for participation or group work.\r\n\r\nFES is designed with a wooden prefabricated system, to foster wood-based architecture in the education area. The geometry is obtained from a construction technology capacity and modulation process. A 1.2m x 3m CLT (Cross Laminated Timber) module, which is easy to transport and meets the requirements of the architectural space, is used for the sidewalls using the manufacturing skills of local wood companies.\r\n\r\nThe educational space’s structure comprises CLT frames that form part of the active sidewalls, with GLT (Glued Laminated Timber) beams for the ceiling’s caisson structure. CLT wall braces are placed between the frames. The walls do not have an indoor coating, leaving the same CLT pine wall. The outdoor covering is a thermally modified tongue and groove.\r\n\r\nThe FES prototype is conceived as a unitary system that can be repeated and joined together to generate new options. Three variants are proposed: EDU SPACE FRONT, EDU SPACE NEXT, and EDU SPACE UP. These are organized by two main elements: the essential indoor space module, and an independent ring surrounding it, forming an intermediate space. The prototype and its variants inspire projecting and building new ways of developing school architecture.	This initiative is aligned with the following goals: \r\nGOAL 3 GOOD HEALTH AND WELL-BEING: “Ensure healthy lives and promote well-being for all at all ages”. \r\nThe FES prototype considers a biophilic design since its incorporation in educational spaces has been emphasized in recent studies, especially after the pandemic, to promote children’s health and well-being. For this reason, it integrates a visual connection with the outside through glazed walls to see the sky and nature. It fosters sensorial stimuli, using a wooden covering with its warmth, texture, and insulation capacities. Thanks to the lucarnes, it generates dynamic lighting that stimulates the Circadian cycle, which is key for the student’s well-being and behavior. All these elements allow restoring the positive experience of nature in built spaces, to attain better psychological and social well-being for our children.\r\n\r\nGOAL  4 QUALITY EDUCATION: ”Ensure inclusive and equitable quality education and promote lifelong learning opportunities for all”.\r\nThis prototype looks to provide a solution to the specific issues Chilean school infrastructure has. Many public schools are in disrepair, directly impacting the country’s most vulnerable students who are their main users. FES contributes to improving classroom quality, providing a level playing field for learning environments, and eliminating gaps between different socioeconomic groups.\r\nDilapidated school infrastructure has repercussions on deficient environmental comfort, and thereby, student well-being. FES guarantees the conditions for a healthy environment and provides quality infrastructure, along with access to an integrative education. It allows creating better conditions for innovative teaching practices that are supported by the classroom’s spatial setting.\r\nThe proposal gives the local Bio-Bio population, educators, designers, wood construction companies, and architects, a demonstration space that combines innovative solutions.\r\n\r\nGOAL  9 INDUSTRIES, INNOVATION, and INFRASTRUCTURE: “Build resilient infrastructure, promote inclusive and sustainable industrialization, and foster innovation”. \r\nFES encourages innovation and the transfer of state-of-the-art models for school infrastructure, as it is linked with the construction industry through innovative construction systems. Modular prefabricated architecture has been evolving in its efficiency and sustainability, permitting a quick, adaptable, light, and quality construction process.\r\nFES is projected as a solid wood construction system and promotes wood-based architecture in the education area, looking to drive innovation among the wood companies of the Bio-Bío region, where the project is based. CLT construction systems allow prefabricating several-story buildings using horizontal and vertical structuring modules. The design’s geometry was projected using the technological construction skills requirements of local wood companies, aligned with the search for innovation in the educational setting.	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	IFF12	Beatriz Piderit (FES Project Director), Maureen Trebilcock (FES Project Coordinator), Alejandra Bancalari (Design Architect), Valentina Chandia (Design Architect), Carlos Coronado (Design Architect), Javiera Leighton  (editor)	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
8545ecb7-bf82-4cff-91c0-412c94eaa4fd	Instituto de Arquitectos do Brazil (IAB)	Ruben Otero Marquez	rubenoterom@gmail.com	Chácara Flórida	IMPLEMENTED	APPROVED	SECTION_V	São Paulo	Brazil	-23.543931	-46.631567	The urban project of Chácara Florida has as main objectives the basic sanitation, the depollution of the existing waterways, which serve as a supply of drinking water to the city of São Paulo, and the elimination of serious geological risk. For this, it is planned to create parks around the streams and on the bank of the dam, which today receive sewage directly from the surrounding houses, containments in the risk areas and the construction of small houses to resettle the residents affected by the work.	The Chácara Florida reurbanization Project main idea lies in the fact that in Latin America we are daily faced with social injustice. This extends to the point the most needed are forced to move into areas such as riversides, wetlands or risky hills, which are amongst our design area. Throughout a participative process, the design aims to not only be a role model of intervention of vulnerable areas, but also to prove that is possible to overcome poverty in addition to sustainable architecture.	Through the urbanization project of Chácara Florida, the sanitation of the more than 3000 families that reside in the place will be carried out, in addition to the depollution of the dam that is part of the drinking water supply system of the city of São Paulo, which suffers from water crises every year. Linked to sanitation, the favela will undergo a major urbanization process with the execution of parks and public facilities, including a market and public garden that will serve as an incentive for sustainable consumption.	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	IFF37	Responsible architects: Ruben Otero and Monica Drucker. Project team: Elisabete França, Maria Teresa Fedeli, Vanessa Padiá, Mariana Guimarães, Juliana Pedroso, Rodrigo Camara, Nicole Milko, Pedro Flosi Trama, Marise Jacobsen, Matheus Alves, Bruna Bonfim and Angelica Di Febbo.	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
f738e8e3-740d-4b30-a0eb-cb055606fe05	Igor de Vetyemy Arquitetura	Igor de Vetyemy	igordevetyemy@gmail.com	Re-bridge	IMPLEMENTED	APPROVED	SECTION_V	Rio de Janeiro	Brazil	-22.902094	-43.128199	Linear park under the Rio-Niteroi bridge with hotels, restaurants, culture facilities, social housing, sustainable mobility, generation of clean energy, and support for recuperating the marine life.	The Guanabara Bay is crossed by a colossal and obsolete structure used only by cars, the Rio-Niteroi bridge. This proposal creates a linear park under the bridge with supporting program including hotels, restaurants, social housing and culture facilities. The project involves sustainable urban mobility, generation of clean energy, mitigation of the housing deficit close to Rio de Janeiro`s city center, creation of spaces for leisure and interaction; and support for recuperating the marine life.	The project ensures healthy lives and promotes well-being for all by creating the possibility of active means of transport to connect the neighbour cities in more inclusive, and sustainable ways. It ensures sustainable management of water and promotes sustainably use of the marine resources with research facilities to work on the recuperation of the bay waters, once house for hundreds of dolphins and whales. It uses the waves, wind and sea tides to generate sustainable energy for public use.	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	IFF2	Igor de Vetyemy, Mariana Barbosa, Rogério Chieza, and Felipe Calazans	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
e6438750-140f-4010-ab0f-41c10b290259	Council of Architecture and Urbanism of Rio Grande do Sul (CAU/RS)	Tiago Holzmann da Silva	gabineteathis@caurs.gov.br	No House without a Bathroom | Nenhuma Casa Sem Banheiro	IMPLEMENTED	APPROVED	SECTION_V	Canoas	Brazil	-29.920059	-51.179004	The project aims to meet basic sanitation needs related to water use, hygiene and proper disposal of sewage by building sanitary facilities in households where there are no or inadequate toilets.	In the midst of the Covid 19 pandemic, the Council of Architects conceived the "No Home without a Bathroom" project to mobilize public authorities around the urgent need for investment in household sanitation. The inter-institutional cooperation between institutions of public interest, governments and institutions of architects supported the implementation of the initiative and some emergency actions to reduce the sanitation deficit in 11 thousand houses in Rio Grande do Sul (IBGE, 2012). To date, 458 families have benefited from the initiative.	The main purpose of the project is to improve inequitable access to public goods and services and adequate housing, and to bring about resolutions on essential health measures necessary to ensure the lives of the population and future generations (SDGs 3, 10, 11, 16). The project also promotes reducing the impact on access to water in times of drought or flooding through the construction of water storage facilities and the proper disposal of household sewage (SDGs 6, 13). Finally, the Architects' Council has offered courses for municipal managers and technicians to promote knowledge sharing on the means to implement housing programs in Brazilian cities (SDG 17).	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	LDP37	Council of Architecture and Urbanism of Rio Grande do Sul (CAU/RS), Association of Architects and Engineer of Canoas (SEACA), State Department of Housing (SOP/RS), Municipality of Canoas, Secretary of Urban Development and Housing (SMDUH).	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
3b521d88-422c-4aa7-8153-2fc6851ce135	Ubuntu Arquitetura	Vitor Daher	daher.arquitetura@gmail.com	SL House	IMPLEMENTED	APPROVED	SECTION_V	Valinhos	Brazil	-22.970559	-46.995831	Casa SL is a single-family dwelling built with prefabricated materials and designed to embrace the sun, wind, light and surroundings through passive bioclimatic design.	The design of the SL house has been thought out so that it can interact in the best possible way with the terrain and its landscape.\r\nThe social area (ground floor) explores more intensely the relationship with the terrain, while the intimate area (first floor) creates a more intense visual relationship with the landscape and is oriented according to the position of the sun. \r\nThe rotation between the two blocks emerges as a result of the strategies adopted and creates spaces for conviviality and contemplation.	6-Capture and use of rainwater for irrigation and cleaning.\r\n6- Low-flow faucets, showerheads, and toilets to achieve water savings.\r\n7- 100% of the energy used by all structures on the property (2 houses, leisure pavilion, swimming pool, vegetable garden and workers house) is produced by solar panels on the roof of the SL house.\r\n8- Hiring local labour.\r\n9- Production and use of prefabricated parts reducing rubbish and increasing the efficiency of production.\r\n10- Passive bioclimatic design allowing the House to stay between 19ºC and 24ºC without the use of air conditioning.	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	LDP61	Vitor Daher, Pablo Mauleon	600	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
dc8aac47-79db-4f75-b13a-cdd741ae1b23	Prefeitura Municipal de Sobral; Hidrobotânica Ambiental.	Yvo Gabriel Sousa Galvão	yvogalvao@sobral.ce.gov.br	Pajeú Filtering Gardens	IMPLEMENTED	APPROVED	SECTION_V	Sobral	Brazil	-3.670293	-40.314005	The gardens benefit the aquatic ecosystem and the quality of life of citizens residing around the area by improving water quality in addition to landscaping the Pajeú Park.	Considered the largest built in public areas in Brazil, the Biofiltering Gardens of Pajeú Park have 1.19 km of linear gardens, totaling 12,000 m², acting as a natural set of sewage treatment through aquatic plants and substrates, without using chemical products, through a system of natural and constructed wetlands, operating by gravity, promoting the local fauna and flora, in addition to cleaning up the Pajeú creek and Lagoa da Fazenda.	In addition to the main objective of improving water quality and subsequent depollution of Riacho Pajeú and Lagoa da Fazenda using Nature-Based Solutions (NBS), the project included the urbanization of the surroundings of the stream, providing a safe, inclusive, public space accessible and green while strengthening resilience and climate adaptation capacity, restoring a formerly degraded area, reducing the effects of droughts, floods and loss of biodiversity in Pajeú Park.	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	LDP73	Bruno Ary Ferreira; Úrsula Priscyla Santana Nóbrega.	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
b8ec51f8-d25c-4d02-8b49-9ca6c7325808	Universidad de Guadalajara/ Laboratorio Nacional de Vivienda y Comunidades Sustentables.	Fernando Córdova Canela	fernando.cordova@cuaad.udg.mx	Ecotechnological Center for Innovation, Dialogue and Learning for Sustainable Habitat (CEIDAHS in Spanish)	IMPLEMENTED	APPROVED	SECTION_V	Guadalajara	Mexico	20.662066	-103.363739	Ecotechnological Center for Innovation, Dialogue and Learning for Sustainable Habitat (CEIDAHS in Spanish) will be a space for society, together with technicians and specialists, to plan, manage and carry out innovation projects to improve their living conditions and become involved in the decision-making processes together with other actors.	The CEIDAHS project is designed so that different actors related to habitat management can dialogue, learn, and collaboratively generate knowledge on eco-technologies; bioclimate; participatory governance methodologies; development of public policy instruments in housing and innovation; incubation and strengthening of social entrepreneurship; and technological tools related to industry 2.0. The CEIDAHS aims to contribute in the medium and long term to overcoming social backwardness, territorial inequities, and inequalities in fair access to habitat through forms of public action that consider the systemic dimension of the problems in line with the SDGs. The building will have green spaces designed to generate hygrothermal comfort for users, green roofs for experimenting with urban agriculture, solar chimneys, and passive air conditioning. This design will reduce the use of artificial air conditioning by 45%.	SDG 7. The formation of new technological development and energy efficiency practices can improve the quality and affordability of housing. In turn, socio-technical transitions and the application of knowledge in the domestic and neighborhood environment in relation to bioclimatic building materials and accessible eco-technology will help reduce the consumption of fossil fuels and promote energy savings.The CEIDAHS constitutes this space for dialogue between different actors to learn, analyze and apply eco-technologies at the household and neighborhood scale.\r\nSDG 11. Inclusive urbanization requires increasing the capacity for action and planning from the communities in conjunction with the actors who manage and study the territory through knowledgeable dialogue. CEIDAHS as a meeting and learning space will enhance the collaboration of different actors in the development of new policies, processes, and actions that promote energy efficiency, renewable energy production, and waste management to significantly reduce the environmental footprint of cities.	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	IFF34	Fernando Córdova Canela, Hiram Eduardo Urías Barrera, Carlos Emmanuel Aguilar Méndez, Abril Casas Cervantes, Belén Olaya García	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
69ec5a0a-f1de-4df5-85ce-8e6d713eed05	School of Architecture, Planning and Design (SAP+D), Mohammed VI Polytechnic University	Prof. Hassan Radoine	hassan.radoine@um6p.ma	Integrated approach  of sustainable territorial development, case of the villages of Nouaji and Tanmirt	IMPLEMENTED	APPROVED	SECTION_III	Benguerir	Morocco	32.240335	-7.953709	The integrated project of the villages of Nouaji-Tanmirt is a living laboratory of a territorial development approach. It aims to improve the socio-economic conditions of the local population while carrying out urban regeneration and a community-based approach.	The Villages of Nouaji and Tanmirt are located in Benguerir, Morocco, an area that is a model of innovative projects, less than 3 km from the new green city and the Mohammed VI Polytechnic University.\r\nTo support this dynamic, the integrated approach consisted of an urban regeneration of these villages and an improvement of the population's living conditions through the creation of income-generating activities in crafts and agriculture.\r\nThis approach is based on territorial integration by connecting the villages to the city, sectoral integration and finally a participatory approach with the skateholders	This project addresses the following SDGs:\r\n- SDG 4: quality education\r\nBeyond the program for the promotion of school life, we consider that the educational ecosystem, school and university, are the departure point for territorial transformation\r\n- SDG 8: decent work and economic growth\r\nThrough the creation of intra-village and inter-urban economic flows (villages - green city) and through the strengthening of the agricultural and artisanal fabric.\r\n- SDG 11: sustainable city and community\r\nThrough social cohesion, the creation of a green grid and the rehabilitation of a heritage of clay houses.\r\n- SDG 17: partnerships to achieve objectives\r\nThrough a collective intelligence of several partnerships and capacity building offers between the university, the community and the city's stakeholders.	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	IFF62	•\tHassan Radoine •\tIsmail Hammoumi •\tKaoutare Amini Alaoui •\tMohammed Reda Lazreg •\tFouad Maytoussi	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
9361078f-dcd7-43b1-987b-b173de93e7cb	Natureza Urbana	Breno Pilot	breno@naturezaurbana.net	Terminal and Urban Park in São Luís	IMPLEMENTED	APPROVED	SECTION_V	São Luís	Brazil	-2.529973	-44.300193	The project promoted the renovation of an area, focusing on a new park and bus terminal. The Natureza Urbana office imagined new ways of thinking public spaces in an area full of social inequality.	The project comprises a strip from Avenida Vitorino Freire to the Bus Terminal, which is part of the Ring Road around the Old Center. The reorganization of the square and the bus terminal promotes better distribution of commercial points and the elimination of existing physical and visual barriers. The redesign of the space creates small squares with equipment and urban furniture, promoting ideal conditions for the creation of a vibrant public space.	Throughout the project’s development, society and public organizations were involved through participatory processes and workshops. Social surveys and analysis of the pre-existing situation of merchants were carried out, with the aim of developing a proposal that would embrace all local demands and needs. The social surveys directed the location of the commercial points, their typologies, training for merchants and the ways of acting and appropriating the public space.	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	LDP24	Manoela Machado e Pedro Lira (Coordination); Camila Reis e Camila Sanches (Project Leaders); Jalia Marini, Juliana Yoshida, Juliette Tellier, Renata Peres, Raquel Araruna, Renan Ferreira, Roberto Zocchio e Fernando Botton (team).	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
e88c5a03-783e-44cb-9b7b-a27b1cfd2af3	Casa Cidade Arquitetura e Urbanismo	Renata Fragoso Coradin	renata.coradin@casacidade.com.br	Mata Virgem Urban Park	IMPLEMENTED	APPROVED	SECTION_V	São Paulo/Diadema	Brazil	-23.6865	-46.6234	The Mata Virgem Urban Park consists in the development of new leisure and connective structures with better walking conditions, surrounding a preservation area, which provides well being of the inhabitants	The “Mata Virgem” Urban Park is located in a site that ensures environmental preservation between the cities of São Paulo and Diadema. There is an elevated route that surrounds a stream source and connects two areas with 26 meters of level difference, with stairs that provides sights and pleasant walking conditions. On the higher level, there is a deck that extends the sidewalk, creating a belvedere with panoramic view, living areas and public leisure equipment.	Located in a socially deficient neighborhood, the “Mata Virgem” Urban Park improves the well-being of the residents of the area qualifying public spaces with leisure structures for all ages and genres. It’s main route is a staircase that connects two cities whilist shortening daily paths, preserving natural conditions and local spring waters. These aspects of the project are aligned with the third of the seventeen sustainable development goals.	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	LDP65	Renata Fragoso Coradin; Amanda Ramos Silva Santos; Caroline de Souza Moura; Felipe Maike Lima de Souza Oliveira; Giovanna Sambugaro; Ian dos Santos Araújo; Juliana Bizzi Radi de Ponti; Juliana Nunes Watanabe; Letícia Ferreira; Soraya Mayumi Tamate Palmeira de Paula; Suellen Cristina Pivato; Paulo Cássio de Moraes Gonçalves; Guilherme Eduardo Araujo de Souza; Alexandre Horiye Ferreira; Daniela Arduino Dezidera Horiye; Joice Lopes; Elisabete França; Ana Clara Gurgel; Fernanda Souza Silva; Maria Teresa Cardoso Fedeli; Mayra Rodrigues; Vanessa Padiá de Souza	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
9c3c1ef2-65fc-45cc-b366-6703085d84c1	Natureza Urbana	Breno Pilot	breno@naturezaurbana.net	Iguaçu National Park	IMPLEMENTED	APPROVED	SECTION_V	Foz do Iguaçu	Brazil	-25.538124	-54.585437	The project is part of the studies for the concession aimed at providing public services to support visitation, modernization, operation, and maintenance of tourist services in Iguaçu National Park.	The project included territorial planning of the park's attraction poles, identifying their vocation and opportunities for enhancing each one. Along with expanding tourism services, new visitor support infrastructure and requalification of existing public use assets and equipment were planned. The main premise was to redefine the park visit experience by providing sustainable interventions for visitors to have greater contact and connection with nature and new experiences.	The project guidelines were based on innovation in public use management, accessibility, sustainability, and increased visitation with the motto "park for all". Sustainability was addressed in environmental, cultural, social, and economic aspects, i.e., solutions that go beyond the implementation of sustainable technologies, considering relationships with the surroundings and intervention environment, and seeking to encompass the entire project lifecycle.	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	IFF17	Pedro Lira and Manoela Machado (Coordination); Camila Sanches (Project Leader), Camila Reis, David Couto, Fernanda Morais, Julia Ximenes and Laura Figueiredo (team).	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
2142a3cb-0d1a-4ed9-90be-adf7aebb534c	Colegio de Arquitectos del Peru	Carlos Zeballos	czeballos@unsa.edu.pe	Place Building: Enhancing Urban Resilience in Hazard-Prone Areas’ Public Spaces. The Case of Arequipa, Peru	IMPLEMENTED	APPROVED	SECTION_V	Arequipa	Peru	-16.397	-71.53748	This project proposes the concept of Place Building as a tool for integrating fragmented communities near seasonal ravines in Arequipa, Peru through low-cost and easy-to-implement urban elements in public spaces.	The main goal of these modular, scalable and flexible urban elements is to enable social exchanges and connections in public spaces, contributing to the consolidation of organized social capital and laying the groundwork for permanent projects that address the needs of an organized community. The design project is based on an intervention model that articulates urban, environmental, social, and institutional aspects to increase the communities' resilience and mitigates the risk in these areas.	Our concept of Place Building proposes creating communal identity by transforming so-called non-places. Unlike Placemaking, which is typically ephemeral, Place Building creates permanent, gradually-developed communal infraestructure based on an initial module developed in collaboration with the community and local authorities. This approach enhances social capital and community reselience. Our proposal is based on the Urban Linkages project and is directly linked to SDGs 11, 15 and 16	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	IFF51	Carlos Zeballos & Sheyla Chevarria	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
dc8a398b-e077-438b-92aa-c102ab4237ef	Conselho de Arquitetura e Urbanismo do Brasil	Ananda Oliveira Henklain	contato.anandahenklain@gmail.com	Among rivers, lagoons and streams: from the Amazon's self-production to bonding with waters	IMPLEMENTED	APPROVED	SECTION_V	Boa Vista	Brazil	2.820337	-60.671799	This project is an Amazon-based arrangement of a housing prototype that adapts to different aquatic contexts by stilts, enabling self-constructive efforts, flexibility, and low-environmental impact assets by a wooden arched geometry, to achieve SDG 11 focusing on societal bonding to waters.	Flooding events are urban issues worldwide being intensified by climate change. It threats people by spreading infectious diseases, damaging mobility, buildings and the environment, especially in urban poverty. In this matter, the housing shortage is a structural problem that excludes people from multiple devices and deepens segregation. This project aims to tackle it by valuing Amazon's social and constructive knowledge presenting a self-constructive response through Da Vinci's Arch, stilts and bioclimatic studies, gathering technologies and practices easily incorporated and reproduced with local assets and regional heritage to achieve SDG 11.	From John Turner's ideas, who took slums by their potential, this proposal highlights how informal settlements could be a source of transformative practices by turning the lack of urbanization into alternative solutions to the relationship with the environment. Therefore, to build SUSTAINABLE CITIES AND COMMUNITIES, the project enlights the millennial power inscribed in so-called "The Hybrid Men" in the Amazon region, of self-constructing houses and villages over and among waters, adapting and comprehending environmental dynamics and through them managing communities more concerned with carrying capacity and sustainability.	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	IFF55	Ananda Oliveira Henklain/Rui do Rosário	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
f467f05d-a89b-4b0b-a039-e85702fd5f21	TECTON Urban Planning and Consultancy	Pascoal Mario Costa Guglielmi	planejamento@tectonurbanismo.com.br	Jardim Apurá - Social Urbanism and Park	IMPLEMENTED	APPROVED	SECTION_V	São Paulo	Brazil	-23.543931	-46.631567	The Jardim Apurá project consists in the creation of public spaces providing environmental recuperation in the margins of the Billings Reservoir qualificating leisure, sports and housing areas.	The Jardim Apurá Project was developed to reconcile guidelines that ensure environmental preservation, with opening new public spaces and improving local housing conditions. It resulted in an urban park with approximately 30.000m² that promotes sports and leisure activities, as well as the recomposition of the territory and its community through the main goal of land property regularization in its entirety.	In 2019, it was developed the “Jardim Apurá” Project. In compliance with the Sustainable Development Goals, it visualized the reduction of social vulnerability. Considering the implementation of essential infrastructure networks in addition with the implementation of the Park and recovery of the Apucás and Guacuri Basins. It was made possible to improve and recover the waters and the terrestrial bioma. \r\nAll of the actions have the main goal of improving social housing quality for those who remain.	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	LDP47	Pascoal Mario Costa Guglielmi; Letícia R. Guglielmi; Elisabete França; Vanessa Padiá de Souza, Maria Teresa Cardoso Fedeli, Ana Clara Gurgel, Mayra Rodrigues, Fernanda Souza Silva.	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
1a31b13c-1036-4a13-9565-d20205efbfa5	Athabasca University RAIC Centre for Architecture	Henry Tsang	htsang@athabascau.ca	Athabasca Cultural Community Centre	IMPLEMENTED	APPROVED	SECTION_V	Athabasca	Canada	54.716497	-113.284176	The Athabasca Cultural Community Centre is a hypothetical virtual building project designed as a learning tool to explore and demonstrate an integrated approach to a regenerative framework in the context of a rural town in northern Canada.	The design for the Athabasca Cultural Community Centre focuses on highlighting an integrated design approach to designing a regenerative project adapted to the northern biome and climate of Athabasca, Canada. The integrated design process takes a three-step approach: Step 1) The programmatic needs are developed through a collaborative engagement of listening and dialogue with the local community; Step 2) Considering its cultural context, climate, and physical characteristics, a deep understanding of the site is formed; Step 3) The program and natural systems are woven together to optimize the passive design opportunities while enhancing the celebration of the environment. \r\n\r\nThe final design is highlighted by a holistic understanding and adaptation to the site as an integrated living system. The sculptural building massing & form expresses a strong sense of place and identity informed by indigenous knowledge. The use of sustainable and renewable materials including regional mass timber are able to efficiently sequester carbon. The spatial and experiential design improves the indoor environmental quality, health and wellbeing for its tenants, and is accessible, inclusive and welcoming to all.\r\n\r\nPassive Systems: Some design elements that evolved from this process were envelope specific, such as R-values, window wall ratios and shape/size of windows with shading options. The use of the landscape as part of the overall environmental strategy – to moderate solar and stormwater, and to be a purifier of the ventilation air. The landscape design overflowed into a biophilic approach to the architecture with natural materials and systems, such as the solar chimney and extensive green roofs. \r\n\t\r\nActive Systems: The heat is delivered through in-floor – fed via heat pumps connected to the geo-exchange piling system – an integrated engineering structural and environmental strategy. Outside air volumes are doubled with no energy penalty through the use of the earth tube systems, which also provide passive cooling in conjunction with natural ventilation. Renewable energy extends to the roof and parking areas with integrated solar panels.	The faculty members of the RAIC Centre for Architecture at Athabasca University collaborated with many interdisciplinary experts in the development of the design, including indigenous knowledge keepers (SDG 17). Together, they have developed this innovative project as a sustainable, accessible, inclusive, safe space and a hub for the residents of the Town of Athabasca. (SDG 10, 11, 16). The Centre is designed with a community-centric planning consideration that focuses on the social and cultural value of space as well as the health and wellbeing of the occupants. (SDG 3) The numerous regenerative design strategies directly advances SDGs that focus on sustainable development and climate action. (SDG 11, 13)	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	IFF46	Dr. Henry Tsang, Veronica Madonna, Dr. Trevor Butler, Dr. Douglas MacLeod, Jessica Williams	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
9e9eb386-c630-4886-913c-775ee7282ecf	Ubuntu Arquitetura	Vitor Daher	daher.arquitetura@gmail.com	Vitor Daher	IMPLEMENTED	APPROVED	SECTION_V	Nazaré Paulista	Brazil	-23.183331	-46.399813	The Nazaré Ecosystem transforms a former eucalyptus plantation land into an educational centre meeting the contemporary sustainable demands using a simple and vernacular aesthetic, respecting the client's desire for an architecture with the atmosphere of "a house that was born old, that has always been there".	The Nazare Ecosystem have a complex architectural programme, including: A summer house, small rental units, a cultural space, an industrial kitchen, spa, swimming pool, and an art gallery.\r\nSeeking the best efficiency, a modular structural system made of reforested wood was created using the minimum module of all parts is 300mm with a maximum span of 6m.\r\nAll rooms were designed with passive bioclimatic strategies using the sun, the wind and the natural elements in a sustainable approach.	From the outset, the project aimed to meet the 17 SDGs.\r\n1- Use of local labor and materials\r\n2- Productive landscaping with native species.\r\n3- Sports infrastructure\r\n4- Educational cultural centre\r\n5- LGBTQI+ lecturers\r\n6.14- Recovery of springs\r\n7- 100% solar energy\r\n8- Attraction of tourism to the city\r\n9,10,11,12- Connection with local producers\r\n15- Discouraging hunting\r\n16- Free educational courses\r\n17- Free cultural agenda with tax incentive.	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	IFF49	Vitor Daher, Pablo Mauleon	200000	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
38abe0c5-74b6-4dc8-a355-dd072abe05ee	Boldarini Arquitetos Associados	Marcos Boldarini	contato@boldarini.com.br	Cantinho do Céu	IMPLEMENTED	APPROVED	SECTION_V	São Paulo	Brazil	-23.543931	-46.631567	The Cantinho do Céu project, located in São Paulo, Brazil, comprises the urbanization\r\nof informal settlements and the recovery of a water reservoir´s edges through the\r\nimplementation of a linear park	The Cantinho do Céu urbanization project was developed based on the understanding\r\nof the importance and urgent need of the territory’s urban qualification. Its main element is\r\nrepresented by the six phases that make up the linear park, which, in addition to creating\r\nspaces for sports and leisure, seeks to explore possibilities for bringing people closer to the\r\nwater and, in an articulated way, respecting social structures and local morphology, resulted\r\nfrom collective construction.	The project brings urban infrastructures and public recreational spaces to a community that lacked access to clean water, sanitation services and public spaces (goals 1, 3, 4, 6, 9, 10 and 11); reforests and preserves the banks of the reservoir and reverses the discharge of sewage into the water body (goals 13, 14, 15); and was developed alongside the community, ensuring community-generated interventions and the continuity and preservation of the project through social engagement (goal 17).	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	LDP48	General architectural coordinator: Marcos Boldarini, Urban/Landscape coordinator: Marcos Boldarini and Lucas Nobre; Project Management: Elisabete França, Maria Teresa Fedeli, Vanessa Padiá, Letícia Tamisari and Laura Dallabrida Leite.	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
942773d6-f384-44a0-88e1-1b02adeeb9db	BVO ARQUITECTOS / VD ARQUITECTOS	Gustavo Vera Ocampo	veraocampo@me.com	GASOMETER 5 / Urban design and social housing	IMPLEMENTED	APPROVED	SECTION_V	Montevideo	Uruguay	-34.894443	-56.173933	RIGHT TO THE CITY\r\nThe housing policies developed in the last 50 years through the five-year plans of the successive governments have yielded access to strategic urban soil of privileged characteristics, and have enabled the construction of this 100 social housing units overlooking the sea.	Our tower intends to continue and reaffirm this dialogue of social, cultural and urban integration, restoring Gasometer 5 as the symbolic reference of a possible metaphor. A welcome addition to an emblematic space within the city, it accommodates a variety of typologies as it takes into account economic and administrative constraints.\r\nThe building is inserted into the public promenade within a neighborhood that has an identity and a history of its own.	Starting in the 1960s, the land reclaimed from the sea by the design of the coastal Rambla enabled the new hygienist proposals for high-rise social housing buildings that would come to define the new southern border between the city and the Río de la Plata.\r\nRambla is one of the most prominent urban elements of the city and its quintessential public space. A place for the public expression of all citizens, and a site for the exchange of collective experiences\r\nOur tower intends to continue and reaffirm this dialogue of social, cultural and urban integration, restoring Gasometer 5  part of the industrial heritage of the late 19th-century city.\r\nThe Sur and Palermo neighborhoods are known as the cradle of the Afro-Uruguayan culture. The parade of the llamadas and the musical style of candombe are a major contribution to the establishment of a sense of belonging.	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	LDP38	Martín Boga, Gustavo Vera Ocampo, Juan Manuel Varela	8150	\N	\N	\N	