0078e935-2043-457b-a948-c9a2eeb565b1	Unknown	Unknown	gmartins.oficina@gmail.com	HANDBALL AND GOALBALL ARENA RIO 2016 OLYMPIC GAMES (ARENA OF THE FUTURE)/ OLYMPIC SCHOOLS	IMPLEMENTED	SUBMITTED	SECTION_V	Rio de Janeiro	Brazil	-22.9068	-43.1729	TRANSIENT AND MUTANT Rio 2016 Olympic Games Handball and Goalball Arena/Olympic Schools  In preparation for the Rio 2016 Olympic and Paralympic Games, the Arena do Futuro emerged as a visionary project that transcended its temporary function of hosting handball and goalball competitions. Located in the Barra da Tijuca Olympic Park, this 12,000-seat structure was conceived from the outset with a dual purpose: to serve brilliantly at the sporting event and, later, to be reborn as a permanent educational facility. Aligning perfectly with SDG 12, the arena was designed with modular construction systems that allowed its complete disassembly and reuse. Its structural components gave rise to four municipal schools in Bangu, Campo Grande, Rio das Pedras, and Santa Cruz, benefiting between 1,500 and 2,000 students from the West Zone of Rio. This innovative approach exemplifies how the circular economy can be applied on a large scale in the construction sector.  The transformation of the arena into educational spaces significantly advances SDG 4 by providing adequate infrastructure for learning in regions lacking public facilities.  The schools resulting from this process are not mere adaptations, but pedagogical spaces specially designed to meet the needs of local communities, promoting inclusion and equal opportunities.  The project also contributes to SDG 9 by demonstrating the viability of flexible and adaptable construction systems. The rationalization of assembly and disassembly processes, combined with the efficiency in the reuse of materials, establishes new parameters for sustainable civil construction, reducing costs and environmental impacts.  More than a technical solution, the Arena of the Future represents a paradigmatic change in the planning of major sporting events.  While conventional structures often become white elephants after competitions, this initiative proves that it is possible to combine temporariness and permanence, transforming ephemeral investments into lasting benefits. By becoming schools, the arenas fulfill a virtuous cycle that goes from high-performance sports to basic education, demonstrating how architecture can be an instrument of social justice and sustainable development.	TRANSIENT AND MUTANT Rio 2016 Olympic Games Handball and Goalball Arena/Olympic Schools  In preparation for the Rio 2016 Olympic and Paralympic Games, the Arena do Futuro emerged as a visionary project that transcended its temporary function of hosting handball and goalball competitions. Located in the Barra da Tijuca Olympic Park, this 12,000-seat structure was conceived from the outset with a dual purpose: to serve brilliantly at the sporting event and, later, to be reborn as a permanent educational facility. Aligning perfectly with SDG 12, the arena was designed with modular construction systems that allowed its complete disassembly and reuse. Its structural components gave rise to four municipal schools in Bangu, Campo Grande, Rio das Pedras, and Santa Cruz, benefiting between 1,500 and 2,000 students from the West Zone of Rio. This innovative approach exemplifies how the circular economy can be applied on a large scale in the construction sector.  The transformation of the arena into educational spaces significantly advances SDG 4 by providing adequate infrastructure for learning in regions lacking public facilities.  The schools resulting from this process are not mere adaptations, but pedagogical spaces specially designed to meet the needs of local communities, promoting inclusion and equal opportunities.  The project also contributes to SDG 9 by demonstrating the viability of flexible and adaptable construction systems. The rationalization of assembly and disassembly processes, combin