323a6dc2-f115-4c1d-8f17-13ff76bd1b1f	Unknown	Unknown	urbicraft10@gmail.com	Vital Urban Space: A Resilient and Inclusive Design for Health and Clean Energy	PLANNED	SUBMITTED	SECTION_III	Sour El Ghozlane	Algeria	36.1375	3.6856	This project addresses the critical issue of urban decay by proposing a regenerative model rooted in environmental sustainability and human well-being. Anchored in the Sustainable Development Goals—specifically Goal 3 (Good Health and Well-being) and Goal 7 (Affordable and Clean Energy)—the intervention reclaims a neglected urban site through an integrative design approach that is environmentally sensitive, climatically adaptive, and socially inclusive.  The spatial organization prioritizes walkability, passive ventilation, and solar-oriented building placement. The project introduces green corridors and vegetative buffers to mitigate air pollution and urban heat stress, thereby enhancing both physical and mental health. Public spaces are carefully dimensioned and enriched with multi-sensory experiences to promote psychological comfort, social interaction, and active lifestyles.  Energy-wise, the project integrates photovoltaic panels and solar-powered street lighting to ensure clean, renewable energy supply. Materials are locally sourced with a low carbon footprint, supporting both ecological and economic sustainability. Smart urban furniture—such as solar benches and intelligent waste bins—further amplifies the space’s usability and resilience.  Key features include:  A green mobility loop ensuring seamless movement for pedestrians and cyclists;  A mixed-use program blending healthcare, education, and communal spaces;  Renewable energy hubs integrated into the public realm;  Climate-sensitive landscaping using native plants to reduce water consumption;  ENVI-met simulations guiding the design towards optimal microclimatic performance, including shade management, airflow, and thermal comfort.  By combining environmental intelligence with social responsibility, this project offers more than a site-specific solution—it proposes a transferable model for sustainable urban recovery. It reimagines the city as a vessel for life, not just infrastructure. In regions across the Mediterranean basin suffering from neglect and urban decay, such a model holds potential for scalable impact.  Crucially, the project reframes the relationship between space and people. It calls for a shift from car-dominated, fragmented environments to holistic, human-centered urbanism. It reinvigorates the foundational principle that cities should serve the rhythms, needs, and health of their inhabitants.  This design stands as a replicable, context-aware response to the dual challenges of environmental degradation and social fragmentation. It contributes a blueprint for cities that aspire to be livable, equitable, and ecologically attuned—offering a Mediterranean paradigm that places the human experience at its core.	This project addresses the critical issue of urban decay by proposing a regenerative model rooted in environmental sustainability and human well-being. Anchored in the Sustainable Development Goals—specifically Goal 3 (Good Health and Well-being) and Goal 7 (Affordable and Clean Energy)—the intervention reclaims a neglected urban site through an integrative design approach that is environmentally sensitive, climatically adaptive, and socially inclusive.  The spatial organization prioritizes walkability, passive ventilation, and solar-oriented building placement. The project introduces green corridors and vegetative buffers to mitigate air pollution and urban heat stress, thereby enhancing both physical and mental health. Public spaces are carefully dimensioned and enriched with multi-sensory experiences to promote psychological comfort, social interaction, and active lifestyles.  Energy-wise, the project integrates photovoltaic panels and solar-powered street lighting to ensure clean, renewable energy supply. Materials are locally sourced with a low carbon footprint, supporting both ecological and economic sustainability. Smart urban furniture—such as solar benches and intelligent waste bins—further amplifies the space’s usability and resilience.  Key features include:  A green mobility loop ensuring seamless movement for pedestrians and cyclists;  A mixed-use program blending healthcare, education, and communal spaces;  Renewable energy hubs integrated into the public realm;  Climate-sensitive landscaping using native plants to reduce water consumption;  ENVI-met simulations guiding the design towards optimal microclimatic performance, including shade management, airflow, and thermal comfort.  By combining environmental intelligence with social responsibility, this project offers more than a site-specific solution—it proposes a transferable model for sustainable urban recovery. It reimagines the city as a vessel for life, not just infrastructure. In regions across the Mediterranean basin suffering from neglect and urban decay, such a model holds potential for scalable impact.  Crucially, the project reframes the relationship between space and people. It calls for a shift from car-dominated, fragmented environments to holistic, human-centered urbanism. It reinvigorates the foundational principle that cities should serve the rhythms, needs, and health of their inhabitants.  This design stands as a replicable, context-aware response to the dual challenges of environmental degradation and social fragmentation. It contributes a blueprint for cities that aspire to be livable, equitable, and ecologically attuned—offering a Mediterranean paradigm that places the human experience at its core.	See detailed description	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-04-18 13:00:00.604992	2026-04-18 13:00:00.604992	P38	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
a55ecc48-d859-4fc9-b59a-a37a96c57d16	Unknown	Unknown	khalirayane@gmail.com	The Pulsating Void: SDG 11 Climate-Responsive Public Space in Algeria	PLANNED	SUBMITTED	SECTION_III	Sour El Ghozlane	Algeria	36.1375	3.6856	In response to the growing climatic and social challenges in Algerian cities, this project proposes a conceptual and actionable model—“The Pulsating Void”—to revitalize public spaces through a sustainable, human-centered lens. Using Sour El Ghozlane as a case study, the project employs deep cartographic analysis (topography, slopes, orientation, shadows, noise, and land use) and advanced digital tools such as GIS and SoundPLAN to assess microclimatic and acoustic comfort. The methodology blends participatory design, data layering, and environmental simulation to identify the most responsive site for urban intervention. By viewing public space as a living entity shaped by climate, people, and identity, this approach transcends traditional functionalism. Early results show improvements in ventilation and noise reduction, contributing to increased user comfort and social engagement. The project directly supports SDG 11 (sustainable cities), SDG 13 (climate action), and SDG 3 (well-being), offering a replicable model for other contexts .	In response to the growing climatic and social challenges in Algerian cities, this project proposes a conceptual and actionable model—“The Pulsating Void”—to revitalize public spaces through a sustainable, human-centered lens. Using Sour El Ghozlane as a case study, the project employs deep cartographic analysis (topography, slopes, orientation, shadows, noise, and land use) and advanced digital tools such as GIS and SoundPLAN to assess microclimatic and acoustic comfort. The methodology blends participatory design, data layering, and environmental simulation to identify the most responsive site for urban intervention. By viewing public space as a living entity shaped by climate, people, and identity, this approach transcends traditional functionalism. Early results show improvements in ventilation and noise reduction, contributing to increased user comfort and social engagement. The project directly supports SDG 11 (sustainable cities), SDG 13 (climate action), and SDG 3 (well-being), offering a replicable model for other contexts .	See detailed description	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-04-18 13:00:08.127452	2026-04-18 13:00:08.127452	P72	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
e6ef880d-cfa5-4d66-8bb7-891e1ca8d097	King Salman International University, RMT	Prof. Dr Rasha Sayed, Arch. Islam Ashraf , Arch. Zeyad Salah	rasha.sayed@ksiu.edu.eg	ECOADAPT	PLANNED	APPROVED	SECTION_III	Alexandria	Egypt	30.92	29.77	This project, originally initiated in collaboration with the Chair Initiative, has been adapted in partnership with Eyes in Germany to address pandemics and other hazards, including climate change and environmental challenges. It focuses on ensuring access to basic needs and well-being for all individuals, emphasizing the importance of sustainable living. Each family is provided with a single dwelling designed to prioritize agricultural spaces and living areas.  The project began as a pilot in Cairo, aimed at testing how the SHOWER framework can function in a densely populated urban environment with unique challenges. The second pilot, currently underway near King Maryout Lake, involves collaboration between local universities and government bodies. This phase aims to assess how communities can adapt to climate change hazards, focusing on both mitigation and adaptation strategies using our sustainable dwelling designs, which contribute to reduced CO2 emissions.  The SHOWER initiative emerged in the latter half of 2020, following the catastrophic global impact of the COVID-19 pandemic. This crisis highlighted the fragility of urban environments, even those deemed sustainable. Despite advancements in green building technologies and urban resilience, they proved insufficient against the pandemic. The central question for the SHOWER team is whether the built environment can be effectively designed to protect people from future health threats.  The initiative addresses the following six cognitive areas, aligning with the SDGs:  - *Sustainability* (SDG 11: Sustainable Cities and Communities) - *Health & Safety* (SDG 3: Good Health and Well-being) - *Architecture* (SDG 9: Industry, Innovation, and Infrastructure) - *Wellbeing* (SDG 3: Good Health and Well-being) - *Environment* (SDG 13: Climate Action) - *Resilience* (SDG 11: Sustainable Cities and Communities)  Our goal is to create a comprehensive scientific and technical framework that integrates local and international codes for safeguarding built environments against diseases. We aim to develop a post-pandemic architectural trend inspired by rich Egyptian heritage, ensuring it serves as a valuable resource for construction practices in Egypt and beyond.  Over nearly 24 months, this reference code has been developed through collaboration among Egypt, Germany, and Italy, with a dedicated focus on climate change, sustainability, and urban resilience. We hope this initiative will benefit not only Egypt but also the broader Arab and international communities, aligning with the global commitment to the SDGs.	This project, originally initiated in collaboration with the Chair Initiative, has been adapted in partnership with Eyes in Germany to address pandemics and other hazards, including climate change and environmental challenges. It focuses on ensuring access to basic needs and well-being for all individuals, emphasizing the importance of sustainable living. Each family is provided with a single dwelling designed to prioritize agricultural spaces and living areas.  The project began as a pilot in Cairo, aimed at testing how the SHOWER framework can function in a densely populated urban environment with unique challenges. The second pilot, currently underway near King Maryout Lake, involves collaboration between local universities and government bodies. This phase aims to assess how communities can adapt to climate change hazards, focusing on both mitigation and adaptation strategies using our sustainable dwelling designs, which contribute to reduced CO2 emissions.  The SHOWER initiative emerged in the latter half of 2020, following the catastrophic global impact of the COVID-19 pandemic. This crisis highlighted the fragility of urban environments, even those deemed sustainable. Despite advancements in green building technologies and urban resilience, they proved insufficient against the pandemic. The central question for the SHOWER team is whether the built environment can be effectively designed to protect people from future health threats.  The initiative addresses the following six cognitive areas, aligning with the SDGs:  - *Sustainability* (SDG 11: Sustainable Cities and Communities) - *Health & Safety* (SDG 3: Good Health and Well-being) - *Architecture* (SDG 9: Industry, Innovation, and Infrastructure) - *Wellbeing* (SDG 3: Good Health and Well-being) - *Environment* (SDG 13: Climate Action) - *Resilience* (SDG 11: Sustainable Cities and Communities)  Our goal is to create a comprehensive scientific and technical framework that integrates local and international codes for safeguarding built environments against diseases. We aim to develop a post-pandemic architectural trend inspired by rich Egyptian heritage, ensuring it serves as a valuable resource for construction practices in Egypt and beyond.  Over nearly 24 months, this reference code has been developed through collaboration among Egypt, Germany, and Italy, with a dedicated focus on climate change, sustainability, and urban resilience. We hope this initiative will benefit not only Egypt but also the broader Arab and international communities, aligning with the global commitment to the SDGs.	See detailed description	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-04-18 12:59:53.078529	2026-04-18 12:59:53.078529	P5	Prof. Dr Rasha Sayed, Arch. Islam Ashraf , Arch. Zeyad Salah	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
763f74b5-0ecb-4abe-838d-3dd06336b1b9	AOS Architecture Ltd	Ar. Corrin Chan Chui Yi	aos.architecture@gmail.com	TWGHs E-Co Village	IMPLEMENTED	APPROVED	SECTION_IV	Hong Kong	China	22.3193	114.1694	TWHGs E-Co Village TKO: From Landfill to Sustainable Oasis  Once a landfill in Tseung Kwan O, E-Co Village is now a pioneering eco-camping and education hub, transforming waste into a thriving green space that promotes sustainability, community, and environmental healing. This groundbreaking project, initiated by the Hong Kong SAR Environmental Protection Department and operated by the Tung Wah Group of Hospitals, stands as Asia’s first advancing-zero-carbon development on a rehabilitated landfill.   Award-Winning Sustainability-  The project has received the following awards:  - 2021 Green Building Award (Grand Award – Unbuilt Category) - 2024 Hong Kong Institute of Architects Sustainable Architecture Award - HK BEAM Plus Platinum (New Buildings & Neighbourhood)  From Waste to Treasure:  Embracing the theme “From Garbage to Garden, From Waste to Treasure,”E-Co Village has turned a barren landfill into a lush public retreat—a place for relaxation, connection, and environmental education.   Advancing the UN Sustainable Development Goals (SDGs):  E-Co Village actively contributes to multiple UNSDGs, including:  - SDG 3– by promoting Health & Well-being  - SDG 6– Clean Water & Sanitation available  - SDG 7– 100% Solar-Powered Operations  - SDG 8 – support Green Economy & Social Impact  - SDG 9– promote Green Innovations  - SDG 11– Village as a base to create a Sustainable Community  - SDG 13– Climate Action - E-Co Village a Zero Carbon project to support Hong Kong arriving Carbon Neutrality by 2050.  - SDG 15– Biodiversity Enhancement through enhancement of green landscaping  - SDG 16– the operator TWHGs as a respected local NGO with Inclusivicity & Responsible Governance   E-Co Village as a Model of Green Innovation - E-Co Village is fully solar-powered, with surplus energy fed back into the grid  - Passive Design for green stations maximizes natural light and ventilation, reducing energy use  - the use of Eco-friendly materials for buildings, including bamboo, palm fiber board, and recycled construction waste  - Sustainable water management with rainwater harvesting and greywater filtration   Master Plan - A Heart for Nature & Community:  Inspired by New Caledonia’s heart-shaped Mangrove Island, E-Co Village’s design symbolizes nature’s unconditional love and humanity’s care for the planet. The site has 2 platforms and each centred with a heart-shaped central space, each with its own symbolic meanings:  - Big Heart– Represents nature’s all-embracing generosity  - Small Heart– Reflects meticulous attention to sustainability in every detail   The site features:  - Upper & Lower Platforms with camping, farming, and event spaces  - Community Farming (Farm-to-Table)  - Butterfly Garden & Biodiversity Zones - Children’s Green Education & Play Areas  - Green Theatre & Demonstrative Green Stations  E-Co Village is a Living Laboratory for Sustainability.  As an Experiential, Experimental, and Environmental Education Centre, E-Co Village demonstrates how waste land can be reborn as value—for people, nature, and future generations.   Since its 2024 completion, E-Co Village has become Hong Kong’s premier green education hub, hosting tours and inspiring action toward carbon neutrality, ecological harmony and social cohesion.	TWHGs E-Co Village TKO: From Landfill to Sustainable Oasis  Once a landfill in Tseung Kwan O, E-Co Village is now a pioneering eco-camping and education hub, transforming waste into a thriving green space that promotes sustainability, community, and environmental healing. This groundbreaking project, initiated by the Hong Kong SAR Environmental Protection Department and operated by the Tung Wah Group of Hospitals, stands as Asia’s first advancing-zero-carbon development on a rehabilitated landfill.   Award-Winning Sustainability- 