052fa15a-ea97-4205-881b-437af1c19ba8	AIA	Lisa Ferretto	lisaferretto@aia.org	AIA Framework for Design Excellence	IMPLEMENTED	SUBMITTED	SECTION_V	Washington, DC	United States of America	38.9072	-77.0369	The architect’s call to protect health, safety, and welfare has a broader meaning amid challenges of climate extremes and social inequity. Our architectural profession can harness the power of design to contribute to solutions addressing the most significant needs of our time. The AIA Framework for Design Excellence, intended to be accessible and relevant for every project, represents 10 defining principles informing progress toward an equitable, healthy, resilient, and zero-carbon built environment. It intersects and aligns with the United Nations’ Sustainable Development Goals, and the ESG pillars, demonstrating our common goal of an urgent call to action for Climate Action and Equity.	The architect’s call to protect health, safety, and welfare has a broader meaning amid challenges of climate extremes and social inequity. Our architectural profession can harness the power of design to contribute to solutions addressing the most significant needs of our time. The AIA Framework for Design Excellence, intended to be accessible and relevant for every project, represents 10 defining principles informing progress toward an equitable, healthy, resilient, and zero-carbon built environment. It intersects and aligns with the United Nations’ Sustainable Development Goals, and the ESG pillars, demonstrating our common goal of an urgent call to action for Climate Action and Equity.	See detailed description	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-04-18 13:00:21.972357	2026-04-18 13:00:21.972357	P106	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
9f0b3467-1ad9-41cb-a675-048c69a3d6f4	Nelson Mandela University	Magda Minguzzi	magda.minguzzi@mandela.ac.za	Investigation on First Nation built environment and dwellings in the Eastern Cape, South Africa	IMPLEMENTED	APPROVED	SECTION_III	Bavianskloof Valley	South Africa	-33.68027	24.51481	With this ongoing community-led project, the working group (First Indigenous Peoples-Nelson Mandela University staff and students) is documenting, studying, and moving awareness of the First Indigenous Peoples of South Africa’s settlements and dwellings (self-built with local materials) located in a remote area of the Eastern Cape, and never studied before. A unique example of a regenerative approach to the built environment where the Indigenous building knowledge, typology, technique and materials (Indigenous Knowledge System) have been handed down from generation to generation, from pre-colonial times till the present, orally, despite the long history of repression and segregation, the Indigenous Peoples went through since the arrival of the settler colonialists. The working group was formed in 2015, under the umbrella of the Nelson Mandela University School of Architecture, and led by Dr Magda Minguzzi. Since then, their focus is on community engagement projects, based on practice research, that involve teaching, learning and research.	In the current environmental-socio-economic crisis that we are facing, globally, these First Nations dwellings under study and the IKS applied to represent a unique example of equal opportunity to housing, which empowers people (self-building), improves their living conditions and creates food security lifestyle. It is urgent to open a global to re-activate our forgotten indigenous knowledge, rooted in a regenerative approach to the built environment and resources. Trailer of a documentary: https://vimeo.com/812088198?activityReferer=1	This community engagement project (Nelson Mandela University-First Nations of South Africa) promotes inclusivity, social cohesion and equity. The village under study is a remarkable example of equal opportunity to housing (the land is owned by the community), which empowers people (self-building), uses a sustainable model (materials used are self-collected in the area) improves people's living conditions and creates food security lifestyle (each house has a vegetable garden). It’s an example that can be used in other similar climate contexts to alleviate poverty and promote a regenerative approach to the environment.	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	EFP1	Dr Magda Minguzzi (NMU), Gaob/Chief Margaret Coetzee, in collaboration with Arch Lucy Vosloo (NMU)	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
08776049-5c31-48fd-ba50-b5369e9d6ef8	Pyramids Higher institute (PHI) FOR ENGINEERING AND TECHNOLOGY- Cairo University faculty of Engineering , Architecture Department	Vitta Abdulrahim Ibrahim	vitta174@hotmail.com	Boundaries	IMPLEMENTED	APPROVED	SECTION_III	Cairo	Egypt	30.046784	31.239582	- creating communal space where barriers are dissolved/ mangling of various activities\r\n -man long time ago lives in communities, set his own boundary.\r\n-digital technology dissolves time and place barrier, never the less let the gap increase between people (social interaction, face-to-face …)\r\n- Creating a space where all children can mingle, engaging kids in social community activities	Concept\r\n•\tChoosing the triangle by which its 3 vertices suggest the 3 pillars of sustainability concept: Social, Environmental and Economic \r\n•\tReasons of choosing this concept: The triangular shape \r\n•\tThe Nubian Heritage represent part of the Egyptian Identity\r\nAiming to:\r\nSocial relations\r\nCommunity participation\r\nSustainable (using local materials)\r\nImprove quality of life (opportunities for children in education and playing)\r\nEquity (role of women)	•\tSocial activities (relations) \r\n•\tCommunity participation (of all ages to serve children)\r\n•\tImprove the quality of life (natural ventilation, solar power electricity for lighting) \r\n•\tSustainability ( using local /recyclable materials) ( sustainable cities and communities)\r\n•\tSelf sufficient of some crops / zero hunger ( eat or sell) /rain\r\n•\tImprove the quality of life ( good health and well-being)	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	IFF59	Vitta Abdelrahim / Manar Eltanbouly	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
10a1a4c3-4459-4af5-a2ea-3b02b7743741	Localworks	Angela Nkurunziza	angela@localworks.ug	Mustardseed Junior School	IMPLEMENTED	APPROVED	SECTION_III	Wakiso	Uganda	0.40444	32.45944	MJS is a newly founded private initiative with the aim of creating an exemplary kindergarten and primary school that provides an inspirational and practical education to the young children in its care. It is located near Sentema, a village about 20km west of Kampala. The inspiration for the design was to create a ‘large home’ for the children that functions as a comfortable enabling educational environment. The architectural ambition is not programmatically prescriptive, but rather to inspire teachers and students alike to inhabit spaces in multiple and creative ways, to (literally) think outside the box and to treat the entire school, not just the classroom, as a greater learning environment.	At Mustardseed, no two classrooms are alike and none of them are in the shape of a rectangle. Spaces are organically shaped and characterised by a warm, natural materiality accentuated by playful and inspiring colours. The thick, earthen, undulating external walls stop short of the roof allowing the flow of fresh air to cool down the spaces. Direct sunlight is filtered through the roof in selected areas filling the space with comfortable levels of natural light. Along circulation routes, colourful window shutters enclose relatively small and squarish openings. Each classroom has a dedicated outdoor learning area shaded by trees which can be accessed through a series of double doors. Across the school, furniture has been carefully designed and integrated into the program: this includes built-in benches and shelves, cubby holes, large full-height black boards and light-weight yet sturdy tables and chairs.\r\nThe landscape and architectural design are in complete harmony with each other. Free flowing forms of internal teaching spaces resonate in the landscape design in fluid, flowing lines which seek to nurture curiosity for learning within children. A holistic approach to teaching is core to the overall concept of Mustardseed which means learning from and with nature is of central importance. This objective is taken seriously in the design by literally creating a space for nature. Another ambition of this project is to improve biodiversity, despite the construction, and to (re-) create indigenous forests, whilst ensuring human activities on the land are sustainable, practical, and enrich the overall environment. These goals are being achieved through conservation agriculture, soil regeneration and sustainable indigenous timber plantations.	Alongside the application of extensive passive design systems, all building materials have been carefully selected. Almost all of the building material is sourced and harvested on or within a 2km radius of the site keeping production costs low and the carbon foot print close to zero. Not only is this project constructed sustainability, but also, it leaves the site with more biodiversity that it started with. Conservation agriculture, soil regeneration and planting an on-site forestry program using fast growing indigenous species have been developed in concert with the schools ecologically-oriented curriculum.\r\nIn addition to efforts to improve local school building standards, this innovation protects the environment ecologically. The non-stabilized earth building material not only prevents deforestation stimulated by the burning of commonly used clay bricks but also, all buildings retain the potential to be demolished with minimal damage to the site which can be easily repurposed. Across Uganda, fast growing eucalyptus trees are being planted more and more frequently; it is a non-indigenous species that degrades the local environment. Whilst necessary to meet the high firewood demand for cooking, instead of eucalyptus, this project will use indigenous softwood trees, planted as part of a carbon-positive sustainable forestry program. This effort promotes and encourages the return of local vegetation species that are slowly dying out.	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	LDP23	Allan Semakula, Deborah Tusiime, Edson Agume, Felix Holland, Geoffrey Addah, Guy Namanya, Morgane Charron, Norbert Ahumuza, Paul Kyoma Asiimwe, Peter Ssemakula Mukiibi, Philip Matovu, Robert Mugisha, Sarah K Ndagire, Torsten Lorange	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
bc6ccf22-d914-4c81-bb36-b5a672a92c7d	Tunisian Order of Architects	Adel Hidar	adel.hidar@gmail.com	Oil mill & cannery of Segermès - Zaghouan / Tunisia	IMPLEMENTED	APPROVED	SECTION_III	Zaghouan	Tunisia	36.404973	10.142706	The oil mill & cannery project is a concept fully integrated into the site, from picking to bottling and labeling. It’s also an attempt to rehabilitate a fringe of territory by infusing new productive energy. An energy that creates values, jobs and well-being.\r\nRespecting the waxworks of organic farming, the olive growing complex now allows the production of very high-quality organic olive oil following a process fully integrated into the site. It employs around 100 men and women during the production phases. Modern technologies allow the use of local resources and place sustainability at the heart of all agricultural and business activities.\r\nOlive cultivation plays an essential role in the social and economic life of Tunisia and represents around 15% of the total value of final agricultural production. In addition, the olive sector represents the direct or indirect livelihood of more than 1 million people.\r\nRural Tunisian women participate very actively in the picking of olive trees; these jobs, although seasonal, provide rural families with very appreciable annual income which generally contributes to financing children's education ...\r\nToday, agricultural products from the Segermès estate stand out for their high quality both on the Tunisian market and internationally. Rewarded with numerous distinctions on a worldwide scale.	Route & confluence: The establishment of the project emanates from a territorial position. The chosen location maintains a privileged dialogue with a water reservoir as well as a basilica from the Byzantine period. The project is part of the logic of a confluence, an emergence built by the directional multiplicity of the natural and “civilizational” components of this unique place.\r\nA historical past: The foundations of the new building are nourished by the historical roots of the place whose Byzantine remains remain. The ground floor opens onto the landscape and overlooks the old basilica through the presence of a Forum which becomes a semi-public space for meetings and contemplation. The staging of the archaeological remains also helps to revive the historical past of the region which was previously abandoned.\r\nThe olive tree at the heart of the process: The architecture of the oil mill, resulting from the framework of the olive grove, also tells the story of the extraction process. The oil is kept in the center of the building and the volume of the silos thus constitutes a link between the two levels of the new building.	1. End poverty in all its forms everywhere\r\nIn Tunisia, regional disparities, particularly those between the center of the country and the Mediterranean coasts, represent the essence of social inequalities. The development of agricultural areas neglected by the country's youth is the only way to curb the rural exodus and illegal immigration to Europe. In this sense, our project represents a brake on poverty and inequalities of opportunity.\r\n\r\n2. End hunger, achieve food security and improved nutrition and promote sustainable agriculture\r\nThe production of premium quality organic olive oil is mainly for export to the whole world. The income generated by this fair trade, insofar as it also benefits rural families living in the region, makes it possible to feed the interior regions of the country. Encouragement from the Tunisian government for the labeling of organic olive oil has made it possible to develop sustainable agriculture.\r\n\r\n5. Achieve gender equality and empower all women and girls\r\nOlive growing traditionally represents an annual income for rural women in Tunisia. Generally this pension is intended to finance the studies of a child and represents the hope of a better future for many needy families. Although the empowerment of women and girls is still far from being achieved in the rural world, the olive tree and its crops have always been a vector of hope and a major asset for female emancipation.\r\n\r\n8. Promote sustained, inclusive and sustainable economic growth, full and productive employment and decent work for all\r\nThe fact of combining the functions of an oil mill with those of a cannery has made it possible to offer employment positions throughout the year. Indeed, the olive-growing activity in itself was not enough to guarantee full employment for agricultural workers in the region. The new building which houses these two combined functions is described as the “castle of the olive tree” by its employees, who find there all the conveniences of a dignified job in fair working conditions.\r\n\r\n9. Build resilient infrastructure, promote inclusive and sustainable industrialization and foster innovation\r\nThe creation of a fully autonomous and integrated infrastructure for the production of olive oil and certain derived agricultural products is a first in Tunisia. This concept of “bottling at the château” is borrowed from the “Appellations d’Origines Contrôlées (A.O.C)” which exist in the economic models of the northern Mediterranean. Typically, processed agricultural products are produced off-site in polluting industrial areas on the outskirts of major cities. The resilience of this project comes mainly from its geographical location and its mixed program.\r\n\r\n10. Reduce inequality within and among countries\r\nThe project aims to ensure stable and decent jobs in the interior regions of the country. It therefore reduces inequalities and curbs rural exodus and irregular immigration to the northern Mediterranean.\r\n\r\n12. Ensure sustainable consumption and production patterns\r\nOrganic olive growing sets in motion a whole series of eco-sustainable parameters in its production. Part of the energy is provided by the combustion of the pomace and the vegetable water is recycled for the manufacture of by-products. Moreover, the consumption of olive oil, whose health benefits are well established, is an integral part of Tunisian culinary traditions.\r\n\r\n13. Take urgent action to combat climate change and its impacts*\r\nAn ecological architecture mainly based on local materials and resources combined with a programmatic study to ensure full employment for the inhabitants of the region are assets that contribute in their scales to these great ambitions for humanity...\r\n\r\n15. Protect, restore and promote sustainable use of terrestrial ecosystems, sustainably manage forests, combat desertification, and halt and reverse land degradation and halt biodiversity loss\r\nOur integrated agricultural project uses local resources: plantations of olive groves from Roman times, reverse osmosis water from a well from Roman times, natural fertilizers from farms in the region... Its sustainability depends directly on the preservation resources that surround it and that allow its existence. We believe that this type of equations is good for the balance and preservation of ecosystems.\r\n\r\n17. Strengthen the means of implementation and revitalize the global partnership for sustainable development\r\nThe production of high-quality organic olive oil in Tunisia makes it possible to compete with Italian and Spanish producers. The economic balance generated in recent years by the major Tunisian labels helps to reduce the disparities between the north and the south. Today, Tunisia is beginning to regain a leading position in the production of early olive oil on a global scale. Small steps that can inspire other agricultural sectors that do not have their place on the scale of the Mediterranean and global economy.	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	LDP70	Adel Hidar - architect	1485	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
f4bb3d59-c214-46c5-9264-8731dc641973	Natureza Urbana	Breno Pilot	breno@naturezaurbana.net	Tourism Masterplan for Sal Island - Cape Verde	IMPLEMENTED	SUBMITTED	SECTION_III	Sal Island	Cape Verde	16.775533	-22.921133	This work included the development of the Sal Island tourism master plan, aiming to identify the particularities, potentialities and needs of the island for a territory coherent tourism development.	The Tourism Masterplan for Sal Island, Cape Verde, aimed to identify the particularities, potentialities and needs of the island for a territory coherent tourism development. The initial step consisted in understanding issues related to the dynamics of tourism in the island, analysis of the tourist inventory, attractions and tourist infrastructure and identification of the opportunities and challenges for composition of new routes or strengthening of existing products.	The construction of the future vision for the island starts from the intersection of the analyzes, aiming at the definition of strategies and action plans based on the following premises: sustainability, circular economy, and experience tourism, prioritizing opportunities for visitor engagement with the place. In the areas of strategic action, potential tourist segments and products that lead to proposals are identified, divided between actions and projects.	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	IFF18	Pedro Lira and Manoela Machado (Coordination); Camila Sanches Julia Ximenes (Project Leaders), Carolina Passos, Julia Marini, Laís Pimentel, Laura Figueiredo and Tiago Martinelli (team).	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
ab1e49ec-5d9a-4c56-a27e-883c66c74757	Natureza Urbana	Breno Pilot	breno@naturezaurbana.net	Tourism Masterplan for São Nicolau, São Vicente and Santo Antão Island, Cape Verde	IMPLEMENTED	SUBMITTED	SECTION_III	São Nicolau	Cape Verde	16.835	-24.8076	This project aimed the development of the tourism Master Plan of the islands in the north consistent with the territory and with its socioeconomic demands considering their cultural and natural particularities.	The implementation plan guided the execution of the Master Plan, which indicated the coordination structure responsible for implementing the plans and projects, prioritization, and implementation scenarios. In the initial stage, the project addressed tourism dynamics in the region, tourist demand on the islands, inventory and infrastructure analysis, and identified opportunities and challenges for the composition of new itineraries or strengthening of existing products.	The future vision for each island was constructed by intersecting the analyses, aiming to define action plans based on: sustainability, circular economy, and experiential tourism, prioritizing opportunities for visitor engagement with the local area. Additionally, considering the projects' relationship with the United Nations Sustainable Development Goals (SDG), studies were conducted to assess socio-environmental and socio-cultural impacts, as well as mitigation processes.	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	IFF19	Pedro Lira and Manoela Machado (Coordination); Camila Sanches (Project Leader), Carolina Passos, Julia Marini, Julia Ximenes, Laís Pimentel, Laura Figueiredo and Tiago Martinelli (team).	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
cbde3a5d-73f7-4e7b-849d-1e07c3105e82	Oriental Group Architects (Hamdy EL-Setouhy)	Hamdy EL-Setouhy	INFO@OG-ARCHITECTS.COM	Reviving AL-Nazlah	IMPLEMENTED	SUBMITTED	SECTION_III	Fayoum	Egypt	29.311889	30.8268	Reviving the Al-Nazlah area in Fayoum aims to create a pilot project in contexts of specificity. The valuable district incubates pottery workshops which have been producing special pots used for construction since Ancient Egyptian Civilization. Thus, the upgraded construction technique which enhanced the bonding material gluing the pots together via the help of lab experiments maintained the traditional technique. Also, new forms have been introduced for the roofing construction, which enabled the local community to explore a wider range of spans through introducing domes & vaults constructed by pots. The project was initiated by Arch. El-Setouhy with an aim to indulge the local community in a participatory process which enables the locals to learn, appreciate, create and govern their cultural product. Thus, enabling them to achieve the three pillars of sustainability for the project, social, economic and environmental sustenance.  The project has been awarded the second prize of the Baku Award in 2019, Category A, with the support of UIA for creating a sustainable environmental development nucleus that has many positive impacts on the whole region. The project was nominated to receive the Aga-Khan Award cycle 2022. Also, shortlisted in the Arab Association Award for the last cycle 2022.	Concept: Develop the Nazlah area by reviving its cultural heritage and returning it to become a cultural product again that the local people can be proud of it. \r\nGoals:\r\nPilot project, give a model about improving performance and maximize benefits for areas which has different kinds of arts of their local culture over hundreds of years, that Egypt has many of it. \r\nCreate a sustain environmental development nucleus that has many positive impacts on the whole region.\r\nReviving the traditional crafts that characterize the region, to protect it from extinction.\r\nSeeking to restore the place to its former value that brought happiness to the local people, while restoring confidence in their cultural heritage.\r\n\r\nThe interlocking of the pots forms a continuous arch, which creates a load-bearing mechanism. The variations and repetition of the load-bearing elements create a variety of spaces and roof treatments. The climatic sustainability stems from the zero-waste process adopted in the construction technique. The Visitor witness a powerful environmentally friendly climatic nature in terms of adequacy of internal temperatures and also as to its coherence with the surrounding nature. The geometrical iterations in the construction of the roof, which created diffused sunlight radiations on the building added an important layer in the lower temperatures inside the buildings.  This manipulation of the roof results in less heat transfer into the internal spaces than the conventional R.C. and mud bricks construction modes. The project created a process of discovery of a heritage asset, the capitalization of the architect through a participatory methodology of a familiar practice of construction that was about to go extinct, in a contemporary mode which explores architectural aesthetical values and adventurous journeys in the spatial experiences of the Visitor center. \r\nProgram:\r\n-Visitor center:\r\nIntroduces the historical value of this site, which facilitates marketing issue.\r\nContains a number of halls. The first, displays samples and information on the various pottery products produced by the people of the region, attached to it is a hall on the tools they use in making pottery, next to a hall documenting artwork (movies and songs) that were filmed in the region.\r\nAttached to the visitor center is a space used to sit and enjoy the beautiful scenery of the waterway.\r\n-An exhibition for displaying and selling pottery products, consisting of three rooms attached to an open space next to the current pergola to be an extension of the products display.\r\n-Development of workshops:\r\nThe development of new workshops that were built soon, of white limestone blocks, which are not commensurate with the nature of the place and its cultural heritage.\r\n-Services – Landscape:\r\nProvide a multipurpose space for different cultural and related activities.\r\nFacilitate a secured passing way for visitors that do not interrupt that of workers.\r\nThe project is closely linked to the SDGs, and sought to achieve a set of its goals, whether in the stages of implementation or after implementation, especially the goals numbers (1-3-7-13)	The project is closely linked to the SDGs, and sought to achieve a set of its goals, whether in the stages of implementation or after implementation, especially the goals numbers (1-7-3-13)\r\nGoal 01:\r\nThe Al-Nazlah area is characterized by many potentials, however, the poverty rate is very high in a way that makes us have to act responsibly, and the projects have a positive impact on this point, and this is what the project sought.\r\nPottery is made in the region in a way that dates back to the ancient Egyptian civilization and there is no analogue in the world, besides it is an attractive area that attracted many creators to evaluate their artworks there.\r\n1- He relied on the local population to implement the project, which added economic value to them.\r\n2- After the establishment of the project, many scholars and media professionals were attracted to it, which helped the people of the region market their products and added to them an appropriate financial return.\r\nWhich achieved Goal No. (1) NO POVERTY\r\nGoal (03):\r\nAfter its implementation, the project turned into a recreational area for all ages, providing a healthy life and promoting well-being for all ages. It has become a recreation area for everyone and a pride for them. Suffice it to say that it has become the main park in all holidays and a major shrine for all guests of the region. Besides, it connected the people of the region with their cultural heritage.\r\nWhich seriously sought to achieve goal number (03) GOOD HEALTH & WELL-BEING\r\nGoal (07):\r\nAccess to clean and affordable energy starts primarily with our use of building materials themselves, as we have tended in the recent period to use materials that are not environmentally friendly and do not suit the climatic conditions.\r\nOne of the goals of the project is to draw attention to our ability to use local raw materials that are compatible with the environment, and achieve good results. The use of pottery in construction achieved a decrease in the temperature inside the buildings 10-12 degrees lower than outside, which attributed the local residents to their confidence in the local raw materials. Which helped achieve Goal No. (7) AFORDABLE & CLEAN ENERGY\r\nGoal (13):\r\nThe project aimed to revive our cultural heritage, and to point out in an effective practical way that we have within our cultural heritage solutions to the problem of climate change, not only to protect our heritage, but also to protect our current lives and our future heritage. Which achieved effective results in the pursuit of goal (13) CLIAMTE ACTION	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	2026-03-01 19:41:05.683573	LDP4	Hamdy EL-Setouhy	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
582442e0-f835-40ca-a7ab-09695f8968a0	Natureza Urbana	Breno	breno@naturezaurbana.net	Rehabilitation of the Fish Market in Mindelo	PLANNED	SUBMITTED	SECTION_III	Mindelo	Cabo Verde	16.889	-24.995	The Rehabilitation and Modernization Project of the Mindelo Fish Market in Cabo Verde aims to strengthen the blue economy and resilient tourism through a functional, culturally rooted, and environmentally conscious facility. Preserving its historic façade facing Avenida Marginal, the market is reimagined with a new configuration inspired by pano di terra, traditional Cape Verdean textiles that inform the roof’s geometric design.The layout enhances usability and public comfort, and with both land and sea access, the market connects to the nearby Sea Museum and the waterfront, transforming into an active public space and a cultural landmark.	The Rehabilitation and Modernization Project of the Mindelo Fish Market in Cabo Verde aims to strengthen the blue economy and resilient tourism through a functional, culturally rooted, and environmentally conscious facility. Preserving its historic façade facing Avenida Marginal, the market is reimagined with a new configuration inspired by pano di terra, traditional Cape Verdean textiles that inform the roof’s geometric design.The layout enhances usability and public comfort, and with both land and sea access, the market connects to the nearby Sea Museum and the waterfront, transforming into an active public space and a cultural landmark.	See detailed description	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	2026-04-18 12:59:53.078529	2026-04-18 12:59:53.078529	P12	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
